<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-4000I"></a>Introduction</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-6"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-4001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-4002"></a>
<!--l. 87--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Gnuplot </span>is a portable command-line driven graphing utility for Linux, OS/2, MS Windows, OSX, VMS, and many
other platforms. The source code is copyrighted but freely distributed (i.e., you don&#8217;t have to pay for it). It was
originally created to allow scientists and students to visualize mathematical functions and data interactively, but has
grown to support many non-interactive uses such as web scripting. It is also used as a plotting engine by
third-party applications like Octave. Gnuplot has been supported and under active development since
1986.
<!--l. 96--><p class="noindent" >Gnuplot supports many types of plots in either 2D and 3D. It can draw using lines, points, boxes,
contours, vector fields, surfaces, and various associated text. It also supports various specialized plot
types.
<!--l. 100--><p class="noindent" >Gnuplot supports many different types of output: interactive screen terminals (with mouse and hotkey input),
direct output to pen plotters or modern printers, and output to many file formats (eps, emf, fig, jpeg,
LaTeX, pdf, png, postscript, ...). Gnuplot is easily extensible to include new output modes. Recent
additions include interactive terminals based on wxWidgets (usable on multiple platforms), and Qt.
Mouseable plots embedded in web pages can be generated using the svg or HTML5 canvas terminal
drivers.
<!--l. 108--><p class="noindent" >The command language of <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>is case sensitive, i.e. commands and function names written in lowercase are not
the same as those written in capitals. All command names may be abbreviated as long as the abbreviation is not
ambiguous. Any number of commands may appear on a line, separated by semicolons (;). Strings may be set off by
either single or double quotes, although there are some subtle differences. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">syntax (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-58000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">51</span><!--tex4ht:ref: syntax --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-4003"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">quotes (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-59000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">52</span><!--tex4ht:ref: quotes --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-4004"></a>
for more details. Examples:
<!--l. 117--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;load</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"filename"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;cd</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;dir&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 120--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 123--><p class="noindent" >Commands may extend over several input lines by ending each line but the last with a backslash (<span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>). The backslash
must be the <span 
class="cmti-10">last </span>character on each line. The effect is as if the backslash and newline were not there. That is, no
white space is implied, nor is a comment terminated. Therefore, commenting out a continued line comments out the
entire command (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">comments (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-19000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">24</span><!--tex4ht:ref: comments --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-4005"></a>). But note that if an error occurs somewhere on a multi-line command,
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
the parser may not be able to locate precisely where the error is and in that case will not necessarily point to the
correct line.
<!--l. 132--><p class="noindent" >In this document, curly braces (<span 
class="cmsy-10">{}</span>) denote optional arguments and a vertical bar (<span 
class="cmsy-10">|</span>) separates mutually exclusive
choices. <span 
class="cmbx-10">Gnuplot </span>keywords or <span 
class="cmbx-10">help </span>topics are indicated by backquotes or <span 
class="cmbx-10">boldface </span>(where available). Angle
brackets (<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;&#x003E;</span>) are used to mark replaceable tokens. In many cases, a default value of the token will be taken for
optional arguments if the token is omitted, but these cases are not always denoted with braces around the angle
brackets.
<!--l. 140--><p class="noindent" >For built-in help on any topic, type <span 
class="cmbx-10">help </span>followed by the name of the topic or <span 
class="cmbx-10">help ? </span>to get a menu of available
topics.
<!--l. 143--><p class="noindent" >The new <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>user should begin by reading about <span 
class="cmbx-10">plotting </span>(if in an interactive session, type <span 
class="cmbx-10">help</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">plotting</span>).
<!--l. 146--><p class="noindent" >See the simple.dem demo, also available together with other demos on the web page
<!--l. 147--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/ </span></a>
<!--l. 150--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Gnuplot </span>can be started from a command line or from an icon according to the desktop environment. Running it
from command line can take the syntax <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;gnuplot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{OPTIONS}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;file1</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;file2</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;...</span>
<!--l. 155--><p class="noindent" ></pre> where file1, file2, etc. are input file as in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">load </span>command. On X11-based systems, you can use
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;gnuplot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{X11OPTIONS}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{OPTIONS}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;file1</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;file2</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;...</span>
<!--l. 162--><p class="noindent" ></pre> see your X11 documentation and <span 
class="cmbx-10">x11 (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-485000IV"><span 
class="cmbx-10">310</span><!--tex4ht:ref: x11 --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-4006"></a> in this document.
<!--l. 166--><p class="noindent" >Options interpreted by gnuplot may come anywhere on the line. Files are executed in the order specified, as are
commands supplied by the -e option, for example <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;gnuplot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;file1.in</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-e</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"reset"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;file2.in</span>
<!--l. 172--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 175--><p class="noindent" >The special filename <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>-<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is used to force reading from stdin. <span 
class="cmbx-10">Gnuplot </span>exits after the last file is processed. If no load
files are named, <span 
class="cmbx-10">Gnuplot </span>takes interactive input from stdin. See help <span 
class="cmbx-10">batch/interactive (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-16000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">22</span><!--tex4ht:ref: batch/interactive --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-4007"></a> for more details.
The options specific to gnuplot can be listed by typing <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;gnuplot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;--help</span>
<!--l. 182--><p class="noindent" ></pre> See <span 
class="cmbx-10">command line options (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-16000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">22</span><!--tex4ht:ref: command line options --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-4008"></a> for more details.
<!--l. 186--><p class="noindent" >In sessions with an interactive plot window you can hit &#8217;h&#8217; anywhere on the plot for help about <span 
class="cmbx-10">hotkeys </span>and
<span 
class="cmbx-10">mousing </span>features. Section <span 
class="cmbx-10">seeking-assistance </span>will help you to find further information, help and
FAQ.
