<!--l. 438--><p class="noindent" >
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-16000I"></a>Batch/Interactive Operation</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-30"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-16001"></a>
<!--l. 443--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Gnuplot </span>may be executed in either batch or interactive modes, and the two may even be mixed together on many
systems.
<!--l. 446--><p class="noindent" >Any command-line arguments are assumed to be either program options (first character is -) or names of
files containing <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>commands. The option -e <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>command<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>may be used to force execution of a
gnuplot command. Each file or command string will be executed in the order specified. The special
filename <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>-<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is indicates that commands are to be read from stdin. <span 
class="cmbx-10">Gnuplot </span>exits after the last file is
processed. If no load files and no command strings are specified, <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>accepts interactive input from
stdin.
<!--l. 455--><p class="noindent" >Both the <span 
class="cmbx-10">exit </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">quit </span>commands terminate the current command file and <span 
class="cmbx-10">load </span>the next one, until all have been
processed.
<!--l. 458--><p class="noindent" >Examples:
<!--l. 460--><p class="noindent" >To launch an interactive session: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;gnuplot</span>
<!--l. 464--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 467--><p class="noindent" >To launch a batch session using two command files <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>input1<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>and <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>input2<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;gnuplot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;input1</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;input2</span>
<!--l. 471--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 474--><p class="noindent" >To launch an interactive session after an initialization file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>header<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>and followed by another command file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>trailer<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>:
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;gnuplot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;header</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;trailer</span>
<!--l. 479--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 482--><p class="noindent" >To give <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>commands directly in the command line, using the <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>-persist<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>option so that the plot remains on
the screen afterwards: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;gnuplot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-persist</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-e</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;Sine</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;curve&#8217;;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sin(x)"</span>
<!--l. 487--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 490--><p class="noindent" >To set user-defined variables a and s prior to executing commands from a file: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;gnuplot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-e</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"a=2;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;s=&#8217;file.png&#8217;"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;input.gpl</span>
<!--l. 494--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 497--><p class="noindent" >
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-17000I"></a>Canvas size</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-32"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-17001"></a>
<!--l. 504--><p class="noindent" >In earlier versions of gnuplot, some terminal types used the values from <span 
class="cmbx-10">set size </span>to control also the size of the
output canvas; others did not. The use of &#8217;set size&#8217; for this purpose was deprecated in version 4.2. Since version 4.4
almost all terminals now behave as follows:
<!--l. 509--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">set term </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">terminal</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">_type</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span><span 
class="cmbx-10">size </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">XX</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">, </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">YY</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>controls the size of the output file, or <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>canvas<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. Please see
individual terminal documentation for allowed values of the size parameters. By default, the plot will fill this
canvas.
<!--l. 513--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">set size </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">XX</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">, </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">YY</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>scales the plot itself relative to the size of the canvas. Scale values less than 1 will cause
the plot to not fill the entire canvas. Scale values larger than 1 will cause only a portion of the plot to fit on the
canvas. Please be aware that setting scale values larger than 1 may cause problems on some terminal
types.
<!--l. 519--><p class="noindent" >The major exception to this convention is the PostScript driver, which by default continues to act as it has in earlier
versions. Be warned that the next version of gnuplot may change the default behaviour of the PostScript driver as
well.
<!--l. 524--><p class="noindent" >Example:
<!--l. 527--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;size</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0.5,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0.5</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;term</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;png</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;size</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;600,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;400</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;output</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"figure.png"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"data"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lines</span>
<!--l. 532--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 535--><p class="noindent" >These commands will produce an output file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>figure.png<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>that is 600 pixels wide and 400 pixels tall. The plot will
fill the lower left quarter of this canvas. This is consistent with the way multiplot mode has always
worked.
<!--l. 539--><p class="noindent" >
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
