<!--l. 580--><p class="noindent" >
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-19000I"></a>Comments</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-36"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-19001"></a>
<!--l. 584--><p class="noindent" >Comments are supported as follows: a <span 
class="cmbx-10"># </span>may appear in most places in a line and <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>will ignore the rest of the
line. It will not have this effect inside quotes, inside numbers (including complex numbers), inside command
substitutions, etc. In short, it works anywhere it makes sense to work.
<!--l. 589--><p class="noindent" >See also <span 
class="cmbx-10">set datafile commentschars (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-213000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">145</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set datafile commentschars --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-19002"></a> for specifying comment characters in data files. Note that if a
comment line ends in &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>&#8217; then the subsequent line is also treated as a comment.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-20000I"></a>Coordinates</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-38"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-20001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-20002"></a>
<!--l. 597--><p class="noindent" >The commands <span 
class="cmbx-10">set arrow</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">set key</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">set label </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set object </span>allow you to draw something at an arbitrary
position on the graph. This position is specified by the syntax:
<!--l. 602--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;system&#x003E;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;x&#x003E;,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;system&#x003E;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;y&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{,{&#x003C;system&#x003E;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;z&#x003E;}</span>
<!--l. 604--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 607--><p class="noindent" >Each <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>system<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>can either be <span 
class="cmbx-10">first</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">second</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">graph</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">screen</span>, or <span 
class="cmbx-10">character</span>.
<!--l. 610--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">first </span>places the x, y, or z coordinate in the system defined by the left and bottom axes; <span 
class="cmbx-10">second </span>places it in the
system defined by the second axes (top and right); <span 
class="cmbx-10">graph </span>specifies the area within the axes &#8212; 0,0 is bottom left and
1,1 is top right (for splot, 0,0,0 is bottom left of plotting area; use negative z to get to the base &#8212; see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xyplane</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-338000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">224</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set xyplane --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-20003"></a>); <span 
class="cmbx-10">screen </span>specifies the screen area (the entire area &#8212; not just the portion selected by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set size</span>), with 0,0 at
bottom left and 1,1 at top right; and <span 
class="cmbx-10">character </span>gives the position in character widths and heights from
the bottom left of the screen area (screen 0,0), <span 
class="cmbx-10">character </span>coordinates depend on the chosen font
size.
<!--l. 621--><p class="noindent" >If the coordinate system for x is not specified, <span 
class="cmbx-10">first </span>is used. If the system for y is not specified, the one used for x is
adopted.
<!--l. 624--><p class="noindent" >In some cases, the given coordinate is not an absolute position but a relative value (e.g., the second position in <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmbx-10">arrow </span>... <span 
class="cmbx-10">rto</span>). In most cases, the given value serves as difference to the first position. If the given coordinate resides
in a logarithmic axis the value is interpreted as factor. For example,
<!--l. 631--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;logscale</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;arrow</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;100,5</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;rto</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;10,2</span>
<!--l. 634--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 637--><p class="noindent" >plots an arrow from position 100,5 to position 1000,7 since the x axis is logarithmic while the y axis is
linear.
<!--l. 640--><p class="noindent" >If one (or more) axis is timeseries, the appropriate coordinate should be given as a quoted time string according to
the <span 
class="cmbx-10">timefmt </span>format string. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xdata (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-330000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">216</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set xdata --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-20004"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set timefmt (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-313000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">211</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set timefmt --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-20005"></a>. <span 
class="cmbx-10">Gnuplot </span>will also accept an
integer expression, which will be interpreted as seconds from 1 January 2000.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-21000I"></a>Datastrings</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-40"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-21001"></a>
<!--l. 648--><p class="noindent" >Data files may contain string data consisting of either an arbitrary string of printable characters containing no
whitespace or an arbitrary string of characters, possibly including whitespace, delimited by double quotes. The
following sample line from a datafile is interpreted to contain four columns, with a text field in column
3:
<!--l. 655--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1.000</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;2.000</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"Third</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;column</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;is</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;all</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;of</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;this</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;text"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;4.00</span>
<!--l. 657--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 660--><p class="noindent" >Text fields can be positioned within a 2-D or 3-D plot using the commands:
<!--l. 663--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;datafile&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2:4</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;labels</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;splot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;datafile</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2:3:4</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;labels</span>
<!--l. 666--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 669--><p class="noindent" >A column of text data can also be used to label the ticmarks along one or more of the plot axes. The example below
plots a line through a series of points with (X,Y) coordinates taken from columns 3 and 4 of the input datafile.
However, rather than generating regularly spaced tics along the x axis labeled numerically, gnuplot will position a
tic mark along the x axis at the X coordinate of each point and label the tic mark with text taken from column 1 of
the input datafile.
<!--l. 678--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xtics</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;datafile&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;3:4:xticlabels(1)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;linespoints</span>
<!--l. 681--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<a 
 id="dx1-21002"></a>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 685--><p class="noindent" >There is also an option that will interpret the first entry in a column of input data (i.e. the column heading) as a
text field, and use it as the key title for data plotted from that column. The example given below will use the first
entry in column 2 to generate a title in the key box, while processing the remainder of columns 2 and 4 to draw the
required line:
<!--l. 692--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;datafile&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:(f($2)/$4)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lines</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;columnhead(2)</span>
<!--l. 694--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 697--><p class="noindent" >Another example:
<!--l. 700--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;for</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[i=2:6]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;datafile&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;i</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"Results</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;for</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;".columnhead(i)</span>
<!--l. 702--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 705--><p class="noindent" >See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style labels (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-82000II"><span 
class="cmbx-10">69</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set style labels --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-21003"></a>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">using xticlabels (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-167000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">112</span><!--tex4ht:ref: using xticlabels --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-21004"></a>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot title (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-179000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">119</span><!--tex4ht:ref: plot title --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-21005"></a>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">using (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-164000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">109</span><!--tex4ht:ref: using --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-21006"></a>.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-22000I"></a>Enhanced text mode</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-42"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-22001"></a>
<!--l. 711--><p class="noindent" >Many terminal types support an enhanced text mode in which additional formatting information is embedded in the
text string. For example, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>x<span class="obeylines-h"><span class="verb"><span 
class="cmtt-10">^</span></span></span>2<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>will write x-squared as we are used to seeing it, with a superscript 2. This mode is
normally selected when you set the terminal, e.g. <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>set term png enhanced<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, but may also be toggled
afterward using <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>set termoption enhanced<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, or by marking individual strings as in <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>set label &#8217;x_2&#8217;
noenhanced<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.
