<!--l. 735--><p class="noindent" >Braces can be used to place multiple-character text where a single character is expected (e.g., 2<span class="obeylines-h"><span class="verb"><span 
class="cmtt-10">^</span></span></span><span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>10<span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>). To change
the font and/or size, use the full form: <span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>/[fontname][=fontsize <span 
class="cmsy-10">| </span>*fontscale] text<span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>. Thus <span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>/Symbol=20 G<span 
class="cmsy-10">} </span>is a 20 pt
GAMMA and <span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>/*0.75 K<span 
class="cmsy-10">} </span>is a K at three-quarters of whatever fontsize is currently in effect. (The &#8217;/&#8217; character
MUST be the first character after the &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>&#8217;.)
<!--l. 741--><p class="noindent" >The phantom box is useful for a@<span class="obeylines-h"><span class="verb"><span 
class="cmtt-10">^</span></span></span>b_c to align superscripts and subscripts but does not work well for overwriting an
accent on a letter. For the latter, it is much better to use an encoding (e.g. iso_8859_1 or utf8) that contains a large
variety of letters with accents or other diacritical marks. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set encoding (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-218000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">150</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set encoding --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-22002"></a>. Since the box is
non-spacing, it is sensible to put the shorter of the subscript or superscript in the box (that is, after the
@).
<!--l. 748--><p class="noindent" >Space equal in length to a string can be inserted using the &#8217;&amp;&#8217; character. Thus <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;abc&amp;{def}ghi&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 753--><p class="noindent" ></pre> would produce <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;abc</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ghi&#8217;.</span>
<!--l. 759--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 762--><p class="noindent" >The &#8217;<img 
src="gnuplot1x.png" alt="&#x02DC;  "  class="tilde" >&#8217; character causes the next character or bracketed text to be overprinted by the following character or
bracketed text. The second text will be horizontally centered on the first. Thus &#8217;<img 
src="gnuplot2x.png" alt="&#x02DC;  "  class="tilde" >a/&#8217; will result in an &#8217;a&#8217; with a
slash through it. You can also shift the second text vertically by preceding the second text with a number, which
will define the fraction of the current fontsize by which the text will be raised or lowered. In this case the number
and text must be enclosed in brackets because more than one character is necessary. If the overprinted text begins
with a number, put a space between the vertical offset and the text (&#8217;<img 
src="gnuplot3x.png" alt="&#x02DC;  "  class="tilde" ><span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>abc<span 
class="cmsy-10">}{</span>.5 000<span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>&#8217;); otherwise no space is
needed (&#8217;<img 
src="gnuplot4x.png" alt="&#x02DC;  "  class="tilde" ><span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>abc<span 
class="cmsy-10">}{</span>.5 &#8212; <span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>&#8217;). You can change the font for one or both strings (&#8217;<img 
src="gnuplot5x.png" alt="&#x02DC;  "  class="tilde" >a<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>.5 /*.2 o<span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>&#8217; &#8212; an &#8217;a&#8217; with a
one-fifth-size &#8217;o&#8217; on top &#8212; and the space between the number and the slash is necessary), but you
can&#8217;t change it after the beginning of the string. Neither can you use any other special syntax within
either string. You can, of course, use control characters by escaping them (see below), such as &#8217;<img 
src="gnuplot6x.png" alt="&#x02DC;
"  class="tilde" >a<span 
class="cmsy-10">{\</span><span class="obeylines-h"><span class="verb"><span 
class="cmtt-10">^</span></span></span><span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>&#8217;
<!--l. 778--><p class="noindent" >You can access special symbols numerically by specifying <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>character-code (in octal), e.g., <span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>/Symbol <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>245<span 
class="cmsy-10">} </span>is the
symbol for infinity. This does not work for multibyte encodings like UTF-8, however. In a UTF-8 environment, you
should be able to enter multibyte sequences implicitly by typing or otherwise selecting the character you
want.
<!--l. 784--><p class="noindent" >You can escape control characters using <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>, e.g., <span 
class="cmsy-10">\\</span>, <span 
class="cmsy-10">\{</span>, and so on.
<!--l. 786--><p class="noindent" >But be aware that strings in double-quotes are parsed differently than those enclosed in single-quotes. The major
difference is that backslashes may need to be doubled when in double-quoted strings.
<!--l. 790--><p class="noindent" >Examples (these are hard to describe in words &#8212; try them!): <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xlabel</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;Time</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(10^6</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{/Symbol</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;m}s)&#8217;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;{/Symbol=18</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\\362@_{/=9.6</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0}^{/=12</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x}}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\\</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{/Helvetica</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;e^{-{/Symbol</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;m}^2/2}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;d}{/Symbol</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;m}&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 796--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 799--><p class="noindent" >The file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>ps_guide.ps<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>in the /docs/psdoc subdirectory of the gnuplot source distribution contains more examples of
the enhanced syntax.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-23000I"></a>Environment</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-44"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-23001"></a>
<!--l. 805--><p class="noindent" >A number of shell environment variables are understood by <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot</span>. None of these are required, but may be
useful.
<!--l. 808--><p class="noindent" >If GNUTERM is defined, it is used as the name of the terminal type to be used. This overrides any terminal type
sensed by <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>on start-up, but is itself overridden by the .gnuplot (or equivalent) start-up file (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">startup</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-52000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">47</span><!--tex4ht:ref: startup --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-23002"></a>) and, of course, by later explicit changes.
<!--l. 813--><p class="noindent" >GNUHELP may be defined to be the pathname of the HELP file (gnuplot.gih).
<!--l. 815--><p class="noindent" >On VMS, the logical name GNUPLOT$HELP should be defined as the name of the help library for <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot</span>. The
<span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>help can be put inside any system help library, allowing access to help from both within and outside
<span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>if desired.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 820--><p class="noindent" >On Unix, HOME is used as the name of a directory to search for a .gnuplot file if none is found in the current
directory. On MS-DOS, Windows and OS/2, GNUPLOT is used. On Windows, the NT-specific variable
USERPROFILE is also tried. VMS, SYS$LOGIN: is used. Type <span 
class="cmbx-10">help startup</span>.
<!--l. 825--><p class="noindent" >On Unix, PAGER is used as an output filter for help messages.
<!--l. 827--><p class="noindent" >On Unix, SHELL is used for the <span 
class="cmbx-10">shell </span>command. On MS-DOS and OS/2, COMSPEC is used for the <span 
class="cmbx-10">shell</span>
command.
<!--l. 830--><p class="noindent" >FIT_SCRIPT may be used to specify a <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>command to be executed when a fit is interrupted &#8212; see <span 
class="cmbx-10">fit</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-106000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">79</span><!--tex4ht:ref: fit --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-23003"></a>. FIT_LOG specifies the default filename of the logfile maintained by fit.
<!--l. 834--><p class="noindent" >GNUPLOT_LIB may be used to define additional search directories for data and command files. The variable may
contain a single directory name, or a list of directories separated by a platform-specific path separator, eg. &#8217;:&#8217; on
Unix, or &#8217;;&#8217; on DOS/Windows/OS/2 platforms. The contents of GNUPLOT_LIB are appended to the <span 
class="cmbx-10">loadpath</span>
variable, but not saved with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">save </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">save set </span>commands.
<!--l. 841--><p class="noindent" >Several gnuplot terminal drivers access TrueType fonts via the gd library. For these drivers the font search path is
controlled by the environmental variable GDFONTPATH. Furthermore, a default font for these drivers may be set
via the environmental variable GNUPLOT_DEFAULT_GDFONT.
<!--l. 846--><p class="noindent" >The postscript terminal uses its own font search path. It is controlled by the environmental variable
GNUPLOT_FONTPATH. The format is the same as for GNUPLOT_LIB. The contents of GNUPLOT_FONTPATH are
appended to the <span 
class="cmbx-10">fontpath </span>variable, but not saved with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">save </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">save set </span>commands.
<!--l. 851--><p class="noindent" >GNUPLOT_PS_DIR is used by the postscript driver to search for external prologue files. Depending on the build
process, gnuplot contains either a built-in copy of those files or a default hardcoded path. You can use this variable
have the postscript terminal use custom prologue files rather than the default files. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">postscript prologue</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-458000IV"><span 
class="cmbx-10">294</span><!--tex4ht:ref: postscript prologue --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-23004"></a>.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-24000I"></a>Expressions</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-46"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-24001"></a>
<!--l. 860--><p class="noindent" >In general, any mathematical expression accepted by C, FORTRAN, Pascal, or BASIC is valid. The precedence of
these operators is determined by the specifications of the C programming language. White space (spaces and tabs) is
ignored inside expressions.
<!--l. 865--><p class="noindent" >Complex constants are expressed as <span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>real<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>,<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>imag<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>, where <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>real<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>imag<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>must be numerical constants.
For example, <span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>3,2<span 
class="cmsy-10">} </span>represents 3 + 2i; <span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>0,1<span 
class="cmsy-10">} </span>represents &#8217;i&#8217; itself. The curly braces are explicitly required
here.
<a 
 id="dx1-24002"></a>
<!--l. 870--><p class="noindent" >Note that gnuplot uses both <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>real<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>and <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>integer<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>arithmetic, like FORTRAN and C. Integers are entered as <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>1<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>,
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>-10<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, etc; reals as <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>1.0<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>-10.0<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>1e1<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, 3.5e-1, etc. The most important difference between the two forms is in
division: division of integers truncates: 5/2 = 2; division of reals does not: 5.0/2.0 = 2.5. In mixed expressions,
integers are <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>promoted<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>to reals before evaluation: 5/2e0 = 2.5. The result of division of a negative integer by a
positive one may vary among compilers. Try a test like <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>print -5/2<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>to determine if your system chooses -2 or -3 as
the answer.
<!--l. 879--><p class="noindent" >The integer expression <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>1/0<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>may be used to generate an <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>undefined<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>flag, which causes a point to ignored. Or you
can use the pre-defined variable NaN to achieve the same result. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">using (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-164000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">109</span><!--tex4ht:ref: using --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-24003"></a> for an example.
<a 
 id="dx1-24004"></a>
<!--l. 884--><p class="noindent" >The real and imaginary parts of complex expressions are always real, whatever the form in which they are entered:
in <span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>3,2<span 
class="cmsy-10">} </span>the <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>3<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>and <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>2<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>are reals, not integers.
<!--l. 888--><p class="noindent" >Gnuplot can also perform simple operations on strings and string variables. For example, the expression (<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>A<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>.
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>B<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>eq <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>AB<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>) evaluates as true, illustrating the string concatenation operator and the string equality
operator.
<!--l. 892--><p class="noindent" >A string which contains a numerical value is promoted to the corresponding integer or real value if used in
a numerical expression. Thus (<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>3<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>+ <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>4<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>== 7) and (6.78 == <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>6.78<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>) both evaluate to true. An
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
integer, but not a real or complex value, is promoted to a string if used in string concatenation. A
typical case is the use of integers to construct file names or other strings; e.g. (<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>file<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>. 4 eq <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>file4<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>) is
true.
<!--l. 899--><p class="noindent" >Substrings can be specified using a postfixed range descriptor [beg:end]. For example, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>ABCDEF<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>[3:4] == <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>CD<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>
and <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>ABCDEF<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>[4:*] == <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>DEF<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>The syntax <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>string<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>[beg:end] is exactly equivalent to calling the built-in
string-valued function substr(<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>string<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>,beg,end), except that you cannot omit either beg or end from the function
call.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-25000I"></a>Functions</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-48"></a>
<!--l. 907--><p class="noindent" >The math functions in <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>are the same as the corresponding functions in the Unix math library, except that
all functions accept integer, real, and complex arguments unless otherwise noted. Functions that accept or return
angles (e.g. sin(x), cos(x), arg(z)) treat angle values as radians, but this may be changed to degrees using the
command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set angles</span>.
