<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-28000I"></a>Value</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-54"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-28001"></a>
<!--l. 1283--><p class="noindent" >B = value(<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>A<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>) is effectively the same as B = A, where A is the name of a user-defined variable. This is useful when
the name of the variable is itself held in a string variable. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">user-defined variables (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-35000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">35</span><!--tex4ht:ref: user-defined variables --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-28002"></a>. It also allows you
to read the name of a variable from a data file. If the argument is a numerical expression, value() returns the value
of that expression. If the argument is a string that does not correspond to a currently defined variable, value()
returns NaN.
<!--l. 1291--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-29000I"></a>Operators</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-56"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-29001"></a>
<!--l. 1296--><p class="noindent" >The operators in <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>are the same as the corresponding operators in the C programming language, except that
all operators accept integer, real, and complex arguments, unless otherwise noted. The ** operator (exponentiation)
is supported, as in FORTRAN.
<!--l. 1301--><p class="noindent" >Parentheses may be used to change order of evaluation.
