<!--l. 1380--><p class="noindent" >(*) Starred explanations indicate that the operator requires integer arguments. Capital letters A and B indicate that
the operator requires string arguments.
<!--l. 1384--><p class="noindent" >Logical AND (&amp;&amp;) and OR (<span 
class="cmsy-10">||</span>) short-circuit the way they do in C. That is, the second <span 
class="cmbx-10">&amp;&amp; </span>operand is not evaluated
if the first is false; the second <span 
class="cmsy-10">|| </span>operand is not evaluated if the first is true.
<!--l. 1388--><p class="noindent" >Serial evaluation occurs only in parentheses and is guaranteed to proceed in left to right order. The value of the
rightmost subexpression is returned.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-32000I"></a>Ternary</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-62"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-32001"></a>
<!--l. 1396--><p class="noindent" >There is a single ternary operator:
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 1399--><p class="noindent" >
<div class="tabular"> <table id="TBL-9" class="tabular" 
cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" rules="groups" 
><colgroup id="TBL-9-1g"><col 
id="TBL-9-1"><col 
id="TBL-9-2"><col 
id="TBL-9-3"></colgroup><tr 
class="hline"><td><hr></td><td><hr></td><td><hr></td></tr><tr  
 style="vertical-align:baseline;" id="TBL-9-1-"><td colspan="3" style="white-space:nowrap; text-align:center;" id="TBL-9-1-1"  
class="td11">        <div class="multicolumn"  style="white-space:nowrap; text-align:center;">Ternary Operator</div>
</td></tr><tr 
class="hline"><td><hr></td><td><hr></td><td><hr></td></tr><tr 
class="hline"><td><hr></td><td><hr></td><td><hr></td></tr><tr  
 style="vertical-align:baseline;" id="TBL-9-2-"><td  style="white-space:nowrap; text-align:center;" id="TBL-9-2-1"  
class="td11">Symbol</td><td  style="white-space:nowrap; text-align:center;" id="TBL-9-2-2"  
