<!--l. 1409--><p class="noindent" >The ternary operator behaves as it does in C. The first argument (a), which must be an integer, is evaluated. If it is
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
true (non-zero), the second argument (b) is evaluated and returned; otherwise the third argument (c) is evaluated
and returned.
<!--l. 1414--><p class="noindent" >The ternary operator is very useful both in constructing piecewise functions and in plotting points only when certain
conditions are met.
<!--l. 1417--><p class="noindent" >Examples:
<!--l. 1419--><p class="noindent" >Plot a function that is to equal sin(x) for 0 <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>= x <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C; </span>1, 1/x for 1 <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>= x <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C; </span>2, and undefined elsewhere:
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;f(x)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0&#x003C;=x</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&amp;&amp;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x&#x003C;1</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;?</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sin(x)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1&#x003C;=x</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&amp;&amp;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x&#x003C;2</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;?</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1/x</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1/0</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;f(x)</span>
<!--l. 1425--><p class="noindent" ></pre> Note that <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>quietly ignores undefined values, so the final branch of the function (1/0) will produce no
plottable points. Note also that f(x) will be plotted as a continuous function across the discontinuity if a line style is
used. To plot it discontinuously, create separate functions for the two pieces. (Parametric functions are also useful
for this purpose.)
<!--l. 1433--><p class="noindent" >For data in a file, plot the average of the data in columns 2 and 3 against the datum in column 1, but only if the
datum in column 4 is non-negative:
<!--l. 1437--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:(</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$4&#x003C;0</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;?</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1/0</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;($2+$3)/2</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;)</span>
<!--l. 1439--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 1442--><p class="noindent" >For an explanation of the <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>syntax, please see <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot datafile using (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-164000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">109</span><!--tex4ht:ref: plot datafile using --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-32002"></a>.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-33000I"></a>Summation</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-64"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-33001"></a>
<!--l. 1449--><p class="noindent" >A summation expression has the form <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sum</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[&#x003C;var&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;start&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;end&#x003E;]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;expression&#x003E;</span>
<!--l. 1453--><p class="noindent" ></pre> <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>var<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is treated as an integer variable that takes on successive integral values from <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>start<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>to <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>end<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. For each of
these, the current value of <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>expression<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is added to a running total whose final value becomes the value of the
summation expression. Examples: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;print</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sum</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[i=1:10]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;i</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;55.</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;#</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Equivalent</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;to</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;data&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:($2+$3+$4+$5+$6+...)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;data&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(sum</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[col=2:MAXCOL]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;column(col))</span>
<!--l. 1466--><p class="noindent" ></pre> It is not necessary that <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>expression<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>contain the variable <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>var<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. Although <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>start<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>end<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>can
be specified as variables or expressions, their value cannot be changed dynamically as a side-effect
of carrying out the summation. If <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>end<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is less than <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>start<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>then the value of the summation is
zero.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-34000I"></a>Gnuplot-defined variables</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-66"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-34001"></a>
<!--l. 1478--><p class="noindent" >Gnuplot maintains a number of read-only variables that reflect the current internal state of the program and the
most recent plot. These variables begin with the prefix <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>GPVAL_<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. Examples include GPVAL_TERM,
GPVAL_X_MIN, GPVAL_X_MAX, GPVAL_Y_MIN. Type <span 
class="cmbx-10">show variables all </span>to display the complete list and
current values. Values related to axes parameters (ranges, log base) are values used during the last plot, not those
currently <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>.
<!--l. 1486--><p class="noindent" >Example: To calculate the fractional screen coordinates of the point [X,Y] <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;GRAPH_X</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(X</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;GPVAL_X_MIN)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;/</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(GPVAL_X_MAX</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;GPVAL_X_MIN)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;GRAPH_Y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(Y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;GPVAL_Y_MIN)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;/</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(GPVAL_Y_MAX</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;GPVAL_Y_MIN)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;SCREEN_X</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;GPVAL_TERM_XMIN</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;+</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;GRAPH_X</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;*</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(GPVAL_TERM_XMAX</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;GPVAL_TERM_XMIN)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;SCREEN_Y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;GPVAL_TERM_YMIN</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;+</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;GRAPH_Y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;*</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(GPVAL_TERM_YMAX</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;GPVAL_TERM_YMIN)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;FRAC_X</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;SCREEN_X</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;/</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;GPVAL_TERM_XSIZE</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;FRAC_Y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;SCREEN_Y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;/</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;GPVAL_TERM_YSIZE</span>
<!--l. 1495--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<a 
 id="dx1-34002"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-34003"></a>
<!--l. 1500--><p class="noindent" >The read-only variable GPVAL_ERRNO is set to a non-zero value if any gnuplot command terminates early due to
an error. The most recent error message is stored in the string variable GPVAL_ERRMSG. Both GPVAL_ERRNO
and GPVAL_ERRMSG can be cleared using the command <span 
class="cmbx-10">reset errors</span>.
<!--l. 1505--><p class="noindent" >Interactive terminals with <span 
class="cmbx-10">mouse </span>functionality maintain read-only variables with the prefix <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>MOUSE_<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. See
<span 
class="cmbx-10">mouse variables (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-50000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">45</span><!--tex4ht:ref: mouse variables --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-34004"></a> for details.
<!--l. 1508--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">fit </span>mechanism uses several variables with names that begin <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>FIT_<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. It is safest to avoid using such names.
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>FIT_LIMIT<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, however, is one that you may wish to redefine. Under <span 
class="cmbx-10">set fit errorvariables</span>, the error for each
fitted parameter will be stored in a variable named like the parameter, but with <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>_err<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>appended. See the
documentation on <span 
class="cmbx-10">fit (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-106000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">79</span><!--tex4ht:ref: fit --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-34005"></a> for details.
<!--l. 1514--><p class="noindent" >See <span 
class="cmbx-10">user-defined variables (p.</span><span 
