 id="dx1-35010"></a>.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-36000I"></a>Fonts</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-70"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-36001"></a>
<!--l. 1614--><p class="noindent" >Gnuplot does not provide any fonts of its own. It relies on external font handling, the details of which unfortunately
vary from one terminal type to another. Brief documentation of font mechanisms that apply to more than one
terminal type is given here. For information on font use by other individual terminals, see the documentation for
that terminal.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-37000I"></a>Cairo (pdfcairo, pngcairo, epscairo, wxt terminals)</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-72"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-37001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-37002"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-37003"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-37004"></a>
<!--l. 1626--><p class="noindent" >Sorry, this section is under construction. These terminals find and access fonts using the external fontconfig tool set.
Please see the
<!--l. 1629--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://fontconfig.org/fontconfig-user.html" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">fontconfig user manual. </span></a>
<!--l. 1632--><p class="noindent" >It is usually sufficient in gnuplot to request a font by a generic name and size, letting fontconfig substitute a similar
font if necessary. The following will probably all work: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;term</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pdfcairo</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"sans,12"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;term</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pdfcairo</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"Times,12"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;term</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pdfcairo</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"Times-New-Roman,12"</span>
<!--l. 1640--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 1643--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-38000I"></a>Gd (png, gif, jpeg terminals)</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-74"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-38001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-38002"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-38003"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-38004"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-38005"></a>
<!--l. 1652--><p class="noindent" >Font handling for the png, gif, and jpeg terminals is done by the external library libgd. Five basic fonts are provided
directly by libgd. These are <span 
class="cmbx-10">tiny </span>(5x8 pixels), <span 
class="cmbx-10">small </span>(6x12 pixels), <span 
class="cmbx-10">medium</span>, (7x13 Bold), <span 
class="cmbx-10">large </span>(8x16) or <span 
class="cmbx-10">giant</span>
(9x15 pixels). These fonts cannot be scaled or rotated. Use one of these keywords instead of the <span 
class="cmbx-10">font </span>keyword. E.g.
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;term</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;png</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;tiny</span>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 1660--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 1663--><p class="noindent" >On most systems libgd also provides access to Adobe Type 1 fonts (*.pfa) and TrueType fonts (*.ttf). You must give
the name of the font file, not the name of the font inside it, in the form <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>face<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span><span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>,<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>pointsize<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>face<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is either
the full pathname to the font file, or the first part of a filename in one of the directories listed in the
GDFONTPATH environmental variable. That is, &#8217;set term png font <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>Face<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>&#8217; will look for a font file named either
<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>somedirectory<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>/Face.ttf or <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>somedirectory<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>/Face.pfa. For example, if GDFONTPATH contains
<span 
class="cmbx-10">/usr/local/fonts/ttf:/usr/local/fonts/pfa </span>then the following pairs of commands are equivalent
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
