<!--l. 1684--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 1687--><p class="noindent" >Both TrueType and Adobe Type 1 fonts are fully scalable and rotatable. If no specific font is requested in the <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>set
term<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>command, gnuplot checks the environmental variable GNUPLOT_DEFAULT_GDFONT to see if there is a
preferred default font.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-39000I"></a>Postscript (also encapsulated postscript *.eps)</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-76"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-39001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-39002"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-39003"></a>
<!--l. 1697--><p class="noindent" >PostScript font handling is done by the printer or viewing program. Gnuplot can create valid PostScript or
encapsulated PostScript (*.eps) even if no fonts at all are installed on your computer. Gnuplot simply refers to the
font by name in the output file, and assumes that the printer or viewing program will know how to find or
approximate a font by that name.
<!--l. 1703--><p class="noindent" >All PostScript printers or viewers should know about the standard set of Adobe fonts <span 
class="cmbx-10">Times-Roman</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">Helvetica</span>,
<span 
class="cmbx-10">Courier</span>, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">Symbol</span>. It is likely that many additional fonts are also available, but the specific set depends on
your system or printer configuration. Gnuplot does not know or care about this; the output *.ps or *.eps files that it
creates will simply refer to whatever font names you request.
<!--l. 1710--><p class="noindent" >Thus <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;term</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;postscript</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;eps</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"Times-Roman,12"</span>
<!--l. 1714--><p class="noindent" ></pre> will produce output that is suitable for all printers and viewers.
<!--l. 1718--><p class="noindent" >On the other hand <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;term</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;postscript</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;eps</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"Garamond-Premier-Pro-Italic"</span>
<!--l. 1722--><p class="noindent" ></pre> will produce an output file that contains valid PostScript, but since it refers to a specialized font, only some
printers or viewers will be able to display the specific font that was requested. Most will substitute a different
font.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 1729--><p class="noindent" >However, it is possible to embed a specific font in the output file so that all printers will be able to use it. This
requires that the a suitable font description file is available on your system. Note that some font files require specific
licensing if they are to be embedded in this way. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">postscript fontfile (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-457000IV"><span 
class="cmbx-10">292</span><!--tex4ht:ref: postscript fontfile --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-39004"></a> for more detailed description
and examples.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-40000I"></a>Glossary</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-78"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-40001"></a>
<!--l. 1738--><p class="noindent" >Throughout this document an attempt has been made to maintain consistency of nomenclature. This cannot be
wholly successful because as <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>has evolved over time, certain command and keyword names have been
adopted that preclude such perfection. This section contains explanations of the way some of these terms are
used.
<!--l. 1744--><p class="noindent" >A <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>page<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>or <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>screen<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>or <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>canvas<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is the entire area addressable by <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot</span>. On a desktop it is a full window; on a
plotter, it is a single sheet of paper; in svga mode it is the full monitor screen.
<!--l. 1748--><p class="noindent" >A screen may contain one or more <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>plots<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. A plot is defined by an abscissa and an ordinate, although these need not
actually appear on it, as well as the margins and any text written therein.
<!--l. 1752--><p class="noindent" >A plot contains one <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>graph<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. A graph is defined by an abscissa and an ordinate, although these need not actually
appear on it.
<!--l. 1755--><p class="noindent" >A graph may contain one or more <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>lines<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. A line is a single function or data set. <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>Line<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is also a plotting
style. The word will also be used in sense <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>a line of text<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. Presumably the context will remove any
ambiguity.
<!--l. 1759--><p class="noindent" >The lines on a graph may have individual names. These may be listed together with a sample of the plotting style
used to represent them in the <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>key<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, sometimes also called the <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>legend<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.
<!--l. 1763--><p class="noindent" >The word <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>title<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>occurs with multiple meanings in <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot</span>. In this document, it will always be preceded by
the adjective <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>plot<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>line<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, or <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>key<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>to differentiate among them. A 2D graph may have up to four
labelled <span 
class="cmbx-10">axes</span>. The names of the four axes are <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>x<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>for the axis along the bottom border of the plot, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>y<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>
for the axis along the left border, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>x2<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>for the top border, and <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>y2<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>for the right border. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">axes</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-127000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">93</span><!--tex4ht:ref: axes --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-40002"></a>.
<!--l. 1771--><p class="noindent" >A 3D graph may have up to three labelled <span 
class="cmbx-10">axes </span>&#8211; <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>x<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>y<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>and <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>z<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. It is not possible to say where on the graph any
particular axis will fall because you can change the direction from which the graph is seen with <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">view</span>.
<!--l. 1775--><p class="noindent" >When discussing data files, the term <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>record<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>will be resurrected and used to denote a single line of text in the file,
that is, the characters between newline or end-of-record characters. A <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>point<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is the datum extracted from a single
record. A <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>datablock<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is a set of points from consecutive records, delimited by blank records. A line, when referred
to in the context of a data file, is a subset of a datablock.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-41000I"></a>Linetypes, colors, and styles</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-80"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-41001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-41002"></a>
<!--l. 1787--><p class="noindent" >Each gnuplot terminal type provides a set of distinct <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>linetypes<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. These may differ in color, in thickness, in
dot/dash pattern, or in some combination of color and dot/dash. The default linetypes for a particular terminal can
be previewed by issuing the <span 
class="cmbx-10">test </span>command after setting the terminal type. The pre-defined colors and dot/dash
patterns are not guaranteed to be consistent for all terminal types, but all terminals use the special linetype -1 to
mean a solid line in the primary foreground color (normally black). Most terminals also recognize the special
linetype <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>bgnd<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>to mean a solid line in the background color.
<!--l. 1797--><p class="noindent" >You can redefine the default linetype properties either interactively or via an initialization file. This allows you to
customize the colors and other properties of the lines used by all gnuplot plotting commands. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set linetype</span>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-235000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">166</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set linetype --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-41003"></a>.
<!--l. 1802--><p class="noindent" >By default, successive functions or datafiles plotted by a single command will be assigned successive linetypes. You
can override this default sequence by specifying a particular linetype for any function, datafile, or plot
element.
