 id="dx1-42008"></a>.
<!--l. 1898--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>colorname<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>refers to one of the color names built in to gnuplot. For a list of the available names, see <span 
class="cmbx-10">show</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">colornames (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-205000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">141</span><!--tex4ht:ref: show colornames --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-42009"></a>.
<!--l. 1901--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>#RRGGBB<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is a hexadecimal constant preceded by the <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>#<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>symbol. The RRGGBB represents the red, green, and
blue components of the color, each on a scale from 0 - 255. For example, magenta = full-scale red + full-scale blue
would be represented by #FF00FF, which is the hexadecimal representation of (255 <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;&#x003C; </span>16) + (0 <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;&#x003C; </span>8) +
(255).
<!--l. 1907--><p class="noindent" >The color palette is a linear gradient of colors that smoothly maps a single numerical value onto a particular color.
Two such mappings are always in effect. <span 
class="cmbx-10">palette frac </span>maps a fractional value between 0 and 1 onto the full range of
the color palette. <span 
class="cmbx-10">palette cb </span>maps the range of the color axis onto the same palette. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set cbrange (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-367000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">230</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set cbrange --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-42010"></a>.
See also <span 
class="cmbx-10">set colorbox (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-204000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">140</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set colorbox --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-42011"></a>. You can use either of these to select a constant color from the current
palette.
<!--l. 1915--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>palette z<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>maps the z value of each plot segment or plot element into the cbrange mapping of the palette. This
allows smoothly-varying color along a 3d line or surface. It also allows coloring 2D plots by palette values read from
an extra column of data (not all 2D plot styles allow an extra column).
