<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-45000I"></a>Rgbcolor variable</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-88"></a>
<!--l. 1974--><p class="noindent" >You can assign a separate color for each data point, line segment, or label in your plot. <span 
class="cmbx-10">lc rgbcolor variable </span>tells
the program to read RGB color information for each line in the data file. This requires a corresponding additional
column in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>specifier. The extra column is interpreted as a 24-bit packed RGB triple. If the value is
provided directly in the data file it is easiest to give it as a hexidecimal value (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">rgbcolor (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-42000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">40</span><!--tex4ht:ref: rgbcolor --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-45001"></a>). Alternatively,
the <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>specifier can contain an expression that evaluates to a 24-bit RGB color as in the example below. Text
colors are similarly set using <span 
class="cmbx-10">tc rgbcolor variable</span>.
