<!--l. 2018--><p class="noindent" >
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-47000I"></a>Mouse input</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-92"></a>
<!--l. 2021--><p class="noindent" >Many terminals allow interaction with the current plot using the mouse. Some also support the definition of hotkeys
to activate pre-defined functions by hitting a single key while the mouse focus is in the active plot window. It is
even possible to combine mouse input with <span 
class="cmbx-10">batch </span>command scripts, by invoking the command <span 
class="cmbx-10">pause</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">mouse </span>and then using the mouse variables returned by mouse clicking as parameters for subsequent
scripted actions. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">bind (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-48000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">43</span><!--tex4ht:ref: bind --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-47001"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">mouse variables (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-50000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">45</span><!--tex4ht:ref: mouse variables --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-47002"></a>. See also the command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set mouse</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-243000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">171</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set mouse --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-47003"></a>.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-48000I"></a>Bind</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-94"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-48001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-48002"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-48003"></a>
