<!--l. 2198--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2201--><p class="noindent" >When <span 
class="cmbx-10">pause mouse keypress </span>is terminated by a keypress, then MOUSE_KEY will contain the ascii character
value of the key that was pressed. MOUSE_CHAR will contain the character itself as a string variable. If the pause
command is terminated abnormally (e.g. by ctrl-C or by externally closing the plot window) then MOUSE_KEY
will equal -1.
<!--l. 2207--><p class="noindent" >Note that after a zoom by mouse, you can read the new ranges as GPVAL_X_MIN, GPVAL_X_MAX,
GPVAL_Y_MIN, and GPVAL_Y_MAX, see <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot-defined variables (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-34000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">35</span><!--tex4ht:ref: gnuplot-defined variables --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-50001"></a>.
<!--l. 2211--><p class="noindent" >
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-51000I"></a>Plotting</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-100"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-51001"></a>
<!--l. 2215--><p class="noindent" >There are three <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>commands which actually create a plot: <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">replot</span>. <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>generates 2D plots,
<span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>generates 3D plots (actually 2D projections, of course), and <span 
class="cmbx-10">replot </span>appends its arguments to the previous
<span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>and executes the modified command.
<!--l. 2221--><p class="noindent" >Much of the general information about plotting can be found in the discussion of <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>; information specific to 3D
can be found in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>section.
<!--l. 2224--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>operates in either rectangular or polar coordinates &#8211; see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set polar (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-284000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">194</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set polar --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-51002"></a> for details of the latter. <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>
operates only in rectangular coordinates, but the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set mapping </span>command allows for a few other coordinate systems
to be treated. In addition, the <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>option allows both <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>to treat almost any coordinate system you&#8217;d
care to define.
<a 
 id="dx1-51003"></a>
<!--l. 2231--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>also lets you use each of the four borders &#8211; x (bottom), x2 (top), y (left) and y2 (right) &#8211; as an independent
axis. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">axes </span>option lets you choose which pair of axes a given function or data set is plotted against. A full
complement of <span 
class="cmbx-10">set </span>commands exists to give you complete control over the scales and labelling of each axis. Some
commands have the name of an axis built into their names, such as <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xlabel</span>. Other commands have one or more
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
axis names as options, such as <span 
class="cmbx-10">set logscale xy</span>. Commands and options controlling the z axis have no effect on 2D
graphs.
<!--l. 2240--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>can plot surfaces and contours in addition to points and/or lines. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set isosamples (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-230000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">158</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set isosamples --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-51004"></a> for
information about defining the grid for a 3D function. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot datafile (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-371000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">231</span><!--tex4ht:ref: splot datafile --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-51005"></a> for information about the
requisite file structure for 3D data values, <span 
class="cmbx-10">set contour (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-206000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">141</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set contour --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-51006"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set cntrparam (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-203000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">138</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set cntrparam --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-51007"></a> for information
about contours.
<!--l. 2245--><p class="noindent" >In <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>, control over the scales and labels of the axes are the same as with <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>, except that commands and
options controlling the x2 and y2 axes have no effect whereas of course those controlling the z axis do take
effect.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-52000I"></a>Start-up (initialization)</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-102"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-52001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-52002"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-52003"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-52004"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-52005"></a>
<!--l. 2260--><p class="noindent" >When gnuplot is run, it first looks for a system-wide initialization file named <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplotrc</span>. The location of this file is
determined when the program is built and is reported by <span 
class="cmbx-10">show loadpath</span>. The program then looks in
the user&#8217;s HOME directory for a file called <span 
class="cmbx-10">.gnuplot </span>on Unix-like systems or <span 
class="cmbx-10">GNUPLOT.INI </span>on
other systems. (Windows and OS/2 will look for it in the directory named in the environment variable
<span 
class="cmbx-10">GNUPLOT</span>; Windows will use <span 
class="cmbx-10">USERPROFILE </span>if GNUPLOT is not defined). Note: The program can be
configured to look first in the current directory, but this is not recommended because it is bad security
practice.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-53000I"></a>String constants and string variables</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-104"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-53001"></a>
<!--l. 2274--><p class="noindent" >In addition to string constants, most gnuplot commands also accept a string variable, a string expression, or a
function that returns a string. For example, the following four methods of creating a plot all result in the same plot
title:
<!--l. 2280--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;four</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"4"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;graph4</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"Title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;for</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;#4"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;graph(n)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sprintf("Title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;for</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;#%d",n)</span>
<!--l. 2284--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2288--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;data.4&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"Title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;for</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;#4"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;data.4&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;graph4</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;data.4&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"Title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;for</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;#".four</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;data.4&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;graph(4)</span>
<!--l. 2293--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2296--><p class="noindent" >Since integers are promoted to strings when operated on by the string concatenation operator, the following method
also works:
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 2300--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;N</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;4</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;data.&#8217;.N</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"Title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;for</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;#".N</span>
<!--l. 2303--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2306--><p class="noindent" >In general, elements on the command line will only be evaluated as possible string variables if they are not otherwise
recognizable as part of the normal gnuplot syntax. So the following sequence of commands is legal, although
probably should be avoided so as not to cause confusion:
<!--l. 2312--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"my_datafile.dat"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"My</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Title"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span>
<!--l. 2316--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2319--><p class="noindent" >There are three binary operators that require string operands: the string concatenation operator <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, the
string equality operator <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>eq<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>and the string inequality operator <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>ne<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. The following example will print
TRUE.
<!--l. 2324--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;if</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;("A"."B"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;eq</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"AB")</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;print</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"TRUE"</span>
<!--l. 2326--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2329--><p class="noindent" >See also the two string formatting functions <span 
class="cmbx-10">gprintf (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-222000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">152</span><!--tex4ht:ref: gprintf --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-53002"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">sprintf (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-25000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">30</span><!--tex4ht:ref: sprintf --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-53003"></a>.
<a 
 id="dx1-53004"></a>
<!--l. 2332--><p class="noindent" >Substrings can be specified by appending a range specifier to any string, string variable, or string-valued function.
The range specifier has the form [begin:end], where begin is the index of the first character of the substring and end
is the index of the last character of the substring. The first character has index 1. The begin or end fields may be
empty, or contain &#8217;*&#8217;, to indicate the true start or end of the original string. E.g. str[:] and str[*:*] both describe the
full string str.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-54000I"></a>Substitution and Command line macros</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-106"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-54001"></a>
<!--l. 2343--><p class="noindent" >When a command line to gnuplot is first read, i.e. before it is interpreted or executed, two forms of lexical
substitution are performed. These are triggered by the presence of text in backquotes (ascii character 96) or
preceded by @ (ascii character 64).
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-55000I"></a>Substitution of system commands in backquotes</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-108"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-55001"></a>
<!--l. 2353--><p class="noindent" >Command-line substitution is specified by a system command enclosed in backquotes. This command is spawned
and the output it produces replaces the backquoted text on the command line. Some implementations also support
pipes; see <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot datafile special-filenames (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-162000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">106</span><!--tex4ht:ref: plot datafile special-filenames --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-55002"></a>.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 2358--><p class="noindent" >Command-line substitution can be used anywhere on the <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>command line, except inside strings delimited by
single quotes.
<!--l. 2361--><p class="noindent" >Example:
<!--l. 2363--><p class="noindent" >This will run the program <span 
class="cmbx-10">leastsq </span>and replace <span 
class="cmbx-10">leastsq </span>(including backquotes) on the command line with its output:
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;f(x)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;leastsq&#8216;</span>
<!--l. 2368--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2371--><p class="noindent" >or, in VMS <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;f(x)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;run</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;leastsq&#8216;</span>
<!--l. 2375--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2378--><p class="noindent" >These will generate labels with the current time and userid: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;label</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"generated</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;on</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;date</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;+%Y-%m-%d&#8216;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;by</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;whoami&#8216;"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;at</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1,1</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;timestamp</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"generated</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;on</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;%Y-%m-%d</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;by</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;whoami&#8216;"</span>
<!--l. 2383--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-56000I"></a>Substitution of string variables as macros</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-110"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-56001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-56002"></a>
<!--l. 2391--><p class="noindent" >Substitution of command line macros is disabled by default, but may be enabled using the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set macros </span>command. If
macro substitution is enabled, the character @ is used to trigger substitution of the current value of a string variable
into the command line. The text in the string variable may contain any number of lexical elements. This allows
string variables to be used as command line macros. Only string constants may be expanded using this mechanism,
not string-valued expressions. For example:
<!--l. 2401--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;macros</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;style1</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"lines</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lt</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;4</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lw</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;2"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;style2</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"points</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lt</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;3</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pt</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;5</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ps</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;2"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;range1</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:3"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;range2</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:5"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"foo"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;@range1</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;@style1,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"bar"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;@range2</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;@style2</span>
<!--l. 2408--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2411--><p class="noindent" >The line containing @ symbols is expanded on input, so that by the time it is executed the effect is identical to
having typed in full
<!--l. 2415--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"foo"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:3</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lines</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lt</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;4</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lw</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;2,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"bar"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:5</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;points</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lt</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;3</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pt</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;5</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ps</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;2</span>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 2418--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2421--><p class="noindent" >The function exists() may be useful in connection with macro evaluation. The following example checks that C can
safely be expanded as the name of a user-defined variable:
<!--l. 2426--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;C</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"pi"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;if</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(exists(C))</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;print</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;C,"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;",</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;@C</span>
<!--l. 2429--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2432--><p class="noindent" >Macro expansion does not occur inside either single or double quotes. However macro expansion does occur inside
backquotes.
<!--l. 2435--><p class="noindent" >Macro expansion is handled as the very first thing the interpreter does when looking at a new line of commands and
is only done once. Therefore, code like the following will execute correctly:
<!--l. 2440--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;A</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"c=1"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;@A</span>
<!--l. 2443--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2446--><p class="noindent" >but this line will not, since the macro is defined on the same line and will not be expanded in time
<!--l. 2450--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;A</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"c=1";</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;@A</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;#</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;will</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;not</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;expand</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;to</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;c=1</span>
<!--l. 2452--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2455--><p class="noindent" >For execution of complete commands the <span 
class="cmbx-10">evaluate </span>command may also be handy.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-57000I"></a>String variables, macros, and command line substitution</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-112"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-57001"></a>
<!--l. 2461--><p class="noindent" >The interaction of string variables, backquotes and macro substitution is somewhat complicated. Backquotes do not
block macro substitution, so
<!--l. 2465--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;filename</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"mydata.inp"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lines</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;wc</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;--lines</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;@filename</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sed</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"s/</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;.*//"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;</span>
<!--l. 2468--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2471--><p class="noindent" >results in the number of lines in mydata.inp being stored in the integer variable lines. And double quotes do not
block backquote substitution, so
<!--l. 2475--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;mycomputer</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"&#8216;uname</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-n&#8216;"</span>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 2477--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2480--><p class="noindent" >results in the string returned by the system command <span 
class="cmbx-10">uname -n </span>being stored in the string variable
mycomputer.
<!--l. 2483--><p class="noindent" >However, macro substitution is not performed inside double quotes, so you cannot define a system command as a
macro and then use both macro and backquote substitution at the same time.
<!--l. 2488--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;machine_id</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"uname</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-n"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;mycomputer</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"&#8216;@machine_id&#8216;"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;#</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;doesn&#8217;t</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;work!!</span>
<!--l. 2491--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2494--><p class="noindent" >This fails because the double quotes prevent @machine_id from being interpreted as a macro. To store a system
command as a macro and execute it later you must instead include the backquotes as part of the macro itself. This
is accomplished by defining the macro as shown below. Notice that the sprintf format nests all three types of
quotes.
<!--l. 2501--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;machine_id</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sprintf(&#8217;"&#8216;uname</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-n&#8216;"&#8217;)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;mycomputer</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;@machine_id</span>
<!--l. 2504--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-58000I"></a>Syntax</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-114"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-58001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-58002"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-58003"></a>
<!--l. 2514--><p class="noindent" >Options and any accompanying parameters are separated by spaces whereas lists and coordinates are separated by
commas. Ranges are separated by colons and enclosed in brackets [], text and file names are enclosed in quotes, and
a few miscellaneous things are enclosed in parentheses.
<!--l. 2519--><p class="noindent" >Commas are used to separate coordinates on the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set </span>commands <span 
class="cmbx-10">arrow</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">key</span>, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">label</span>; the list of variables
being fitted (the list after the <span 
class="cmbx-10">via </span>keyword on the <span 
class="cmbx-10">fit </span>command); lists of discrete contours or the loop
parameters which specify them on the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set cntrparam </span>command; the arguments of the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set </span>commands
<span 
class="cmbx-10">dgrid3d</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">dummy</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">isosamples</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">offsets</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">origin</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">samples</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">size</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">time</span>, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">view</span>; lists of tics or the loop
parameters which specify them; the offsets for titles and axis labels; parametric functions to be used to
calculate the x, y, and z coordinates on the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">replot </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>commands; and the complete
sets of keywords specifying individual plots (data sets or functions) on the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">replot </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>
commands.
<!--l. 2531--><p class="noindent" >Parentheses are used to delimit sets of explicit tics (as opposed to loop parameters) and to indicate computations in
the <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>filter of the <span 
class="cmbx-10">fit</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">replot </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>commands.
<!--l. 2535--><p class="noindent" >(Parentheses and commas are also used as usual in function notation.)
<!--l. 2537--><p class="noindent" >Square brackets are used to delimit ranges given in <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>commands.
<!--l. 2540--><p class="noindent" >Colons are used to separate extrema in <span 
class="cmbx-10">range </span>specifications (whether they are given on <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>
or <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>commands) and to separate entries in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>filter of the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">replot</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">fit</span>
commands.
<!--l. 2544--><p class="noindent" >Semicolons are used to separate commands given on a single command line.
<!--l. 2546--><p class="noindent" >Curly braces are used in the syntax for enhanced text mode and to delimit blocks in if/then/else statements. They
are also used to denote complex numbers: <span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>3,2<span 
class="cmsy-10">} </span>= 3 + 2i.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 2550--><p class="noindent" >The EEPIC, Imagen, Uniplex, LaTeX, and TPIC drivers allow a newline to be specified by <span 
class="cmsy-10">\\ </span>in a single-quoted
string or <span 
class="cmsy-10">\\\\ </span>in a double-quoted string.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-59000I"></a>Quote Marks</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-116"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-59001"></a>
<!--l. 2557--><p class="noindent" >Gnuplot uses three forms of quote marks for delimiting text strings, double-quote (ascii 34), single-quote (ascii 39),
and backquote (ascii 96).
<!--l. 2560--><p class="noindent" >Filenames may be entered with either single- or double-quotes. In this manual the command examples generally
single-quote filenames and double-quote other string tokens for clarity.
<!--l. 2564--><p class="noindent" >String constants and text strings used for labels, titles, or other plot elements may be enclosed in either
single quotes or double quotes. Further processing of the quoted text depends on the choice of quote
marks.
<!--l. 2568--><p class="noindent" >Backslash processing of special characters like <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>n (newline) and <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>345 (octal character code) is performed for
double-quoted strings. In single-quoted strings, backslashes are just ordinary characters. To get a single-quote (ascii
39) in a single-quoted string, it has to be doubled. Thus the strings <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>d<span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>s&#8217; b<span 
class="cmsy-10">\\</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>and &#8217;d<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>s&#8217; &#8217; b<span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>&#8217; are completely
equivalent.
<!--l. 2574--><p class="noindent" >Text justification is the same for each line of a multi-line string. Thus the center-justified string <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"This</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;is</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;the</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;first</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;line</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;of</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;text.\nThis</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;is</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;the</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;second</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;line."</span>
<!--l. 2579--><p class="noindent" ></pre> will produce <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
