class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;first</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;line</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;of</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;text.\nThis</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;is</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;the</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;second</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;line.</span>
<!--l. 2598--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2601--><p class="noindent" >Enhanced text processing is performed for both double-quoted text and single-quoted text, but only by terminals
supporting this mode. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">enhanced text (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-22000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">26</span><!--tex4ht:ref: enhanced text --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-59002"></a>.
<!--l. 2605--><p class="noindent" >Back-quotes are used to enclose system commands for substitution into the command line. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">substitution</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-54000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">48</span><!--tex4ht:ref: substitution --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-59003"></a>.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-60000I"></a>Time/Date data</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-118"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-60001"></a>
<!--l. 2611--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>supports the use of time and/or date information as input data. This feature is activated by the commands
<span 
class="cmbx-10">set xdata time</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">set ydata time</span>, etc.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 2615--><p class="noindent" >Internally all times and dates are converted to the number of seconds from the year 2000. The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">timefmt </span>defines the format for all inputs: data files, ranges, tics, label positions &#8212; in short, anything that accepts a
data value must receive it in this format. Since only one input format can be in force at a given time, all time/date
quantities being input at the same time must be presented in the same format. Thus if both x and y data in a file
are time/date, they must be in the same format.
<!--l. 2623--><p class="noindent" >The conversion to and from seconds assumes Universal Time (which is the same as Greenwich Standard Time).
There is no provision for changing the time zone or for daylight savings. If all your data refer to the same time zone
(and are all either daylight or standard) you don&#8217;t need to worry about these things. But if the absolute time is
crucial for your application, you&#8217;ll need to convert to UT yourself.
<!--l. 2630--><p class="noindent" >Commands like <span 
class="cmbx-10">show xrange </span>will re-interpret the integer according to <span 
class="cmbx-10">timefmt</span>. If you change <span 
class="cmbx-10">timefmt</span>, and then
<span 
class="cmbx-10">show </span>the quantity again, it will be displayed in the new <span 
class="cmbx-10">timefmt</span>. For that matter, if you give the deactivation
command (like <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xdata</span>), the quantity will be shown in its numerical form.
<!--l. 2636--><p class="noindent" >The commands <span 
class="cmbx-10">set format </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">set tics format </span>define the format that will be used for tic labels, whether or not the
specified axis is time/date.
<!--l. 2639--><p class="noindent" >If time/date information is to be plotted from a file, the <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>option <span 
class="cmti-10">must </span>be used on the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>command.
These commands simply use white space to separate columns, but white space may be embedded within the
time/date string. If you use tabs as a separator, some trial-and-error may be necessary to discover how your system
treats them.
<!--l. 2645--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">time </span>function can be used to get the current system time. This value can be converted to a date string with the
<span 
class="cmbx-10">strftime </span>function, or it can be used in conjunction with <span 
class="cmbx-10">timecolumn </span>to generate relative time/date plots. The
type of the argument determines what is returned. If the argument is an integer, <span 
class="cmbx-10">time </span>returns the current time as
an integer, in seconds from 1 Jan 2000. If the argument is real (or complex), the result is real as well. The precision
of the fractional (sub-second) part depends on your operating system. If the argument is a string,
it is assumed to be a format string, and it is passed to <span 
class="cmbx-10">strftime </span>to provide a formatted time/date
string.
<!--l. 2655--><p class="noindent" >The following example demonstrates time/date plotting.
<!--l. 2657--><p class="noindent" >Suppose the file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>data<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>contains records like
<!--l. 2660--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;03/21/95</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;10:00</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;6.02e23</span>
<!--l. 2662--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2665--><p class="noindent" >This file can be plotted by
<!--l. 2668--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xdata</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;time</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;timefmt</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"%m/%d/%y"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xrange</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;["03/21/95":"03/22/95"]</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;format</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"%m/%d"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;timefmt</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"%m/%d/%y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;%H:%M"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"data"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:3</span>
<!--l. 2675--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2678--><p class="noindent" >which will produce xtic labels that look like <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>03/21<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.
<!--l. 2680--><p class="noindent" >See <span 
class="cmbx-10">time</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">_specifiers (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-224000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">154</span><!--tex4ht:ref: time_specifiers --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-60002"></a>.
<h1 class="partHead"><span class="titlemark">Part&#x00A0;II<br /></span><a 
 id="x1-61000II"></a>Plotting styles</h1>
<!--l. 2684--><p class="noindent" >There are many plotting styles available in gnuplot. They are listed alphabetically below. The commands <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">style data </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style function </span>change the default plotting style for subsequent <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>
commands.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 2689--><p class="noindent" >You also have the option to specify the plot style explicitly as part of the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>command. If you want to
mix plot styles within a single plot, you must specify the plot style for each component.
<!--l. 2693--><p class="noindent" >Example:
<!--l. 2696--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;data&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;boxes,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sin(x)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lines</span>
<!--l. 2698--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2701--><p class="noindent" >Each plot style has its own expected set of data entries in a data file. For example by default the <span 
class="cmbx-10">lines </span>style expects
either a single column of y values (with implicit x ordering) or a pair of columns with x in the first and y in the
second. For more information on how to fine-tune how columns in a file are interpreted as plot data, see <span 
class="cmbx-10">using</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-164000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">109</span><!--tex4ht:ref: using --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-61001"></a>.
<!--l. 2707--><p class="noindent" >
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-62000II"></a>Boxerrorbars</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-121"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-62001"></a>
<!--l. 2715--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">boxerrorbars </span>style is only relevant to 2D data plotting. It is a combination of the <span 
class="cmbx-10">boxes </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">yerrorbars</span>
styles. It uses 3, 4, or 5 columns of data:
<!--l. 2720--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;3</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;columns:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ydelta</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;4</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;columns:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ydelta</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xdelta</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;#</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;boxwidth</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;!=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-2</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;4</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;columns:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ylow</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;yhigh</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;#</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;boxwidth</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;==</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-2</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;5</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;columns:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ylow</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;yhigh</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xdelta</span>
<!--l. 2725--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2728--><p class="noindent" >[r][rt][width=3in,keepaspectratio]figure&#x02D9;boxerrorbars The boxwidth will come from the fourth column if the y errors
are given as <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>ydelta<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>and the boxwidth was not previously set to -2.0 (<span 
class="cmbx-10">set boxwidth -2.0</span>) or from the fifth column
if the y errors are in the form of <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>ylow yhigh<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. The special case <span 
class="cmbx-10">boxwidth = -2.0 </span>is for four-column data
with y errors in the form <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>ylow yhigh<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. In this case the boxwidth will be calculated so that each box
touches the adjacent boxes. The width will also be calculated in cases where three-column data are
used.
<!--l. 2737--><p class="noindent" >An additional (4th, 5th or 6th) input column may be used to provide variable (per-datapoint) color information (see
<span 
class="cmbx-10">linecolor (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-42000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">41</span><!--tex4ht:ref: linecolor --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-62002"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">rgbcolor variable (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-45000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">42</span><!--tex4ht:ref: rgbcolor variable --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-62003"></a>). The error bar will be drawn in the same color as the border
of the box.
<!--l. 2741--><p class="noindent" >The box height is determined from the y error in the same way as it is for the <span 
class="cmbx-10">yerrorbars </span>style &#8212; either from
y-ydelta to y+ydelta or from ylow to yhigh, depending on how many data columns are provided. See
also
<!--l. 2745--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/mgr.html" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">errorbar demo. </span></a>
<!--l. 2748--><p class="noindent" >
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-63000II"></a>Boxes</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-123"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-63001"></a>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 2756--><p class="noindent" >[r][rt][width=3in,keepaspectratio]figure&#x02D9;boxes The <span 
class="cmbx-10">boxes </span>style is only relevant to 2D plotting. It draws a box
centered about the given x coordinate that extends from the x axis (not from the graph border) to the given y
coordinate. It uses 2 or 3 columns of basic data. Additional input columns may be used to provide information such
as variable line or fill color (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">rgbcolor variable (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-45000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">42</span><!--tex4ht:ref: rgbcolor variable --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-63002"></a>).
<!--l. 2764--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;2</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;columns:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;3</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;columns:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x_width</span>
<!--l. 2767--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2770--><p class="noindent" >The width of the box is obtained in one of three ways. If the input data has a third column, this will be used to set
the width of the box. If not, if a width has been set using the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set boxwidth </span>command, this will be used. If neither
of these is available, the width of each box will be calculated automatically so that it touches the adjacent
boxes.
<!--l. 2776--><p class="noindent" >The interior of the boxes is drawn according to the current fillstyle. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style fill (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-297000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">202</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set style fill --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-63003"></a> for details.
Alternatively a new fillstyle may be specified in the plot command.
<!--l. 2780--><p class="noindent" >For fillstyle <span 
class="cmbx-10">empty </span>the box is not filled.
<!--l. 2782--><p class="noindent" >For fillstyle <span 
class="cmbx-10">solid </span>the box is filled with a solid rectangle of the current drawing color. There is an optional
parameter <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>density<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>that controls the fill density; it runs from 0 (background color) to 1 (current drawing
color).
<!--l. 2787--><p class="noindent" >For fillstyle <span 
class="cmbx-10">pattern </span>the box is filled in the current drawing color with a pattern, if supported by the terminal
driver.
<!--l. 2790--><p class="noindent" >Examples:
<!--l. 2792--><p class="noindent" >To plot a data file with solid filled boxes with a small vertical space separating them (bargraph):
<!--l. 2796--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;boxwidth</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0.9</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;relative</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;style</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fill</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;solid</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1.0</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
