<!--l. 2949--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 2952--><p class="noindent" >The width of the rectangle can be controlled by the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set boxwidth </span>command. For backwards compatibility with
earlier gnuplot versions, when the boxwidth parameter has not been set then the width of the candlestick rectangle
is controlled by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set bars </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">width</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>.
<!--l. 2957--><p class="noindent" >Alternatively, an explicit width for each box-and-whiskers grouping may be specified in an optional 6th column of
data. The width must be given in the same units as the x coordinate.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 2961--><p class="noindent" >An additional (6th, or 7th if the 6th column is used for width data) input column may be used to
provide variable (per-datapoint) color information (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">linecolor (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-42000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">41</span><!--tex4ht:ref: linecolor --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-66002"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">rgbcolor variable</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-45000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">42</span><!--tex4ht:ref: rgbcolor variable --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-66003"></a>).
<!--l. 2965--><p class="noindent" >By default the vertical line segments have no crossbars at the top and bottom. If you want crossbars, which are
typically used for box-and-whisker plots, then add the keyword <span 
class="cmbx-10">whiskerbars </span>to the plot command. By default these
whiskerbars extend the full horizontal width of the candlestick, but you can modify this by specifying a fraction of
the full width.
<!--l. 2971--><p class="noindent" >The usual convention for financial data is that the rectangle is empty if (open <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C; </span>close) and solid fill if (close <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>
open). This is the behavior you will get if the current fillstyle is set to <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>empty<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">fillstyle (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-297000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">202</span><!--tex4ht:ref: fillstyle --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-66004"></a>. If you set
the fillstyle to solid or pattern, then this will be used for all boxes independent of open and close values. See also <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">bars (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-196000III"><span 
