<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-67000II"></a>Circles</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-131"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-67001"></a>
<!--l. 3015--><p class="noindent" >[r][rt][width=3in,keepaspectratio]figure&#x02D9;circles The <span 
class="cmbx-10">circles </span>style plots a circle with an explicit radius at each data
point. If three columns of data are present, they are interpreted as x, y, radius. The radius is always interpreted in
the units of the plot&#8217;s horizontal axis (x or x2). The scale on y and the aspect ratio of the plot are both ignored. If
only two columns are present, the radius is taken from <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style circle</span>. In this case the radius may be given in
graph or screen coordinates. By default a full circle will be drawn. It is possible to plot arc segments instead of
full circles by specifying a start and end angle in the 4th and 5th columns. An optional 4th or 6th
column can specify per-circle color. The start and end angles of the circle segments must be specified in
degrees.
