class="cmbx-10">points </span>plot with variable size points and pointstyle 7, except that the circles will
scale with the x axis range. See also <span 
class="cmbx-10">set object circle (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-258000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">179</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set object circle --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-67002"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">fillstyle (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-297000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">202</span><!--tex4ht:ref: fillstyle --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-67003"></a>.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-68000II"></a>Ellipses</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-133"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-68001"></a>
<!--l. 3070--><p class="noindent" >[r][rt][width=3in,keepaspectratio]figure&#x02D9;ellipses The <span 
class="cmbx-10">ellipses </span>style plots an ellipse at each data point. This style is
only relevant for 2D plotting. Each ellipse is described in terms of its center, major and minor diameters, and the
angle between its major diameter and the x axis.
<!--l. 3077--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;2</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;columns:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;3</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;columns:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;major_diam</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;4</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;columns:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;major_diam</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;minor_diam</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;5</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;columns:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;major_diam</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;minor_diam</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;angle</span>
<!--l. 3082--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 3085--><p class="noindent" >If only two input columns are present, they are taken as the coordinates of the centers, and the ellipses will be
drawn with the default extent (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style ellipse (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-304000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">206</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set style ellipse --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-68002"></a>). The orientation of the ellipse, which
is defined as the angle between the major diameter and the plot&#8217;s x axis, is taken from the default
ellipse style (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style ellipse (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-304000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">206</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set style ellipse --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-68003"></a>). If three input columns are provided, the third column is
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
used for both diameters. The orientation angle defaults to zero. If four columns are present, they are
interpreted as x, y, major diameter, minor diameter. Note that these are diameters, not radii. An
optional 5th column may be used to specify the orientation angle in degrees. The ellipses will also
be drawn with their default extent if either of the supplied diameters in the 3-4-5 column form is
negative.
<!--l. 3099--><p class="noindent" >In all of the above cases, optional variable color data may be given in an additional last (3th, 4th, 5th or 6th)
column. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">colorspec (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-42000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">40</span><!--tex4ht:ref: colorspec --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-68004"></a> for further information.
<!--l. 3103--><p class="noindent" >By default, the major diameter is interpreted in the units of the plot&#8217;s horizontal axis (x or x2) while the minor
diameter in that of the vertical (y or y2). This implies that if the x and y axis scales are not equal, then the
major/minor diameter ratio will no longer be correct after rotation. This behavior can be changed with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">units</span>
keyword, however.
<!--l. 3109--><p class="noindent" >There are three alternatives: if <span 
class="cmbx-10">units xy </span>is included in the plot specification, the axes will be scaled as described
above. <span 
class="cmbx-10">units xx </span>ensures that both diameters are interpreted in units of the x axis, while <span 
class="cmbx-10">units yy </span>means that both
diameters are interpreted in units of the y axis. In the latter two cases the ellipses will have the correct aspect ratio,
even if the plot is resized.
<!--l. 3116--><p class="noindent" >If <span 
class="cmbx-10">units </span>is omitted, the default setting will be used, which is equivalent to <span 
class="cmbx-10">units xy</span>. This can be redefined by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">style ellipse</span>.
<!--l. 3119--><p class="noindent" >Example (draws ellipses, cycling through the available line types):
<!--l. 3122--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;data&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2:3:4:(0):0</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ellipses</span>
<!--l. 3124--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 3127--><p class="noindent" >See also <span 
class="cmbx-10">set object ellipse (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-257000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">178</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set object ellipse --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-68005"></a>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style ellipse (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-304000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">206</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set style ellipse --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-68006"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">fillstyle (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-297000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">202</span><!--tex4ht:ref: fillstyle --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-68007"></a>.
