<!--l. 3222--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">above </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">below </span>options apply both to commands of the form <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;...</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;filledcurves</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;above</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{x1|x2|y1|y2|r}=&#x003C;val&#x003E;</span>
<!--l. 3226--><p class="noindent" ></pre> and to commands of the form <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;...</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2:3</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;filledcurves</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;below</span>
<!--l. 3232--><p class="noindent" ></pre> In either case the option limits the filled area to one side of the bounding line or curve.
<!--l. 3237--><p class="noindent" >Note: Not all terminal types support this plotting mode.
<!--l. 3239--><p class="noindent" >Zooming a filled curve drawn from a datafile may produce empty or incorrect areas because gnuplot is clipping
points and lines, and not areas.
<!--l. 3242--><p class="noindent" >If the values of <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>a<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>, <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>x<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>, <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>y<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>are out of the drawing boundary, then they are moved to the graph
boundary. Then the actually filled area in the case of option xy=<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>x<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>,<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>y<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>will depend on xrange and
yrange.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-71000II"></a>Financebars</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-139"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-71001"></a>
<!--l. 3253--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">financebars </span>style is only relevant for 2D data plotting of financial data. It requires 1 x coordinate (usually a
date) and 4 y values (prices).
<!--l. 3257--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;5</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;columns:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;date</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;open</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;low</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;high</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;close</span>
<!--l. 3259--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 3262--><p class="noindent" >An additional (6th) input column may be used to provide variable (per-record) color information (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">linecolor</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-42000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">41</span><!--tex4ht:ref: linecolor --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-71002"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">rgbcolor variable (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-45000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">42</span><!--tex4ht:ref: rgbcolor variable --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-71003"></a>).
<!--l. 3265--><p class="noindent" >[r][rt][width=3in,keepaspectratio]figure&#x02D9;financebars The symbol is a vertical line segment, located horizontally at the
x coordinate and limited vertically by the high and low prices. A horizontal tic on the left marks the opening price
and one on the right marks the closing price. The length of these tics may be changed by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set bars</span>. The symbol will
be unchanged if the high and low prices are interchanged. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set bars (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-196000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">133</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set bars --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-71004"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">candlesticks (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-66000II"><span 
class="cmbx-10">57</span><!--tex4ht:ref: candlesticks --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-71005"></a>, and
also the
<!--l. 3272--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/finance.html" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">finance demo. </span></a>
<!--l. 3275--><p class="noindent" >
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-72000II"></a>Fsteps</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-141"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-72001"></a>
<!--l. 3283--><p class="noindent" >[r][rt][width=3in,keepaspectratio]figure&#x02D9;fsteps The <span 
class="cmbx-10">fsteps </span>style is only relevant to 2D plotting. It connects
consecutive points with two line segments: the first from (x1,y1) to (x1,y2) and the second from (x1,y2) to (x2,y2).
The input column requires are the same as for plot styles <span 
class="cmbx-10">lines </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">points</span>. The difference between <span 
class="cmbx-10">fsteps </span>and
<span 
class="cmbx-10">steps </span>is that <span 
class="cmbx-10">fsteps </span>traces first the change in y and then the change in x. <span 
class="cmbx-10">steps </span>traces first the change in x and
then the change in y.
<!--l. 3291--><p class="noindent" >See also
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 3292--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/steps.html" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">steps demo. </span></a>
<!--l. 3295--><p class="noindent" >
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-73000II"></a>Fillsteps</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-143"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-73001"></a>
<!--l. 3302--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">fillsteps </span>style is exactly like <span 
class="cmbx-10">steps </span>except that the area between the curve and y=0 is filled in the current fill
style. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">steps (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-87000II"><span 
class="cmbx-10">71</span><!--tex4ht:ref: steps --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-73002"></a>.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-74000II"></a>Histeps</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-145"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-74001"></a>
<!--l. 3312--><p class="noindent" >[r][rt][width=3in,keepaspectratio]figure&#x02D9;histeps The <span 
class="cmbx-10">histeps </span>style is only relevant to 2D plotting. It is intended for
plotting histograms. Y-values are assumed to be centered at the x-values; the point at x1 is represented as a
horizontal line from ((x0+x1)/2,y1) to ((x1+x2)/2,y1). The lines representing the end points are extended so that
the step is centered on at x. Adjacent points are connected by a vertical line at their average x, that is, from
((x1+x2)/2,y1) to ((x1+x2)/2,y2). The input column requires are the same as for plot styles <span 
class="cmbx-10">lines </span>and
<span 
class="cmbx-10">points</span>.
<!--l. 3321--><p class="noindent" >If <span 
class="cmbx-10">autoscale </span>is in effect, it selects the xrange from the data rather than the steps, so the end points will appear only
half as wide as the others. See also
<!--l. 3324--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/steps.html" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">steps demo. </span></a>
<!--l. 3328--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">histeps </span>is only a plotting style; <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>does not have the ability to create bins and determine their population
from some data set.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-75000II"></a>Histograms</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-147"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-75001"></a>
<!--l. 3338--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">histograms </span>style is only relevant to 2D plotting. It produces a bar chart from a sequence of parallel data
columns. Each element of the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command must specify a single input data source (e.g. one column of the input
file), possibly with associated tic values or key titles. Four styles of histogram layout are currently
supported.
<!--l. 3345--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;style</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;histogram</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;clustered</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{gap</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;gapsize&#x003E;}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
