class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ymin</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;to</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ymax</span>
<!--l. 3377--><p class="noindent" ></pre> The appearance of the error bars is controlled by the current value of <span 
class="cmbx-10">set bars </span>and by the optional <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>linewidth<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>
specification.
<!--l. 3382--><p class="noindent" >Two styles of stacked histogram are supported, chosen by the command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style histogram</span>
<span 
class="cmbsy-10">{</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">rowstacked</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">|</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">columnstacked</span><span 
class="cmbsy-10">}</span>. In these styles the data values from the selected columns are collected into stacks
of boxes. Positive values stack upwards from y=0; negative values stack downwards. Mixed positive and
negative values will produce both an upward stack and a downward stack. The default stacking mode is
<span 
class="cmbx-10">rowstacked</span>.
<!--l. 3389--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">rowstacked </span>style places a box resting on the x-axis for each data value in the first selected column; the first
data value results in a box a x=1, the second at x=2, and so on. Boxes corresponding to the second and subsequent
data columns are layered on top of these, resulting in a stack of boxes at x=1 representing the first data value from
each column, a stack of boxes at x=2 representing the second data value from each column, and so on. All
boxes derived from any one column are given the same fill color and/or pattern (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style fill</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-297000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">202</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set style fill --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-75003"></a>).
<!--l. 3398--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">columnstacked </span>style is similar, except that each stack of boxes is built up from a single data column.
Each data value from the first specified column yields a box in the stack at x=1, each data value from
the second specified column yields a box in the stack at x=2, and so on. In this style the color of
each box is taken from the row number, rather than the column number, of the corresponding data
field.
<!--l. 3405--><p class="noindent" >Box widths may be modified using the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set boxwidth </span>command. Box fill styles may be set using the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style fill</span>
command.
<!--l. 3408--><p class="noindent" >Histograms always use the x1 axis, but may use either y1 or y2. If a plot contains both histograms and other plot
styles, the non-histogram plot elements may use either the x1 or the x2 axis.
<!--l. 3412--><p class="noindent" >Examples: [r][rt][width=3in,keepaspectratio]figure&#x02D9;histclust Suppose that the input file contains data
values in columns 2, 4, 6, ... and error estimates in columns 3, 5, 7, ... This example plots the values in
columns 2 and 4 as a histogram of clustered boxes (the default style). Because we use iteration in
the plot command, any number of data columns can be handled in a single command. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">iteration</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-122000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">90</span><!--tex4ht:ref: iteration --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-75004"></a>.
<!--l. 3421--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
