<!--l. 3635--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">image </span>style handles input pixels containing a grayscale or color palette value. Thus 2D plots (<span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command)
require 3 columns of data (x,y,value), while 3D plots (<span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>command) require 4 columns of data
(x,y,z,value).
<!--l. 3639--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">rgbimage </span>style handles input pixels that are described by three separate values for the red, green, and blue
components. Thus 5D data (x,y,r,g,b) is needed for <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and 6D data (x,y,z,r,g,b) for <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>. The individual red,
green, and blue components are assumed to lie in the range [0:255].
<!--l. 3644--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">rgbalpha </span>style handles input pixels that contain alpha channel (transparency) information in
addition to the red, green, and blue components. Thus 6D data (x,y,r,g,b,a) is needed for <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and
7D data (x,y,z,r,g,b,a) for <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>. The r, g, b, and alpha components are assumed to lie in the range
[0:255].
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-79000II"></a>Transparency</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-155"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-79001"></a>
<!--l. 3655--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">rgbalpha </span>plotting style assumes that each pixel of input data contains an alpha value in the range [0:255]. A
pixel with alpha = 0 is purely transparent and does not alter the underlying contents of the plot. A pixel with alpha
= 255 is purely opaque. All terminal types can handle these two extreme cases. A pixel with 0 <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C; </span>alpha <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C; </span>255 is
partially transparent. Only a few terminal types can handle this correctly; other terminals will approximate this by
treating alpha as being either 0 or 255.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-80000II"></a>Image failsafe</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-157"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-80001"></a>
<!--l. 3671--><p class="noindent" >Some terminal drivers provide code to optimize rendering of image data within a rectangular 2D area. However this
code is known to be imperfect. This optimized code may be disabled by using the keyword <span 
class="cmbx-10">failsafe</span>.
E.g.
<!--l. 3676--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;data&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;image</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;failsafe</span>
<!--l. 3678--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
