 id="dx1-84003"></a>
<!--l. 3803--><p class="noindent" >[r][rt][width=3in,keepaspectratio]figure&#x02D9;linespoints The <span 
class="cmbx-10">linespoints </span>style connects adjacent points with straight line
segments and then goes back to draw a small symbol at each point. The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set pointsize </span>may be used to
change the default size of the points. 1 or 2 columns of basic input data are required in 2D plots; 1 or 3 columns are
required if 3D plots. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">style lines (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-83000II"><span 
class="cmbx-10">70</span><!--tex4ht:ref: style lines --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-84004"></a>. Additional input columns may be used to provide information such as
variable point size or line color.
<!--l. 3811--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">pointinterval </span>(short form <span 
class="cmbx-10">pi</span>) property of the linetype can be used to control whether or not every point in the
plot is given a symbol. For example, &#8217;with lp pi 3&#8217; will draw line segments through every data point, but will
only place a symbol on every 3rd point. A negative value for <span 
class="cmbx-10">pointinterval </span>will erase the portion of
line segment that passes underneath the symbol. The size of the erased portion is controlled by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">pointintervalbox</span>.
<!--l. 3818--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">linespoints </span>may be abbreviated <span 
class="cmbx-10">lp</span>.
