<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-87000II"></a>Steps</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-171"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-87001"></a>
<!--l. 3852--><p class="noindent" >[r][rt][width=3in,keepaspectratio]figure&#x02D9;steps The <span 
class="cmbx-10">steps </span>style is only relevant to 2D plotting. It connects consecutive
points with two line segments: the first from (x1,y1) to (x2,y1) and the second from (x2,y1) to (x2,y2). The input
column requires are the same as for plot styles <span 
class="cmbx-10">lines </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">points</span>. The difference between <span 
class="cmbx-10">fsteps </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">steps </span>is that
<span 
class="cmbx-10">fsteps </span>traces first the change in y and then the change in x. <span 
class="cmbx-10">steps </span>traces first the change in x and
then the change in y. To fill the area between the curve and the baseline at y=0, use <span 
class="cmbx-10">fillsteps</span>. See
also
<!--l. 3861--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/steps.html" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">steps demo. </span></a>
