<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-105000III"></a>Exit</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-206"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-105001"></a>
<!--l. 4375--><p class="noindent" >The commands <span 
class="cmbx-10">exit </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">quit</span>, as well as the END-OF-FILE character (usually Ctrl-D) terminate input from the
current input stream: terminal session, pipe, and file input (pipe).
<!--l. 4379--><p class="noindent" >If input streams are nested (inherited <span 
class="cmbx-10">load </span>scripts), then reading will continue in the parent stream. When the top
level stream is closed, the program itself will exit.
<!--l. 4383--><p class="noindent" >The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">exit gnuplot </span>will immediately and unconditionally cause gnuplot to exit even if the input
stream is multiply nested. In this case any open output files may not be completed cleanly. Example of
use:
<!--l. 4388--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;bind</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"ctrl-x"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;output;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;exit</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;gnuplot"</span>
<!--l. 4390--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 4393--><p class="noindent" >See help for <span 
class="cmbx-10">batch/interactive (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-16000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">22</span><!--tex4ht:ref: batch/interactive --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-105002"></a> for more details.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-106000III"></a>Fit</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-208"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-106001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-106002"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-106003"></a>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 4403--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">fit </span>command can fit a user-supplied expression to a set of data points (x,z) or (x,y,z), using an
implementation of the nonlinear least-squares (NLLS) Marquardt-Levenberg algorithm. Any user-defined variable
occurring in the expression may serve as a fit parameter, but the return type of the expression must be
real.
<!--l. 4409--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fit</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;ranges&#x003E;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;expression&#x003E;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;&#x003C;datafile&#x003E;&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{datafile-modifiers}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;via</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;&#x003C;parameter</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;file&#x003E;&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;var1&#x003E;{,&#x003C;var2&#x003E;,...}</span>
<!--l. 4415--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 4418--><p class="noindent" >Ranges may be specified to temporarily limit the data which is to be fitted; any out-of-range data points are
ignored. The syntax is <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[{dummy_variable=}{&#x003C;min&#x003E;}{:&#x003C;max&#x003E;}],</span>
<!--l. 4423--><p class="noindent" ></pre> analogous to <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>; see <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot ranges (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-177000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">116</span><!--tex4ht:ref: plot ranges --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-106004"></a>.
<!--l. 4427--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>expression<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is any valid <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>expression, although it is usual to use a previously user-defined function of the
form f(x) or f(x,y).
<!--l. 4430--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>datafile<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is treated as in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command. All the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot datafile </span>modifiers (<span 
class="cmbx-10">using</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">every</span>,...) except <span 
class="cmbx-10">smooth</span>
and the deprecated <span 
class="cmbx-10">thru </span>are applicable to <span 
class="cmbx-10">fit</span>. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot datafile (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-148000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">99</span><!--tex4ht:ref: plot datafile --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-106005"></a>.
<!--l. 4434--><p class="noindent" >The default data formats for fitting functions with a single independent variable, z=f(x), are z or x:z. That is, if
there is only a single column then it is the dependent variable and the line numbers is the independent
variable. If there are two columns, the first is the independent variable and the second is the dependent
variable.
<!--l. 4441--><p class="noindent" >Those formats can be changed with the datafile <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>qualifier, for example to take the z value from a different
column or to calculate it from several columns. A third <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>qualifier (a column number or an expression), if
present, is interpreted as the standard deviation of the corresponding z value and is used to compute a weight for
the datum, 1/s**2. Otherwise, all data points are weighted equally, with a weight of one. Note that if you don&#8217;t
specify a <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>option at all, no z standard deviations are read from the datafile even if it does have a third column,
so you&#8217;ll always get unit weights.
<!--l. 4452--><p class="noindent" >To fit a function with two independent variables, z=f(x,y), the required format is <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>with four items,
x:y:z:s. The complete format must be given &#8212; no default columns are assumed for a missing token.
Weights for each data point are evaluated from &#8217;s&#8217; as above. If error estimates are not available, a
constant value can be specified as a constant expression (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot datafile using (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-164000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">109</span><!--tex4ht:ref: plot datafile using --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-106006"></a>), e.g., <span 
class="cmbx-10">using</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">1:2:3:(1)</span>.
<!--l. 4459--><p class="noindent" >The fit function may have up to five independent variables. There must be two more <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>qualifiers than there are
independent variables, unless there is only one variable. The allowed formats, and the default dummy variable
names, are as follows:
<!--l. 4465--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;z</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x:z</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x:z:s</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x:y:z:s</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x:y:t:z:s</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x:y:t:u:z:s</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x:y:t:u:v:z:s</span>
<!--l. 4473--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 4476--><p class="noindent" >The dummy variable names may be changed with ranges as noted above. The first range corresponds to the first
<span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>spec, etc. A range may also be given for z (the dependent variable), but that name cannot be
changed.
<!--l. 4481--><p class="noindent" >Multiple datasets may be simultaneously fit with functions of one independent variable by making y a
&#8217;pseudo-variable&#8217;, e.g., the dataline number, and fitting as two independent variables. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">fit multi-branch</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-115000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">86</span><!--tex4ht:ref: fit multi-branch --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-106007"></a>.
