<!--l. 5073--><p class="noindent" >This version of gnuplot supports block-structured if/else statements. If the keyword <span 
class="cmbx-10">if </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">else </span>is immediately
followed by an opening <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, then conditional execution applies to all statements, possibly on multiple input lines,
until a matching <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>terminates the block. If commands may be nested.
<!--l. 5078--><p class="noindent" >The old single-line if/else syntax is still supported, but can not be mixed with the new block-structured syntax. See
<span 
class="cmbx-10">if-old (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-121000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">89</span><!--tex4ht:ref: if-old --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-120002"></a>.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-121000III"></a>If-old</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-238"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-121001"></a>
<!--l. 5085--><p class="noindent" >Through gnuplot version 4.4, the scope of the if/else commands was limited to a single input line. This has been
replaced by allowing a multi-line clause to be enclosed in curly brackets. The old syntax is still honored by itself but
cannot be used inside a bracketed clause.
<!--l. 5090--><p class="noindent" >If no opening <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>follows the <span 
class="cmbx-10">if </span>keyword, the command(s) in <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>command-line<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>will be executed if <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>condition<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is
true (non-zero) or skipped if <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>condition<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is false (zero). Either case will consume commands on the input line until
the end of the line or an occurrence of <span 
class="cmbx-10">else</span>. Note that use of <span 
class="cmbx-10">; </span>to allow multiple commands on the same line will <span 
class="cmti-10">not</span>
end the conditionalized commands.
