<!--l. 5169--><p class="noindent" >
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-123000III"></a>Load</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-242"></a>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<a 
 id="dx1-123001"></a>
<!--l. 5174--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">load </span>command executes each line of the specified input file as if it had been typed in interactively. Files created
by the <span 
class="cmbx-10">save </span>command can later be <span 
class="cmbx-10">load</span>ed. Any text file containing valid commands can be created and then
executed by the <span 
class="cmbx-10">load </span>command. Files being <span 
class="cmbx-10">load</span>ed may themselves contain <span 
class="cmbx-10">load </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">call </span>commands. See
<span 
class="cmbx-10">comments (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-19000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">24</span><!--tex4ht:ref: comments --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-123002"></a> for information about comments in commands. To <span 
class="cmbx-10">load </span>with arguments, see <span 
class="cmbx-10">call</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-101000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">77</span><!--tex4ht:ref: call --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-123003"></a>.
<!--l. 5181--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;load</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"&#x003C;input-file&#x003E;"</span>
<!--l. 5185--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 5188--><p class="noindent" >The name of the input file must be enclosed in quotes.
<!--l. 5190--><p class="noindent" >The special filename <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>-<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>may be used to <span 
class="cmbx-10">load </span>commands from standard input. This allows a <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>command file
to accept some commands from standard input. Please see help for <span 
class="cmbx-10">batch/interactive (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-16000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">22</span><!--tex4ht:ref: batch/interactive --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-123004"></a> for more
details.
<!--l. 5194--><p class="noindent" >On some systems which support a popen function (Unix), the load file can be read from a pipe by starting the file
name with a &#8217;<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>&#8217;.
<!--l. 5197--><p class="noindent" >Examples: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;load</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;work.gnu&#8217;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;load</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"func.dat"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;load</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;loadfile_generator.sh"</span>
<!--l. 5203--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 5206--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">load </span>command is performed implicitly on any file names given as arguments to <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot</span>. These are loaded in
the order specified, and then <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>exits.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-124000III"></a>Lower</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-244"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-124001"></a>
<!--l. 5214--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lower</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{plot_window_nb}</span>
<!--l. 5218--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 5221--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">lower </span>command lowers (opposite to <span 
class="cmbx-10">raise</span>) plot window(s) associated with the interactive terminal of your
gnuplot session, i.e. <span 
class="cmbx-10">pm</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">win</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">wxt </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">x11</span>. It puts the plot window to bottom in the z-order windows stack of the
window manager of your desktop.
<!--l. 5226--><p class="noindent" >As <span 
class="cmbx-10">x11 </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">wxt </span>support multiple plot windows, then by default they lower these windows in descending order of
most recently created on top to the least recently created on bottom. If a plot number is supplied as an optional
parameter, only the associated plot window will be lowered if it exists.
<!--l. 5231--><p class="noindent" >The optional parameter is ignored for single plot-window terminals, i.e. <span 
class="cmbx-10">pm </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">win</span>.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-125000III"></a>Pause</h3>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<a 
 id="Q1-1-246"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-125001"></a>
<!--l. 5239--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">pause </span>command displays any text associated with the command and then waits a specified amount
of time or until the carriage return is pressed. <span 
class="cmbx-10">pause </span>is especially useful in conjunction with <span 
class="cmbx-10">load</span>
files.
<!--l. 5243--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pause</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;time&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{"&#x003C;string&#x003E;"}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pause</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;mouse</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;endcondition&#x003E;}{,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;endcondition&#x003E;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{"&#x003C;string&#x003E;"}</span>
<!--l. 5248--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 5251--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>time<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>may be any constant or expression. Choosing -1 will wait until a carriage return is hit, zero (0) won&#8217;t pause
at all, and a positive number will wait the specified number of seconds. The time is rounded to an integer number of
seconds if subsecond time resolution is not supported by the given platform. <span 
class="cmbx-10">pause 0 </span>is synonymous with
<span 
class="cmbx-10">print</span>.
<!--l. 5257--><p class="noindent" >If the current terminal supports <span 
class="cmbx-10">mousing</span>, then <span 
class="cmbx-10">pause mouse </span>will terminate on either a mouse click or
on ctrl-C. For all other terminals, or if mousing is not active, <span 
class="cmbx-10">pause mouse </span>is equivalent to <span 
class="cmbx-10">pause</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">-1</span>.
<!--l. 5261--><p class="noindent" >If one or more end conditions are given after <span 
class="cmbx-10">pause mouse</span>, then any one of the conditions will terminate the pause.
The possible end conditions are <span 
class="cmbx-10">keypress</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">button1</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">button2</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">button3</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">close</span>, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">any</span>. If the pause
terminates on a keypress, then the ascii value of the key pressed is returned in MOUSE_KEY. The
character itself is returned as a one character string in MOUSE_CHAR. Hotkeys (bind command) are
disabled if keypress is one of the end conditions. Zooming is disabled if button3 is one of the end
conditions.
<!--l. 5270--><p class="noindent" >In all cases the coordinates of the mouse are returned in variables MOUSE_X, MOUSE_Y, MOUSE_X2,
MOUSE_Y2. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">mouse variables (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-50000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">45</span><!--tex4ht:ref: mouse variables --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-125002"></a>.
<!--l. 5273--><p class="noindent" >Note: Since <span 
class="cmbx-10">pause </span>communicates with the operating system rather than the graphics, it may behave differently with
different device drivers (depending upon how text and graphics are mixed).
