<!--l. 5311--><p class="noindent" >
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-126000III"></a>Plot</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-248"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-126001"></a>
<!--l. 5316--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>is the primary command for drawing plots with <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot</span>. It creates plots of functions and data in many, many
ways. <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>is used to draw 2D functions and data; <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>draws 2D projections of 3D surfaces and data. <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and
<span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>offer many features in common; see <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-370000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">231</span><!--tex4ht:ref: splot --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-126002"></a> for differences. Note specifically that although the
<span 
class="cmbx-10">binary </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">binary list</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>variation does work for both <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>, there are small differences between
them.
<!--l. 5323--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;ranges&#x003E;}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
