<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-127000III"></a>Axes</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-250"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-127001"></a>
<!--l. 5361--><p class="noindent" >There are four possible sets of axes available; the keyword <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>axes<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is used to select the axes for which a particular
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
line should be scaled. <span 
class="cmbx-10">x1y1 </span>refers to the axes on the bottom and left; <span 
class="cmbx-10">x2y2 </span>to those on the top and right; <span 
class="cmbx-10">x1y2 </span>to
those on the bottom and right; and <span 
class="cmbx-10">x2y1 </span>to those on the top and left. Ranges specified on the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command apply
only to the first set of axes (bottom left).
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-128000III"></a>Binary</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-252"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-128001"></a>
<!--l. 5374--><p class="noindent" >BINARY DATA FILES:
<!--l. 5376--><p class="noindent" >Some earlier versions of <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>automatically detected binary data files. It is now necessary to provide the
keyword <span 
class="cmbx-10">binary </span>after the filename. Adequate details of the file format must be given on the command line or
extracted from the file itself for a supported binary <span 
class="cmbx-10">filetype</span>. In particular, there are two structures for binary files,
binary matrix format and binary general format.
<!--l. 5383--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">binary matrix </span>format contains a two dimensional array of 32 bit IEEE float values with an additional column
and row of coordinate values. As with ASCII matrix, in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>list, enumeration of the coordinate row
constitutes column 1, enumeration of the coordinate column constitutes column 2, and the array of values
constitutes column 3.
<!--l. 5389--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">binary general </span>format contains an arbitrary number of columns for which information must be specified at
the command line. For example, <span 
class="cmbx-10">array</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">record</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">format </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>can indicate the size, format and dimension of
data. There are a variety of useful commands for skipping file headers and changing endianess. There are a set of
commands for positioning and translating data since often coordinates are not part of the file when uniform
sampling is inherent in the data. Different from matrix binary or ASCII, general binary does not treat the generated
columns as 1, 2 or 3 in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>list. Rather, column 1 begins with column 1 of the file, or as specified in the
<span 
class="cmbx-10">format </span>list.
<!--l. 5400--><p class="noindent" >There are global default settings for the various binary options which may be set using the same syntax as the
options when used as part of the <span 
class="cmbx-10">(s)plot </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">filename</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span><span 
class="cmbx-10">binary ... </span>command. This syntax is <span 
class="cmbx-10">set datafile binary</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">...</span>. The general rule is that common command-line specified parameters override file-extracted parameters which
override default parameters.
<!--l. 5406--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Binary matrix </span>is the default binary format when no keywords specific to <span 
class="cmbx-10">binary general </span>are given, i.e., <span 
class="cmbx-10">array</span>,
<span 
class="cmbx-10">record</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">format</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">filetype</span>.
<!--l. 5409--><p class="noindent" >General binary data can be entered at the command line via the special file name &#8217;-&#8217;. However, this is intended for
use through a pipe where programs can exchange binary data, not for keyboards. There is no <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>end of record<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>
character for binary data. Gnuplot continues reading from a pipe until it has read the number of points
declared in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">array </span>qualifier. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">binary matrix (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-372000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">232</span><!--tex4ht:ref: binary matrix --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-128002"></a> or <span 
class="cmbx-10">binary general (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-129000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">94</span><!--tex4ht:ref: binary general --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-128003"></a> for more
details.
<!--l. 5416--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">index </span>keyword is not supported, since the file format allows only one surface per file. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">every </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">using</span>
filters are supported. <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>operates as if the data were read in the above triplet form.
<!--l. 5419--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/binary.html" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">Binary File Splot Demo. </span></a>
<!--l. 5422--><p class="noindent" >
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-129000III"></a>General</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-254"></a>
<!--l. 5431--><p class="noindent" >General binary data in which format information is not necessarily part of the file can be read by giving further
details about the file format at the command line. Although the syntax is slightly arcane to the casual user, general
binary is particularly useful for application programs using gnuplot and sending large amounts of
data.
<!--l. 5437--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;&#x003C;file_name&#x003E;&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{binary</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;binary</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;list&#x003E;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;...</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;splot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;&#x003C;file_name&#x003E;&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{binary</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;binary</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;list&#x003E;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;...</span>
<!--l. 5442--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 5445--><p class="noindent" >General binary format is activated by keywords in <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>binary list<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>pertaining to information about file structure, i.e.,
<span 
class="cmbx-10">array</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">record</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">format </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">filetype</span>. Otherwise, matrix binary format is assumed. (See <span 
class="cmbx-10">binary matrix (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-372000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">232</span><!--tex4ht:ref: binary matrix --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-129001"></a>
for more details.)
<!--l. 5450--><p class="noindent" >There are some standard file types that may be read for which details about the binary format may be extracted
automatically. (Type <span 
class="cmbx-10">show datafile binary </span>at the command line for a list.) Otherwise, details must be specified at
the command line or set in the defaults. Keywords are described below.
<!--l. 5456--><p class="noindent" >The keyword <span 
class="cmbx-10">filetype </span>in <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>binary list<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>controls the routine used to read the file, i.e., the format of the data. For a
list of the supported file types, type <span 
class="cmbx-10">show datafile binary filetypes</span>. If no file type is given, the rule is that
traditional gnuplot binary is assumed for <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>if the <span 
class="cmbx-10">binary </span>keyword stands alone. In all other circumstances, for
<span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>or when one of the <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>binary list<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>keywords appears, a raw binary file is assumed whereby the keywords specify
the binary format.
<!--l. 5464--><p class="noindent" >General binary data files fall into two basic classes, and some files may be of both classes depending upon how they
are treated. There is that class for which uniform sampling is assumed and point coordinates must be generated.
This is the class for which full control via the <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>binary list<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>keywords applies. For this class, the settings precedence
is that command line parameters override in-file parameters, which override default settings. The other class is that
set of files for which coordinate information is contained within the file or there is possibly a non-uniform sampling
such as gnuplot binary.
<!--l. 5474--><p class="noindent" >Other than for the unique data files such as gnuplot binary, one should think of binary data as conceptually the
same as ASCII data. Each point has columns of information which are selected via the <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">using list</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>associated
with <span 
class="cmbx-10">using</span>. When no <span 
class="cmbx-10">format </span>string is specified, gnuplot will retrieve a number of binary variables equal to the
largest column given in the <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">using list</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. For example, <span 
class="cmbx-10">using 1:3 </span>will result in three columns being read,
of which the second will be ignored. There are default using lists based upon the typical number of
parameters associated with a certain plot type. For example, <span 
class="cmbx-10">with image </span>has a default of <span 
class="cmbx-10">using 1</span>, while
<span 
class="cmbx-10">with rgbimage </span>has a default of <span 
class="cmbx-10">using 1:2:3</span>. Note that the special characters for <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>representing
point/line/index generally should not be used for binary data. There are keywords in <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>binary list<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>that control
this.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-130000III"></a>Array</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-256"></a>
<!--l. 5490--><p class="noindent" >Describes the sampling array dimensions associated with the binary file. The coordinates will be generated by
gnuplot. A number must be specified for each dimension of the array. For example, <span 
class="cmbx-10">array=(10,20) </span>means the
underlying sampling structure is two-dimensional with 10 points along the first (x) dimension and 20 points along
the second (y) dimension. A negative number indicates that data should be read until the end of file. If there is only
one dimension, the parentheses may be omitted. A colon can be used to separate the dimensions for
multiple records. For example, <span 
class="cmbx-10">array=25:35 </span>indicates there are two one-dimensional records in the file.
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Note:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Gnuplot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;version</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;4.2</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;used</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;the</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;syntax</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;array=128x128</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;rather</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;than</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;array=(128,128).</span><span 
