<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-131000III"></a>Record</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-258"></a>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 5511--><p class="noindent" >This keyword serves the same function as <span 
class="cmbx-10">array</span>, having the same syntax. However, <span 
class="cmbx-10">record </span>causes gnuplot to not
generate coordinate information. This is for the case where such information may be included in one of the columns
of the binary data file.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-132000III"></a>Skip</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-260"></a>
<!--l. 5518--><p class="noindent" >This keyword allows you to skip sections of a binary file. For instance, if the file contains a 1024 byte header before
the start of the data region you would probably want to use <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;&#x003C;file_name&#x003E;&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;binary</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;skip=1024</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;...</span>
<!--l. 5524--><p class="noindent" ></pre> If there are multiple records in the file, you may specify a leading offset for each. For example, to skip 512 bytes
before the 1st record and 256 bytes before the second and third records <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;&#x003C;file_name&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;binary</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;record=356:356:356</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;skip=512:256:256</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;...</span>
<!--l. 5532--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-133000III"></a>Format</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-262"></a>
<!--l. 5537--><p class="noindent" >The default binary format is a float. For more flexibility, the format can include details about variable sizes. For
example, <span 
class="cmbx-10">format=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">%uchar%int%float</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>associates an unsigned character with the first using column, an int
with the second column and a float with the third column. If the number of size specifications is less
than the greatest column number, the size is implicitly taken to be similar to the last given variable
size.
<!--l. 5544--><p class="noindent" >Furthermore, similar to the <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>specification, the format can include discarded columns via the <span 
class="cmbx-10">* </span>character
and have implicit repetition via a numerical repeat-field. For example, <span 
class="cmbx-10">format=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">%*2int%3float</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>
causes gnuplot to discard two ints before reading three floats. To list variable sizes, type <span 
class="cmbx-10">show datafile</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">binary datasizes</span>. There are a group of names that are machine dependent along with their sizes in
bytes for the particular compilation. There is also a group of names which attempt to be machine
independent.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
