<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-135000III"></a>Filetype</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-266"></a>
<!--l. 5574--><p class="noindent" >For some standard binary file formats gnuplot can extract all the necessary information from the file in question. As
an example, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>format=edf<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>will read ESRF Header File format files. For a list of the currently supported file formats,
type <span 
class="cmbx-10">show datafile binary filetypes</span>.
<!--l. 5579--><p class="noindent" >There is a special file type called <span 
class="cmbx-10">auto </span>for which gnuplot will check if the binary file&#8217;s extension is a quasi-standard
extension for a supported format.
<!--l. 5582--><p class="noindent" >Command line keywords may be used to override settings extracted from the file. The settings from the file override
any defaults. (See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set datafile binary (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-214000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">146</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set datafile binary --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-135001"></a> for details.)
<!--l. 5585--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-136000III"></a>Avs</span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-268"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-136001"></a>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">avs </span>is one of the automatically recognized binary file types for images. AVS is an extremely simple format, suitable
mostly for streaming between applications. It consists of 2 longs (xwidth, ywidth) followed by a stream of pixels,
each with four bytes of information alpha/red/green/blue.
<!--l. 5595--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-137000III"></a>Edf</span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-270"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-137001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-137002"></a>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">edf </span>is one of the automatically recognized binary file types for images. EDF stands for ESRF Data Format, and it
supports both edf and ehf formats (the latter means ESRF Header Format). More information on specifications can
be found at
<!--l. 5610--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;http://www.edfplus.info/specs</span>
<!--l. 5612--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 5614--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-138000III"></a>Png</span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-272"></a>
If gnuplot was configured to use the libgd library for png/gif/jpeg output, then it can also be used to read these
same image types as binary files. You can use an explicit command <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;file.png&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;binary</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;filetype=png</span>
<!--l. 5628--><p class="noindent" ></pre> Or the file type will be recognized automatically from the extension if you have previously requested
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;datafile</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;binary</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;filetype=auto</span>
<!--l. 5635--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-139000III"></a>Keywords</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-274"></a>
<!--l. 5640--><p class="noindent" >The following keywords apply only when generating coordinates from binary data files. That is, the control mapping
the individual elements of a binary array, matrix, or image to specific x/y/z positions.
<!--l. 5643--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-140000III"></a>Scan</span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-276"></a>
A great deal of confusion can arise concerning the relationship between how gnuplot scans a binary file and the
dimensions seen on the plot. To lessen the confusion, conceptually think of gnuplot <span 
class="cmti-10">always </span>scanning the binary file
point/line/plane or fast/medium/slow. Then this keyword is used to tell gnuplot how to map this scanning
convention to the Cartesian convention shown in plots, i.e., x/y/z. The qualifier for scan is a two or three letter code
representing where point is assigned (first letter), line is assigned (second letter), and plane is assigned
(third letter). For example, <span 
class="cmbx-10">scan=yx </span>means the fastest, point-by-point, increment should be mapped
along the Cartesian y dimension and the middle, line-by-line, increment should be mapped along the x
dimension.
<!--l. 5658--><p class="noindent" >When the plotting mode is <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>, the qualifier code can include the two letters x and y. For <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>, it can include the
three letters x, y and z.
<!--l. 5661--><p class="noindent" >There is nothing restricting the inherent mapping from point/line/plane to apply only to Cartesian coordinates. For
this reason there are cylindrical coordinate synonyms for the qualifier codes where t (theta), r and z are analogous
to the x, y and z of Cartesian coordinates.
<!--l. 5665--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-141000III"></a>Transpose</span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-278"></a>
Shorthand notation for <span 
class="cmbx-10">scan=yx </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">scan=yxz</span>.
<!--l. 5669--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-142000III"></a>Dx, dy, dz</span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-280"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-142001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-142002"></a>
When gnuplot generates coordinates, it uses the spacing described by these keywords. For example <span 
class="cmbx-10">dx=10 dy=20</span>
would mean space samples along the x dimension by 10 and space samples along the y dimension by 20. <span 
class="cmbx-10">dy </span>cannot
appear if <span 
class="cmbx-10">dx </span>does not appear. Similarly, <span 
class="cmbx-10">dz </span>cannot appear if <span 
class="cmbx-10">dy </span>does not appear. If the underlying dimensions are
greater than the keywords specified, the spacing of the highest dimension given is extended to the other dimensions.
For example, if an image is being read from a file and only <span 
class="cmbx-10">dx=3.5 </span>is given gnuplot uses a delta x and delta y of
3.5.
<!--l. 5686--><p class="noindent" >The following keywords also apply only when generating coordinates. However they may also be used with matrix
binary files.
<!--l. 5688--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-143000III"></a>Flipx, flipy, flipz</span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-282"></a>
Sometimes the scanning directions in a binary datafile are not consistent with that assumed by gnuplot. These
keywords can flip the scanning direction along dimensions x, y, z.
<!--l. 5694--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-144000III"></a>Origin </span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-284"></a>
When gnuplot generates coordinates based upon transposition and flip, it attempts to always position the lower left
point in the array at the origin, i.e., the data lies in the first quadrant of a Cartesian system after transpose and
flip.
<!--l. 5702--><p class="noindent" >To position the array somewhere else on the graph, the <span 
class="cmbx-10">origin </span>keyword directs gnuplot to position the
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
lower left point of the array at a point specified by a tuple. The tuple should be a double for <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>
and a triple for <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>. For example, <span 
class="cmbx-10">origin=(100,100):(100,200) </span>is for two records in the file and
intended for plotting in two dimensions. A second example, <span 
class="cmbx-10">origin=(0,0,3.5)</span>, is for plotting in three
dimensions.
<!--l. 5708--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-145000III"></a>Center</span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-286"></a>
Similar to <span 
class="cmbx-10">origin</span>, this keyword will position the array such that its center lies at the point given by the tuple. For
example, <span 
class="cmbx-10">center=(0,0)</span>. Center does not apply when the size of the array is <span 
class="cmbx-10">Inf</span>.
<!--l. 5715--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-146000III"></a>Rotate</span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-288"></a>
The transpose and flip commands provide some flexibility in generating and orienting coordinates. However, for full
degrees of freedom, it is possible to apply a rotational vector described by a rotational angle in two
dimensions.
<!--l. 5723--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">rotate </span>keyword applies to the two-dimensional plane, whether it be <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>. The rotation is done with
respect to the positive angle of the Cartesian plane.
<!--l. 5727--><p class="noindent" >The angle can be expressed in radians, radians as a multiple of pi, or degrees. For example, <span 
class="cmbx-10">rotate=1.5708</span>,
<span 
class="cmbx-10">rotate=0.5pi </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">rotate=90deg </span>are equivalent.
<!--l. 5730--><p class="noindent" >If <span 
class="cmbx-10">origin </span>is specified, the rotation is done about the lower left sample point before translation. Otherwise, the
rotation is done about the array <span 
class="cmbx-10">center</span>.
<!--l. 5733--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-147000III"></a>Perpendicular</span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-290"></a>
For <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>, the concept of a rotational vector is implemented by a triple representing the vector to be oriented
normal to the two-dimensional x-y plane. Naturally, the default is (0,0,1). Thus specifying both rotate and
perpendicular together can orient data myriad ways in three-space.
<!--l. 5741--><p class="noindent" >The two-dimensional rotation is done first, followed by the three-dimensional rotation. That is, if R&#8217; is the rotational
2 x 2 matrix described by an angle, and P is the 3 x 3 matrix projecting (0,0,1) to (xp,yp,zp), let R be constructed
from R&#8217; at the upper left sub-matrix, 1 at element 3,3 and zeros elsewhere. Then the matrix formula for
translating data is v&#8217; = P R v, where v is the 3 x 1 vector of data extracted from the data file. In cases
where the data of the file is inherently not three-dimensional, logical rules are used to place the data
in three-space. (E.g., usually setting the z-dimension value to zero and placing 2D data in the x-y
plane.)
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-148000III"></a>Data</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-292"></a>
<a 
