<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-151000III"></a>Index</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-298"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-151001"></a>
<!--l. 6011--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">index </span>keyword allows you to select specific data sets in a multi-data-set file for plotting.
<!--l. 6014--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;index</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;m&#x003E;{:&#x003C;n&#x003E;{:&#x003C;p&#x003E;}}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"&#x003C;name&#x003E;"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;}</span>
<!--l. 6018--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6021--><p class="noindent" >Data sets are separated by pairs of blank records. <span 
class="cmbx-10">index </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">m</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>selects only set <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>m<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>; <span 
class="cmbx-10">index </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">m</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">:</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">n</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>selects sets
in the range <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>m<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>to <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>n<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>; and <span 
class="cmbx-10">index </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">m</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">:</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">n</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">:</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">p</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>selects indices <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>m<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>, <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>m<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>+<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>p<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>, <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>m<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>+2<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>p<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>, etc., but
stopping at <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>n<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. Following C indexing, the index 0 is assigned to the first data set in the file. Specifying too large
an index results in an error message. If <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>p<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is specified but <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>n<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is left blank then every <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>p<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>-th dataset
is read until the end of the file. If <span 
class="cmbx-10">index </span>is not specified, the entire file is plotted as a single data
set.
<!--l. 6030--><p class="noindent" >Example: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;index</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;4:5</span>
<!--l. 6034--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6037--><p class="noindent" >For each point in the file, the index value of the data set it appears in is available via the pseudo-column
<span 
class="cmbx-10">column(-2)</span>. This leads to an alternative way of distinguishing individual data sets within a file as shown below.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
This is more awkward than the <span 
class="cmbx-10">index </span>command if all you are doing is selecting one data set for plotting, but is very
useful if you want to assign different properties to each data set. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">pseudocolumns (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-166000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">111</span><!--tex4ht:ref: pseudocolumns --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-151002"></a>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">lc variable</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-44000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">42</span><!--tex4ht:ref: lc variable --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-151003"></a>.
<!--l. 6044--><p class="noindent" >Example: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:(column(-2)==4</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;?</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$2</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;NaN)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;#</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;very</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;awkward</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2:(column(-2))</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;linecolor</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;variable</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;#</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;very</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;useful!</span>
<!--l. 6049--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6052--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">index &#8217;</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">name</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#8217; </span>selects the data set with name &#8217;<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>name<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>&#8217;. Names are assigned to data sets in comment lines. The
comment character and leading white space are removed from the comment line. If the resulting line starts with
<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>name<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>, the following data set is now named <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>name<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>and can be selected.
<!--l. 6057--><p class="noindent" >Example: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;index</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;Population&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 6061--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6064--><p class="noindent" >Please note that every comment that starts with <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>name<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>will name the following data set. To avoid problems it
may be useful to choose a naming scheme like &#8217;== Population ==&#8217; or &#8217;[Population]&#8217;.
<!--l. 6068--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/multimsh.html" ></a>
<!--l. 6070--><p class="noindent" >
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-152000III"></a>Smooth</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-300"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-152001"></a>
<!--l. 6079--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>includes a few general-purpose routines for interpolation and approximation of data; these are grouped
under the <span 
class="cmbx-10">smooth </span>option. More sophisticated data processing may be performed by preprocessing the data
externally or by using <span 
class="cmbx-10">fit </span>with an appropriate model.
<!--l. 6084--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;smooth</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{unique</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;frequency</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;cumulative</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;cnormal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;kdensity</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;csplines</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;acsplines</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;bezier</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sbezier}</span>
<!--l. 6089--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6092--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">unique</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">frequency</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">cumulative </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">cnormal </span>plot the data after making them monotonic. Each of the other
routines uses the data to determine the coefficients of a continuous curve between the endpoints of the data. This
curve is then plotted in the same manner as a function, that is, by finding its value at uniform intervals along the
abscissa (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set samples (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-291000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">197</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set samples --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-152002"></a>) and connecting these points with straight line segments (if a line style is
chosen).
<!--l. 6100--><p class="noindent" >If <span 
class="cmbx-10">autoscale </span>is in effect, the ranges will be computed such that the plotted curve lies within the borders of the
graph.
<!--l. 6103--><p class="noindent" >If <span 
class="cmbx-10">autoscale </span>is not in effect, and the smooth option is either <span 
class="cmbx-10">acspline </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">cspline</span>, the sampling of the generated
curve is done across the intersection of the x range covered by the input data and the fixed abscissa range as defined
by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xrange</span>.
<!--l. 6108--><p class="noindent" >If too few points are available to allow the selected option to be applied, an error message is produced. The
minimum number is one for <span 
class="cmbx-10">unique </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">frequency</span>, four for <span 
class="cmbx-10">acsplines</span>, and three for the others.
<!--l. 6112--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">smooth </span>options have no effect on function plots.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 6113--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-153000III"></a>Acsplines</span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-302"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-153001"></a>
The <span 
class="cmbx-10">acsplines </span>option approximates the data with a <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>natural smoothing spline<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. After the data are made
monotonic in x (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">smooth unique (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-157000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">105</span><!--tex4ht:ref: smooth unique --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-153002"></a>), a curve is piecewise constructed from segments of cubic
polynomials whose coefficients are found by the weighting the data points; the weights are taken from the
third column in the data file. That default can be modified by the third entry in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>list, e.g.,
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;data-file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2:(1.0)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;smooth</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;acsplines</span>
<!--l. 6133--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6136--><p class="noindent" >Qualitatively, the absolute magnitude of the weights determines the number of segments used to construct the
curve. If the weights are large, the effect of each datum is large and the curve approaches that produced by
connecting consecutive points with natural cubic splines. If the weights are small, the curve is composed of fewer
segments and thus is smoother; the limiting case is the single segment produced by a weighted linear least squares fit
to all the data. The smoothing weight can be expressed in terms of errors as a statistical weight for a point divided
by a <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>smoothing factor<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>for the curve so that (standard) errors in the file can be used as smoothing
weights.
<!--l. 6147--><p class="noindent" >Example: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sw(x,S)=1/(x*x*S)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;data_file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2:(sw($3,100))</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;smooth</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;acsplines</span>
<!--l. 6152--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6154--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-154000III"></a>Bezier</span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-304"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-154001"></a>
The <span 
class="cmbx-10">bezier </span>option approximates the data with a Bezier curve of degree n (the number of data points) that connects
the endpoints.
<!--l. 6167--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-155000III"></a>Csplines</span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-306"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-155001"></a>
The <span 
class="cmbx-10">csplines </span>option connects consecutive points by natural cubic splines after rendering the data monotonic (see
<span 
class="cmbx-10">smooth unique (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-157000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">105</span><!--tex4ht:ref: smooth unique --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-155002"></a>).
<!--l. 6180--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-156000III"></a>Sbezier</span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-308"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-156001"></a>
The <span 
class="cmbx-10">sbezier </span>option first renders the data monotonic (<span 
class="cmbx-10">unique</span>) and then applies the <span 
class="cmbx-10">bezier </span>algorithm.
<!--l. 6193--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-157000III"></a>Unique</span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-310"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-157001"></a>
The <span 
class="cmbx-10">unique </span>option makes the data monotonic in x; points with the same x-value are replaced by
a single point having the average y-value. The resulting points are then connected by straight line
segments.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 6207--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-158000III"></a>Frequency</span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-312"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-158001"></a>
The <span 
class="cmbx-10">frequency </span>option makes the data monotonic in x; points with the same x-value are replaced by a single point
having the summed y-values. The resulting points are then connected by straight line segments. See
also
<!--l. 6222--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/smooth.html" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">smooth.dem </span></a>
<!--l. 6225--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-159000III"></a>Cumulative</span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-314"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-159001"></a>
The <span 
class="cmbx-10">cumulative </span>option makes the data monotonic in x; points with the same x-value are replaced by a single point
containing the cumulative sum of y-values of all data points with lower x-values (i.e. to the left of the
current data point). This can be used to obtain a cumulative distribution function from data. See
also
<!--l. 6242--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/smooth.html" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">smooth.dem </span></a>
<!--l. 6245--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-160000III"></a>Cnormal</span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-316"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-160001"></a>
The <span 
class="cmbx-10">cnormal </span>option makes the data monotonic in x and normalises the y-values onto the range [0:1]. Points with
the same x-value are replaced by a single point containing the cumulative sum of y-values of all data points with
lower x-values (i.e. to the left of the current data point) divided by the total sum of all y-values. This can be used to
obtain a normalised cumulative distribution function from data (useful when comparing sets of samples with
differing numbers of members). See also
<!--l. 6265--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/smooth.html" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">smooth.dem </span></a>
<!--l. 6269--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
 id="x1-161000III"></a>Kdensity</span>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-318"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-161001"></a>
The <span 
class="cmbx-10">kdensity </span>option is a way to plot a kernel density estimate (which is a smooth histogram) for a random
collection of points, using Gaussian kernels. A Gaussian is placed at the location of each point in the first column
and the sum of all these Gaussians is plotted as a function. The value in the second column is taken as weight of the
Gaussian. (To obtain a normalized histogram, this should be 1/number-of-points). The value of the third
column, if supplied, is taken as the bandwidth for the kernels. If only two columns have been specified,
or if the value of the third column is zero or less, gnuplot calculates the bandwidth which would be
optimal if the input data was normally distributed. (This will usually be a very conservative, i.e. broad
bandwidth.)
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-162000III"></a>Special-filenames</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-320"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-162001"></a>
<!--l. 6299--><p class="noindent" >There are a few filenames that have a special meaning: &#8217; &#8217;, &#8217;-&#8217;, &#8217;+&#8217; and &#8217;++&#8217;.
<!--l. 6301--><p class="noindent" >The empty filename &#8217; &#8217; tells gnuplot to re-use the previous input file in the same plot command. So to plot two
columns from the same input file:
<!--l. 6305--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;filename&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:3</span>
<!--l. 6307--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6310--><p class="noindent" >The special filenames &#8217;+&#8217; and &#8217;++&#8217; are a mechanism to allow the full range of <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>specifiers and plot styles with
in-line functions. Normally a function plot can only have a single y (or z) value associated with each sampled point.
The pseudo-file &#8217;+&#8217; treats the sampled points as column 1, and allows additional column values to be specified via a
<span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>specification, just as for a true input file. The number of samples returned is controlled by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set samples</span>.
Example:
<!--l. 6320--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;+&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;($1):(sin($1)):(sin($1)**2)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;filledcurves</span>
<!--l. 6322--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6325--><p class="noindent" >Similarly the pseudo-file &#8217;++&#8217; returns 2 columns of data forming a regular grid of [x,y] coordinates with the number
of points along x controlled by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set samples </span>and the number of points along y controlled by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set isosamples</span>. You
must set xrange and yrange before plotting &#8217;++&#8217;. Examples:
<!--l. 6332--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;splot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;++&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2:(sin($1)*sin($2))</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pm3d</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;++&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2:(sin($1)*sin($2))</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;image</span>
<!--l. 6335--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6338--><p class="noindent" >The special filename <span 
class="cmbx-10">&#8217;-&#8217; </span>specifies that the data are inline; i.e., they follow the command. Only the data follow the
command; <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>options like filters, titles, and line styles remain on the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command line. This is similar to <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;&#x003C; </span>in
unix shell script, and $DECK in VMS DCL. The data are entered as though they are being read from a file, one
data point per record. The letter <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>e<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>at the start of the first column terminates data entry. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>option can be
applied to these data &#8212; using it to filter them through a function might make sense, but selecting columns probably
doesn&#8217;t!
<!--l. 6347--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#8217;-&#8217; </span>is intended for situations where it is useful to have data and commands together, e.g., when <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>is run as a
sub-process of some front-end application. Some of the demos, for example, might use this feature. While <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>
options such as <span 
class="cmbx-10">index </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">every </span>are recognized, their use forces you to enter data that won&#8217;t be used. For example,
while
<!--l. 6354--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;-&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;index</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;-&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;index</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;2</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;4</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;6</span>
<!--l. 6359--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6364--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;10</span>
<span 
