class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:3,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:4</span>
<!--l. 6412--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6415--><p class="noindent" >(If you use both <span 
class="cmbx-10">&#8217;-&#8217; </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">&#8217; &#8217; </span>on the same <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command, you&#8217;ll need to have two sets of inline data, as in the example
above.)
<!--l. 6418--><p class="noindent" >On systems with a popen function, the datafile can be piped through a shell command by starting the file name
with a &#8217;<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>&#8217;. For example,
<!--l. 6422--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pop(x)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;103*exp(-x/10)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;awk</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;{print</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$1-1965,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$2}&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;population.dat",</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pop(x)</span>
