class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;!~</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;/^#/</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{print</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$1-1965,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$2}&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;population.dat"</span>
<!--l. 6437--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6440--><p class="noindent" >While this approach is most flexible, it is possible to achieve simple filtering with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">thru</span>
keywords.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-163000III"></a>Thru</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-322"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-163001"></a>
<!--l. 6451--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">thru </span>function is provided for backward compatibility.
<!--l. 6453--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;thru</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;f(x)</span>
<!--l. 6457--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6460--><p class="noindent" >It is equivalent to:
<!--l. 6463--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:(f($2))</span>
<!--l. 6465--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6468--><p class="noindent" >While the latter appears more complex, it is much more flexible. The more natural
<!--l. 6472--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;thru</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;f(y)</span>
<!--l. 6474--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6477--><p class="noindent" >also works (i.e. you can use y as the dummy variable).
<!--l. 6479--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">thru </span>is parsed for <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">fit </span>but has no effect.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-164000III"></a>Using</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-324"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-164001"></a>
<!--l. 6489--><p class="noindent" >The most common datafile modifier is <span 
class="cmbx-10">using</span>. It tells the program which columns of data in the input file are to be
plotted.
<!--l. 6492--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;entry&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{:&#x003C;entry&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{:&#x003C;entry&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;...}}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#8217;format&#8217;}</span>
<!--l. 6496--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6499--><p class="noindent" >If a format is specified, it is used to read in each datafile record using the C library &#8217;scanf&#8217; function. Otherwise the
record is interpreted as consisting of columns (fields) of data separated by whitespace (spaces and/or tabs), but see
<span 
class="cmbx-10">datafile separator (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-212000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">144</span><!--tex4ht:ref: datafile separator --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-164002"></a>.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 6504--><p class="noindent" >Each <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>entry<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>may be a simple column number that selects the value from one field of the input file, a string that
matches a column label in the first line of a data set, an expression enclosed in parentheses, or a special function not
enclosed in parentheses such as xticlabels(2).
<!--l. 6509--><p class="noindent" >If the entry is an expression in parentheses, then the function column(N) may be used to indicate the value in
column N. That is, column(1) refers to the first item read, column(2) to the second, and so on. The special symbols
$1, $2, ... are shorthand for column(1), column(2) ... The function <span 
class="cmbx-10">valid(N) </span>tests whether the value in the Nth
column is a valid number. <a 
 id="dx1-164003"></a><a 
 id="dx1-164004"></a> If each column of data in the input file contains a label in the first row rather than a
data value, this label can be used to identify the column on input and/or in the plot legend. The column() function
can be used to select an input column by label rather than by column number. For example, if the data file contains
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
