<!--l. 6538--><p class="noindent" >To use the column labels in the plot legend, use <span 
class="cmbx-10">set key autotitle columnhead</span>.
<!--l. 6541--><p class="noindent" >In addition to the actual columns 1...N in the input data file, gnuplot presents data from several <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>pseudo-columns<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>
that hold bookkeeping information. E.g. $0 or column(0) returns the sequence number of this data record within a
dataset. Please see <span 
class="cmbx-10">pseudocolumns (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-166000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">111</span><!--tex4ht:ref: pseudocolumns --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-164005"></a>.
<!--l. 6546--><p class="noindent" >An empty <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>entry<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>will default to its order in the list of entries. For example, <span 
class="cmbx-10">using ::4 </span>is interpreted as <span 
class="cmbx-10">using</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">1:2:4</span>.
<!--l. 6549--><p class="noindent" >If the <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>list has only a single entry, that <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>entry<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>will be used for y and the data point number (pseudo-column
$0) is used for x; for example, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">plot &#8217;file&#8217; using 1</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is identical to <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">plot &#8217;file&#8217; using 0:1</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. If the <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>list has two
entries, these will be used for x and y. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-293000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">198</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set style --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-164006"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">fit (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-106000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">79</span><!--tex4ht:ref: fit --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-164007"></a> for details about plotting styles that
make use of data from additional columns of input.
<!--l. 6556--><p class="noindent" >&#8217;scanf&#8217; accepts several numerical specifications but <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>requires all inputs to be double-precision floating-point
variables, so <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>%lf<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is essentially the only permissible specifier. A format string given by the user must contain at
least one such input specifier, and no more than seven of them. &#8217;scanf&#8217; expects to see white space &#8212; a blank, tab
(<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>t<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>), newline (<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>n<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>), or formfeed (<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>f<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>) &#8212; between numbers; anything else in the input stream must be explicitly
skipped.
<!--l. 6565--><p class="noindent" >Note that the use of <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>t<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>n<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, or <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>f<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>requires use of double-quotes rather than single-quotes.
<!--l. 6567--><p class="noindent" ><span class="likeparagraphHead"><a 
