<!--l. 6603--><p class="noindent" >One trick is to use the ternary <span 
class="cmbx-10">?: </span>operator to filter data:
<!--l. 6606--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:($3&#x003E;10</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;?</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$2</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1/0)</span>
<!--l. 6608--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6611--><p class="noindent" >which plots the datum in column two against that in column one provided the datum in column three exceeds ten.
<span 
class="cmbx-10">1/0 </span>is undefined; <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>quietly ignores undefined points, so unsuitable points are suppressed. Or you can use the
pre-defined variable NaN to achieve the same result. <a 
 id="dx1-165002"></a>
<!--l. 6617--><p class="noindent" >In fact, you can use a constant expression for the column number, provided it doesn&#8217;t start with an opening
parenthesis; constructs like <span 
class="cmbx-10">using 0+(complicated expression) </span>can be used. The crucial point is that the
expression is evaluated once if it doesn&#8217;t start with a left parenthesis, or once for each data point read if it
does.
<!--l. 6623--><p class="noindent" >If timeseries data are being used, the time can span multiple columns. The starting column should be specified. Note
that the spaces within the time must be included when calculating starting columns for other data. E.g., if the
first element on a line is a time with an embedded space, the y value should be specified as column
three.
<!--l. 6629--><p class="noindent" >It should be noted that <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot &#8217;file&#8217;</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot &#8217;file&#8217; using 1:2</span>, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot &#8217;file&#8217; using ($1):($2) </span>can be subtly different:
1) if <span 
class="cmbx-10">file </span>has some lines with one column and some with two, the first will invent x values when they are missing, the
second will quietly ignore the lines with one column, and the third will store an undefined value for lines with one
point (so that in a plot with lines, no line joins points across the bad point); 2) if a line contains text at the first
column, the first will abort the plot on an error, but the second and third should quietly skip the
garbage.
<!--l. 6638--><p class="noindent" >In fact, it is often possible to plot a file with lots of lines of garbage at the top simply by specifying
<!--l. 6642--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2</span>
<!--l. 6644--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6647--><p class="noindent" >However, if you want to leave text in your data files, it is safer to put the comment character (#) in the first column
of the text lines.
