<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-172000III"></a>Volatile</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-340"></a>
<!--l. 6743--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">volatile </span>keyword indicates that the data previously read from the input stream or file may not be available for
re-reading. This tells the program to use <span 
class="cmbx-10">refresh </span>rather than <span 
class="cmbx-10">replot </span>commands whenever possible. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">refresh</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-185000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">124</span><!--tex4ht:ref: refresh --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-172001"></a>.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-173000III"></a>Errorbars</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-342"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-173001"></a>
<!--l. 6754--><p class="noindent" >Error bars are supported for 2D data file plots by reading one to four additional columns (or <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>entries); these
additional values are used in different ways by the various errorbar styles.
<!--l. 6758--><p class="noindent" >In the default situation, <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>expects to see three, four, or six numbers on each line of the data file &#8212;
either
<!--l. 6762--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(x,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ydelta),</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(x,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ylow,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;yhigh),</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(x,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xdelta),</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(x,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xlow,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xhigh),</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(x,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xdelta,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ydelta),</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;or</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(x,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xlow,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xhigh,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ylow,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;yhigh).</span>
<!--l. 6769--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6772--><p class="noindent" >The x coordinate must be specified. The order of the numbers must be exactly as given above, though the <span 
class="cmbx-10">using</span>
qualifier can manipulate the order and provide values for missing columns. For example,
<!--l. 6777--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;errorbars</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2:(sqrt($1))</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xerrorbars</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2:($1-$3):($1+$3):4:5</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xyerrorbars</span>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 6781--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6784--><p class="noindent" >The last example is for a file containing an unsupported combination of relative x and absolute y errors. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">using</span>
entry generates absolute x min and max from the relative error.
<!--l. 6788--><p class="noindent" >The y error bar is a vertical line plotted from (x, ylow) to (x, yhigh). If ydelta is specified instead of ylow and yhigh,
ylow = y - ydelta and yhigh = y + ydelta are derived. If there are only two numbers on the record, yhigh and ylow
are both set to y. The x error bar is a horizontal line computed in the same fashion. To get lines plotted between the
data points, <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>the data file twice, once with errorbars and once with lines (but remember to use the <span 
class="cmbx-10">notitle</span>
option on one to avoid two entries in the key). Alternately, use the errorlines command (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">errorlines</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-174000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">114</span><!--tex4ht:ref: errorlines --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-173002"></a>).
<!--l. 6798--><p class="noindent" >The error bars have crossbars at each end unless <span 
class="cmbx-10">set bars </span>is used (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set bars (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-196000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">133</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set bars --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-173003"></a> for details).
<!--l. 6801--><p class="noindent" >If autoscaling is on, the ranges will be adjusted to include the error bars.
<!--l. 6803--><p class="noindent" >See also
<!--l. 6804--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/mgr.html" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">errorbar demos. </span></a>
<!--l. 6808--><p class="noindent" >See <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot using (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-164000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">109</span><!--tex4ht:ref: plot using --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-173004"></a>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot with (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-180000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">120</span><!--tex4ht:ref: plot with --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-173005"></a>, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-293000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">198</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set style --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-173006"></a> for more information.
