<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-175000III"></a>Functions</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-346"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-175001"></a>
<!--l. 6869--><p class="noindent" >Built-in or user-defined functions can be displayed by the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>commands in addition to, or instead of,
data read from a file. The requested function is evaluated by sampling at regular intervals spanning
the independent axis range[s]. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set samples (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-291000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">197</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set samples --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-175002"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set isosamples (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-230000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">158</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set isosamples --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-175003"></a>. Example:
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;approx(ang)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ang</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ang**3</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;/</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(3*2)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sin(x)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"sin(x)",</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;approx(x)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"approximation"</span>
<!--l. 6878--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6881--><p class="noindent" >To set a default plot style for functions, see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style function (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-299000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">203</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set style function --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-175004"></a>. For information on built-in functions, see
<span 
class="cmbx-10">expressions functions (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-25000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">29</span><!--tex4ht:ref: expressions functions --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-175005"></a>. For information on defining your own functions, see <span 
class="cmbx-10">user-defined</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-35000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">35</span><!--tex4ht:ref: user-defined --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-175006"></a>.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-176000III"></a>Parametric</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-348"></a>
<!--l. 6890--><p class="noindent" >When in parametric mode (<span 
class="cmbx-10">set parametric</span>) mathematical expressions must be given in pairs for <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and in
triplets for <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>.
<!--l. 6893--><p class="noindent" >Examples: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sin(t),t**2</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;splot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;cos(u)*cos(v),cos(u)*sin(v),sin(u)</span>
<!--l. 6898--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6901--><p class="noindent" >Data files are plotted as before, except any preceding parametric function must be fully specified before a data file is
given as a plot. In other words, the x parametric function (<span 
class="cmbx-10">sin(t) </span>above) and the y parametric function (<span 
class="cmbx-10">t**2</span>
above) must not be interrupted with any modifiers or data functions; doing so will generate a syntax error stating
that the parametric function is not fully specified.
<!--l. 6908--><p class="noindent" >Other modifiers, such as <span 
class="cmbx-10">with </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">title</span>, may be specified only after the parametric function has been
completed:
<!--l. 6912--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sin(t),t**2</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;Parametric</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;example&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;linespoints</span>
<!--l. 6914--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6917--><p class="noindent" >See also
<!--l. 6918--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/param.html" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">Parametric Mode Demos. </span></a>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 6921--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-177000III"></a>Ranges</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-350"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-177001"></a>
<!--l. 6929--><p class="noindent" >The optional ranges specify the region of the graph that will be displayed. Note that if you specify the
range as part of a plot command rather than using a separate <span 
class="cmbx-10">set range </span>statement, you will not be
able to pan or zoom the plot interactively, and will not be able to change the range later and then
<span 
class="cmbx-10">replot</span>.
<!--l. 6934--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[{&#x003C;dummy-var&#x003E;=}{{&#x003C;min&#x003E;}:{&#x003C;max&#x003E;}}]</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[{{&#x003C;min&#x003E;}:{&#x003C;max&#x003E;}}]</span>
<!--l. 6939--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6942--><p class="noindent" >The first form applies to the independent variable (<span 
class="cmbx-10">xrange </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">trange</span>, if in parametric mode). The second form
applies to the dependent variable <span 
class="cmbx-10">yrange </span>(and <span 
class="cmbx-10">xrange</span>, too, if in parametric mode). <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>dummy-var<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is a new name
for the independent variable. (The defaults may be changed with <span 
class="cmbx-10">set dummy</span>.) The optional <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>min<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>max<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>
terms can be constant expressions or *.
<!--l. 6948--><p class="noindent" >In non-parametric mode, the order in which ranges must be given is <span 
class="cmbx-10">xrange </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">yrange</span>.
<!--l. 6951--><p class="noindent" >In parametric mode, the order for the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command is <span 
class="cmbx-10">trange</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">xrange</span>, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">yrange</span>. The following <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command
shows setting the <span 
class="cmbx-10">trange </span>to [-pi:pi], the <span 
class="cmbx-10">xrange </span>to [-1.3:1.3] and the <span 
class="cmbx-10">yrange </span>to [-1:1] for the duration of the
graph:
<!--l. 6957--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[-pi:pi]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[-1.3:1.3]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[-1:1]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sin(t),t**2</span>
<!--l. 6959--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6962--><p class="noindent" >Note that the x2range and y2range cannot be specified here &#8212; <span 
class="cmbx-10">set x2range </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set y2range </span>must be
used.
<!--l. 6965--><p class="noindent" >Ranges are interpreted in the order listed above for the appropriate mode. Once all those needed are specified,
no further ones must be listed, but unneeded ones cannot be skipped &#8212; use an empty range <span 
class="cmbx-10">[] </span>as a
placeholder.
<!--l. 6969--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">* </span>can be used to allow autoscaling of either of min and max. See also <span 
class="cmbx-10">set autoscale (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-193000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">131</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set autoscale --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-177002"></a>.
<!--l. 6972--><p class="noindent" >Ranges specified on the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>command line affect only that graph; use the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xrange</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">set yrange</span>, etc.,
commands to change the default ranges for future graphs.
<!--l. 6976--><p class="noindent" >With time data, you must provide the range (in the same manner as the time appears in the datafile) within quotes.
<span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>uses the <span 
class="cmbx-10">timefmt </span>string to read the value &#8212; see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set timefmt (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-313000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">211</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set timefmt --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-177003"></a>.
<!--l. 6980--><p class="noindent" >Examples:
<!--l. 6982--><p class="noindent" >This uses the current ranges: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;cos(x)</span>
<!--l. 6986--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6989--><p class="noindent" >This sets the x range only: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[-10:30]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sin(pi*x)/(pi*x)</span>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 6993--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 6996--><p class="noindent" >This is the same, but uses t as the dummy-variable: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[t</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-10</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;:30]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sin(pi*t)/(pi*t)</span>
<!--l. 7000--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7003--><p class="noindent" >This sets both the x and y ranges: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[-pi:pi]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[-3:3]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;tan(x),</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1/x</span>
<!--l. 7007--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7010--><p class="noindent" >This sets only the y range, and turns off autoscaling on both axes: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[-2:sin(5)*-8]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sin(x)**besj0(x)</span>
<!--l. 7014--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7017--><p class="noindent" >This sets xmax and ymin only: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[:200]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[-pi:]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;exp(sin(x))</span>
<!--l. 7021--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7024--><p class="noindent" >This sets the x range for a timeseries: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;timefmt</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"%d/%m/%y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;%H:%M"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;["1/6/93</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;12:00":"5/6/93</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;12:00"]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;timedata.dat&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 7029--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7032--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-178000III"></a>Iteration</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-352"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-178001"></a>
<!--l. 7039--><p class="noindent" >If many similar files or functions are to be plotted together, it may be convenient to do so by iterating over a shared
plot command.
<!--l. 7042--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;for</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[&#x003C;variable&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;start&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;end&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{:&#x003C;increment&#x003E;}]</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;for</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[&#x003C;variable&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;in</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"string</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;of</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;words"]</span>
<!--l. 7047--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7050--><p class="noindent" >The scope of an iteration ends at the next comma or the end of the command, whichever comes first. Iteration can
not be nested.
<!--l. 7053--><p class="noindent" >This will plot one curve, sin(3x), because iteration ends at the comma <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;for</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[i=1:3]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;j=i,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sin(j*x)</span>
<!--l. 7057--><p class="noindent" ></pre> This will plot three curves because there is no comma after the definition of j <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;for</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[i=1:3]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;j=i</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sin(j*x)</span>
<!--l. 7063--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7066--><p class="noindent" >Example: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;for</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[dataset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;in</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"apples</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;bananas"]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;dataset."dat"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;dataset</span>
<!--l. 7070--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7073--><p class="noindent" >In this example iteration is used both to generate a file name and a corresponding title.
<!--l. 7076--><p class="noindent" >Example: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;file(n)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sprintf("dataset_%d.dat",n)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;splot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;for</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[i=1:10]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;file(i)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sprintf("dataset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;%d",i)</span>
<!--l. 7081--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7084--><p class="noindent" >This example defines a string-valued function that generates file names, and plots ten such files together. The
iteration variable (&#8217;i&#8217; in this example) is treated as an integer, and may be used more than once.
<!--l. 7088--><p class="noindent" >Example: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;key</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;left</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;for</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[n=1:4]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x**n</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sprintf("%d",n)</span>
<!--l. 7093--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7096--><p class="noindent" >This example plots a family of functions.
<!--l. 7098--><p class="noindent" >Example: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;list</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"apple</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;banana</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;cabbage</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;daikon</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;eggplant"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
