<!--l. 7251--><p class="noindent" >The first group of styles have associated line, point, and text properties. The second group of styles also have fill
properties. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">fillstyle (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-297000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">202</span><!--tex4ht:ref: fillstyle --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-180003"></a>. Some styles have further sub-styles. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">plotting styles (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-61000II"><span 
class="cmbx-10">53</span><!--tex4ht:ref: plotting styles --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-180004"></a> for details of
each.
<!--l. 7255--><p class="noindent" >A default style may be chosen by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style function </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style data</span>.
<!--l. 7257--><p class="noindent" >By default, each function and data file will use a different line type and point type, up to the maximum number of
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
available types. All terminal drivers support at least six different point types, and re-use them, in order, if more are
required. To see the complete set of line and point types available for the current terminal, type <span 
class="cmbx-10">test</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-378000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">238</span><!--tex4ht:ref: test --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-180005"></a>.
<!--l. 7263--><p class="noindent" >If you wish to choose the line or point type for a single plot, <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>line_type<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>point_type<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>may be specified.
These are positive integer constants (or expressions) that specify the line type and point type to be used for the
plot. Use <span 
class="cmbx-10">test </span>to display the types available for your terminal.
<!--l. 7268--><p class="noindent" >You may also scale the line width and point size for a plot by using <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>line_width<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>point_size<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>, which are
specified relative to the default values for each terminal. The pointsize may also be altered globally &#8212; see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">pointsize (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-283000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">194</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set pointsize --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-180006"></a> for details. But note that both <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>point_size<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>as set here and as set by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set pointsize </span>multiply
the default point size &#8212; their effects are not cumulative. That is, <span 
class="cmbx-10">set pointsize 2; plot x w p ps 3 </span>will use points
three times default size, not six.
<!--l. 7277--><p class="noindent" >It is also possible to specify <span 
class="cmbx-10">pointsize variable </span>either as part of a line style or for an individual plot. In this case
one extra column of input is required, i.e. 3 columns for a 2D plot and 4 columns for a 3D splot. The size of each
individual point is determined by multiplying the global pointsize by the value read from the data
file.
<!--l. 7283--><p class="noindent" >If you have defined specific line type/width and point type/size combinations with <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style line</span>, one of these may
be selected by setting <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>line_style<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>to the index of the desired style.
<!--l. 7287--><p class="noindent" >If gnuplot was built with <span 
class="cmbx-10">pm3d </span>support, the special keyword <span 
class="cmbx-10">palette </span>is allowed for smooth color
change of lines, points and dots in <span 
class="cmbx-10">splots</span>. The color is chosen from a smooth palette which was set
previously with the command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette</span>. The color value corresponds to the z-value of the point
coordinates or to the color coordinate if specified by the 4th parameter in <span 
class="cmbx-10">using</span>. Both 2D and 3D plots
(<span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>commands) can use palette colors as specified by either their fractional value or the
corresponding value mapped to the colorbox range. A palette color value can also be read from an explicitly
specified input column in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>specifier. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">colors (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-41000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">39</span><!--tex4ht:ref: colors --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-180007"></a>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-274000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">187</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set palette --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-180008"></a>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">linetype</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-235000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">166</span><!--tex4ht:ref: linetype --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-180009"></a>.
<!--l. 7298--><p class="noindent" >The keyword <span 
class="cmbx-10">nohidden3d </span>applies only to plots made with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>command. Normally the global option <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">hidden3d </span>applies to all plots in the graph. You can attach the <span 
class="cmbx-10">nohidden3d </span>option to any individual plots that you
want to exclude from the hidden3d processing. The individual elements other than surfaces (i.e. lines, dots, labels,
...) of a plot marked <span 
class="cmbx-10">nohidden3d </span>will all be drawn, even if they would normally be obscured by other plot
elements.
<!--l. 7305--><p class="noindent" >Similarly, the keyword <span 
class="cmbx-10">nocontours </span>will turn off contouring for an individual plot even if the global property <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">contour </span>is active.
<!--l. 7308--><p class="noindent" >Similarly, the keyword <span 
class="cmbx-10">nosurface </span>will turn off the 3D surface for an individual plot even if the global property <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">surface </span>is active.
<!--l. 7311--><p class="noindent" >The keywords may be abbreviated as indicated.
<!--l. 7313--><p class="noindent" >Note that the <span 
class="cmbx-10">linewidth</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">pointsize </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">palette </span>options are not supported by all terminals.
