<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-181000III"></a>Print</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-358"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-181001"></a>
<!--l. 7431--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">print </span>command prints the value of <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>expression<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>to the screen. It is synonymous with <span 
class="cmbx-10">pause 0</span>.
<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>expression<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>may be anything that <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>can evaluate that produces a number, or it can be a
string.
<!--l. 7435--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;print</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;expression&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;expression&#x003E;,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;...}</span>
<!--l. 7439--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7442--><p class="noindent" >See <span 
class="cmbx-10">expressions (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-24000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">28</span><!--tex4ht:ref: expressions --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-181002"></a>. The output file can be set with <span 
class="cmbx-10">set print</span>.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-182000III"></a>Pwd</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-360"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-182001"></a>
<!--l. 7448--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">pwd </span>command prints the name of the working directory to the screen.
<!--l. 7450--><p class="noindent" >Note that if you wish to store the current directory into a string variable or use it in string expressions, then you can
use variable GPVAL_PWD, see <span 
class="cmbx-10">show variables all (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-318000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">213</span><!--tex4ht:ref: show variables all --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-182002"></a>.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-183000III"></a>Quit</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-362"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-183001"></a>
<!--l. 7458--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">exit </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">quit </span>commands and END-OF-FILE character will exit <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot</span>. Each of these commands will clear
the output device (as does the <span 
class="cmbx-10">clear </span>command) before exiting.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-184000III"></a>Raise</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-364"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-184001"></a>
<!--l. 7466--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;raise</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{plot_window_nb}</span>
<!--l. 7470--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7473--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">raise </span>command raises (opposite to <span 
class="cmbx-10">lower</span>) plot window(s) associated with the interactive terminal of your
gnuplot session, i.e. <span 
class="cmbx-10">pm</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">win</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">wxt </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">x11</span>. It puts the plot window to front (top) in the z-order windows stack of
the window manager of your desktop.
<!--l. 7478--><p class="noindent" >As <span 
class="cmbx-10">x11 </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">wxt </span>support multiple plot windows, then by default they raise these windows in descending order of
most recently created on top to the least recently created on bottom. If a plot number is supplied as an optional
parameter, only the associated plot window will be raised if it exists.
<!--l. 7483--><p class="noindent" >The optional parameter is ignored for single plot-windows terminal, i.e. <span 
class="cmbx-10">pm </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">win</span>.
<!--l. 7486--><p class="noindent" >If the window is not raised under X11, then perhaps the plot window is running in a different X11 session
(telnet or ssh session, for example), or perhaps raising is blocked by your window manager policy
setting.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-185000III"></a>Refresh</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-366"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-185001"></a>
<!--l. 7494--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">refresh </span>command is similar to <span 
class="cmbx-10">replot</span>, with two major differences. <span 
class="cmbx-10">refresh </span>reformats and redraws the current
plot using the data already read in. This means that you can use <span 
class="cmbx-10">refresh </span>for plots with in-line data (pseudo-device
&#8217;-&#8217;) and for plots from datafiles whose contents are volatile. You cannot use the <span 
class="cmbx-10">refresh </span>command to add new data
to an existing plot.
<!--l. 7500--><p class="noindent" >Mousing operations, in particular zoom and unzoom, will use <span 
class="cmbx-10">refresh </span>rather than <span 
class="cmbx-10">replot </span>if appropriate.
Example:
