 id="dx1-186006"></a>.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-187000III"></a>Reread</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-370"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-187001"></a>
<!--l. 7557--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">reread </span>command causes the current <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>command file, as specified by a <span 
class="cmbx-10">load </span>command or on the
command line, to be reset to its starting point before further commands are read from it. This essentially
implements an endless loop of the commands from the beginning of the command file to the <span 
class="cmbx-10">reread </span>command. (But
this is not necessarily a disaster &#8212; <span 
class="cmbx-10">reread </span>can be very useful when used in conjunction with <span 
class="cmbx-10">if</span>.) The <span 
class="cmbx-10">reread</span>
command has no effect if input from standard input.
<!--l. 7565--><p class="noindent" >Examples:
<!--l. 7567--><p class="noindent" >Suppose the file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>looper<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>contains the commands <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;a=a+1</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sin(x*a)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pause</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-1</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;if(a&#x003C;5)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;reread</span>
<!--l. 7574--><p class="noindent" ></pre> and from within <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>you submit the commands <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;a=0</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;load</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;looper&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 7581--><p class="noindent" ></pre> The result will be five plots (separated by the <span 
class="cmbx-10">pause </span>message).
<!--l. 7585--><p class="noindent" >Suppose the file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>data<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>contains six columns of numbers with a total yrange from 0 to 10; the first is x and
the next are five different functions of x. Suppose also that the file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>plotter<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>contains the commands
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;c_p</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;c_p+1</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"$0"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:c_p</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lines</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;linetype</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;c_p</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;if(c_p</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;n_p)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;reread</span>
<!--l. 7593--><p class="noindent" ></pre> and from within <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>you submit the commands <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;n_p=6</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;c_p=1</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;key</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;yrange</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[0:10]</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;multiplot</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;call</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;plotter&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;data&#8217;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;multiplot</span>
<!--l. 7605--><p class="noindent" ></pre> The result is a single graph consisting of five plots. The yrange must be set explicitly to guarantee that the five
separate graphs (drawn on top of each other in multiplot mode) will have exactly the same axes. The linetype must
be specified; otherwise all the plots would be drawn with the same type. See animate.dem in demo directory for an
animated example.
<!--l. 7613--><p class="noindent" >
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-188000III"></a>Reset</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-372"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-188001"></a>
<!--l. 7620--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">reset </span>command causes all graph-related options that can be set with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set </span>command to take on their default
values. This command is useful, e.g., to restore the default graph settings at the end of a command file, or to return
to a defined state after lots of settings have been changed within a command file. Please refer to the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set </span>command
to see the default values that the various options take.
<!--l. 7627--><p class="noindent" >The following are <span 
class="cmti-10">not </span>affected by <span 
class="cmbx-10">reset</span>. <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;term&#8216;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;output&#8216;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;loadpath&#8216;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fontpath&#8216;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;linetype&#8216;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;encoding&#8216;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;decimalsign&#8216;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;locale&#8216;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;psdir&#8216;</span>
<!--l. 7632--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<a 
 id="dx1-188002"></a>
<!--l. 7636--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">reset errors </span>clears only the error state variables GPVAL_ERRNO and GPVAL_ERRMSG.
<a 
 id="dx1-188003"></a>
<!--l. 7640--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">reset bind </span>restores all hotkey bindings to their default state.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-189000III"></a>Save</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-374"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-189001"></a>
<!--l. 7647--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">save </span>command saves user-defined functions, variables, the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term </span>status, all <span 
class="cmbx-10">set </span>options, or all of these, plus
the last <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>(<span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>) command to the specified file.
<!--l. 7651--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;save</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;option&#x003E;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;&#x003C;filename&#x003E;&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 7655--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7658--><p class="noindent" >where <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>option<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is <span 
class="cmbx-10">functions</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">variables</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">terminal </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>. If no option is used, <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>saves functions, variables,
<span 
class="cmbx-10">set </span>options and the last <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>(<span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>) command.
<!--l. 7662--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">save</span>d files are written in text format and may be read by the <span 
class="cmbx-10">load </span>command. For <span 
class="cmbx-10">save </span>with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set </span>option or
without any option, the <span 
class="cmbx-10">terminal </span>choice and the <span 
class="cmbx-10">output </span>filename are written out as a comment, to get an output
file that works in other installations of gnuplot, without changes and without risk of unwillingly overwriting
files.
<!--l. 7669--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">save terminal </span>will write out just the <span 
class="cmbx-10">terminal </span>status, without the comment marker in front of it. This is mainly
useful for switching the <span 
class="cmbx-10">terminal </span>setting for a short while, and getting back to the previously set terminal,
afterwards, by loading the saved <span 
class="cmbx-10">terminal </span>status. Note that for a single gnuplot session you may rather use the
other method of saving and restoring current terminal by the commands <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term push </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term pop</span>, see
<span 
class="cmbx-10">set term (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-307000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">208</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set term --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-189002"></a>.
<!--l. 7677--><p class="noindent" >The filename must be enclosed in quotes.
<!--l. 7679--><p class="noindent" >The special filename <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>-<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>may be used to <span 
class="cmbx-10">save </span>commands to standard output. On systems which support a popen
function (Unix), the output of save can be piped through an external program by starting the file
name with a &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">|</span>&#8217;. This provides a consistent interface to <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot</span>&#8217;s internal settings to programs which
communicate with <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>through a pipe. Please see help for <span 
class="cmbx-10">batch/interactive (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-16000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">22</span><!--tex4ht:ref: batch/interactive --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-189003"></a> for more
details.
<!--l. 7686--><p class="noindent" >Examples: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;save</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;work.gnu&#8217;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
