<!--l. 7696--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-190000III"></a>Set-show</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-376"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-190001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-190002"></a>
<!--l. 7707--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set </span>command can be used to set <span 
class="cmti-10">lots </span>of options. No screen is drawn, however, until a <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>, or <span 
class="cmbx-10">replot</span>
command is given.
<!--l. 7710--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">show </span>command shows their settings; <span 
class="cmbx-10">show all </span>shows all the settings.
<!--l. 7712--><p class="noindent" >Options changed using <span 
class="cmbx-10">set </span>can be returned to the default state by giving the corresponding <span 
class="cmbx-10">unset</span>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
command. See also the <span 
class="cmbx-10">reset (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-188000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">126</span><!--tex4ht:ref: reset --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-190003"></a> command, which returns all settable parameters to default
values.
<!--l. 7716--><p class="noindent" >If a variable contains time/date data, <span 
class="cmbx-10">show </span>will display it according to the format currently defined by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">timefmt</span>, even if that was not in effect when the variable was initially defined. <a 
 id="dx1-190004"></a>The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">unset </span>commands may
optionally contain an iteration clause. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">iteration (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-122000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">90</span><!--tex4ht:ref: iteration --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-190005"></a>.
<!--l. 7723--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-191000III"></a>Angles</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-378"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-191001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-191002"></a>
<!--l. 7736--><p class="noindent" >By default, <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>assumes the independent variable in polar graphs is in units of radians. If <span 
class="cmbx-10">set angles degrees</span>
is specified before <span 
class="cmbx-10">set polar</span>, then the default range is [0:360] and the independent variable has units of degrees.
This is particularly useful for plots of data files. The angle setting also applies to 3D mapping as set via the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">mapping </span>command.
<!--l. 7742--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;angles</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{degrees</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;radians}</span>
<span 
