<!--l. 7816--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7819--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>tag<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is an integer that identifies the arrow. If no tag is given, the lowest unused tag value is assigned
automatically. The tag can be used to delete or change a specific arrow. To change any attribute of an existing
arrow, use the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set arrow </span>command with the appropriate tag and specify the parts of the arrow to be
changed.
<!--l. 7825--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>position<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>s are specified by either x,y or x,y,z, and may be preceded by <span 
class="cmbx-10">first</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">second</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">graph</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">screen</span>, or
<span 
class="cmbx-10">character </span>to select the coordinate system. Unspecified coordinates default to 0. The end points can be specified in
one of five coordinate systems &#8212; <span 
class="cmbx-10">first </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">second </span>axes, <span 
class="cmbx-10">graph</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">screen</span>, or <span 
class="cmbx-10">character</span>. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">coordinates (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-20000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">24</span><!--tex4ht:ref: coordinates --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-192003"></a> for
details. A coordinate system specifier does not carry over from the <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>from<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>position to the <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>to<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>position.
Arrows outside the screen boundaries are permitted but may cause device errors. If the end point is
specified by <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>rto<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>instead of <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>to<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>it is drawn relatively to the start point. For linear axes, <span 
class="cmbx-10">graph </span>and
<span 
class="cmbx-10">screen </span>coordinates, the distance between the start and the end point corresponds to the given relative
coordinate. For logarithmic axes, the relative given coordinate corresponds to the factor of the coordinate
between start and end point. Thus, a negative relative value or zero are not allowed for logarithmic
axes.
<!--l. 7840--><p class="noindent" >Specifying <span 
class="cmbx-10">nohead </span>produces an arrow drawn without a head &#8212; a line segment. This gives you yet another way to
draw a line segment on the plot. By default, an arrow has a head at its end. Specifying <span 
class="cmbx-10">backhead </span>draws an arrow
head at the start point of the arrow while <span 
class="cmbx-10">heads </span>draws arrow heads on both ends of the line. Not all terminal types
support double-ended arrows.
<!--l. 7846--><p class="noindent" >Head size can be controlled by <span 
class="cmbx-10">size </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">length</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">,</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">angle</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">size </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">length</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">,</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">angle</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">,</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">backangle</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>, where
<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">length</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>defines length of each branch of the arrow head and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">angle</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>the angle (in degrees) they make with the
arrow. <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">Length</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is in x-axis units; this can be changed by <span 
class="cmbx-10">first</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">second</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">graph</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">screen</span>, or <span 
class="cmbx-10">character </span>before the
<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>length<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>; see <span 
class="cmbx-10">coordinates (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-20000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">24</span><!--tex4ht:ref: coordinates --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-192004"></a> for details. <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">Backangle</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>only takes effect when <span 
class="cmbx-10">filled </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">empty </span>is also
used. Then, <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">backangle</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is the angle (in degrees) the back branches make with the arrow (in the
same direction as <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">angle</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>). The <span 
class="cmbx-10">fig </span>terminal has a restricted backangle function. It supports three
different angles. There are two thresholds: Below 70 degrees, the arrow head gets an indented back angle.
Above 110 degrees, the arrow head has an acute back angle. Between these thresholds, the back line is
straight.
<!--l. 7859--><p class="noindent" >Specifying <span 
class="cmbx-10">filled </span>produces filled arrow heads (if heads are used). Filling is supported on filled-polygon capable
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
terminals, see help of <span 
class="cmbx-10">pm3d (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-265000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">182</span><!--tex4ht:ref: pm3d --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-192005"></a> for their list, otherwise the arrow heads are closed but not filled. The same
result (closed but not filled arrow head) is reached by specifying <span 
class="cmbx-10">empty</span>. Further, filling and outline is obviously not
supported on terminals drawing arrows by their own specific routines, like <span 
class="cmbx-10">metafont</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">metapost</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">latex </span>or
<span 
class="cmbx-10">tgif</span>.
<!--l. 7867--><p class="noindent" >The line style may be selected from a user-defined list of line styles (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style line (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-301000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">204</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set style line --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-192006"></a>) or may be defined
here by providing values for <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>line_type<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>(an index from the default list of styles) and/or <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>line_width<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>(which is a
multiplier for the default width).
<!--l. 7872--><p class="noindent" >Note, however, that if a user-defined line style has been selected, its properties (type and width) cannot be altered
merely by issuing another <span 
class="cmbx-10">set arrow </span>command with the appropriate index and <span 
class="cmbx-10">lt </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">lw</span>.
<!--l. 7876--><p class="noindent" >If <span 
class="cmbx-10">front </span>is given, the arrow is written on top of the graphed data. If <span 
class="cmbx-10">back </span>is given (the default), the arrow is
written underneath the graphed data. Using <span 
class="cmbx-10">front </span>will prevent an arrow from being obscured by dense
data.
<!--l. 7880--><p class="noindent" >Examples:
<!--l. 7882--><p class="noindent" >To set an arrow pointing from the origin to (1,2) with user-defined style 5, use: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;arrow</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;to</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1,2</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ls</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;5</span>
<!--l. 7887--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7890--><p class="noindent" >To set an arrow from bottom left of plotting area to (-5,5,3), and tag the arrow number 3, use: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;arrow</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;3</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;from</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;graph</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0,0</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;to</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-5,5,3</span>
<!--l. 7895--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7898--><p class="noindent" >To change the preceding arrow to end at 1,1,1, without an arrow head and double its width, use:
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;arrow</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;3</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;to</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1,1,1</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;nohead</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lw</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;2</span>
<!--l. 7903--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7906--><p class="noindent" >To draw a vertical line from the bottom to the top of the graph at x=3, use: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;arrow</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;from</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;3,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;graph</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;to</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;3,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;graph</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;nohead</span>
<!--l. 7910--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7913--><p class="noindent" >To draw a vertical arrow with T-shape ends, use: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;arrow</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;3</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;from</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0,-5</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;to</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0,5</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;heads</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;size</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;screen</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0.1,90</span>
<!--l. 7917--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7920--><p class="noindent" >To draw an arrow relatively to the start point, where the relative distances are given in graph coordinates, use:
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;arrow</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;from</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0,-5</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;rto</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;graph</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0.1,0.1</span>
<!--l. 7925--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7928--><p class="noindent" >To draw an arrow with relative end point in logarithmic x axis, use: <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;logscale</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;arrow</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;from</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;100,-5</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;rto</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;10,10</span>
<!--l. 7933--><p class="noindent" ></pre> This draws an arrow from 100,-5 to 1000,5. For the logarithmic x axis, the relative coordinate 10 means <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>factor 10<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>
while for the linear y axis, the relative coordinate 10 means <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>difference 10<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.
<!--l. 7939--><p class="noindent" >To delete arrow number 2, use: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;arrow</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;2</span>
<!--l. 7943--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7946--><p class="noindent" >To delete all arrows, use: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;arrow</span>
<!--l. 7950--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7953--><p class="noindent" >To show all arrows (in tag order), use: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;arrow</span>
<!--l. 7957--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7960--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/arrowstyle.html" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">arrows demos. </span></a>
<!--l. 7964--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-193000III"></a>Autoscale</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-382"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-193001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-193002"></a>
<!--l. 7976--><p class="noindent" >Autoscaling may be set individually on the x, y or z axis or globally on all axes. The default is to autoscale all axes.
If you want to autoscale based on a subset of the plots in the figure, you can mark the other ones with the flag
<span 
class="cmbx-10">noautoscale</span>. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">datafile (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-148000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">99</span><!--tex4ht:ref: datafile --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-193003"></a>.
<!--l. 7981--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;autoscale</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;axes&#x003E;{|min|max|fixmin|fixmax|fix}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fix</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;keepfix}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;autoscale</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;axes&#x003E;}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;autoscale</span>
<!--l. 7987--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 7990--><p class="noindent" >where <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>axes<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is either <span 
class="cmbx-10">x</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">y</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">z</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">cb</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">x2</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">y2 </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">xy</span>. A keyword with <span 
class="cmbx-10">min </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">max </span>appended (this cannot be done with
<span 
class="cmbx-10">xy</span>) tells <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>to autoscale just the minimum or maximum of that axis. If no keyword is given, all axes are
autoscaled.
<!--l. 7995--><p class="noindent" >A keyword with <span 
class="cmbx-10">fixmin</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">fixmax </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">fix </span>appended tells gnuplot to disable extension of the axis range to the next tic
mark position, for autoscaled axes using equidistant tics; <span 
class="cmbx-10">set autoscale fix </span>sets this for all axes. Command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">autoscale keepfix </span>autoscales all axes while keeping the fix settings.
<!--l. 8001--><p class="noindent" >When autoscaling, the axis range is automatically computed and the dependent axis (y for a <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and z for <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>) is
scaled to include the range of the function or data being plotted.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 8005--><p class="noindent" >If autoscaling of the dependent axis (y or z) is not set, the current y or z range is used.
<!--l. 8008--><p class="noindent" >Autoscaling the independent variables (x for <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and x,y for <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>) is a request to set the domain to match any
data file being plotted. If there are no data files, autoscaling an independent variable has no effect. In other words,
in the absence of a data file, functions alone do not affect the x range (or the y range if plotting z =
f(x,y)).
<!--l. 8014--><p class="noindent" >Please see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xrange (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-334000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">218</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set xrange --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-193004"></a> for additional information about ranges.
<!--l. 8016--><p class="noindent" >The behavior of autoscaling remains consistent in parametric mode, (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set parametric (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-263000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">181</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set parametric --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-193005"></a>).
However, there are more dependent variables and hence more control over x, y, and z axis scales. In
parametric mode, the independent or dummy variable is t for <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>s and u,v for <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>s. <span 
class="cmbx-10">autoscale</span>
in parametric mode, then, controls all ranges (t, u, v, x, y, and z) and allows x, y, and z to be fully
autoscaled.
<!--l. 8023--><p class="noindent" >Autoscaling works the same way for polar mode as it does for parametric mode for <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>, with the extension that in
polar mode <span 
class="cmbx-10">set dummy </span>can be used to change the independent variable from t (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set dummy</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-217000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">149</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set dummy --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-193006"></a>).
<!--l. 8027--><p class="noindent" >When tics are displayed on second axes but no plot has been specified for those axes, x2range and y2range are
inherited from xrange and yrange. This is done <span 
class="cmti-10">before </span>xrange and yrange are autoextended to a whole
number of tics, which can cause unexpected results. You can use the <span 
class="cmbx-10">fixmin </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">fixmax </span>options to avoid
this.
<!--l. 8033--><p class="noindent" >Examples:
<!--l. 8035--><p class="noindent" >This sets autoscaling of the y axis (other axes are not affected): <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;autoscale</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y</span>
<!--l. 8039--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 8042--><p class="noindent" >This sets autoscaling only for the minimum of the y axis (the maximum of the y axis and the other axes are not
affected): <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;autoscale</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ymin</span>
<!--l. 8047--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 8050--><p class="noindent" >This disables extension of the x2 axis tics to the next tic mark, thus keeping the exact range as found in the plotted
data and functions: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;autoscale</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x2fixmin</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;autoscale</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x2fixmax</span>
<!--l. 8056--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 8059--><p class="noindent" >This sets autoscaling of the x and y axes: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;autoscale</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xy</span>
<!--l. 8063--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 8066--><p class="noindent" >This sets autoscaling of the x, y, z, x2 and y2 axes: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;autoscale</span>
<!--l. 8070--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 8073--><p class="noindent" >This disables autoscaling of the x, y, z, x2 and y2 axes: <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;autoscale</span>
<!--l. 8077--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 8080--><p class="noindent" >This disables autoscaling of the z axis only: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;autoscale</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;z</span>
<!--l. 8084--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-194000III"></a>Parametric mode</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-384"></a>
<!--l. 8091--><p class="noindent" >When in parametric mode (<span 
class="cmbx-10">set parametric</span>), the xrange is as fully scalable as the y range. In other words, in
parametric mode the x axis can be automatically scaled to fit the range of the parametric function that is being
plotted. Of course, the y axis can also be automatically scaled just as in the non-parametric case. If autoscaling on
the x axis is not set, the current x range is used.
<!--l. 8098--><p class="noindent" >Data files are plotted the same in parametric and non-parametric mode. However, there is a difference in mixed
function and data plots: in non-parametric mode with autoscaled x, the x range of the datafile controls the x range
of the functions; in parametric mode it has no influence.
<!--l. 8103--><p class="noindent" >For completeness a last command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set autoscale t </span>is accepted. However, the effect of this <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>scaling<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is very minor.
When <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>determines that the t range would be empty, it makes a small adjustment if autoscaling is true.
Otherwise, <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>gives an error. Such behavior may, in fact, not be very useful and the command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set autoscale</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">t </span>is certainly questionable.
<!--l. 8109--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>extends the above ideas as you would expect. If autoscaling is set, then x, y, and z ranges are computed and
each axis scaled to fit the resulting data.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-195000III"></a>Polar mode</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-386"></a>
<!--l. 8116--><p class="noindent" >When in polar mode (<span 
class="cmbx-10">set polar</span>), the xrange and the yrange may be left in autoscale mode. If <span 
class="cmbx-10">set rrange </span>is used to
limit the extent of the polar axis, then xrange and yrange will adjust to match this automatically. However, explicit
xrange and yrange commands can later be used to make further adjustments. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set rrange (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-289000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">196</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set rrange --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-195001"></a>. The trange
may also be autoscaled. Note that if the trange is contained within one quadrant, autoscaling will produce a polar
plot of only that single quadrant.
<!--l. 8124--><p class="noindent" >Explicitly setting one or two ranges but not others may lead to unexpected results. See also
<!--l. 8127--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/poldat.html" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">polar demos. </span></a>
<!--l. 8130--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-196000III"></a>Bars</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-388"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-196001"></a>
<!--l. 8138--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set bars </span>command controls the tics at the ends of error bars, and also at the end of the whiskers belonging to a
boxplot.
<!--l. 8141--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;bars</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{small</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;large</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fullwidth</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;size&#x003E;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{front</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;back}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;bars</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;bars</span>
<!--l. 8147--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 8150--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">small </span>is a synonym for 0.0, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">large </span>for 1.0. The default is 1.0 if no size is given.
<!--l. 8153--><p class="noindent" >The keyword <span 
class="cmbx-10">fullwidth </span>is relevant only to boxplots and to histograms with errorbars. It sets the width of the
errorbar ends to be the same as the width of the associated box. It does not change the width of the box
itself.
<!--l. 8157--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">front </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">back </span>keywords are relevant only to errorbars attached to filled rectangles (boxes, candlesticks,
histograms).
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-197000III"></a>Bind</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-390"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-197001"></a>
<!--l. 8164--><p class="noindent" >Show the current state of all hotkey bindings. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">bind (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-48000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">43</span><!--tex4ht:ref: bind --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-197002"></a>.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-198000III"></a>Bmargin</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-392"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-198001"></a>
<!--l. 8171--><p class="noindent" >The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set bmargin </span>sets the size of the bottom margin. Please see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set margin (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-242000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">170</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set margin --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-198002"></a> for
details.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-199000III"></a>Border</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-394"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-199001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-199002"></a>
<!--l. 8185--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set border </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">unset border </span>commands control the display of the graph borders for the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>
commands. Note that the borders do not necessarily coincide with the axes; with <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>they often do, but with <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>
they usually do not.
<!--l. 8190--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;border</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;integer&#x003E;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{front</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;back}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{linewidth</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lw</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;line_width&#x003E;}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{{linestyle</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ls</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;line_style&#x003E;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{linetype</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lt</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;line_type&#x003E;}}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;border</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;border</span>
<!--l. 8197--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 8200--><p class="noindent" >With a <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>displayed in an arbitrary orientation, like <span 
class="cmbx-10">set view 56,103</span>, the four corners of the x-y plane can
be referred to as <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>front<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>back<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>left<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>and <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>right<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. A similar set of four corners exist for the top
surface, of course. Thus the border connecting, say, the back and right corners of the x-y plane is
the <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>bottom right back<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>border, and the border connecting the top and bottom front corners is the
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>front vertical<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. (This nomenclature is defined solely to allow the reader to figure out the table that
follows.)
<!--l. 8208--><p class="noindent" >The borders are encoded in a 12-bit integer: the bottom four bits control the border for <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and the sides of the
base for <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>; the next four bits control the verticals in <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>; the top four bits control the edges on top
of the <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>. In detail, <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">integer</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>should be the sum of the appropriate entries from the following
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
table:
