<!--l. 8298--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-200000III"></a>Boxwidth</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-396"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-200001"></a>
<!--l. 8306--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set boxwidth </span>command is used to set the default width of boxes in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">boxes</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">boxerrorbars</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">boxplot</span>,
<span 
class="cmbx-10">candlesticks </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">histograms </span>styles.
<!--l. 8309--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;boxwidth</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;width&#x003E;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{absolute|relative}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;boxwidth</span>
<!--l. 8314--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 8317--><p class="noindent" >By default, adjacent boxes are extended in width until they touch each other. A different default width may be
specified using the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set boxwidth </span>command. <span 
class="cmbx-10">Relative </span>widths are interpreted as being a fraction of this default
width.
<!--l. 8321--><p class="noindent" >An explicit value for the boxwidth is interpreted as being a number of units along the current x axis
(<span 
class="cmbx-10">absolute</span>) unless the modifier <span 
class="cmbx-10">relative </span>is given. If the x axis is a log-scale (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set log (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-239000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">168</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set log --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-200002"></a>) then the
value of boxwidth is truly <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>absolute<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>only at x=1; this physical width is maintained everywhere along
the axis (i.e. the boxes do not become narrower the value of x increases). If the range spanned by
a log scale x axis is far from x=1, some experimentation may be required to find a useful value of
boxwidth.
<!--l. 8329--><p class="noindent" >The default is superseded by explicit width information taken from an extra data column in styles <span 
class="cmbx-10">boxes </span>or
<span 
class="cmbx-10">boxerrorbars</span>. In a four-column data set, the fourth column will be interpreted as the box width unless the width
is set to -2.0, in which case the width will be calculated automatically. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">style boxes (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-63000II"><span 
class="cmbx-10">54</span><!--tex4ht:ref: style boxes --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-200003"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">style</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">boxerrorbars (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-62000II"><span 
class="cmbx-10">54</span><!--tex4ht:ref: style boxerrorbars --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-200004"></a> for more details.
<!--l. 8335--><p class="noindent" >To set the box width to automatic use the command <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;boxwidth</span>
<!--l. 8339--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 8342--><p class="noindent" >or, for four-column data, <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;boxwidth</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-2</span>
<!--l. 8346--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 8349--><p class="noindent" >The same effect can be achieved with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>keyword in <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2:3:4:(-2)</span>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 8353--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 8356--><p class="noindent" >To set the box width to half of the automatic size use <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;boxwidth</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0.5</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;relative</span>
<!--l. 8360--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 8363--><p class="noindent" >To set the box width to an absolute value of 2 use <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;boxwidth</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;2</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;absolute</span>
<!--l. 8367--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-201000III"></a>Clabel</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-398"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-201001"></a>
<!--l. 8379--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>will vary the linetype used for each contour level when clabel is set. When this option on (the default), a
legend labels each linestyle with the z level it represents. It is not possible at present to separate the contour labels
from the surface key.
<!--l. 8384--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;clabel</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#8217;&#x003C;format&#x003E;&#8217;}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;clabel</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;clabel</span>
<!--l. 8390--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 8393--><p class="noindent" >The default for the format string is %8.3g, which gives three decimal places. This may produce poor label alignment
if the key is altered from its default configuration.
<!--l. 8397--><p class="noindent" >The first contour linetype, or only contour linetype when clabel is off, is the surface linetype +1; contour points are
the same style as surface points.
<!--l. 8400--><p class="noindent" >See also <span 
class="cmbx-10">set contour (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-206000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">141</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set contour --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-201002"></a>.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-202000III"></a>Clip</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-400"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-202001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-202002"></a>
<!--l. 8413--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>can clip data points and lines that are near the boundaries of a graph.
<!--l. 8416--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;clip</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;clip-type&#x003E;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;clip</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;clip-type&#x003E;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;clip</span>
<!--l. 8422--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 8425--><p class="noindent" >Three clip types for points and lines are supported by <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot</span>: <span 
class="cmbx-10">points</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">one</span>, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">two</span>. One, two, or all three
clip types may be active for a single graph. Note that clipping of color filled quadrangles drawn by
<span 
class="cmbx-10">pm3d </span>maps and surfaces is not controlled by this command, but by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set pm3d clip1in </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set pm3d</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">clip4in</span>.
<!--l. 8432--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">points </span>clip type forces <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>to clip (actually, not plot at all) data points that fall within but too close to
the boundaries. This is done so that large symbols used for points will not extend outside the boundary lines.
Without clipping points near the boundaries, the plot may look bad. Adjusting the x and y ranges may give similar
results.
<!--l. 8438--><p class="noindent" >Setting the <span 
class="cmbx-10">one </span>clip type causes <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>to draw a line segment which has only one of its two endpoints within the
graph. Only the in-range portion of the line is drawn. The alternative is to not draw any portion of the line
segment.
<!--l. 8443--><p class="noindent" >Some lines may have both endpoints out of range, but pass through the graph. Setting the <span 
class="cmbx-10">two </span>clip-type allows the
visible portion of these lines to be drawn.
<!--l. 8447--><p class="noindent" >In no case is a line drawn outside the graph.
<!--l. 8449--><p class="noindent" >The defaults are <span 
class="cmbx-10">noclip points</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">clip one</span>, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">noclip two</span>.
<!--l. 8451--><p class="noindent" >To check the state of all forms of clipping, use <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;clip</span>
<!--l. 8455--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 8458--><p class="noindent" >For backward compatibility with older versions, the following forms are also permitted: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;clip</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;clip</span>
<!--l. 8464--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 8467--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">set clip </span>is synonymous with <span 
class="cmbx-10">set clip points</span>; <span 
class="cmbx-10">unset clip </span>turns off all three types of clipping.
