<!--l. 8496--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 8499--><p class="noindent" >This command has two functions. First, it sets the values of z for which contour points are to be determined (by
linear interpolation between data points or function isosamples.) Second, it controls the way contours are drawn
between the points determined to be of equal z. <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>n<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>should be an integral constant expression and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>z1<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>, <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>z2<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>...
any constant expressions. The parameters are:
<!--l. 8506--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">linear</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">cubicspline</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">bspline </span>&#8212; Controls type of approximation or interpolation. If <span 
class="cmbx-10">linear</span>, then straight line
segments connect points of equal z magnitude. If <span 
class="cmbx-10">cubicspline</span>, then piecewise-linear contours are interpolated
between the same equal z points to form somewhat smoother contours, but which may undulate. If
<span 
class="cmbx-10">bspline</span>, a guaranteed-smoother curve is drawn, which only approximates the position of the points of
equal-z.
<!--l. 8513--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">points </span>&#8212; Eventually all drawings are done with piecewise-linear strokes. This number controls the number of line
segments used to approximate the <span 
class="cmbx-10">bspline </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">cubicspline </span>curve. Number of cubicspline or bspline segments
(strokes) = <span 
class="cmbx-10">points </span>* number of linear segments.
<!--l. 8518--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">order </span>&#8212; Order of the bspline approximation to be used. The bigger this order is, the smoother the resulting
contour. (Of course, higher order bspline curves will move further away from the original piecewise linear data.) This
option is relevant for <span 
class="cmbx-10">bspline </span>mode only. Allowed values are integers in the range from 2 (linear) to
10.
<!--l. 8524--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">levels </span>&#8212; Selection of contour levels, controlled by <span 
class="cmbx-10">auto </span>(default), <span 
class="cmbx-10">discrete</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">incremental</span>, and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>n<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>, number of
contour levels.
<!--l. 8527--><p class="noindent" >For <span 
class="cmbx-10">auto</span>, <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>n<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>specifies a nominal number of levels; the actual number will be adjusted to give simple labels.
If the surface is bounded by zmin and zmax, contours will be generated at integer multiples of dz
between zmin and zmax, where dz is 1, 2, or 5 times some power of ten (like the step between two tic
marks).
<!--l. 8533--><p class="noindent" >For <span 
class="cmbx-10">levels discrete</span>, contours will be generated at z = <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>z1<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>, <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>z2<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>... as specified; the number of
discrete levels sets the number of contour levels. In <span 
class="cmbx-10">discrete </span>mode, any <span 
class="cmbx-10">set cntrparam levels </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">n</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>are
ignored.
<!--l. 8537--><p class="noindent" >For <span 
class="cmbx-10">incremental</span>, contours are generated at values of z beginning at <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>start<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>and increasing by <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>increment<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>, until
the number of contours is reached. <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>end<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is used to determine the number of contour levels, which will be changed
by any subsequent <span 
class="cmbx-10">set cntrparam levels </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">n</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. If the z axis is logarithmic, <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>increment<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>will be interpreted as a
factor, just like in <span 
class="cmbx-10">set ztics</span>.
<!--l. 8543--><p class="noindent" >If the command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set cntrparam </span>is given without any arguments specified, the defaults are used: linear, 5 points,
order 4, 5 auto levels.
