class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-204005"></a>.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-205000III"></a>Colornames</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-406"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-205001"></a>
<!--l. 8681--><p class="noindent" >Gnuplot knows a limited number of color names. You can use these to define the color range spanned by a pm3d
palette, or to assign a terminal-independent color to a particular linetype or linestyle. To see the list of known color
names, use the command <span 
class="cmbx-10">show colornames (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-205000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">141</span><!--tex4ht:ref: show colornames --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-205002"></a>. Example:
<!--l. 8687--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;style</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;line</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;linecolor</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;rgb</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"sea-green"</span>
<!--l. 8689--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-206000III"></a>Contour</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-408"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-206001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-206002"></a>
<!--l. 8703--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">set contour </span>enables contour drawing for surfaces. This option is available for <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>only. It requires grid data, see
<span 
class="cmbx-10">grid</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">_data (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-374000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">235</span><!--tex4ht:ref: grid_data --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-206003"></a> for more details. If contours are desired from non-grid data, <span 
class="cmbx-10">set dgrid3d </span>can be used to
create an appropriate grid.
<!--l. 8708--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;contour</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{base</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;surface</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;both}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;contour</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;contour</span>
<!--l. 8714--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 8717--><p class="noindent" >The three options specify where to draw the contours: <span 
class="cmbx-10">base </span>draws the contours on the grid base where the x/ytics
are placed, <span 
class="cmbx-10">surface </span>draws the contours on the surfaces themselves, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">both </span>draws the contours on both the base
and the surface. If no option is provided, the default is <span 
class="cmbx-10">base</span>.
<!--l. 8722--><p class="noindent" >See also <span 
class="cmbx-10">set cntrparam (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-203000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">138</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set cntrparam --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-206004"></a> for the parameters that affect the drawing of contours, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set clabel (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-201000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">137</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set clabel --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-206005"></a>
for control of labelling of the contours.
<!--l. 8725--><p class="noindent" >The surface can be switched off (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set surface (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-305000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">207</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set surface --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-206006"></a>), giving a contour-only graph. Though it is possible to
use <span 
class="cmbx-10">set size </span>to enlarge the plot to fill the screen, more control over the output format can be obtained by writing
the contour information to a file, and rereading it as a 2D datafile plot:
<!--l. 8731--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
