<!--l. 8859--><p class="noindent" >The first <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>will recognize only the first datum in the <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>3 ?<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>line. It will use the single-datum-on-a-line convention
that the line number is <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>x<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>and the datum is <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>y<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, so the point will be plotted (in this case erroneously) at
(2,3).
<!--l. 8864--><p class="noindent" >The second and third <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>commands will correctly ignore the middle line. The plotted line will connect the points
at (2,20) and (4,40).
<!--l. 8867--><p class="noindent" >The fourth <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>will also correctly ignore the middle line, but the plotted line will not connect the points at (2,20)
and (4,40).
<!--l. 8870--><p class="noindent" >There is no default character for <span 
class="cmbx-10">missing</span>, but in many cases any non-parsible string of characters found where a
numerical value is expected will be treated as missing data.
<!--l. 8874--><p class="noindent" >
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-212000III"></a>Set datafile separator</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-420"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-212001"></a>
<!--l. 8881--><p class="noindent" >The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set datafile separator </span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">char</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>tells <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>that data fields in subsequent input
files are separated by <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>char<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>rather than by whitespace. The most common use is to read in csv
(comma-separated value) files written by spreadsheet or database programs. By default data fields are separated by
whitespace.
<!--l. 8887--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;datafile</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;separator</span><span 
