<!--l. 9197--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set dummy </span>command changes the default dummy variable names.
<!--l. 9199--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;dummy</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;dummy-var&#x003E;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{,&#x003C;dummy-var&#x003E;}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;dummy</span>
<!--l. 9204--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 9207--><p class="noindent" >By default, <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>assumes that the independent, or <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>dummy<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, variable for the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command is <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>t<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>
if in parametric or polar mode, or <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>x<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>otherwise. Similarly the independent variables for the <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>
command are <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>u<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>and <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>v<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>in parametric mode (<span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>cannot be used in polar mode), or <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>x<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>and <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>y<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>
otherwise.
<!--l. 9213--><p class="noindent" >It may be more convenient to call a dummy variable by a more physically meaningful or conventional name. For
example, when plotting time functions:
<!--l. 9217--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;dummy</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;t</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sin(t),</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;cos(t)</span>
<!--l. 9220--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 9223--><p class="noindent" >At least one dummy variable must be set on the command; <span 
class="cmbx-10">set dummy </span>by itself will generate an error
message.
<!--l. 9226--><p class="noindent" >Examples: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
