<!--l. 9282--><p class="noindent" >The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set encoding locale </span>is different from the other options. It attempts to determine the current locale
from the runtime environment. On most systems this is controlled by the environmental variables LC_ALL,
LC_CTYPE, or LANG. This mechanism is necessary, for example, to pass multibyte character encodings
such as UTF-8 or EUC_JP to the wxt and cairopdf terminals. This command does not affect the
locale-specific representation of dates or numbers. See also <span 
class="cmbx-10">set locale (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-238000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">168</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set locale --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-218005"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set decimalsign</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-215000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">146</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set decimalsign --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-218006"></a>.
<!--l. 9291--><p class="noindent" >Generally you must set the encoding before setting the terminal type. Note that encoding is not supported by all
terminal drivers and that the device must be able to produce the desired non-standard characters.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-219000III"></a>Fit</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-434"></a>
<!--l. 9300--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">fit </span>setting defines where the <span 
class="cmbx-10">fit </span>command writes its output.
<!--l. 9302--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fit</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{logfile</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{"&#x003C;filename&#x003E;"}}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{{no}errorvariables}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{{no}quiet}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fit</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fit</span>
<!--l. 9308--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 9311--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>filename<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>argument must be enclosed in single or double quotes.
<!--l. 9313--><p class="noindent" >If no filename is given or <span 
class="cmbx-10">unset fit </span>is used the log file is reset to its default value <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>fit.log<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>or the value of the
environmental variable <span 
class="cmbx-10">FIT</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">_LOG</span>.
<!--l. 9317--><p class="noindent" >If the given logfile name ends with a / or <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>, it is interpreted to be a directory name, and the actual filename will be
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>fit.log<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>in that directory.
<!--l. 9321--><p class="noindent" >If the <span 
class="cmbx-10">errorvariables </span>option is turned on, the error of each fitted parameter computed by <span 
class="cmbx-10">fit </span>will be copied to a
user-defined variable whose name is formed by appending <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>_err<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>to the name of the parameter itself. This is useful
mainly to put the parameter and its error onto a plot of the data and the fitted function, for reference, as
in:
<!--l. 9328--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fit</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;errorvariables</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fit</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;f(x)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;datafile&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;via</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;a,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;b</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;print</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"error</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;of</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;a</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;is:",</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;a_err</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;label</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;a=%6.2f&#8217;,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;a,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;+/-</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;%6.2f&#8217;,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;a_err</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;datafile&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;f(x)</span>
<!--l. 9334--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 9337--><p class="noindent" >By default the information written to the log file is also echoed to the terminal session. <span 
class="cmbx-10">set fit quiet </span>turns off the
echo.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-220000III"></a>Fontpath</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-436"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-220001"></a>
<!--l. 9347--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">fontpath </span>setting defines additional locations for font files searched when including font files. Currently only the
postscript terminal supports <span 
class="cmbx-10">fontpath</span>. If a file cannot be found in the current directory, the directories in <span 
class="cmbx-10">fontpath</span>
are tried. Further documentation concerning the supported file formats is included in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">terminal postscript</span>
section of the documentation.
<!--l. 9354--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fontpath</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{"pathlist1"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{"pathlist2"...}}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fontpath</span>
<!--l. 9359--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 9362--><p class="noindent" >Path names may be entered as single directory names, or as a list of path names separated by a platform-specific
path separator, eg. colon (&#8217;:&#8217;) on Unix, semicolon (&#8217;;&#8217;) on DOS/Windows/OS/2 platforms. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">show fontpath</span>,
<span 
class="cmbx-10">save </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">save set </span>commands replace the platform-specific separator with a space character (&#8217; &#8217;) for maximum
portability. If a directory name ends with an exclamation mark (&#8217;!&#8217;) also the subdirectories of this directory are
searched for font files.
<!--l. 9370--><p class="noindent" >If the environmental variable GNUPLOT_FONTPATH is set, its contents are appended to <span 
class="cmbx-10">fontpath</span>. If it is not
set, a system dependent default value is used. It is set by testing several directories for existence when using the
fontpath the first time. Thus, the first call of <span 
class="cmbx-10">set fontpath</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">show fontpath</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">save fontpath</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>, or <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>with
embedded font files takes a little more time. If you want to save this time you may set the environmental variable
GNUPLOT_FONTPATH since probing is switched off, then. You can find out which is the default fontpath by
using <span 
class="cmbx-10">show fontpath</span>.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 9380--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">show fontpath </span>prints the contents of the user-defined fontpath and the system fontpath separately. However, the
<span 
class="cmbx-10">save </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">save set </span>commands save only the user-specified parts of <span 
class="cmbx-10">fontpath</span>.
<!--l. 9384--><p class="noindent" >For terminal drivers that access fonts by filename via the gd library, the font search path is controlled by the
environmental variable GDFONTPATH.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-221000III"></a>Format</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-438"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-221001"></a>
<!--l. 9395--><p class="noindent" >The format of the tic-mark labels can be set with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set format </span>command or with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set tics format </span>or
individual <span 
class="cmbx-10">set </span><span 
class="cmbsy-10">{</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">axis</span><span 
class="cmbsy-10">}</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">tics format </span>commands.
<!--l. 9398--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;format</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;axes&#x003E;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{"&#x003C;format-string&#x003E;"}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;format</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;axes&#x003E;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#8217;&#x003C;format-string&#x003E;&#8217;}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;format</span>
<!--l. 9404--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 9407--><p class="noindent" >where <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>axes<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is either <span 
class="cmbx-10">x</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">y</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">xy</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">x2</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">y2</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">z</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">cb </span>or nothing (which applies the format to all axes). The following two
commands are equivalent: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;format</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"%.2f"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ytics</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;format</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"%.2f"</span>
<!--l. 9414--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 9417--><p class="noindent" >The length of the string is restricted to 100 characters. The default format is <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>% g<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, but other formats such as
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>%.2f<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>or <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>%3.0em<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>are often desirable. The format <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>$%g$<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is often desirable for LaTeX. If no format string is
given, the format will be returned to the default. If the empty string <span 
class="cmtt-10">"" </span>is given, tics will have no labels,
although the tic mark will still be plotted. To eliminate the tic marks, use <span 
class="cmbx-10">unset xtics </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">set tics scale</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">0</span>.
<!--l. 9424--><p class="noindent" >Newline (<span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>n) and enhanced text markup is accepted in the format string. Use double-quotes rather than
single-quotes in this case. See also <span 
class="cmbx-10">syntax (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-58000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">51</span><!--tex4ht:ref: syntax --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-221002"></a>. Characters not preceded by <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>%<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>are printed verbatim. Thus
you can include spaces and labels in your format string, such as <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>%g m<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, which will put <span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>m<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>after each number. If
you want <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>%<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>itself, double it: <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>%g %%<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.
<!--l. 9430--><p class="noindent" >See also <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xtics (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-335000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">220</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set xtics --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-221003"></a> for more information about tic labels, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set decimalsign (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-215000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">146</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set decimalsign --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-221004"></a> for how to use
non-default decimal separators in numbers printed this way. See also
<!--l. 9434--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/electron.html" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">electron demo (electron.dem). </span></a>
<!--l. 9437--><p class="noindent" >
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-222000III"></a>Gprintf</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-440"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-222001"></a>
<!--l. 9441--><p class="noindent" >The string function gprintf(<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>format<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>,x) uses gnuplot&#8217;s own format specifiers, as do the gnuplot commands <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">format</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">set timestamp</span>, and others. These format specifiers are not the same as those used by the standard
C-language routine sprintf(). gprintf() accepts only a single variable to be formatted. Gnuplot also provides an
sprintf(<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>format<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>,x1,x2,...) routine if you prefer. For a list of gnuplot&#8217;s format options, see <span 
class="cmbx-10">format specifiers</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-223000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">153</span><!--tex4ht:ref: format specifiers --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-222002"></a>.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
