<!--l. 9664--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 9667--><p class="noindent" >The grid can be enabled and disabled for the major and/or minor tic marks on any axis, and the linetype and
linewidth can be specified for major and minor grid lines, also via a predefined linestyle, as far as the active terminal
driver supports this.
<!--l. 9672--><p class="noindent" >Additionally, a polar grid can be selected for 2D plots &#8212; circles are drawn to intersect the selected
tics, and radial lines are drawn at definable intervals. (The interval is given in degrees or radians,
depending on the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set angles </span>setting.) Note that a polar grid is no longer automatically generated in polar
mode.
<!--l. 9678--><p class="noindent" >The pertinent tics must be enabled before <span 
class="cmbx-10">set grid </span>can draw them; <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>will quietly ignore instructions to draw
grid lines at non-existent tics, but they will appear if the tics are subsequently enabled.
<!--l. 9682--><p class="noindent" >If no linetype is specified for the minor gridlines, the same linetype as the major gridlines is used. The default polar
angle is 30 degrees.
<!--l. 9685--><p class="noindent" >If <span 
class="cmbx-10">front </span>is given, the grid is drawn on top of the graphed data. If <span 
class="cmbx-10">back </span>is given, the grid is drawn
underneath the graphed data. Using <span 
class="cmbx-10">front </span>will prevent the grid from being obscured by dense data. The
default setup, <span 
class="cmbx-10">layerdefault</span>, is equivalent to <span 
class="cmbx-10">back </span>for 2D plots. In 3D plots the default is to split up
the grid and the graph box into two layers: one behind, the other in front of the plotted data and
functions. Since <span 
class="cmbx-10">hidden3d </span>mode does its own sorting, it ignores all grid drawing order options and
passes the grid lines through the hidden line removal machinery instead. These options actually affect
not only the grid, but also the lines output by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set border </span>and the various ticmarks (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xtics</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-335000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">220</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set xtics --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-227003"></a>).
<!--l. 9697--><p class="noindent" >Z grid lines are drawn on the bottom of the plot. This looks better if a partial box is drawn around the plot &#8212; see
<span 
class="cmbx-10">set border (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-199000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">134</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set border --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-227004"></a>.
