<!--l. 9839--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-229000III"></a>Historysize</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-454"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-229001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-229002"></a>
<!--l. 9848--><p class="noindent" >Note: the command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set historysize </span>is only available when gnuplot has been configured to use the GNU readline
library.
<!--l. 9851--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;historysize</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;int&#x003E;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;historysize</span>
<!--l. 9856--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 9859--><p class="noindent" >When leaving gnuplot, the value of historysize is used for truncating the history to at most that much lines. The
default is 500. <span 
class="cmbx-10">unset historysize </span>will disable history truncation and thus allow an infinite number of lines to be
written to the history file.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-230000III"></a>Isosamples</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-456"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-230001"></a>
<!--l. 9873--><p class="noindent" >The isoline density (grid) for plotting functions as surfaces may be changed by the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set isosamples</span>
command.
<!--l. 9876--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;isosamples</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;iso_1&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{,&#x003C;iso_2&#x003E;}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;isosamples</span>
<!--l. 9881--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 9884--><p class="noindent" >Each function surface plot will have <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>iso_1<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>iso-u lines and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>iso_2<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>iso-v lines. If you only specify <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>iso_1<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>,
<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>iso_2<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>will be set to the same value as <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>iso_1<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. By default, sampling is set to 10 isolines per u or v axis. A higher
sampling rate will produce more accurate plots, but will take longer. These parameters have no effect on data file
plotting.
<!--l. 9890--><p class="noindent" >An isoline is a curve parameterized by one of the surface parameters while the other surface parameter is fixed.
Isolines provide a simple means to display a surface. By fixing the u parameter of surface s(u,v), the iso-u lines of
the form c(v) = s(u0,v) are produced, and by fixing the v parameter, the iso-v lines of the form c(u) = s(u,v0) are
produced.
<!--l. 9896--><p class="noindent" >When a function surface plot is being done without the removal of hidden lines, <span 
class="cmbx-10">set samples </span>controls the number of
points sampled along each isoline; see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set samples (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-291000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">197</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set samples --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-230002"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set hidden3d (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-228000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">156</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set hidden3d --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-230003"></a>. The contour algorithm
assumes that a function sample occurs at each isoline intersection, so change in <span 
class="cmbx-10">samples </span>as well as <span 
class="cmbx-10">isosamples </span>may
be desired when changing the resolution of a function surface/contour.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-231000III"></a>Key</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-458"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-231001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-231002"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-231003"></a>
<!--l. 9916--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set key </span>command enables a key (or legend) describing plots on a plot.
<!--l. 9918--><p class="noindent" >The contents of the key, i.e., the names given to each plotted data set and function and samples of the lines and/or
symbols used to represent them, are determined by the <span 
class="cmbx-10">title </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">with </span>options of the <span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">s</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command. Please see
<span 
class="cmbx-10">plot title (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-179000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">119</span><!--tex4ht:ref: plot title --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-231004"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot with (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-180000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">120</span><!--tex4ht:ref: plot with --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-231005"></a> for more information.
