<!--l. 9946--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 9949--><p class="noindent" >The key contains a title and a sample (line, point, box) for each plot in the graph. The key may be turned off by
requesting <span 
class="cmbx-10">set key off </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">unset key</span>. Individual key entries may be turned off by using the <span 
class="cmbx-10">notitle </span>keyword in the
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
corresponding plot command.
<!--l. 9954--><p class="noindent" >Elements within the key are stacked according to <span 
class="cmbx-10">vertical </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">horizontal</span>. In the case of <span 
class="cmbx-10">vertical</span>, the key occupies
as few columns as possible. That is, elements are aligned in a column until running out of vertical space at
which point a new column is started. The vertical space may be limited using &#8217;maxrows&#8217;. In the case
of <span 
class="cmbx-10">horizontal</span>, the key occupies as few rows as possible. The horizontal space may be limited using
&#8217;maxcols&#8217;.
<!--l. 9961--><p class="noindent" >By default the key is placed in the upper right inside corner of the graph. The keywords <span 
class="cmbx-10">left</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">right</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">top</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">bottom</span>,
<span 
class="cmbx-10">center</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">inside</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">outside</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">lmargin</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">rmargin</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">tmargin</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">bmargin </span>(, <span 
class="cmbx-10">above</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">over</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">below </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">under</span>) may be used
to automatically place the key in other positions of the graph. Also an <span 
class="cmbx-10">at </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">position</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>may be given to
indicate precisely where the plot should be placed. In this case, the keywords <span 
class="cmbx-10">left</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">right</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">top</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">bottom</span>
and <span 
class="cmbx-10">center </span>serve an analogous purpose for alignment. For more information, see <span 
class="cmbx-10">key placement</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-232000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">161</span><!--tex4ht:ref: key placement --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-231006"></a>.
<!--l. 9970--><p class="noindent" >Justification of the plot titles within the key is controlled by <span 
class="cmbx-10">Left </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">Right </span>(default). The text and sample can be
reversed (<span 
class="cmbx-10">reverse</span>) and a box can be drawn around the key (<span 
class="cmbx-10">box </span><span 
class="cmbsy-10">{</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">...</span><span 
class="cmbsy-10">}</span>) in a specified <span 
class="cmbx-10">linetype </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">linewidth</span>, or a
user-defined <span 
class="cmbx-10">linestyle</span>.
<!--l. 9975--><p class="noindent" >By default the key is built up one plot at a time. That is, the key symbol and title are drawn at the same time as
the corresponding plot. That means newer plots may sometimes place elements on top of the key. <span 
class="cmbx-10">set key opaque</span>
causes the key to be generated after all the plots. In this case the key area is filled with background color and then
the key symbols and titles are written. Therefore the key itself may obscure portions of some plot elements. The
default can be restored by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set key noopaque</span>.
<!--l. 9983--><p class="noindent" >By default the first plot label is at the top of the key and successive labels are entered below it. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">invert </span>option
causes the first label to be placed at the bottom of the key, with successive labels entered above it. This option is
useful to force the vertical ordering of labels in the key to match the order of box types in a stacked
histogram.
<!--l. 9989--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>height_increment<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is a number of character heights to be added to or subtracted from the height of the key
box. This is useful mainly when you are putting a box around the key and want larger borders around the key
entries.
<!--l. 9993--><p class="noindent" >All plotted curves of <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>s and <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>s are titled according to the default option <span 
class="cmbx-10">autotitles</span>. The automatic
generation of titles can be suppressed by <span 
class="cmbx-10">noautotitles</span>; then only those titles explicitly defined by <span 
class="cmbx-10">(s)plot ... title</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">... </span>will be drawn.
<a 
 id="dx1-231007"></a>
<!--l. 9999--><p class="noindent" >The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set key autotitle columnheader </span>causes the first entry in each column of input data to
be interpreted as a text string and used as a title for the corresponding plot. If the quantity being
plotted is a function of data from several columns, gnuplot may be confused as to which column to
draw the title from. In this case it is necessary to specify the column explicitly in the plot command,
e.g.
<!--l. 10007--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"datafile"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(($2+$3)/$4)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;columnhead(3)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lines</span>
<!--l. 10009--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 10012--><p class="noindent" >An overall title can be put on the key (<span 
class="cmbx-10">title </span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">text</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>) &#8212; see also <span 
class="cmbx-10">syntax (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-58000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">51</span><!--tex4ht:ref: syntax --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-231008"></a> for the distinction between
text in single- or double-quotes. The key title uses the same justification as do the plot titles.
<!--l. 10016--><p class="noindent" >The defaults for <span 
class="cmbx-10">set key </span>are <span 
class="cmbx-10">on</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">right</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">top</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">vertical</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">Right</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">noreverse</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">noinvert</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">samplen 4</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">spacing 1.25</span>,
<span 
class="cmbx-10">title </span><span 
class="cmtt-10">""</span>, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">nobox</span>. The default <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>linetype<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is the same as that used for the plot borders. Entering <span 
class="cmbx-10">set key</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">default </span>returns the key to its default configuration.
<!--l. 10022--><p class="noindent" >The key is drawn as a sequence of lines, with one plot described on each line. On the right-hand side (or the
left-hand side, if <span 
class="cmbx-10">reverse </span>is selected) of each line is a representation that attempts to mimic the way the curve is
plotted. On the other side of each line is the text description (the line title), obtained from the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command. The
lines are vertically arranged so that an imaginary straight line divides the left- and right-hand sides of the key. It is
the coordinates of the top of this line that are specified with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set key </span>command. In a <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>, only the x and y
coordinates are used to specify the line position. For a <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>, x, y and z are all used as a 3D location mapped
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
using the same mapping as the graph itself to form the required 2D screen position of the imaginary
line.
<!--l. 10034--><p class="noindent" >When using the TeX or other terminals where formatting information is embedded in the string, <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>can only
estimate the correctly exact width of the string for key positioning. If the key is to be positioned at the left, it may
be convenient to use the combination <span 
class="cmbx-10">set key left Left reverse</span>.
<!--l. 10039--><p class="noindent" >If <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>is being used to draw contours, the contour labels will be listed in the key. If the alignment of these labels is
poor or a different number of decimal places is desired, the label format can be specified. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set clabel (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-201000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">137</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set clabel --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-231009"></a>
for details.
<!--l. 10044--><p class="noindent" >Examples:
<!--l. 10046--><p class="noindent" >This places the key at the default location: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;key</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;default</span>
<!--l. 10050--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 10053--><p class="noindent" >This disables the key: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;key</span>
<!--l. 10057--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 10060--><p class="noindent" >This places a key at coordinates 2,3.5,2 in the default (first) coordinate system: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;key</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;at</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;2,3.5,2</span>
<!--l. 10065--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 10068--><p class="noindent" >This places the key below the graph: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;key</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;below</span>
<!--l. 10072--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 10075--><p class="noindent" >This places the key in the bottom left corner, left-justifies the text, gives it a title, and draws a box around it in
linetype 3: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;key</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;left</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;bottom</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Left</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;Legend&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;box</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;3</span>
<!--l. 10080--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-232000III"></a>Key placement</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-460"></a>
<!--l. 10087--><p class="noindent" >To understand positioning, the best concept is to think of a region, i.e., inside/outside, or one of the margins. Along
with the region, keywords <span 
class="cmbx-10">left/center/right </span>(l/c/r) and <span 
class="cmbx-10">top/center/bottom </span>(t/c/b) control where within the
particular region the key should be placed.
<!--l. 10092--><p class="noindent" >When in <span 
class="cmbx-10">inside </span>mode, the keywords <span 
class="cmbx-10">left </span>(l), <span 
class="cmbx-10">right </span>(r), <span 
class="cmbx-10">top </span>(t), <span 
class="cmbx-10">bottom </span>(b), and <span 
class="cmbx-10">center </span>(c) push the key out
toward the plot boundary as illustrated:
<!--l. 10097--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;t/l</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;t/c</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;t/r</span>
<!--l. 10099--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 10103--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;c/l</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;c</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;c/r</span>
<!--l. 10105--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 10109--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;b/l</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;b/c</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;b/r</span>
<!--l. 10111--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 10115--><p class="noindent" >When in <span 
class="cmbx-10">outside </span>mode, automatic placement is similar to the above illustration, but with respect to the view,
rather than the graph boundary. That is, a border is moved inward to make room for the key outside of the
plotting area, although this may interfere with other labels and may cause an error on some devices. The
particular plot border that is moved depends upon the position described above and the stacking
direction. For options centered in one of the dimensions, there is no ambiguity about which border to
move. For the corners, when the stack direction is <span 
class="cmbx-10">vertical</span>, the left or right border is moved inward
appropriately. When the stack direction is <span 
class="cmbx-10">horizontal</span>, the top or bottom border is moved inward
appropriately.
<!--l. 10126--><p class="noindent" >The margin syntax allows automatic placement of key regardless of stack direction. When one of the margins
<span 
class="cmbx-10">lmargin </span>(lm), <span 
class="cmbx-10">rmargin </span>(rm), <span 
class="cmbx-10">tmargin </span>(tm), and <span 
class="cmbx-10">bmargin </span>(bm) is combined with a single, non-conflicting
direction keyword, the following illustrated positions may contain the key:
<!--l. 10132--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
