<!--l. 10236--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 10239--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>position<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is specified by either x,y or x,y,z, and may be preceded by <span 
class="cmbx-10">first</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">second</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">graph</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">screen</span>, or
<span 
class="cmbx-10">character </span>to select the coordinate system. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">coordinates (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-20000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">24</span><!--tex4ht:ref: coordinates --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-234003"></a> for details.
<!--l. 10243--><p class="noindent" >The tag is an integer that is used to identify the label. If no <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>tag<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is given, the lowest unused tag value is assigned
automatically. The tag can be used to delete or modify a specific label. To change any attribute of an existing
label, use the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set label </span>command with the appropriate tag, and specify the parts of the label to be
changed.
<!--l. 10249--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>label text<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>can be a string constant, a string variable, or a string- valued expression. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">strings (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-53000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">47</span><!--tex4ht:ref: strings --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-234004"></a>,
<span 
class="cmbx-10">sprintf (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-25000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">30</span><!--tex4ht:ref: sprintf --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-234005"></a>, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">gprintf (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-222000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">152</span><!--tex4ht:ref: gprintf --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-234006"></a>.
<!--l. 10252--><p class="noindent" >By default, the text is placed flush left against the point x,y,z. To adjust the way the label is positioned with respect
to the point x,y,z, add the justification parameter, which may be <span 
class="cmbx-10">left</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">right </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">center</span>, indicating that the point is
to be at the left, right or center of the text. Labels outside the plotted boundaries are permitted but may interfere
with axis labels or other text.
<!--l. 10259--><p class="noindent" >If <span 
class="cmbx-10">rotate </span>is given, the label is written vertically (if the terminal can do so, of course). If <span 
class="cmbx-10">rotate by </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">degrees</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is
given, conforming terminals will try to write the text at the specified angle; non-conforming terminals will treat this
as vertical text.
<!--l. 10264--><p class="noindent" >Font and its size can be chosen explicitly by <span 
class="cmbx-10">font </span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">name</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmbsy-10">{</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">,</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">size</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmbsy-10">}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>if the terminal supports font settings.
Otherwise the default font of the terminal will be used.
<!--l. 10268--><p class="noindent" >Normally the enhanced text mode string interpretation, if enabled for the current terminal, is applied to all text
strings including label text. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">noenhanced </span>property can be used to exempt a specific label from the enhanced
text mode processing. The can be useful if the label contains underscores, for example. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">enhanced text</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-22000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">26</span><!--tex4ht:ref: enhanced text --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-234007"></a>.
<!--l. 10274--><p class="noindent" >If <span 
class="cmbx-10">front </span>is given, the label is written on top of the graphed data. If <span 
class="cmbx-10">back </span>is given (the default), the label is
written underneath the graphed data. Using <span 
class="cmbx-10">front </span>will prevent a label from being obscured by dense
data.
<!--l. 10278--><p class="noindent" ><span 
