class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>stringvariablename<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">substitution</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-54000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">48</span><!--tex4ht:ref: substitution --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-240001"></a>.
<!--l. 10612--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;macros</span>
<!--l. 10616--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 10619--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-241000III"></a>Mapping</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-478"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-241001"></a>
<!--l. 10627--><p class="noindent" >If data are provided to <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>in spherical or cylindrical coordinates, the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set mapping </span>command should be used to
instruct <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>how to interpret them.
<!--l. 10631--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;mapping</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{cartesian</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;spherical</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;cylindrical}</span>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 10635--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 10638--><p class="noindent" >A cartesian coordinate system is used by default.
<!--l. 10640--><p class="noindent" >For a spherical coordinate system, the data occupy two or three columns (or <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>entries). The first two are
interpreted as the azimuthal and polar angles theta and phi (or <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>longitude<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>and <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>latitude<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>), in the units specified
by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set angles</span>. The radius r is taken from the third column if there is one, or is set to unity if there is no third
column. The mapping is:
<!--l. 10648--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;r</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;*</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;cos(theta)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;*</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;cos(phi)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;r</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;*</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sin(theta)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;*</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;cos(phi)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;z</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;r</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;*</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sin(phi)</span>
<!--l. 10652--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 10655--><p class="noindent" >Note that this is a <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>geographic<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>spherical system, rather than a <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>polar<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>one (that is, phi is measured from the
equator, rather than the pole).
<!--l. 10658--><p class="noindent" >For a cylindrical coordinate system, the data again occupy two or three columns. The first two are interpreted as
theta (in the units specified by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set angles</span>) and z. The radius is either taken from the third column or set to unity,
as in the spherical case. The mapping is:
<!--l. 10664--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;r</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;*</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;cos(theta)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
