<!--l. 10702--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 10705--><p class="noindent" >The default units of <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>margin<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>are character heights or widths, as appropriate. A positive value defines the absolute
size of the margin. A negative value (or none) causes <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>to revert to the computed value. For 3D plots, only
the left margin can be set using character units.
<!--l. 10710--><p class="noindent" >The keywords <span 
class="cmbx-10">at screen </span>indicates that the margin is specified as a fraction of the full drawing area. This can be
used to precisely line up the corners of individual 2D and 3D graphs in a multiplot. This placement ignores the
current values of <span 
class="cmbx-10">set origin </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set size</span>, and is intended as an alternative method for positioning graphs within a
multiplot.
<!--l. 10716--><p class="noindent" >Normally the margins of a plot are automatically calculated based on tics, tic labels, axis labels, the plot title, the
timestamp and the size of the key if it is outside the borders. If, however, tics are attached to the axes (<span 
class="cmbx-10">set xtics</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">axis</span>, for example), neither the tics themselves nor their labels will be included in either the margin calculation or
the calculation of the positions of other text to be written in the margin. This can lead to tic labels overwriting
other text if the axis is very close to the border.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-243000III"></a>Mouse</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-482"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-243001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-243002"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-243003"></a>
<!--l. 10735--><p class="noindent" >The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set mouse </span>enables mouse actions for the current interactive terminal. It is usually
enabled by default in interactive mode, but disabled by default if commands are being read from a
file.
<!--l. 10739--><p class="noindent" >There are two mouse modes. The 2D mode works for <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>commands and for <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>maps (i.e. <span 
class="cmbx-10">set view</span>
with z-rotation 0, 90, 180, 270 or 360 degrees, including <span 
class="cmbx-10">set view map</span>). In this mode the mouse
position is tracked and you can pan or zoom using the mouse buttons or arrow keys. Some terminals
support toggling individual plots on/off by clicking on the corresponding key title or on a separate
widget.
<!--l. 10746--><p class="noindent" >For 3D graphs <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>, the view and scaling of the graph can be changed with mouse buttons 1 and 2, respectively. A
vertical motion of Button 2 with the shift key held down changes the <span 
class="cmbx-10">xyplane</span>. If additionally to these buttons the
modifier <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>ctrl<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is held down, the coordinate axes are displayed but the data are suppressed. This is useful for large
data sets.
<!--l. 10752--><p class="noindent" >Mousing is not available inside multiplot mode. When multiplot is completed using <span 
class="cmbx-10">unset multiplot</span>, then the
mouse will be turned on again but acts only on the most recent plot within the multiplot (like replot
does).
