<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-246000III"></a>Scrolling</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-488"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-246001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-246002"></a>
<!--l. 10855--><p class="noindent" >X and Y axis scaling in both 2D and 3D graphs can be adjusted using the mouse wheel. <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>wheel-up<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>scrolls up
(increases both YMIN and YMAX by ten percent of the Y range, and increases both Y2MIN and Y2MAX likewise),
and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>wheel down<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>scrolls down. <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>shift-wheel-up<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>scrolls left (decreases both XMIN and XMAX,
and both X2MIN and X2MAX), and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>shift-wheel-down<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>scrolls right. <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>control-wheel-up<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>zooms in
toward the center of the plot, and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>control-wheel-down<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>zooms out. <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>shift-control-wheel-up<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>zooms in
along the X and X2 axes only, and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>shift-control-wheel-down<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>zooms out along the X and X2 axes
only.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-247000III"></a>X11 mouse</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-490"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-247001"></a>
<!--l. 10870--><p class="noindent" >If multiple X11 plot windows have been opened using the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term x11 </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">n</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>terminal option, then only the
current plot window supports the entire range of mouse commands and hotkeys. The other windows will, however,
continue to display mouse coordinates at the lower left.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-248000III"></a>Zoom</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-492"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-248001"></a>
<!--l. 10879--><p class="noindent" >Zooming is usually accomplished by holding down the left mouse button and dragging the mouse to delineate a
zoom region. Some platforms may require using a different mouse button. The original plot can be restored by
typing the &#8217;u&#8217; hotkey in the plot window. The hotkeys &#8217;p&#8217; and &#8217;n&#8217; step back and forth through a history of zoom
operations.
<!--l. 10885--><p class="noindent" >The option <span 
class="cmbx-10">zoomcoordinates </span>determines if the coordinates of the zoom box are drawn at the edges while zooming.
This is on by default.
<!--l. 10888--><p class="noindent" >If the option <span 
class="cmbx-10">zoomjump </span>is on, the mouse pointer will be automatically offset a small distance after starting a zoom
region with button 3. This can be useful to avoid a tiny (or even empty) zoom region. <span 
class="cmbx-10">zoomjump </span>is off by
default.
<!--l. 10893--><p class="noindent" >
