class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;origin</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0.1,0.1</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sin(x)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;size</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0.2,0.2</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;origin</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0.5,0.5</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;cos(x)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;multiplot</span>
<!--l. 10956--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 10959--><p class="noindent" >This displays a plot of cos(x) stacked above a plot of sin(x).
<!--l. 10961--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">set size </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set origin </span>refer to the entire plotting area used for each plot. Please also see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term size (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-17000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">23</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set term size --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-249005"></a>.
If you want to have the axes themselves line up, you can guarantee that the margins are the same
size with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set margin </span>commands. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set margin (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-242000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">170</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set margin --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-249006"></a> for their use. Note that the margin
settings are absolute, in character units, so the appearance of the graph in the remaining space will
depend on the screen size of the display device, e.g., perhaps quite different on a video display and a
printer.
<!--l. 10969--><p class="noindent" >With the <span 
class="cmbx-10">layout </span>option you can generate simple multiplots without having to give the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set size </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">origin </span>commands before each plot: Those are generated automatically, but can be overridden at any
time. With <span 
class="cmbx-10">layout </span>the display will be divided by a grid with <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>rows<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>rows and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>cols<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>columns. This
grid is filled rows first or columns first depending on whether the corresponding option is given in the
multiplot command. The stack of plots can grow <span 
class="cmbx-10">downwards </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">upwards</span>. Default is <span 
class="cmbx-10">rowsfirst </span>and
<span 
class="cmbx-10">downwards</span>.
<!--l. 10978--><p class="noindent" >Each plot can be scaled by <span 
class="cmbx-10">scale </span>and shifted with <span 
class="cmbx-10">offset</span>; if the y-values for scale or offset are omitted, the x-value
will be used. <span 
class="cmbx-10">unset multiplot </span>will turn off the automatic layout and restore the values of <span 
class="cmbx-10">set size </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set origin</span>
as they were before <span 
class="cmbx-10">set multiplot layout</span>.
<!--l. 10983--><p class="noindent" >Example: <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;size</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1,1</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;origin</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0,0</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;multiplot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;layout</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;3,2</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;columnsfirst</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;scale</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1.1,0.9</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;up</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;to</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;6</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;commands</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;here</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;]</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;multiplot</span>
<!--l. 10991--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 10994--><p class="noindent" >The above example will produce 6 plots in 2 columns filled top to bottom, left to right. Each plot will have a
horizontal size of 1.1/2 and a vertical size of 0.9/3.
