<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-255000III"></a>Object</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-506"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-255001"></a>
<!--l. 11139--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set object </span>command defines a single object which will appear in all subsequent 2D plots. You may define as
many objects as you like. Currently the supported object types are <span 
class="cmbx-10">rectangle</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">circle</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">ellipse</span>, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">polygon</span>.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
Rectangles inherit a default set of style properties (fill, color, border) from those set by the command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">rectangle</span>, but each object can also be given individual style properties. Circles, ellipses, and polygons inherit the
fill style from <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style fill</span>.
<!--l. 11147--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;object</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;index&#x003E;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;object-type&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;object-properties&#x003E;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{front|back|behind}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{fc|fillcolor</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;colorspec&#x003E;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{fs</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;fillstyle&#x003E;}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{default}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{lw|linewidth</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;width&#x003E;}</span>
<!--l. 11154--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 11157--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>object-type<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is either <span 
class="cmbx-10">rectangle</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">ellipse</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">circle</span>, or <span 
class="cmbx-10">polygon</span>. Each object type has its own set of characteristic
properties.
<!--l. 11160--><p class="noindent" >Setting <span 
class="cmbx-10">front </span>will draw the object in front of all plot elements, but behind any labels that are also marked <span 
class="cmbx-10">front</span>.
Setting <span 
class="cmbx-10">back </span>will place the object behind all plot curves and labels. Setting <span 
class="cmbx-10">behind </span>will place the object behind
everything including the axes and <span 
class="cmbx-10">back </span>rectangles, thus <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;object</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;rectangle</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;from</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;screen</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0,0</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;to</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;screen</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1,1</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;behind</span>
<!--l. 11167--><p class="noindent" ></pre> can be used to provide a colored background for the entire graph or page.
<!--l. 11171--><p class="noindent" >The fill color of the object is taken from the <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>colorspec<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. <span 
class="cmbx-10">fillcolor </span>may be abbreviated <span 
class="cmbx-10">fc</span>. The fill style is taken
from <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>fillstyle<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">colorspec (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-42000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">40</span><!--tex4ht:ref: colorspec --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-255002"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">fillstyle (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-297000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">202</span><!--tex4ht:ref: fillstyle --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-255003"></a>. If the keyword <span 
class="cmbx-10">default </span>is given, these
properties are inherited from the default settings at the time a plot is drawn. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style rectangle</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-303000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">206</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set style rectangle --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-255004"></a>.
