class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;orientation&#x003E;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{units</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xy|xx|yy}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;other-object-properties&#x003E;}</span>
<!--l. 11244--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 11247--><p class="noindent" >The position of the ellipse is specified by giving the center followed by the width and the height (actually the major
and minor axes). The keywords <span 
class="cmbx-10">at </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">center </span>are synonyms. The center position may be given in axis, graph, or
screen coordinates. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">coordinates (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-20000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">24</span><!--tex4ht:ref: coordinates --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-257002"></a>. The major and minor axis lengths must be given in axis coordinates.
The orientation of the ellipse is specified by the angle between the horizontal axis and the major diameter of the
ellipse. If no angle is given, the default ellipse orientation will be used instead (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style ellipse (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-304000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">206</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set style ellipse --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-257003"></a>). The
<span 
class="cmbx-10">units </span>keyword controls the scaling of the axes of the ellipse. <span 
class="cmbx-10">units xy </span>means that the major axis is
interpreted in terms of units along the x axis, while the minor axis in that of the y axis. <span 
class="cmbx-10">units xx</span>
means that both axes of the ellipses are scaled in the units of the x axis, while <span 
class="cmbx-10">units yy </span>means that
both axes are in units of the y axis. The default is <span 
class="cmbx-10">xy </span>or whatever <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style ellipse units </span>was set
to.
<!--l. 11262--><p class="noindent" >NB: If the x and y axis scales are not equal, (e.g. <span 
class="cmbx-10">units xy </span>is in effect) then the major/minor axis ratio will no
longer be correct after rotation.
<!--l. 11266--><p class="noindent" >Note that <span 
class="cmbx-10">set object ellipse size </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">2r</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">,</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">2r</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>does not in general produce the same result as <span 
class="cmbx-10">set object</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">circle </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">r</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. The circle radius is always interpreted in terms of units along the x axis, and will always
produce a circle even if the x and y axis scales are different and even if the aspect ratio of your plot
is not 1. If <span 
class="cmbx-10">units </span>is set to <span 
class="cmbx-10">xy</span>, then &#8217;set object ellipse&#8217; interprets the first <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>2r<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>in terms of x axis
units and the second <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>2r<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>in terms of y axis units. This will only produce a circle if the x and y axis
scales are identical and the plot aspect ratio is 1. On the other hand, if <span 
class="cmbx-10">units </span>is set to <span 
class="cmbx-10">xx </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">yy</span>,
then the diameters specified in the &#8217;set object&#8217; command will be interpreted in the same units, so
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
the ellipse will have the correct aspect ratio, and it will maintain its aspect ratio even if the plot is
resized.
<!--l. 11279--><p class="noindent" >
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-258000III"></a>Circle</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-512"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-258001"></a>
<!--l. 11287--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;object</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;index&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;circle</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{at|center}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;position&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;size</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;radius&#x003E;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{arc</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[&#x003C;begin&#x003E;:&#x003C;end&#x003E;]}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;other-object-properties&#x003E;}</span>
<!--l. 11293--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 11296--><p class="noindent" >The position of the circle is specified by giving the position of the center center followed by the radius. The
keywords <span 
class="cmbx-10">at </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">center </span>are synonyms. The position and radius may be given in x-axis, graph, or canvas
coordinates. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">coordinates (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-20000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">24</span><!--tex4ht:ref: coordinates --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-258002"></a>. In all cases the radius is calculated relative to the horizontal scale of the
axis, graph, or canvas. Any disparity between the horizontal and vertical scaling will be corrected for so that the
result is always a circle.
<!--l. 11304--><p class="noindent" >By default a full circle is drawn. The optional qualifier <span 
class="cmbx-10">arc </span>specifies a starting angle and ending angle, in degrees, for
one arc of the circle. The arc is always drawn counterclockwise.
<!--l. 11308--><p class="noindent" >
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-259000III"></a>Polygon</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-514"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-259001"></a>
<!--l. 11316--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;object</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;index&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;polygon</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;from</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;position&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;to</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;position&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;...</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{to</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;position&#x003E;}</span>
<!--l. 11321--><p class="noindent" ></pre> or <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;from</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;position&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;rto</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;position&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;...</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{rto</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;position&#x003E;}</span>
<!--l. 11327--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 11330--><p class="noindent" >The position of the polygon may be specified by giving the position of a sequence of vertices. These may be given in
axis, graph, or screen coordinates. If relative coordinates are used (rto) then the coordinate type must match that of
the previous vertex. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">coordinates (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-20000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">24</span><!--tex4ht:ref: coordinates --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-259002"></a>.
<!--l. 11336--><p class="noindent" >Example: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;object</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;polygon</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;from</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0,0</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;to</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1,1</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;to</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;2,0</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;object</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fc</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;rgb</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"cyan"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fillstyle</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;solid</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1.0</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;border</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lt</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-1</span>
<!--l. 11341--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 11344--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-260000III"></a>Offsets</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-516"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-260001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-260002"></a>
<!--l. 11356--><p class="noindent" >Offsets provide a mechanism to put an empty boundary around the data inside an autoscaled graph. The offsets
only affect the x1 and y1 axes, and only in 2D <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>commands.
<!--l. 11360--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;offsets</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;left&#x003E;,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;right&#x003E;,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;top&#x003E;,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;bottom&#x003E;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;offsets</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;offsets</span>
<!--l. 11366--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 11369--><p class="noindent" >Each offset may be a constant or an expression. Each defaults to 0. By default, the left and right offsets are given in
units of the first x axis, the top and bottom offsets in units of the first y axis. Alternatively, you may specify the
offsets as a fraction of the total axis range by using the keyword <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>graph<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. A positive offset expands
the axis range in the specified direction, e.g., a positive bottom offset makes ymin more negative.
Negative offsets, while permitted, can have unexpected interactions with autoscaling and clipping. To
prevent the auto-scaling from further adjusting your axis ranges, it is useful to also specify <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>set auto
fix<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.
<!--l. 11379--><p class="noindent" >Example: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;auto</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fix</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;offsets</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;graph</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0.05,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;2,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;2</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sin(x)</span>
<!--l. 11385--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 11388--><p class="noindent" >This graph of sin(x) will have a y range [-3:3] because the function will be autoscaled to [-1:1] and the vertical offsets
are each two. The x range will be [-11:10] because the default is [-10:10] and it has been expanded to the left by 0.05
of that total range.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-261000III"></a>Origin</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-518"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-261001"></a>
<!--l. 11400--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set origin </span>command is used to specify the origin of a plotting surface (i.e., the graph and its margins) on the
screen. The coordinates are given in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">screen </span>coordinate system (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">coordinates (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-20000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">24</span><!--tex4ht:ref: coordinates --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-261002"></a> for information about
this system).
<!--l. 11405--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;origin</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;x-origin&#x003E;,&#x003C;y-origin&#x003E;</span>
<!--l. 11409--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-262000III"></a>Output</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-520"></a>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<a 
 id="dx1-262001"></a>
<!--l. 11420--><p class="noindent" >By default, screens are displayed to the standard output. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set output </span>command redirects the display to the
specified file or device.
<!--l. 11423--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;output</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{"&#x003C;filename&#x003E;"}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;output</span>
<!--l. 11428--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 11431--><p class="noindent" >The filename must be enclosed in quotes. If the filename is omitted, any output file opened by a previous invocation
of <span 
class="cmbx-10">set output </span>will be closed and new output will be sent to STDOUT. (If you give the command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set output</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">STDOUT</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, your output may be sent to a file named <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>STDOUT<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>! [<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>May be<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, not <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>will be<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, because some
terminals, like <span 
class="cmbx-10">x11 </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">wxt</span>, ignore <span 
class="cmbx-10">set output</span>.])
<!--l. 11437--><p class="noindent" >When both <span 
class="cmbx-10">set terminal </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set output </span>are used together, it is safest to give <span 
class="cmbx-10">set terminal </span>first, because some
terminals set a flag which is needed in some operating systems. This would be the case, for example,
if the operating system needs to know whether or not a file is to be formatted in order to open it
properly.
<!--l. 11443--><p class="noindent" >On machines with popen functions (Unix), output can be piped through a shell command if the first non-whitespace
character of the filename is &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">|</span>&#8217;. For instance,
<!--l. 11448--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;output</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"|lpr</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-Plaser</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;filename"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;output</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"|lp</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-dlaser</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;filename"</span>
<!--l. 11451--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 11454--><p class="noindent" >On MSDOS machines, <span 
class="cmbx-10">set output </span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">PRN</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>will direct the output to the default printer. On VMS, output can be
sent directly to any spooled device. It is also possible to send the output to DECnet transparent tasks, which allows
some flexibility.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-263000III"></a>Parametric</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-522"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-263001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-263002"></a>
<!--l. 11470--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set parametric </span>command changes the meaning of <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>(<span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>) from normal functions to parametric
functions. The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">unset parametric </span>restores the plotting style to normal, single-valued expression
plotting.
<!--l. 11474--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;parametric</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;parametric</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;parametric</span>
<!--l. 11480--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 11483--><p class="noindent" >For 2D plotting, a parametric function is determined by a pair of parametric functions operating on a parameter. An
example of a 2D parametric function would be <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot sin(t),cos(t)</span>, which draws a circle (if the aspect ratio is set
correctly &#8212; see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set size (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-292000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">197</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set size --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-263003"></a>). <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>will display an error message if both functions are not provided for a
parametric <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 11489--><p class="noindent" >For 3D plotting, the surface is described as x=f(u,v), y=g(u,v), z=h(u,v). Therefore a triplet of functions is
required. An example of a 3D parametric function would be <span 
class="cmbx-10">cos(u)*cos(v),cos(u)*sin(v),sin(u)</span>, which draws a
sphere. <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>will display an error message if all three functions are not provided for a parametric
<span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>.
<!--l. 11495--><p class="noindent" >The total set of possible plots is a superset of the simple f(x) style plots, since the two functions can describe the x
and y values to be computed separately. In fact, plots of the type t,f(t) are equivalent to those produced with f(x)
because the x values are computed using the identity function. Similarly, 3D plots of the type u,v,f(u,v) are
equivalent to f(x,y).
<!--l. 11502--><p class="noindent" >Note that the order the parametric functions are specified is xfunction, yfunction (and zfunction) and that each
operates over the common parametric domain.
<!--l. 11506--><p class="noindent" >Also, the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set parametric </span>function implies a new range of values. Whereas the normal f(x) and f(x,y) style plotting
assume an xrange and yrange (and zrange), the parametric mode additionally specifies a trange, urange, and vrange.
These ranges may be set directly with <span 
class="cmbx-10">set trange</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">set urange</span>, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set vrange</span>, or by specifying the range on the
<span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>commands. Currently the default range for these parametric variables is [-5:5]. Setting the ranges to
something more meaningful is expected.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-264000III"></a>Plot</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-524"></a>
<!--l. 11517--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">show plot </span>command shows the current plotting command as it results from the last <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and/or <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>and
possible subsequent <span 
class="cmbx-10">replot </span>commands.
<!--l. 11520--><p class="noindent" >In addition, the <span 
class="cmbx-10">show plot add2history </span>command adds this current plot command into the <span 
class="cmbx-10">history</span>. It is useful if
you have used <span 
class="cmbx-10">replot </span>to add more curves to the current plot and you want to edit the whole command
now.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-265000III"></a>Pm3d</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-526"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-265001"></a>
