<!--l. 11556--><p class="noindent" >A pm3d color surface is drawn if the splot command specifies <span 
class="cmbx-10">with pm3d</span>, if the data or function <span 
class="cmbx-10">style </span>is
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
set to pm3d globally, or if the pm3d mode is <span 
class="cmbx-10">set pm3d implicit</span>. In the latter two cases, the pm3d
surface is draw in addition to the mesh produced by the style specified in the plot command. E.g.
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;splot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;fred.dat&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lines,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;lola.dat&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lines</span>
<!--l. 11563--><p class="noindent" ></pre> would draw both a mesh of lines and a pm3d surface for each data set. If the option <span 
class="cmbx-10">explicit </span>is on (or
<span 
class="cmbx-10">implicit </span>is off) only plots specified by the <span 
class="cmbx-10">with pm3d </span>attribute are plotted with a pm3d surface, e.g.:
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;splot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;fred.dat&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lines,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;lola.dat&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pm3d</span>
<!--l. 11571--><p class="noindent" ></pre> would plot &#8217;fred.dat&#8217; with lines (only) and &#8217;lola.dat&#8217; with a pm3d surface.
<!--l. 11575--><p class="noindent" >On gnuplot start-up, the mode is <span 
class="cmbx-10">explicit</span>. For historical and compatibility reasons, the commands <span 
class="cmbx-10">set pm3d; </span>(i.e.
no options) and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set pm3d at X ... </span>(i.e. <span 
class="cmbx-10">at </span>is the first option) change the mode to <span 
class="cmbx-10">implicit</span>. The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">pm3d; </span>sets other options to their default state.
<!--l. 11580--><p class="noindent" >If you set the default data or function style to <span 
class="cmbx-10">pm3d</span>, e.g.: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;style</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;data</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pm3d</span>
<!--l. 11584--><p class="noindent" ></pre> then the options <span 
class="cmbx-10">implicit </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">explicit </span>have no effect.
<!--l. 11588--><p class="noindent" >Note that when plotting several plots, they are plotted in the order given on the command line. This
can be of interest especially for filled surfaces which can overwrite and therefore hide part of earlier
plots.
<!--l. 11592--><p class="noindent" >The pm3d coloring can be drawn at any or all of three different positions, <span 
class="cmbx-10">top</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">bottom</span>, or <span 
class="cmbx-10">surface</span>. See
<span 
class="cmbx-10">pm3d position (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-267000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">184</span><!--tex4ht:ref: pm3d position --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-265002"></a>. The following command draws three color surfaces at different altitudes:
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
