class="cmbx-10">demo/pm3d.dem</span>.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-266000III"></a>Algorithm</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-528"></a>
<!--l. 11609--><p class="noindent" >Let us first describe how a map/surface is drawn. The input data come from an evaluated function or from an <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">data file</span>. Each surface consists of a sequence of separate scans (isolines). The pm3d algorithm fills the region
between two neighbouring points in one scan with another two points in the next scan by a gray (or color) according
to z-values (or according to an additional &#8217;color&#8217; column, see help for <span 
class="cmbx-10">using (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-164000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">109</span><!--tex4ht:ref: using --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-266001"></a>) of these 4 corners; by default
the 4 corner values are averaged, but this can be changed by the option <span 
class="cmbx-10">corners2color</span>. In order to
get a reasonable surface, the neighbouring scans should not cross and the number of points in the
neighbouring scans should not differ too much; of course, the best plot is with scans having same number
of points. There are no other requirements (e.g. the data need not be gridded). Another advantage
is that the pm3d algorithm does not draw anything outside of the input (measured or calculated)
region.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 11623--><p class="noindent" >Surface coloring works with the following input data:
<!--l. 11625--><p class="noindent" >1. splot of function or of data file with one or three data columns: The gray/color scale is obtained by mapping the
averaged (or <span 
class="cmbx-10">corners2color</span>) z-coordinate of the four corners of the above-specified quadrangle into the range
[min_color_z,max_color_z] of <span 
class="cmbx-10">zrange </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">cbrange </span>providing a gray value in the range [0:1]. This value can be used
directly as the gray for gray maps. The normalized gray value can be further mapped into a color &#8212; see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-274000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">187</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set palette --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-266002"></a> for the complete description.
<!--l. 11633--><p class="noindent" >2. splot of data file with two or four data columns: The gray/color value is obtained by using the last-column
coordinate instead of the z-value, thus allowing the color and the z-coordinate be mutually independent. This can be
used for 4d data drawing.
<!--l. 11638--><p class="noindent" >Other notes:
<!--l. 11640--><p class="noindent" >1. The term &#8217;scan&#8217; referenced above is used more among physicists than the term &#8217;iso_curve&#8217; referenced in
gnuplot documentation and sources. You measure maps recorded one scan after another scan, that&#8217;s
why.
<!--l. 11644--><p class="noindent" >2. The &#8217;gray&#8217; or &#8217;color&#8217; scale is a linear mapping of a continuous variable onto a smoothly varying palette of colors.
The mapping is shown in a rectangle next to the main plot. This documentation refers to this as a <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>colorbox<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, and
refers to the indexing variable as lying on the colorbox axis. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set colorbox (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-204000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">140</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set colorbox --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-266003"></a>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">set cbrange</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-367000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">230</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set cbrange --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-266004"></a>.
<!--l. 11650--><p class="noindent" >3. To use pm3d coloring to generate a two-dimensional plot rather than a 3D surface, use <span 
class="cmbx-10">set view map </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">pm3d map</span>.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-267000III"></a>Position</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-530"></a>
<!--l. 11655--><p class="noindent" >Color surface can be drawn at the base or top (then it is a gray/color planar map) or at z-coordinates of surface
points (gray/color surface). This is defined by the <span 
class="cmbx-10">at </span>option with a string of up to 6 combinations of <span 
class="cmbx-10">b</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">t </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">s</span>. For
instance, <span 
class="cmbx-10">at b </span>plots at bottom only, <span 
class="cmbx-10">at st </span>plots firstly surface and then top map, while <span 
class="cmbx-10">at bstbst </span>will never by
seriously used.
<!--l. 11661--><p class="noindent" >Colored quadrangles are plotted one after another. When plotting surfaces (<span 
class="cmbx-10">at s</span>), the later quadrangles overlap
(overdraw) the previous ones. (Gnuplot is not virtual reality tool to calculate intersections of filled polygon meshes.)
You may try to switch between <span 
class="cmbx-10">scansforward </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">scansbackward </span>to force the first scan of the data to be plotted
first or last. The default is <span 
class="cmbx-10">scansautomatic </span>where gnuplot makes a guess about scans order. On the other hand,
the <span 
class="cmbx-10">depthorder </span>option completely reorders the quadrangles. The rendering is performed after a depth
sorting, which allows to visualize even complicated surfaces; see <span 
class="cmbx-10">pm3d depthorder (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-268000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">184</span><!--tex4ht:ref: pm3d depthorder --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-267001"></a> for more
details.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-268000III"></a>Scanorder</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-532"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-268001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-268002"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-268003"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-268004"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-268005"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-268006"></a>
<!--l. 11682--><p class="noindent" >By default the quadrangles making up a pm3d solid surface are rendered in the order they are encountered along the
surface grid points. This order may be controlled by the options <span 
class="cmbx-10">scansautomatic</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">|</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">scansforward</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">|</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">scansbackward</span>.
These scan options are not in general compatible with hidden-surface removal.
<!--l. 11687--><p class="noindent" >If two successive scans do not have same number of points, then it has to be decided whether to start taking points
for quadrangles from the beginning of both scans (<span 
class="cmbx-10">flush begin</span>), from their ends (<span 
class="cmbx-10">flush end</span>) or to center them
(<span 
class="cmbx-10">flush center</span>). Note, that <span 
class="cmbx-10">flush (center</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">|</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">end) </span>are incompatible with <span 
class="cmbx-10">scansautomatic</span>: if you specify <span 
class="cmbx-10">flush</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">center </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">flush end </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">scansautomatic </span>is set, it is silently switched to <span 
class="cmbx-10">scansforward</span>.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 11694--><p class="noindent" >If two subsequent scans do not have the same number of points, the option <span 
class="cmbx-10">ftriangles </span>specifies whether color
triangles are drawn at the scan tail(s) where there are not enough points in either of the scan. This can be used to
draw a smooth map boundary.
<!--l. 11699--><p class="noindent" >Gnuplot does not do true hidden surface removal for solid surfaces, but often it is sufficient to render the
component quadrangles in order from furthest to closest. This mode may be selected using the options
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pm3d</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;depthorder</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;hidden3d</span>
<!--l. 11705--><p class="noindent" ></pre> The <span 
class="cmbx-10">depthorder </span>option orders the solid quadrangles; the <span 
class="cmbx-10">hidden3d </span>option similarly orders the bounding lines (if
drawn). Note that the global option <span 
class="cmbx-10">set hidden3d </span>does not affect pm3d surfaces.
<!--l. 11711--><p class="noindent" >
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-269000III"></a>Clipping</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-534"></a>
<!--l. 11714--><p class="noindent" >Clipping with respect to x, y coordinates of quadrangles can be done in two ways. <span 
class="cmbx-10">clip1in</span>: all 4 points of each
quadrangle must be defined and at least 1 point of the quadrangle must lie in the x and y ranges. <span 
class="cmbx-10">clip4in</span>: all 4
points of each quadrangle must lie in the x and y ranges.
<!--l. 11719--><p class="noindent" >
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-270000III"></a>Color_assignment</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-536"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-270001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-270002"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-270003"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-270004"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-270005"></a>
<!--l. 11727--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">3 columns of data (x,y,z)</span>:
<!--l. 11729--><p class="noindent" >The coloring setup as well as the color box drawing are determined by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette</span>. There can be only one palette
for the current plot. Drawing of several surfaces with different palettes can be achieved by <span 
class="cmbx-10">multiplot </span>with fixed
<span 
class="cmbx-10">origin </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">size</span>; don&#8217;t forget to use <span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette maxcolors </span>when your terminal is running out of available
colors.
<!--l. 11735--><p class="noindent" >There is a single gray/color value associated to each drawn pm3d quadrangle (no smooth color change among
vertices). The value is calculated from z-coordinates from the surrounding corners according to <span 
class="cmbx-10">corners2color</span>
<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">option</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. The options &#8217;mean&#8217; (default), &#8217;geomean&#8217; and &#8217;median&#8217; produce various kinds of surface color smoothing,
while options &#8217;min&#8217; and &#8217;max&#8217; choose minimal or maximal value, respectively. This may not be desired for pixel
images or for maps with sharp and intense peaks, in which case the options &#8217;c1&#8217;, &#8217;c2&#8217;, &#8217;c3&#8217; or &#8217;c4&#8217; can be used instead
to assign the quadrangle color based on the z-coordinate of only one corner. Some experimentation may
be needed to determine which corner corresponds to &#8217;c1&#8217;, as the orientation depends on the drawing
direction. Because the pm3d algorithm does not extend the colored surface outside the range of the
input data points, the &#8217;c<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>j<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>&#8217; coloring options will result in pixels along two edges of the grid not
contributing to the color of any quadrangle. For example, applying the pm3d algorithm to the 4x4 grid of
data points in script <span 
class="cmbx-10">demo/pm3d.dem </span>(please have a look) produces only (4-1)x(4-1)=9 colored
rectangles.
<!--l. 11752--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">4 columns of data (x,y,z,color)</span>:
<!--l. 11754--><p class="noindent" >If a fourth column of data is provided, it is normally interpreted as a separate palette-mapped gray value. The
coloring of individual quadrangles works as above, except that the color value is distinct from the z value. As a
separate coloring option, the fourth data column may provide instead an RGB color. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">rgbcolor variable</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-45000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">42</span><!--tex4ht:ref: rgbcolor variable --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-270006"></a>. In this case the plotting command must be
<!--l. 11762--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;splot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;...</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2:3:4</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pm3d</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lc</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;rgb</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;variable</span>
<!--l. 11764--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 11767--><p class="noindent" >Another drawing algorithm, which would draw quadrangles around a given node by taking corners from averaged
(x,y)-coordinates of its surrounding 4 nodes while using node&#8217;s color, could be implemented in the future. This is
already done for drawing images (2D grids) via <span 
class="cmbx-10">image </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">rgbimage </span>styles.
<!--l. 11772--><p class="noindent" >Notice that ranges of z-values and color-values for surfaces are adjustable independently by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set zrange</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">cbrange</span>, as well as <span 
class="cmbx-10">set log </span>for z or cb. Maps can be adjusted by the cb-axis only; see also <span 
class="cmbx-10">set view map</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-320000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">213</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set view map --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-270007"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set colorbox (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-204000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">140</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set colorbox --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-270008"></a>.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-271000III"></a>Hidden3d</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-538"></a>
<!--l. 11780--><p class="noindent" >The option <span 
class="cmbx-10">set pm3d hidden3d </span>draws the bounding lines of each quadrangle at the same time that the
quadrangle itself is drawn. Normally it is used in conjunction with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">depthorder </span>option to achieve an
approximation to true hidden line removal. This is far more efficient than using the command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set hidden3d</span>. The
command takes an optional linestyle controlling the appearance of the bounding lines. If the linestyle parameter is
negative, or omitted, then the line properties given in the plot command are used. Example of recommended
usage:
<!--l. 11790--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pm3d</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;at</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;s</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;hidden3d</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;depthorder</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;hidden3d</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;surf</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;splot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x*x+y*y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;linecolor</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;rgb</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"black"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;linewidth</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0.5</span>
<!--l. 11795--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 11798--><p class="noindent" >
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-272000III"></a>Interpolate</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-540"></a>
<!--l. 11802--><p class="noindent" >The option <span 
class="cmbx-10">interpolate m,n </span>will interpolate grid points into a finer mesh, and color each quadrangle appropriately.
For data files, this will smoothen the color surface, and enhance spikes in a color surface. For functions, interpolation
makes little sense, except to trade off precision for memory. It would usually make more sense to use <span 
class="cmbx-10">samples </span>and
<span 
class="cmbx-10">isosamples </span>when working with functions. For positive m and n, each quadrangle or triangle is interpolated m-times
and n-times in the respective direction. For negative m and n, the interpolation frequency is chosen
so that there will be at least <span 
class="cmsy-10">|</span>m<span 
class="cmsy-10">| </span>and <span 
class="cmsy-10">|</span>n<span 
class="cmsy-10">| </span>points drawn; you can consider this as a special gridding
function. Zeros, i.e. <span 
class="cmbx-10">interpolate 0,0</span>, will automatically choose an optimal number of interpolated surface
points.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-273000III"></a>Deprecated_options</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-542"></a>
<!--l. 11816--><p class="noindent" >There used to be an option <span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>transparent<span 
class="cmsy-10">|</span>solid<span 
class="cmsy-10">} </span>to this command. Now you get the same effect from <span 
class="cmbx-10">set grid</span>
<span 
class="cmbsy-10">{</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">front</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">|</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">layerdefault</span><span 
class="cmbsy-10">}</span>, respectively.
<!--l. 11819--><p class="noindent" >The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set pm3d map </span>is equivalent to <span 
class="cmbx-10">set pm3d at b</span>; <span 
class="cmbx-10">set view map</span>; <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style data pm3d</span>; <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">func pm3d</span>;. It is used for backwards compatibility, when <span 
class="cmbx-10">set view map </span>was not available. Take care that you
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
properly use <span 
class="cmbx-10">zrange </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">cbrange </span>for input data point filtering and color range scaling, respectively; and also <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(no)surface </span>seems to have a (side?) effect.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-274000III"></a>Palette</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-544"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-274001"></a>
<!--l. 11833--><p class="noindent" >Palette is a color storage for use by <span 
class="cmbx-10">pm3d</span>, filled color contours or polygons, color histograms, color gradient
background, and whatever it is or it will be implemented... Here it stands for a palette of smooth <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>continuous<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>
colors or grays, but let&#8217;s call it just a palette.
<!--l. 11838--><p class="noindent" >Color palettes require terminal entries for filled color polygons and palettes of smooth colors, are currently available
for terminals listed in help for <span 
class="cmbx-10">set pm3d</span>. The range of color values are adjustable independently by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set cbrange</span>
and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set log cb</span>. The whole color palette is visualized in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">colorbox</span>.
