<!--l. 11868--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 11871--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette </span>(i.e. without options) sets up the default values. Otherwise, the options can be given in any order.
<span 
class="cmbx-10">show palette </span>shows the current palette properties.
<!--l. 11875--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">show palette gradient </span>displays the gradient defining the palette (if appropriate). <span 
class="cmbx-10">show palette rgbformulae</span>
prints the available fixed gray &#8211;<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>color transformation formulae. <span 
class="cmbx-10">show colornames </span>prints the known color
names.
<!--l. 11879--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">show palette palette </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">n</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>prints to the screen or to the file given by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set print </span>a table of RGB triplets calculated
for the current palette settings and a palette having <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>n<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>discrete colors. The default wide table can be limited to 3
columns of r,g,b float values [0..1] or integer values [0..255] by options float or int, respectively. This way, the current
gnuplot color palette can be loaded into other imaging applications, for example Octave. Additionally to this textual
list of RGB table, you can use the <span 
class="cmbx-10">test palette </span>command to plot the R,G,B profiles for the current
palette.
<!--l. 11888--><p class="noindent" >The following options determine the coloring properties.
<!--l. 11890--><p class="noindent" >Figure using this palette can be <span 
class="cmbx-10">gray </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">color</span>. For instance, in <span 
class="cmbx-10">pm3d </span>color surfaces the gray of each small
spot is obtained by mapping the averaged z-coordinate of the 4 corners of surface quadrangles into
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
the range [min_z,max_z] providing range of grays [0:1]. This value can be used directly as the gray
for gray maps. The color map requires a transformation gray &#8211;<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>(R,G,B), i.e. a mapping [0:1] &#8211;<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>
([0:1],[0:1],[0:1]).
<!--l. 11897--><p class="noindent" >Basically two different types of mappings can be used: Analytic formulae to convert gray to color, or discrete
mapping tables which are interpolated. <span 
class="cmbx-10">palette rgbformulae </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">palette functions </span>use analytic formulae
whereas <span 
class="cmbx-10">palette defined </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">palette file </span>use interpolated tables. <span 
class="cmbx-10">palette rgbformulae </span>reduces the size of
postscript output to a minimum.
<!--l. 11903--><p class="noindent" >The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">show palette fit2rgbformulae </span>finds the best matching <span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette rgbformulae </span>for the current
<span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette</span>. Naturally, it makes sense to use it for non-rgbformulae palettes. This command can be found useful
mainly for external programs using the same rgbformulae definition of palettes as gnuplot, like zimg
(
<!--l. 11908--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://zimg.sourceforge.net" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">http://zimg.sourceforge.net </span></a>
<!--l. 11911--><p class="noindent" >).
<!--l. 11913--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette gray </span>switches to a gray only palette. <span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette rgbformulae</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette defined</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">file </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette functions </span>switch to a color mapping. <span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette color </span>is an easy way to switch back from
the gray palette to the last color mapping.
<!--l. 11918--><p class="noindent" >Automatic gamma correction via <span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette gamma </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">gamma</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>can be done for gray maps (<span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette gray</span>)
and for the <span 
class="cmbx-10">cubehelix </span>color palette schemes. Gamma = 1 produces a linear ramp of intensity. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">test palette</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-378000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">238</span><!--tex4ht:ref: test palette --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-274002"></a>.
<!--l. 11922--><p class="noindent" >Many terminals support only discrete number of colors (e.g. 256 colors in gif). After the default gnuplot linetype
colors are allocated, the rest of the available colors are by default reserved for pm3d. Thus a multiplot using multiple
palettes could fail because the first palette has used all the available color positions. You can mitigate this limitation
by using <span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette maxcolors </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">N</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>with a reasonably small value of N. This option causes N
discrete colors to be selected from a continuous palette sampled at equally spaced intervals. If you
want unequal spacing of N discrete colors, use <span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette defined </span>instead of a single continuous
palette.
<!--l. 11933--><p class="noindent" >RGB color space might not be the most useful color space to work in. For that reason you may change the color
space with <span 
class="cmbx-10">model </span>to one of <span 
class="cmbx-10">RGB</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">HSV</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">CMY</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">YIQ </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">XYZ</span>. Using color names for <span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette defined</span>
tables and a color space other than RGB will result in funny colors. All explanation have been written for RGB
color space, so please note, that <span 
class="cmbx-10">R </span>can be <span 
class="cmbx-10">H</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">C</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">Y</span>, or <span 
class="cmbx-10">X</span>, depending on the actual color space (<span 
class="cmbx-10">G </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">B</span>
accordingly).
<!--l. 11941--><p class="noindent" >All values for all color spaces are limited to [0,1].
<!--l. 11943--><p class="noindent" >RGB stands for Red, Green and Blue; CMY stands for Cyan, Magenta and Yellow; HSV stands for Hue, Saturation,
and Value; YIQ is the color model used by the U.S. Commercial Color Television Broadcasting, it is basically an
RGB recoding with downward compatibility for black and white television; XYZ are the three primary colors of the
color model defined by the &#8217;Commission Internationale de l&#8217;Eclairage&#8217; (CIE). For more information on color models
see:
<!--l. 11950--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Color_space" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Color</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">_space </span></a>
<!--l. 11954--><p class="noindent" >
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-275000III"></a>Rgbformulae</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-546"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-275001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-275002"></a>
<!--l. 11962--><p class="noindent" >For <span 
class="cmbx-10">rgbformulae </span>three suitable mapping functions have to be chosen. This is done via <span 
class="cmbx-10">rgbformulae</span>
<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">r</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">,</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">g</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">,</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">b</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. The available mapping functions are listed by <span 
class="cmbx-10">show palette rgbformulae</span>. Default is <span 
class="cmbx-10">7,5,15</span>,
some other examples are <span 
class="cmbx-10">3,11,6</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">21,23,3 </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">3,23,21</span>. Negative numbers, like <span 
class="cmbx-10">3,-11,-6</span>, mean inverted
color (i.e. 1-gray passed into the formula, see also <span 
class="cmbx-10">positive (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-275000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">189</span><!--tex4ht:ref: positive --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-275003"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">negative (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-275000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">189</span><!--tex4ht:ref: negative --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-275004"></a> options
below).
