enough.
<!--l. 12266--><p class="noindent" >
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-281000III"></a>Postscript</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-558"></a>
<!--l. 12270--><p class="noindent" >In order to reduce the size of postscript files, the gray value and not all three calculated r,g,b values are written to
the file. Therefore the analytical formulae are coded directly in the postscript language as a header just before the
pm3d drawing, see /g and /cF definitions. Usually, it makes sense to write therein definitions of only the 3 formulae
used. But for multiplot or any other reason you may want to manually edit the transformations directly in the
postscript file. This is the default option <span 
class="cmbx-10">nops</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">_allcF</span>. Using the option <span 
class="cmbx-10">ps</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">_allcF </span>writes postscript definitions of all
formulae. This you may find interesting if you want to edit the postscript file in order to have different palettes for
different surfaces in one graph. Well, you can achieve this functionality by <span 
class="cmbx-10">multiplot </span>with fixed <span 
class="cmbx-10">origin </span>and
<span 
class="cmbx-10">size</span>.
<!--l. 12283--><p class="noindent" >If pm3d map has been plotted from gridded or almost regular data with an output to a postscript
file, then it is possible to reduce the size of this postscript file up to at about 50% by the enclosed
awk script <span 
class="cmbx-10">pm3dCompress.awk</span>. This you may find interesting if you intend to keep the file for
including it into your publication or before downloading a very large file into a slow printer. Usage:
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;awk</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-f</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pm3dCompress.awk</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;thefile.ps</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003E;smallerfile.ps</span>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 12292--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 12295--><p class="noindent" >If pm3d map has been plotted from rectangular gridded data with an output to a postscript file, then it is possible
to reduce the file size even more by the enclosed awk script <span 
class="cmbx-10">pm3dConvertToImage.awk</span>. Usage:
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;awk</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-f</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pm3dConvertToImage.awk</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;thefile.ps</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003E;smallerfile.ps</span>
<!--l. 12301--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 12304--><p class="noindent" >You may manually change the postscript output from gray to color and vice versa and change the definition of
<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>maxcolors<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-282000III"></a>Pointintervalbox</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-560"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-282001"></a>
<!--l. 12312--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">pointinterval </span>property of line types is used in plot style <span 
class="cmbx-10">linespoints</span>. A negative value of pointinterval, e.g.
-N, means that point symbols are drawn only for every Nth point, and that a box (actually circle) behind each point
symbol is blanked out by filling with the background color. The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set pointintervalbox </span>controls the
radius of this blanked-out region. It is a multiplier for the default radius, which is equal to the point
size.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-283000III"></a>Pointsize</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-562"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-283001"></a>
<!--l. 12326--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set pointsize </span>command scales the size of the points used in plots.
<!--l. 12328--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pointsize</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;multiplier&#x003E;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pointsize</span>
<!--l. 12333--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 12336--><p class="noindent" >The default is a multiplier of 1.0. Larger pointsizes may be useful to make points more visible in bitmapped
graphics.
<!--l. 12339--><p class="noindent" >The pointsize of a single plot may be changed on the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot with (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-180000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">120</span><!--tex4ht:ref: plot with --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-283002"></a> for
details.
<!--l. 12342--><p class="noindent" >Please note that the pointsize setting is not supported by all terminal types.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-284000III"></a>Polar</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-564"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-284001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-284002"></a>
<!--l. 12356--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set polar </span>command changes the meaning of the plot from rectangular coordinates to polar coordinates.
<!--l. 12359--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;polar</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;polar</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;polar</span>
<!--l. 12365--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 12368--><p class="noindent" >In polar coordinates, the dummy variable (t) is an angle. The default range of t is [0:2*pi], or, if degree units have
been selected, to [0:360] (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set angles (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-191000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">128</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set angles --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-284003"></a>).
<!--l. 12372--><p class="noindent" >The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">unset polar </span>changes the meaning of the plot back to the default rectangular coordinate
system.
<!--l. 12375--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set polar </span>command is not supported for <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>s. See the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set mapping (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-241000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">169</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set mapping --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-284004"></a> command for similar
functionality for <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-370000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">231</span><!--tex4ht:ref: splot --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-284005"></a>s.
<!--l. 12378--><p class="noindent" >While in polar coordinates the meaning of an expression in t is really r = f(t), where t is an angle of rotation. The
trange controls the domain (the angle) of the function. The r, x and y ranges control the extent of the graph in the x
and y directions. Each of these ranges, as well as the rrange, may be autoscaled or set explicitly. For details, see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">rrange (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-289000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">196</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set rrange --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-284006"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xrange (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-334000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">218</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set xrange --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-284007"></a>.
<!--l. 12385--><p class="noindent" >Example: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;polar</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;t*sin(t)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;trange</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[-2*pi:2*pi]</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;rrange</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[0:3]</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;t*sin(t)</span>
<!--l. 12393--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 12396--><p class="noindent" >The first <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>uses the default polar angular domain of 0 to 2*pi. The radius and the size of the graph are scaled
automatically. The second <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>expands the domain, and restricts the size of the graph to the area within 3 units of
the origin. This has the effect of limiting x and y to [-3:3].
<!--l. 12401--><p class="noindent" >You may want to <span 
class="cmbx-10">set size square </span>to have <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>try to make the aspect ratio equal to unity, so that circles look
circular. See also
<!--l. 12404--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/polar.html" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">polar demos (polar.dem) </span></a>
<!--l. 12407--><p class="noindent" >and
<!--l. 12408--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/poldat.html" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">polar data plot (poldat.dem). </span></a>
<!--l. 12411--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-285000III"></a>Print</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-566"></a>
<!--l. 12417--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set print </span>command redirects the output of the <span 
class="cmbx-10">print </span>command to a file.
<!--l. 12419--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;print</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;print</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"-"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;print</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"&#x003C;filename&#x003E;"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;print</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"&#x003C;filename&#x003E;"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;append</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;print</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"|&#x003C;shell_command&#x003E;"</span>
<!--l. 12427--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 12430--><p class="noindent" >Without <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>filename<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, the output file is restored to <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>STDERR<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. The <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>filename<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>-<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>means <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>STDOUT<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. The
<span 
class="cmbx-10">append </span>flag causes the file to be opened in append mode. A <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>filename<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>starting with <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is opened as a pipe to
the <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>shell_command<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>on platforms that support piping.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-286000III"></a>Psdir</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-568"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-286001"></a>
<!--l. 12442--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set psdir </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">directory</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>command controls the search path used by the postscript terminal to find prologue.ps
and character encoding files. You can use this mechanism to switch between different sets of locally-customized
prolog files. The search order is <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;The</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;directory</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;specified</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;by</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;psdir&#8216;,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;if</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;any</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;2)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;The</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;directory</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;specified</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;by</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;environmental</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;variable</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;GNUPLOT_PS_DIR</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;3)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;A</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;built-in</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;header</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;or</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;one</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;from</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;the</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;default</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;system</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;directory</span>
<span 
