<!--l. 12698--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>index<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is an integer that identifies the arrowstyle.
<!--l. 12700--><p class="noindent" >If <span 
class="cmbx-10">default </span>is given all arrow style parameters are set to their default values.
<!--l. 12703--><p class="noindent" >If the linestyle <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>index<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>already exists, only the given parameters are changed while all others are preserved. If not,
all undefined values are set to the default values.
<!--l. 12707--><p class="noindent" >Specifying <span 
class="cmbx-10">nohead </span>produces arrows drawn without a head &#8212; a line segment. This gives you yet another way to
draw a line segment on the plot. By default, arrows have one head. Specifying <span 
class="cmbx-10">heads </span>draws arrow heads on both
ends of the line.
<!--l. 12712--><p class="noindent" >Head size can be controlled by <span 
class="cmbx-10">size </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">length</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">,</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">angle</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">size </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">length</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">,</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">angle</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">,</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">backangle</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>, where
<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">length</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>defines length of each branch of the arrow head and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">angle</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>the angle (in degrees) they make with the
arrow. <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">Length</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is in x-axis units; this can be changed by <span 
class="cmbx-10">first</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">second</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">graph</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">screen</span>, or <span 
class="cmbx-10">character </span>before the
<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>length<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>; see <span 
class="cmbx-10">coordinates (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-20000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">24</span><!--tex4ht:ref: coordinates --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-294002"></a> for details. <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">Backangle</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>only takes effect when <span 
class="cmbx-10">filled </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">empty </span>is also
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
used. Then, <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">backangle</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is the angle (in degrees) the back branches make with the arrow (in the
same direction as <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">angle</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>). The <span 
class="cmbx-10">fig </span>terminal has a restricted backangle function. It supports three
different angles. There are two thresholds: Below 70 degrees, the arrow head gets an indented back angle.
Above 110 degrees, the arrow head has an acute back angle. Between these thresholds, the back line is
straight.
<!--l. 12725--><p class="noindent" >Specifying <span 
class="cmbx-10">filled </span>produces filled arrow heads (if heads are used). Filling is supported on filled-polygon capable
terminals, see help of <span 
class="cmbx-10">pm3d (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-265000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">182</span><!--tex4ht:ref: pm3d --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-294003"></a> for their list, otherwise the arrow heads are closed but not filled. The same
result (closed but not filled arrow head) is reached by specifying <span 
class="cmbx-10">empty</span>. Further, filling and outline is obviously not
supported on terminals drawing arrows by their own specific routines, like <span 
class="cmbx-10">metafont</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">metapost</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">latex </span>or
<span 
class="cmbx-10">tgif</span>.
<!--l. 12733--><p class="noindent" >The line style may be selected from a user-defined list of line styles (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style line (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-301000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">204</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set style line --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-294004"></a>) or may be defined
here by providing values for <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">line</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">_type</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>(an index from the default list of styles) and/or <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">line</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">_width</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>(which is
a multiplier for the default width).
<!--l. 12738--><p class="noindent" >Note, however, that if a user-defined line style has been selected, its properties (type and width) cannot be
altered merely by issuing another <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style arrow </span>command with the appropriate index and <span 
class="cmbx-10">lt </span>or
<span 
class="cmbx-10">lw</span>.
<!--l. 12742--><p class="noindent" >If <span 
class="cmbx-10">front </span>is given, the arrows are written on top of the graphed data. If <span 
class="cmbx-10">back </span>is given (the default), the arrow is
written underneath the graphed data. Using <span 
class="cmbx-10">front </span>will prevent a arrow from being obscured by dense
data.
