<!--l. 13040--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">default </span>sets all line style parameters to those of the linetype with that same index.
<!--l. 13043--><p class="noindent" >If the linestyle <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>index<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>already exists, only the given parameters are changed while all others are preserved. If not,
all undefined values are set to the default values.
<!--l. 13047--><p class="noindent" >Line styles created by this mechanism do not replace the default linetype styles; both may be used. Line styles are
temporary. They are lost whenever you execute a <span 
class="cmbx-10">reset </span>command. To redefine the linetype itself, please see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">linetype (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-235000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">166</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set linetype --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-301007"></a>.
<!--l. 13052--><p class="noindent" >The line and point types default to the index value. The exact symbol that is drawn for that index value may vary
from one terminal type to another.
<!--l. 13055--><p class="noindent" >The line width and point size are multipliers for the current terminal&#8217;s default width and size (but note that
<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>point_size<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>here is unaffected by the multiplier given by the command<span 
class="cmbx-10">set pointsize</span>).
<!--l. 13059--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">pointinterval </span>controls the spacing between points in a plot drawn with style <span 
class="cmbx-10">linespoints</span>. The
default is 0 (every point is drawn). For example, <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style line N pi 3 </span>defines a linestyle that uses
pointtype N, pointsize and linewidth equal to the current defaults for the terminal, and will draw every
3rd point in plots using <span 
class="cmbx-10">with linespoints</span>. A negative value for the interval is treated the same as a
positive value, except that some terminals will try to interrupt the line where it passes through the point
symbol.
<!--l. 13067--><p class="noindent" >Not all terminals support the <span 
class="cmbx-10">linewidth </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">pointsize </span>features; if not supported, the option will be
ignored.
<!--l. 13070--><p class="noindent" >Terminal-independent colors may be assigned using either <span 
class="cmbx-10">linecolor </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">colorspec</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">linetype </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">colorspec</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>,
abbreviated <span 
class="cmbx-10">lc </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">lt</span>. This requires giving a RGB color triple, a known palette color name, a fractional index
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
into the current palette, or a constant value from the current mapping of the palette onto cbrange.
See <span 
class="cmbx-10">colors (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-41000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">39</span><!--tex4ht:ref: colors --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-301008"></a>, <span 
