class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{angle</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;angle&#x003E;}</span>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 13206--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 13209--><p class="noindent" >This command governs whether the diameters of ellipses are interpreted in the same units or not. Default is <span 
class="cmbx-10">xy</span>,
which means that the major diameter (first axis) of ellipses will be interpreted in the same units as the x (or x2)
axis, while the minor (second) diameter in those of the y (or y2) axis. In this mode the ratio of the ellipse axes
depends on the scales of the plot axes and aspect ratio of the plot. When set to <span 
class="cmbx-10">xx </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">yy</span>, both axes of all
ellipses will be interpreted in the same units. This means that the ratio of the axes of the plotted
ellipses will be correct even after rotation, but either their vertical or horizontal extent will not be
correct.
<!--l. 13221--><p class="noindent" >This is a global setting that affects all ellipses, both those defined as objects and those generated with
the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command, however, the value of <span 
class="cmbx-10">units </span>can also be redefined on a per-plot and per-object
basis.
<!--l. 13225--><p class="noindent" >It is also possible to set a default size for ellipses with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">size </span>keyword. This default size applies to data plots with
only 2 columns of data (x,y) and to function plots. The two values are interpreted as the major and minor diameters
(as opposed to semi-major and semi-minor axes) of the ellipse.
<!--l. 13231--><p class="noindent" >The default is <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>set style ellipse size graph 0.05,0.03<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.
<!--l. 13233--><p class="noindent" >Last, but not least it is possible to set the default orientation with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">angle </span>keyword. The orientation, which
is defined as the angle between the major axis of the ellipse and the plot&#8217;s x axis, must be given in
degrees.
<!--l. 13237--><p class="noindent" >For defining ellipse objects, see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set object ellipse (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-257000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">178</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set object ellipse --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-304001"></a>; for the 2D plot style, see <span 
class="cmbx-10">ellipses (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-68000II"><span 
class="cmbx-10">59</span><!--tex4ht:ref: ellipses --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-304002"></a>.
<!--l. 13240--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-305000III"></a>Surface</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-606"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-305001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-305002"></a>
<!--l. 13252--><p class="noindent" >The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set surface </span>controls the display of surfaces by <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>.
<!--l. 13254--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;surface</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;surface</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;surface</span>
<!--l. 13260--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 13263--><p class="noindent" >The surface is drawn with the style specified by <span 
class="cmbx-10">with</span>, or else the appropriate style, data or function.
<!--l. 13266--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">unset surface </span>will cause <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>to not draw points or lines corresponding to any of the function or data file points.
If you want to turn off the surface for an individual function or data file while leaving the others active, use the
<span 
class="cmbx-10">nosurface </span>keyword in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>command. Contours may still be drawn on the surface, depending on the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">contour </span>option. The combination <span 
class="cmbx-10">unset surface; set contour base </span>is useful for displaying contours on the grid
base. See also <span 
class="cmbx-10">set contour (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-206000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">141</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set contour --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-305003"></a>.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-306000III"></a>Table</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-608"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-306001"></a>
<!--l. 13279--><p class="noindent" >When <span 
class="cmbx-10">table </span>mode is enabled, <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>commands print out a multicolumn ASCII table of X Y <span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>Z<span 
class="cmsy-10">} </span>R values
rather than creating an actual plot on the current terminal. The character R takes on one of three values:
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>i<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>if the point is in the active range, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>o<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>if it is out-of-range, or <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>u<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>if it is undefined. The data
format is determined by the format of the axis labels (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set format (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-221000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">152</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set format --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-306002"></a>), and the columns
are separated by single spaces. This can be useful if you want to generate contours and then save
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
them for further use, perhaps for plotting with <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>; see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set contour (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-206000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">141</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set contour --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-306003"></a> for example. The
same method can be used to save interpolated data (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set samples (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-291000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">197</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set samples --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-306004"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set dgrid3d</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-216000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">147</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set dgrid3d --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-306005"></a>).
<!--l. 13290--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;table</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{"outfile"}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;whatever&#x003E;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;table</span>
<!--l. 13296--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 13299--><p class="noindent" >Tabular output is written to the named file, if any, otherwise it is written to the current value of <span 
class="cmbx-10">set output</span>. You
must explicitly <span 
class="cmbx-10">unset table </span>in order to go back to normal plotting on the current terminal.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-307000III"></a>Terminal</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-610"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-307001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-307002"></a>
<!--l. 13322--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>supports many different graphics devices. Use <span 
class="cmbx-10">set terminal </span>to tell <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>what kind of output to
generate. Use <span 
class="cmbx-10">set output </span>to redirect that output to a file or device.
<!--l. 13326--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;terminal-type&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;push</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pop}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span>
<!--l. 13331--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 13334--><p class="noindent" >If <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>terminal-type<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is omitted, <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>will list the available terminal types. <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>terminal-type<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>may be
abbreviated.
<!--l. 13337--><p class="noindent" >If both <span 
class="cmbx-10">set terminal </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set output </span>are used together, it is safest to give <span 
class="cmbx-10">set terminal </span>first, because some
terminals set a flag which is needed in some operating systems.
<!--l. 13341--><p class="noindent" >Some terminals have many additional options. The options used by a previous invocation <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">term</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>
<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">options</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>of a given <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">term</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>are remembered, thus subsequent <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">term</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>does not reset them. This
helps in printing, for instance, when switching among different terminals &#8212; previous options don&#8217;t have to be
repeated.
<!--l. 13347--><p class="noindent" >The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term push </span>remembers the current terminal including its settings while <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term pop </span>restores
it. This is equivalent to <span 
class="cmbx-10">save term </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">load term</span>, but without accessing the filesystem. Therefore they can be
used to achieve platform independent restoring of the terminal after printing, for instance. After gnuplot&#8217;s startup,
the default terminal or that from <span 
class="cmbx-10">startup </span>file is pushed automatically. Therefore portable scripts can rely that <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">term pop </span>restores the default terminal on a given platform unless another terminal has been pushed
explicitly.
<!--l. 13356--><p class="noindent" >For more information, see the <span 
class="cmbx-10">complete list of terminals (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-384000IV"><span 
class="cmbx-10">240</span><!--tex4ht:ref: complete list of terminals --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-307003"></a>.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-308000III"></a>Termoption</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-612"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-308001"></a>
<!--l. 13363--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set termoption </span>command allows you to change the behaviour of the current terminal without requiring a new
<span 
class="cmbx-10">set terminal </span>command. Only one option can be changed per command, and only a small number of options can be
changed this way. Currently the only options accepted are
<!--l. 13369--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;termoption</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{no}enhanced</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;termoption</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"&#x003C;fontname&#x003E;{,&#x003C;fontsize&#x003E;}"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;termoption</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fontscale</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;scale&#x003E;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;termoption</span><span 
