<!--l. 13412--><p class="noindent" >The options in the first set above can be applied individually to any or all axes, i.e., x, y, z, x2, y2, and
cb.
<!--l. 13415--><p class="noindent" >Set tics <span 
class="cmbx-10">front </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">back </span>applies to all axes at once, but only for 2D plots (not splot). It controls whether the tics are
placed behind or in front of the plot elements, in the case that there is overlap.
<!--l. 13419--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">axis </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">border </span>tells <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>to put the tics (both the tics themselves and the accompanying labels)
along the axis or the border, respectively. If the axis is very close to the border, the <span 
class="cmbx-10">axis </span>option will
move the tic labels to outside the border in case the border is printed (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set border (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-199000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">134</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set border --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-309002"></a>).
The relevant margin settings will usually be sized badly by the automatic layout algorithm in this
case.
<!--l. 13426--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">mirror </span>tells <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>to put unlabelled tics at the same positions on the opposite border. <span 
class="cmbx-10">nomirror </span>does what you
think it does.
<!--l. 13429--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">in </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">out </span>change the tic marks to be drawn inwards or outwards.
<!--l. 13431--><p class="noindent" >With <span 
class="cmbx-10">scale</span>, the size of the tic marks can be adjusted. If <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>minor<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is not specified, it is 0.5*<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>major<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. The default
size 1.0 for major tics and 0.5 for minor tics is requested by <span 
class="cmbx-10">scale default</span>.
<!--l. 13435--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">rotate </span>asks <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>to rotate the text through 90 degrees, which will be done if the terminal driver in use supports
text rotation. <span 
class="cmbx-10">norotate </span>cancels this. <span 
class="cmbx-10">rotate by </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">ang</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>asks for rotation by <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>ang<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>degrees, supported by some
terminal types.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 13440--><p class="noindent" >The defaults are <span 
class="cmbx-10">border mirror norotate </span>for tics on the x and y axes, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">border nomirror norotate </span>for tics
on the x2 and y2 axes. For the z axis, the default is <span 
class="cmbx-10">nomirror</span>.
<!--l. 13444--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>offset<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is specified by either x,y or x,y,z, and may be preceded by <span 
class="cmbx-10">first</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">second</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">graph</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">screen</span>, or
<span 
class="cmbx-10">character </span>to select the coordinate system. <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>offset<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is the offset of the tics texts from their default positions, while
the default coordinate system is <span 
class="cmbx-10">character</span>. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">coordinates (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-20000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">24</span><!--tex4ht:ref: coordinates --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-309003"></a> for details. <span 
class="cmbx-10">nooffset </span>switches off the
offset.
<!--l. 13450--><p class="noindent" >By default, tic labels are justified automatically depending on the axis and rotation angle to produce aesthetically
pleasing results. If this is not desired, justification can be overridden with an explicit <span 
class="cmbx-10">left</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">right </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">center </span>keyword.
<span 
class="cmbx-10">autojustify </span>restores the default behavior.
<!--l. 13455--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">set tics </span>with no options restores to place tics inwards. Every other options are retained.
<!--l. 13458--><p class="noindent" >See also <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xtics (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-335000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">220</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set xtics --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-309004"></a> for more control of major (labelled) tic marks and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set mxtics </span>for control of minor tic
marks. These commands provide control at a axis by axis basis.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-310000III"></a>Ticslevel</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-616"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-310001"></a>
<!--l. 13469--><p class="noindent" >Deprecated. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xyplane (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-338000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">224</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set xyplane --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-310002"></a>.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-311000III"></a>Ticscale</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-618"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-311001"></a>
<!--l. 13478--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set ticscale </span>command is deprecated, use <span 
class="cmbx-10">set tics scale </span>instead.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-312000III"></a>Timestamp</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-620"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-312001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-312002"></a>
<!--l. 13491--><p class="noindent" >The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set timestamp </span>places the time and date of the plot in the left margin.
<!--l. 13494--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;timestamp</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{"&#x003C;format&#x003E;"}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{top|bottom}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{{no}rotate}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{offset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;xoff&#x003E;{,&#x003C;yoff&#x003E;}}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"&#x003C;fontspec&#x003E;"}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;timestamp</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;timestamp</span>
<!--l. 13501--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 13504--><p class="noindent" >The format string allows you to choose the format used to write the date and time. Its default value is what
asctime() uses: <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>%a %b %d %H:%M:%S %Y<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>(weekday, month name, day of the month, hours, minutes, seconds,
four-digit year). With <span 
class="cmbx-10">top </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">bottom </span>you can place the timestamp at the top or bottom of the left margin (default:
bottom). <span 
class="cmbx-10">rotate </span>lets you write the timestamp vertically, if your terminal supports vertical text. The constants
<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>xoff<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>yoff<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>are offsets that let you adjust the position more finely. <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>font<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is used to specify the font with
which the time is to be written.
<!--l. 13513--><p class="noindent" >The abbreviation <span 
class="cmbx-10">time </span>may be used in place of <span 
class="cmbx-10">timestamp</span>.
<!--l. 13515--><p class="noindent" >Example: <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;timestamp</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"%d/%m/%y</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;%H:%M"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;offset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;80,-2</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"Helvetica"</span>
<!--l. 13519--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 13522--><p class="noindent" >See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set timefmt (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-313000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">211</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set timefmt --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-312003"></a> for more information about time format strings.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-313000III"></a>Timefmt</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-622"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-313001"></a>
<!--l. 13531--><p class="noindent" >This command applies to timeseries where data are composed of dates/times. It has no meaning unless the
command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xdata time </span>is given also.
<!--l. 13534--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;timefmt</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"&#x003C;format</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;string&#x003E;"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;timefmt</span>
<!--l. 13539--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 13542--><p class="noindent" >The string argument tells <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>how to read timedata from the datafile. The valid formats are:
