<!--l. 13568--><p class="noindent" >Any character is allowed in the string, but must match exactly. <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>t (tab) is recognized. Backslash-octals
(<span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>nnn) are converted to char. If there is no separating character between the time/date elements,
then %d, %m, %y, %H, %M and %S read two digits each. If a decimal point immediately follows
the field read by %S, the decimal and any following digits are interpreted as a fractional second. %Y
reads four digits. %j reads three digits. %b requires three characters, and %B requires as many as it
needs.
<!--l. 13576--><p class="noindent" >Spaces are treated slightly differently. A space in the string stands for zero or more whitespace characters in the file.
That is, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>%H %M<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>can be used to read <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>1220<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>and <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>12 20<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>as well as <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>12 20<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.
<!--l. 13580--><p class="noindent" >Each set of non-blank characters in the timedata counts as one column in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">using n:n </span>specification. Thus <span 
class="cmbx-10">11:11</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">25/12/76 21.0 </span>consists of three columns. To avoid confusion, <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>requires that you provide a complete <span 
class="cmbx-10">using</span>
specification if your file contains timedata.
<!--l. 13585--><p class="noindent" >If the date format includes the day or month in words, the format string must exclude this text. But it can still be
printed with the <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>%a<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>%A<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>%b<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, or <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>%B<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>specifier. <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>will determine the proper month and weekday
from the numerical values. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set format (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-221000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">152</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set format --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-313002"></a> for more details about these and other options for printing
time data.
<!--l. 13591--><p class="noindent" >When reading two-digit years with %y, values 69-99 refer to the 20th century, while values 00-68 refer to the 21st
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
century. NB: This is in accordance with the UNIX98 spec, but conventions vary widely and two-digit year values are
inherently ambiguous.
<!--l. 13596--><p class="noindent" >See also <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xdata (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-330000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">216</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set xdata --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-313003"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">time/date (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-60000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">52</span><!--tex4ht:ref: time/date --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-313004"></a> for more information.
<!--l. 13598--><p class="noindent" >Example: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;timefmt</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"%d/%m/%Y\t%H:%M"</span>
<!--l. 13602--><p class="noindent" ></pre> tells <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>to read date and time separated by tab. (But look closely at your data &#8212; what began as a tab may
have been converted to spaces somewhere along the line; the format string must match what is actually in the file.)
See also
<!--l. 13608--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.gnuplot.info/demo/timedat.html" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">time data demo. </span></a>
<!--l. 13611--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-314000III"></a>Title</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-624"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-314001"></a>
<!--l. 13619--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set title </span>command produces a plot title that is centered at the top of the plot. <span 
class="cmbx-10">set title </span>is a special case of <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">label</span>.
<!--l. 13622--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{"&#x003C;title-text&#x003E;"}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{offset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;offset&#x003E;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"&#x003C;font&#x003E;{,&#x003C;size&#x003E;}"}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{{textcolor</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;tc}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;colorspec&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;default}}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{{no}enhanced}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span>
<!--l. 13628--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 13631--><p class="noindent" >If <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>offset<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is specified by either x,y or x,y,z the title is moved by the given offset. It may be preceded by <span 
class="cmbx-10">first</span>,
<span 
class="cmbx-10">second</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">graph</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">screen</span>, or <span 
class="cmbx-10">character </span>to select the coordinate system. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">coordinates (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-20000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">24</span><!--tex4ht:ref: coordinates --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-314002"></a> for details. By
default, the <span 
class="cmbx-10">character </span>coordinate system is used. For example, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">set title offset 0,-1</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>will change only the y offset
of the title, moving the title down by roughly the height of one character. The size of a character depends on both
the font and the terminal.
<!--l. 13639--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>font<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is used to specify the font with which the title is to be written; the units of the font <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>size<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>depend upon
which terminal is used.
<!--l. 13642--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">textcolor </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">colorspec</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>changes the color of the text. <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>colorspec<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>can be a linetype, an rgb color, or a palette
mapping. See help for <span 
class="cmbx-10">colorspec (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-42000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">40</span><!--tex4ht:ref: colorspec --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-314003"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">palette (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-274000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">187</span><!--tex4ht:ref: palette --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-314004"></a>.
<!--l. 13646--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">noenhanced </span>requests that the title not be processed by the enhanced text mode parser, even if enhanced text
mode is currently active.
<!--l. 13649--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">set title </span>with no parameters clears the title.
<!--l. 13651--><p class="noindent" >See <span 
class="cmbx-10">syntax (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-58000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">51</span><!--tex4ht:ref: syntax --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-314005"></a> for details about the processing of backslash sequences and the distinction between single- and
double-quotes.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-315000III"></a>Tmargin</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-626"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-315001"></a>
<!--l. 13659--><p class="noindent" >The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set tmargin </span>sets the size of the top margin. Please see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set margin (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-242000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">170</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set margin --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-315002"></a> for
details.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-316000III"></a>Trange</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-628"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-316001"></a>
<!--l. 13669--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set trange </span>command sets the parametric range used to compute x and y values when in parametric or polar
modes. Please see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xrange (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-334000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">218</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set xrange --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-316002"></a> for details.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-317000III"></a>Urange</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-630"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-317001"></a>
<!--l. 13680--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set urange </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set vrange </span>commands set the parametric ranges used to compute x, y, and z values when in
<span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>parametric mode. Please see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xrange (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-334000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">218</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set xrange --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-317002"></a> for details.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-318000III"></a>Variables</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-632"></a>
