<!--l. 13701--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-319000III"></a>Version</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-634"></a>
<!--l. 13704--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">show version </span>command lists the version of gnuplot being run, its last modification date, the copyright holders,
and email addresses for the FAQ, the gnuplot-info mailing list, and reporting bugs&#8211;in short, the information listed
on the screen when the program is invoked interactively.
<!--l. 13709--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;version</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{long}</span>
<!--l. 13713--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 13716--><p class="noindent" >When the <span 
class="cmbx-10">long </span>option is given, it also lists the operating system, the compilation options used when <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>was
installed, the location of the help file, and (again) the useful email addresses.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-320000III"></a>View</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-636"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-320001"></a>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 13728--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set view </span>command sets the viewing angle for <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>s. It controls how the 3D coordinates of the plot are
mapped into the 2D screen space. It provides controls for both rotation and scaling of the plotted data, but supports
orthographic projections only. It supports both 3D projection or orthogonal 2D projection into a 2D plot-like
map.
<!--l. 13734--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;view</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;rot_x&#x003E;{,{&#x003C;rot_z&#x003E;}{,{&#x003C;scale&#x003E;}{,&#x003C;scale_z&#x003E;}}}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;view</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;map</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;view</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{no}equal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{xy|xyz}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;view</span>
<!--l. 13741--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 13744--><p class="noindent" >where <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>rot_x<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>rot_z<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>control the rotation angles (in degrees) in a virtual 3D coordinate system
aligned with the screen such that initially (that is, before the rotations are performed) the screen
horizontal axis is x, screen vertical axis is y, and the axis perpendicular to the screen is z. The first
rotation applied is <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>rot_x<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>around the x axis. The second rotation applied is <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>rot_z<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>around the new z
axis.
<!--l. 13751--><p class="noindent" >Command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set view map </span>is used to represent the drawing as a map. It can be used for <span 
class="cmbx-10">contour </span>plots, or for color
<span 
class="cmbx-10">pm3d </span>maps. In the latter, take care that you properly use <span 
class="cmbx-10">zrange </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">cbrange </span>for input data point filtering and
color range scaling, respectively.
<!--l. 13756--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>rot_x<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is bounded to the [0:180] range with a default of 60 degrees, while <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>rot_z<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is bounded to the [0:360] range
with a default of 30 degrees. <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>scale<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>controls the scaling of the entire <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>, while <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>scale_z<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>scales the z axis only.
Both scales default to 1.0.
<!--l. 13761--><p class="noindent" >Examples: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;view</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;60,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;30,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;view</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;,,0.5</span>
<!--l. 13766--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 13769--><p class="noindent" >The first sets all the four default values. The second changes only scale, to 0.5.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-321000III"></a>Equal_axes</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-638"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-321001"></a>
<!--l. 13779--><p class="noindent" >The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set view equal xy </span>forces the unit length of the x and y axes to be on the same scale, and chooses
that scale so that the plot will fit on the page. The command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set view equal xyz </span>additionally sets the z
axis scale to match the x and y axes; however there is no guarantee that the current z axis range will
fit within the plot boundary. By default all three axes are scaled independently to fill the available
area.
<!--l. 13786--><p class="noindent" >See also <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xyplane (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-338000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">224</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set xyplane --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-321002"></a>.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-322000III"></a>Vrange</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-640"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-322001"></a>
<!--l. 13795--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set urange </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set vrange </span>commands set the parametric ranges used to compute x, y, and z values when in
<span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>parametric mode. Please see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xrange (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-334000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">218</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set xrange --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-322002"></a> for details.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
