class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-329003"></a>.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-330000III"></a>Xdata</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-656"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-330001"></a>
<!--l. 13892--><p class="noindent" >This command sets the datatype on the x axis to time/date. A similar command does the same thing for each of the
other axes.
<!--l. 13895--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xdata</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{time}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xdata</span>
<!--l. 13900--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 13903--><p class="noindent" >The same syntax applies to <span 
class="cmbx-10">ydata</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">zdata</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">x2data</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">y2data </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">cbdata</span>.
<!--l. 13905--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">time </span>option signals that the datatype is indeed time/date. If the option is not specified, the datatype reverts to
normal.
<!--l. 13908--><p class="noindent" >See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set timefmt (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-313000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">211</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set timefmt --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-330002"></a> to tell gnuplot how to read date or time data. The time/date is converted to seconds
from start of the century. There is currently only one timefmt, which implies that all the time/date columns must
conform to this format. Specification of ranges should be supplied as quoted strings according to this format to
avoid interpretation of the time/date as an expression.
<!--l. 13915--><p class="noindent" >The function &#8217;strftime&#8217; (type <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>man strftime<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>on unix to look it up) is used to print tic-mark labels. <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>tries to
figure out a reasonable format for this unless the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set format x </span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">string</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>has supplied something that does not look
like a decimal format (more than one &#8217;%&#8217; or neither %f nor %g).
<!--l. 13920--><p class="noindent" >See also <span 
class="cmbx-10">time/date (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-60000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">52</span><!--tex4ht:ref: time/date --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-330003"></a> for more information.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-331000III"></a>Xdtics</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-658"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-331001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-331002"></a>
<!--l. 13933--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xdtics </span>commands converts the x-axis tic marks to days of the week where 0=Sun and 6=Sat. Overflows are
converted modulo 7 to dates. <span 
class="cmbx-10">set noxdtics </span>returns the labels to their default values. Similar commands do the same
things for the other axes.
<!--l. 13938--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xdtics</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xdtics</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xdtics</span>
<!--l. 13944--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 13947--><p class="noindent" >The same syntax applies to <span 
class="cmbx-10">ydtics</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">zdtics</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">x2dtics</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">y2dtics </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">cbdtics</span>.
<!--l. 13950--><p class="noindent" >See also the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set format (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-221000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">152</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set format --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-331003"></a> command.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-332000III"></a>Xlabel</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-660"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-332001"></a>
