class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;norotate}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xlabel</span>
<!--l. 13969--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 13972--><p class="noindent" >The same syntax applies to <span 
class="cmbx-10">x2label</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">ylabel</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">y2label</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">zlabel </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">cblabel</span>.
<!--l. 13975--><p class="noindent" >If <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>offset<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is specified by either x,y or x,y,z the label is moved by the given offset. It may be preceded by <span 
class="cmbx-10">first</span>,
<span 
class="cmbx-10">second</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">graph</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">screen</span>, or <span 
class="cmbx-10">character </span>to select the coordinate system. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">coordinates (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-20000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">24</span><!--tex4ht:ref: coordinates --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-332002"></a> for details. By
default, the <span 
class="cmbx-10">character </span>coordinate system is used. For example, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">set xlabel offset -1,0</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>will change only the x
offset of the title, moving the label roughly one character width to the left. The size of a character depends on both
the font and the terminal.
<!--l. 13983--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>font<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is used to specify the font in which the label is written; the units of the font <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>size<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>depend upon which
terminal is used.
<!--l. 13986--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">noenhanced </span>requests that the label text not be processed by the enhanced text mode parser, even if enhanced text
mode is currently active.
<!--l. 13989--><p class="noindent" >To clear a label, put no options on the command line, e.g., <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">set y2label</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.
<!--l. 13991--><p class="noindent" >The default positions of the axis labels are as follows:
<!--l. 13993--><p class="noindent" >xlabel: The x-axis label is centered below the bottom of the plot.
<!--l. 13995--><p class="noindent" >ylabel: The y-axis label is centered to the left of the plot, defaulting to either horizontal or vertical orientation
depending on the terminal type.
<!--l. 13998--><p class="noindent" >zlabel: The z-axis label is centered along the z axis and placed in the space above the grid level.
<!--l. 14001--><p class="noindent" >cblabel: The color box axis label is centered along the box and placed below or to the right according to horizontal
or vertical color box gradient.
<!--l. 14004--><p class="noindent" >y2label: The y2-axis label is placed to the right of the y2 axis. The position is terminal-dependent in the same
manner as is the y-axis label.
<!--l. 14007--><p class="noindent" >x2label: The x2-axis label is placed above the plot but below the title. It is also possible to create an x2-axis label by
using new-line characters to make a multi-line plot title, e.g.,
<!--l. 14012--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"This</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;is</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;the</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title\n\nThis</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;is</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;the</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x2label"</span>
<!--l. 14014--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 14017--><p class="noindent" >Note that double quotes must be used. The same font will be used for both lines, of course.
<!--l. 14020--><p class="noindent" >The orientation (rotation angle) of the x, x2, y and y2 axis labels in 2D plots can be changed by specifying <span 
class="cmbx-10">rotate</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">by </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">degrees</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. The orientation of the x and y axis labels in 3D plots defaults to horizontal but can be changed to
run parallel to the axis by specifying <span 
class="cmbx-10">rotate parallel</span>.
<!--l. 14025--><p class="noindent" >If you are not satisfied with the default position of an axis label, use <span 
class="cmbx-10">set label </span>instead&#8211;that command gives you
much more control over where text is placed.
<!--l. 14029--><p class="noindent" >Please see <span 
class="cmbx-10">syntax (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-58000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">51</span><!--tex4ht:ref: syntax --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-332003"></a> for further information about backslash processing and the difference between single-
and double-quoted strings.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-333000III"></a>Xmtics</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-662"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-333001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-333002"></a>
<!--l. 14043--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xmtics </span>command converts the x-axis tic marks to months of the year where 1=Jan and 12=Dec. Overflows
are converted modulo 12 to months. The tics are returned to their default labels by <span 
class="cmbx-10">unset xmtics</span>. Similar
commands perform the same duties for the other axes.
<!--l. 14048--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xmtics</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;unset</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xmtics</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xmtics</span>
<!--l. 14054--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 14057--><p class="noindent" >The same syntax applies to <span 
class="cmbx-10">x2mtics</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">ymtics</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">y2mtics</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">zmtics </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">cbmtics</span>.
<!--l. 14060--><p class="noindent" >See also the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set format (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-221000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">152</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set format --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-333003"></a> command.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-334000III"></a>Xrange</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-664"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-334001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-334002"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-334003"></a>
<!--l. 14073--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xrange </span>command sets the horizontal range that will be displayed. A similar command exists
for each of the other axes, as well as for the polar radius r and the parametric variables t, u, and
v.
<!--l. 14077--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xrange</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[{{&#x003C;min&#x003E;}:{&#x003C;max&#x003E;}}]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{{no}reverse}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{{no}writeback}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;restore</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xrange</span>
<!--l. 14083--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 14086--><p class="noindent" >where <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>min<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>max<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>terms are constants, expressions or an asterisk to set autoscaling. See below for full
autoscaling syntax. If the data are time/date, you must give the range as a quoted string according to the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">timefmt </span>format. Any value omitted will not be changed.
<!--l. 14092--><p class="noindent" >The same syntax applies to <span 
class="cmbx-10">yrange</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">zrange</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">x2range</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">y2range</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">cbrange</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">rrange</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">trange</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">urange </span>and
<span 
class="cmbx-10">vrange</span>.
<!--l. 14095--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">reverse </span>option reverses the direction of the axis, e.g., <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xrange [0:1] reverse </span>will produce an axis with 1 on
the left and 0 on the right. This is identical to the axis produced by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xrange [1:0]</span>, of course. <span 
class="cmbx-10">reverse </span>is
intended primarily for use with <span 
class="cmbx-10">autoscale</span>.
<!--l. 14100--><p class="noindent" >Autoscaling: If <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>min<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>(the same applies for correspondingly to <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>max<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>) is an asterisk <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>*<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>autoscaling is turned on.
The range in which autoscaling is being performed may be limited by a lower bound <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>lb<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>or an upper bound <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>ub<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>
or both. The syntax is <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;lb&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;*</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;ub&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;}</span>
<!--l. 14107--><p class="noindent" ></pre> For example, <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;*</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;200</span>
<!--l. 14113--><p class="noindent" ></pre> sets <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>lb<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>= 0 and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>ub<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>= 200. With such a setting <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>min<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>would be autoscaled, but its final value will be
between 0 and 200 (both inclusive despite the &#8217;<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>&#8217; sign). If no lower or upper bound is specified, the &#8217;<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>&#8217; to also be
ommited. If <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>ub<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is lower than <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>lb<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>the constraints will be turned off and full autoscaling will happen. This
feature is useful to plot measured data with autoscaling but providing a limit on the range, to clip outliers,
or to guarantee a minimum range that will be displayed even if the data would not need such a big
range.
<!--l. 14124--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">writeback </span>option essentially saves the range found by <span 
class="cmbx-10">autoscale </span>in the buffers that would be filled by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">xrange</span>. This is useful if you wish to plot several functions together but have the range determined by
only some of them. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">writeback </span>operation is performed during the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>execution, so it must be
specified before that command. To restore, the last saved horizontal range use <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xrange restore</span>. For
example,
<!--l. 14132--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xrange</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[-10:10]</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;yrange</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;writeback</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sin(x)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;yrange</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;restore</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;replot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x/2</span>
<!--l. 14138--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 14141--><p class="noindent" >results in a yrange of [-1:1] as found only from the range of sin(x); the [-5:5] range of x/2 is ignored. Executing
<span 
class="cmbx-10">show yrange </span>after each command in the above example should help you understand what is going
on.
<!--l. 14145--><p class="noindent" >In 2D, <span 
class="cmbx-10">xrange </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">yrange </span>determine the extent of the axes, <span 
class="cmbx-10">trange </span>determines the range of the
parametric variable in parametric mode or the range of the angle in polar mode. Similarly in parametric
3D, <span 
class="cmbx-10">xrange</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">yrange</span>, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">zrange </span>govern the axes and <span 
class="cmbx-10">urange </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">vrange </span>govern the parametric
variables.
<!--l. 14151--><p class="noindent" >In polar mode, <span 
class="cmbx-10">rrange </span>determines the radial range plotted. <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>rmin<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>acts as an additive constant to the radius,
whereas <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>rmax<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>acts as a clip to the radius &#8212; no point with radius greater than <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>rmax<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>will be plotted. <span 
class="cmbx-10">xrange</span>
and <span 
class="cmbx-10">yrange </span>are affected &#8212; the ranges can be set as if the graph was of r(t)-rmin, with rmin added to all the
labels.
<!--l. 14157--><p class="noindent" >Any range may be partially or totally autoscaled, although it may not make sense to autoscale a parametric variable
unless it is plotted with data.
<!--l. 14160--><p class="noindent" >Ranges may also be specified on the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command line. A range given on the plot line will be used for that single
<span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command; a range given by a <span 
class="cmbx-10">set </span>command will be used for all subsequent plots that do not specify their own
ranges. The same holds true for <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>.
<!--l. 14165--><p class="noindent" >Examples:
<!--l. 14167--><p class="noindent" >To set the xrange to the default: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xrange</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[-10:10]</span>
<!--l. 14171--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 14174--><p class="noindent" >To set the yrange to increase downwards: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;yrange</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[10:-10]</span>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 14178--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 14181--><p class="noindent" >To change zmax to 10 without affecting zmin (which may still be autoscaled): <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;zrange</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[:10]</span>
<!--l. 14185--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 14188--><p class="noindent" >To autoscale xmin while leaving xmax unchanged: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xrange</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[*:]</span>
<!--l. 14192--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 14195--><p class="noindent" >To autoscale xmin but keeping xmin positive: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xrange</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[0&#x003C;*:]</span>
<!--l. 14199--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 14202--><p class="noindent" >To autoscale x but keep minimum range of 10 to 50 (actual might be larger): <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xrange</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[*&#x003C;10:50&#x003C;*]</span>
<!--l. 14206--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 14209--><p class="noindent" >Autoscaling but limit maximum xrange to -1000 to 1000, i.e. autoscaling within [-1000:1000] <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xrange</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[-1000&#x003C;*:*&#x003C;1000]</span>
<!--l. 14214--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 14217--><p class="noindent" >Make sure xmin is somewhere between -200 and 100: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
