<!--l. 14509--><p class="noindent" >The form <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xyplane relative </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">frac</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>places the xy plane below the range in Z, where the distance from the xy
plane to Zmin is given as a fraction of the total range in z. The default value is 0.5. Negative values are permitted,
but tic labels on the three axes may overlap. The older, deprecated, form <span 
class="cmbx-10">set ticslevel </span>is retained for backwards
compatibility.
<!--l. 14515--><p class="noindent" >To place the xy-plane at a position &#8217;pos&#8217; on the z-axis, <span 
class="cmbx-10">ticslevel </span>may be set equal to (pos - zmin) / (zmin - zmax).
However, this position will change if the z range is changed.
<!--l. 14519--><p class="noindent" >The alternative form <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xyplane at </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">zvalue</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>fixes the placement of the xy plane at a specific Z value regardless
of the current z range. Thus to force the x, y, and z axes to meet at a common origin one would specify <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xyplane</span>
