<a 
 id="Q1-1-714"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-359001"></a>
<!--l. 14779--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">zero </span>value is the default threshold for values approaching 0.0.
<!--l. 14781--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;zero</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;expression&#x003E;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;show</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;zero</span>
<!--l. 14786--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 14789--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>will not plot a point if its imaginary part is greater in magnitude than the <span 
class="cmbx-10">zero </span>threshold.
This threshold is also used in various other parts of <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>as a (crude) numerical-error threshold.
The default <span 
class="cmbx-10">zero </span>value is 1e-8. <span 
class="cmbx-10">zero </span>values larger than 1e-3 (the reciprocal of the number of pixels
in a typical bitmap display) should probably be avoided, but it is not unreasonable to set <span 
class="cmbx-10">zero </span>to
0.0.
