<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-369000III"></a>Shell</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-734"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-369001"></a>
<!--l. 14956--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">shell </span>command spawns an interactive shell. To return to <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot</span>, type <span 
class="cmbx-10">logout </span>if using VMS, <span 
class="cmbx-10">exit </span>or the
END-OF-FILE character if using Unix, or <span 
class="cmbx-10">exit </span>if using MS-DOS or OS/2.
<!--l. 14960--><p class="noindent" >There are two ways of spawning a shell command: using <span 
class="cmbx-10">system </span>command or via <span 
class="cmbx-10">! </span>($ if using VMS).
The former command takes a string as a parameter and thus it can be used anywhere among other
gnuplot commands, while the latter syntax requires to be the only command on the line. Control
will return immediately to <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>after this command is executed. For example, in MS-DOS or
OS/2,
<!--l. 14968--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;!</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;dir</span>
<!--l. 14970--><p class="noindent" ></pre> or <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;system</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"dir"</span>
<!--l. 14976--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 14979--><p class="noindent" >prints a directory listing and then returns to <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot</span>.
<!--l. 14981--><p class="noindent" >Other examples of the former syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;system</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"date";</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;time;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"a.dat"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;print=1;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;if</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(print)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;replot;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;out;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;system</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"lpr</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x.ps"</span>
<!--l. 14986--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-370000III"></a>Splot</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-736"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-370001"></a>
<!--l. 14993--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>is the command for drawing 3D plots (well, actually projections on a 2D surface, but you knew that). It can
create a plot from functions or data read from files in a manner very similar to the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command. <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>
provides only a single x, y, and z axis; there is no equivalent to the x2 and y2 secondary axes provided by
<span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>.
<!--l. 14999--><p class="noindent" >See the <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-126000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">93</span><!--tex4ht:ref: plot --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-370002"></a> command for many options available in both 2D and 3D plots.
<!--l. 15001--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;splot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;ranges&#x003E;}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;iteration&#x003E;}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;function&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"&#x003C;datafile&#x003E;"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{datafile-modifiers}}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;title-spec&#x003E;}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;style&#x003E;}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{definitions{,}}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;function&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;...}</span>
<!--l. 15009--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 15012--><p class="noindent" >where either a <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>function<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>or the name of a data file enclosed in quotes is supplied. The function can be a
mathematical expression, or a triple of mathematical expressions in parametric mode.
<!--l. 15016--><p class="noindent" >By default <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>draws the xy plane completely below the plotted data. The offset between the lowest ztic and the
xy plane can be changed by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xyplane</span>. The orientation of a <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>projection is controlled by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set view</span>. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">view (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-320000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">213</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set view --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-370003"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xyplane (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-338000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">224</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set xyplane --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-370004"></a> for more information.
<!--l. 15021--><p class="noindent" >The syntax for setting ranges on the <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>command is the same as for <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>. In non-parametric mode, the order in
which ranges must be given is <span 
class="cmbx-10">xrange</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">yrange</span>, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">zrange</span>. In parametric mode, the order is <span 
class="cmbx-10">urange</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">vrange</span>,
<span 
class="cmbx-10">xrange</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">yrange</span>, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">zrange</span>.
<!--l. 15026--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">title </span>option is the same as in <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>. The operation of <span 
class="cmbx-10">with </span>is also the same as in <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>, except that the plotting
styles available to <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>are limited to <span 
class="cmbx-10">lines</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">points</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">linespoints</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">dots</span>, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">impulses</span>; the error-bar capabilities of
<span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>are not available for <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>.
<!--l. 15031--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">datafile </span>options have more differences.
<!--l. 15033--><p class="noindent" >See also <span 
class="cmbx-10">show plot (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-264000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">182</span><!--tex4ht:ref: show plot --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
