<!--l. 15051--><p class="noindent" >The special filenames <span 
class="cmtt-10">"" </span>and <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">-</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>are permitted, as in <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">special-filenames (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-162000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">106</span><!--tex4ht:ref: special-filenames --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-371001"></a>.
<!--l. 15054--><p class="noindent" >In brief, <span 
class="cmbx-10">binary </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">matrix </span>indicate that the data are in a special form, <span 
class="cmbx-10">index </span>selects which data sets
in a multi-data-set file are to be plotted, <span 
class="cmbx-10">every </span>specifies which datalines (subsets) within a single
data set are to be plotted, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>determines how the columns within a single record are to be
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
interpreted.
<!--l. 15060--><p class="noindent" >The options <span 
class="cmbx-10">index </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">every </span>behave the same way as with <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>; <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>does so also, except that the <span 
class="cmbx-10">using </span>list
must provide three entries instead of two.
<!--l. 15064--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>options <span 
class="cmbx-10">thru </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">smooth </span>are not available for <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>, but <span 
class="cmbx-10">cntrparam </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">dgrid3d </span>provide limited
smoothing capabilities.
<!--l. 15067--><p class="noindent" >Data file organization is essentially the same as for <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>, except that each point is an (x,y,z) triple. If only a single
value is provided, it will be used for z, the datablock number will be used for y, and the index of the data point in
the datablock will be used for x. If two or four values are provided, <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>uses the last value for calculating the
color in pm3d plots. Three values are interpreted as an (x,y,z) triple. Additional values are generally used as errors,
which can be used by <span 
class="cmbx-10">fit</span>.
<!--l. 15075--><p class="noindent" >Single blank records separate datablocks in a <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>datafile; <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>treats datablocks as the equivalent of function
y-isolines. No line will join points separated by a blank record. If all datablocks contain the same number of points,
<span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>will draw cross-isolines between datablocks, connecting corresponding points. This is termed <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>grid data<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>,
and is required for drawing a surface, for contouring (<span 
class="cmbx-10">set contour</span>) and hidden-line removal (<span 
class="cmbx-10">set hidden3d</span>). See
also <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot grid</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">_data (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-374000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">235</span><!--tex4ht:ref: splot grid_data --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-371002"></a>.
<!--l. 15083--><p class="noindent" >It is no longer necessary to specify <span 
class="cmbx-10">parametric </span>mode for three-column <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot</span>s.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-372000III"></a>Matrix</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-740"></a>
<!--l. 15097--><p class="noindent" >Gnuplot can interpret matrix input in two different ways. The first of these assumes a uniform grid of x and y
coordinates, and assigns each value in the input matrix to one element of this uniform grid. This is the default
for ascii data input, but not for binary input. Example commands for plotting uniform matrix data:
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;splot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;matrix</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2:3</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;#</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ascii</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;input</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;splot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;file&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;binary</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;general</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:2:3</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;#</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;binary</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;input</span>
<!--l. 15106--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 15109--><p class="noindent" >In a uniform grid matrix the z-values are read in a row at a time, i. e., <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;z11</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;z12</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;z13</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;z14</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;...</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;z21</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;z22</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;z23</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;z24</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;...</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;z31</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;z32</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;z33</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;z34</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;...</span>
<!--l. 15115--><p class="noindent" ></pre> and so forth.
<!--l. 15119--><p class="noindent" >For ascii input, a blank line or comment line ends the matrix, and starts a new surface mesh. You can select among
the meshes inside a file by the <span 
class="cmbx-10">index </span>option to the <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>command, as usual. <a 
 id="dx1-372001"></a>The second interpretation assumes a
non-uniform grid with explicit x and y coordinates. The first row of input data contains the y coordinates; the first
column of input data contains the x coordinates. For binary input data, the first element of the first row must
contain the number of data columns. (This number is ignored for ascii input). Both the coordinates and the data
values in a binary input are treated as single precision floats. Example commands for plotting non-uniform matrix
data: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;splot</span><span 
