<!--l. 15170--><p class="noindent" >A collection of matrix and vector manipulation routines (in C) is provided in <span 
class="cmbx-10">binary.c</span>. The routine to write binary
data is
<!--l. 15174--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;int</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fwrite_matrix(file,m,nrl,nrl,ncl,nch,row_title,column_title)</span>
<!--l. 15176--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 15179--><p class="noindent" >An example of using these routines is provided in the file <span 
class="cmbx-10">bf</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">_test.c</span>, which generates binary files for the demo file
<span 
class="cmbx-10">demo/binary.dem</span>.
<!--l. 15182--><p class="noindent" >Usage in <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;a.dat&#8216;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;matrix</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;a.dat&#8216;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;matrix</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:3</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;a.gpbin&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{matrix}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;binary</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:3</span>
<!--l. 15188--><p class="noindent" ></pre> will plot rows of the matrix, while using 2:3 will plot matrix columns, and using 1:2 the point coordinates (rather
useless). Applying the <span 
class="cmbx-10">every </span>option you can specify explicit rows and columns.
<!--l. 15194--><p class="noindent" >Example &#8211; rescale axes of a matrix in an ascii file: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;splot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;a.dat&#8216;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;matrix</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(1+$1):(1+$2*10):3</span>
<!--l. 15198--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 15201--><p class="noindent" >Example &#8211; plot the 3rd row of a matrix in an ascii file: <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;a.dat&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;matrix</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:3</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;every</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;1:999:1:2</span>
<!--l. 15205--><p class="noindent" ></pre> (rows are enumerated from 0, thus 2 instead of 3).
<!--l. 15209--><p class="noindent" >Gnuplot can read matrix binary files by use of the option <span 
class="cmbx-10">binary </span>appearing without keyword qualifications unique
to general binary, i.e., <span 
class="cmbx-10">array</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">record</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">format</span>, or <span 
class="cmbx-10">filetype</span>. Other general binary keywords for translation should
also apply to matrix binary. (See <span 
class="cmbx-10">binary general (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-129000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">94</span><!--tex4ht:ref: binary general --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-372002"></a> for more details.)
