<!--l. 15262--><p class="noindent" >Note that <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>datafile.dat<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>defines a 4 by 3 grid ( 4 rows of 3 points each ). Rows (datablocks) are separated by blank
records.
<!--l. 15265--><p class="noindent" >Note also that the x value is held constant within each dataline. If you instead keep y constant, and plot with
hidden-line removal enabled, you will find that the surface is drawn &#8217;inside-out&#8217;.
<!--l. 15269--><p class="noindent" >Actually for grid data it is not necessary to keep the x values constant within a datablock, nor is it necessary to keep
the same sequence of y values. <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>requires only that the number of points be the same for each datablock.
However since the surface mesh, from which contours are derived, connects sequentially corresponding points, the
effect of an irregular grid on a surface plot is unpredictable and should be examined on a case-by-case
basis.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-374000III"></a>Grid data</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-744"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-374001"></a>
<!--l. 15282--><p class="noindent" >The 3D routines are designed for points in a grid format, with one sample, datapoint, at each mesh intersection; the
datapoints may originate from either evaluating a function, see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set isosamples (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-230000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">158</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set isosamples --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-374002"></a>, or reading a datafile, see
<span 
class="cmbx-10">splot datafile (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-371000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">231</span><!--tex4ht:ref: splot datafile --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-374003"></a>. The term <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>isoline<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is applied to the mesh lines for both functions and data. Note that the
mesh need not be rectangular in x and y, as it may be parameterized in u and v, see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set isosamples</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-230000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">158</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set isosamples --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-374004"></a>.
<!--l. 15289--><p class="noindent" >However, <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>does not require that format. In the case of functions, &#8217;samples&#8217; need not be equal to
&#8217;isosamples&#8217;, i.e., not every x-isoline sample need intersect a y-isoline. In the case of data files, if there are an
equal number of scattered data points in each datablock, then <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>isolines<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>will connect the points in a
datablock, and <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>cross-isolines<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>will connect the corresponding points in each datablock to generate
a <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>surface<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. In either case, contour and hidden3d modes may give different plots than if the points
were in the intended format. Scattered data can be converted to a <span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>different<span 
class="cmsy-10">} </span>grid format with <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">dgrid3d</span>.
<!--l. 15299--><p class="noindent" >The contour code tests for z intensity along a line between a point on a y-isoline and the corresponding point in the
next y-isoline. Thus a <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>contour of a surface with samples on the x-isolines that do not coincide with a y-isoline
intersection will ignore such samples. Try: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xrange</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[-pi/2:pi/2];</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;yrange</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[-pi/2:pi/2]</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;style</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;function</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lp</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;contour</span>
