<!--l. 15315--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-375000III"></a>Splot surfaces</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-746"></a>
<!--l. 15319--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>can display a surface as a collection of points, or by connecting those points. As with <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>, the points may be
read from a data file or result from evaluation of a function at specified intervals, see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set isosamples (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-230000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">158</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set isosamples --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-375001"></a>.
The surface may be approximated by connecting the points with straight line segments, see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set surface (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-305000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">207</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set surface --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-375002"></a>,
in which case the surface can be made opaque with <span 
class="cmbx-10">set hidden3d. </span>The orientation from which the 3d surface is
viewed can be changed with <span 
class="cmbx-10">set view</span>.
<!--l. 15327--><p class="noindent" >Additionally, for points in a grid format, <span 
class="cmbx-10">splot </span>can interpolate points having a common amplitude (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmbx-10">contour (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-206000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">141</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set contour --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-375003"></a>) and can then connect those new points to display contour lines, either directly
with straight-line segments or smoothed lines (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set cntrparam (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-203000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">138</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set cntrparam --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-375004"></a>). Functions are already
evaluated in a grid format, determined by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set isosamples </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set samples</span>, while file data must
either be in a grid format, as described in <span 
class="cmbx-10">data-file</span>, or be used to generate a grid (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">set dgrid3d</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-216000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">147</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set dgrid3d --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-375005"></a>).
<!--l. 15335--><p class="noindent" >Contour lines may be displayed either on the surface or projected onto the base. The base projections of the contour
lines may be written to a file, and then read with <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>, to take advantage of <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>&#8217;s additional formatting
capabilities.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-376000III"></a>Stats (Statistical Summary)</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-748"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-376001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-376002"></a>
<!--l. 15346--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;stats</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;filename&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[using</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;N[:M]]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[name</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;prefix&#8217;]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[[no]output]]</span>
<!--l. 15350--><p class="noindent" ></pre> This command prepares a statistical summary of the data in one or two columns of a file. The using specifier is
interpreted in the same way as for plot commands. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-126000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">93</span><!--tex4ht:ref: plot --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-376003"></a> for details on the <span 
class="cmbx-10">index (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-151000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">103</span><!--tex4ht:ref: index --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-376004"></a>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">every</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-149000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">101</span><!--tex4ht:ref: every --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-376005"></a>, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">using (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-164000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">109</span><!--tex4ht:ref: using --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-376006"></a> directives. Data points are filtered against both xrange and yrange before
analysis. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set xrange (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-334000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">218</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set xrange --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-376007"></a>. The summary is printed to the screen by default. Output can be
redirected to a file by prior use of the command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set print</span>, or suppressed altogether using the <span 
class="cmbx-10">nooutput</span>
option.
