<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-378000III"></a>Test</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-752"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-378001"></a>
<!--l. 15461--><p class="noindent" >This command graphically tests or presents terminal and palette capabilities.
<!--l. 15463--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;test</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;palette</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;[rgb|rbg|grb|gbr|brg|bgr]}</span>
<!--l. 15467--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 15470--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">test </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">test terminal </span>creates a display of line and point styles and other useful things appropriate for and
supported by the <span 
class="cmbx-10">terminal </span>you are just using.
<!--l. 15474--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">test palette </span>plots profiles of R(z),G(z),B(z), where 0<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>=z<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>=1. These are the RGB components of the current color
<span 
class="cmbx-10">palette</span>. It also plots the apparent net intensity as calculated using NTSC coefficients to map RGB onto a grayscale.
The optional parameter, a permutation of letters rgb, determines the sequence in which the r,g,b profiles are
drawn.
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-379000III"></a>Undefine</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-754"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-379001"></a>
<!--l. 15484--><p class="noindent" >Clear one or more previously defined user variables. This is useful in order to reset the state of a script containing
an initialization test.
<!--l. 15487--><p class="noindent" >A variable name can contain the wildcard character <span 
class="cmbx-10">* </span>as last character. If the wildcard character is found, all
variables with names that begin with the prefix preceding the wildcard will be removed. This is useful to remove
several variables sharing a common prefix. Note that the wildcard character is only allowed at the
end of the variable name! Specifying the wildcard character as sole argument to <span 
class="cmbx-10">undefine </span>has no
effect.
<!--l. 15494--><p class="noindent" >Example:
