<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-381000III"></a>Update</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-758"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-381001"></a>
<!--l. 15541--><p class="noindent" >This command writes the current values of the fit parameters into the given file, formatted as an initial-value file (as
described in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">fit</span>section). This is useful for saving the current values for later use or for restarting a converged or
stopped fit.
<!--l. 15546--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;update</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;filename&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;filename&#x003E;}</span>
<!--l. 15550--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 15553--><p class="noindent" >If a second filename is supplied, the updated values are written to this file, and the original parameter file is left
unmodified.
<!--l. 15556--><p class="noindent" >Otherwise, if the file already exists, <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>first renames it by appending <span 
class="cmbx-10">.old </span>and then opens a new file. That is,
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">update &#8217;fred&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>behaves the same as <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">!rename fred fred.old; update &#8217;fred.old&#8217; &#8217;fred&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. [On DOS and other
systems that use the twelve-character <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>filename.ext<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>naming convention, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>ext<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>will be <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">old</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>and <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>filename<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>will be
related (hopefully recognizably) to the initial name. Renaming is not done at all on VMS systems, since they use
file-versioning.]
<!--l. 15564--><p class="noindent" >Please see <span 
class="cmbx-10">fit (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-106000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">79</span><!--tex4ht:ref: fit --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-381002"></a> for more information.
