class="cmtt-10">"</span>), <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>x<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; &#x003C;</span>y<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is the size of the plot (default is 846x594 pt = 11.75x8.25
in).
<!--l. 15665--><p class="noindent" >Use <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>fontname<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>to specify the font (default is <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>Times-Roman<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>), and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>fontsize<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>to specify the font size (default is
14.0 pt).
<!--l. 15668--><p class="noindent" >The aqua terminal supports enhanced text mode (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">enhanced (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-22000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">26</span><!--tex4ht:ref: enhanced --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-387003"></a>), except for overprint. Font support is
limited to the fonts available on the system. Character encoding can be selected by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set encoding </span>and currently
supports iso_latin_1, iso_latin_2, cp1250, and UTF8 (default).
<!--l. 15673--><p class="noindent" >Lines can be drawn either solid or dashed, (default is solid) and the dash spacing can be modified by <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>dashlength<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>
which is a multiplier <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>0.
<!--l. 15676--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-388000IV"></a>Be</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-771"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-388001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-388002"></a>
<!--l. 15687--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">be </span>terminal type is present if gnuplot is built for the <span 
class="cmbx-10">beos </span>operating system and for use with X servers. It is
selected at program startup if the <span 
class="cmbx-10">DISPLAY </span>environment variable is set, if the <span 
class="cmbx-10">TERM </span>environment variable is set
to <span 
class="cmbx-10">xterm</span>, or if the <span 
class="cmbx-10">-display </span>command line option is used.
<!--l. 15693--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;be</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{reset}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;n&#x003E;}</span>
<!--l. 15697--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 15700--><p class="noindent" >Multiple plot windows are supported: <span 
class="cmbx-10">set terminal be </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">n</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>directs the output to plot window number n. If n<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>0,
the terminal number will be appended to the window title and the icon will be labeled <span 
class="cmbx-10">gplt </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">n</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. The active
window may distinguished by a change in cursor (from default to crosshair.)
<!--l. 15706--><p class="noindent" >Plot windows remain open even when the <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>driver is changed to a different device. A plot window can be
closed by pressing the letter q while that window has input focus, or by choosing <span 
class="cmbx-10">close </span>from a window manager
menu. All plot windows can be closed by specifying <span 
class="cmbx-10">reset</span>, which actually terminates the subprocess which
maintains the windows (unless <span 
class="cmbx-10">-persist </span>was specified).
<!--l. 15713--><p class="noindent" >Plot windows will automatically be closed at the end of the session unless the <span 
class="cmbx-10">-persist </span>option was
given.
<!--l. 15716--><p class="noindent" >The size or aspect ratio of a plot may be changed by resizing the <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>window.
<!--l. 15719--><p class="noindent" >Linewidths and pointsizes may be changed from within <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>with <span 
class="cmbx-10">set linestyle</span>.
<!--l. 15722--><p class="noindent" >For terminal type <span 
class="cmbx-10">be</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>accepts (when initialized) the standard X Toolkit options and resources such as
geometry, font, and name from the command line arguments or a configuration file. See the X(1) man page (or its
equivalent) for a description of such options.
<!--l. 15727--><p class="noindent" >A number of other <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>options are available for the <span 
class="cmbx-10">be </span>terminal. These may be specified either as
command-line options when <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>is invoked or as resources in the configuration file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.Xdefaults<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. They are set
upon initialization and cannot be altered during a <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>session.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
