<!--l. 15761--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 15764--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>also provides a command line option (<span 
class="cmbx-10">-pointsize </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">v</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>) and a resource, <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot*pointsize: </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">v</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>, to
control the size of points plotted with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">points </span>plotting style. The value <span 
class="cmbx-10">v </span>is a real number (greater than 0 and
less than or equal to ten) used as a scaling factor for point sizes. For example, <span 
class="cmbx-10">-pointsize 2 </span>uses points twice the
default size, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">-pointsize 0.5 </span>uses points half the normal size.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-390000IV"></a>Monochrome_options</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-775"></a>
<!--l. 15776--><p class="noindent" >For monochrome displays, <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>does not honor foreground or background colors. The default is black-on-white.
<span 
class="cmbx-10">-rv </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot*reverseVideo: on </span>requests white-on-black.
