<!--l. 15929--><p class="noindent" >The cairolatex terminal prints a plot like <span 
class="cmbx-10">terminal epscairo </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">terminal pdfcairo </span>but transfers the texts to
LaTeX instead of including them in the graph. For reference of options not explained here see <span 
class="cmbx-10">pdfcairo</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-450000IV"><span 
class="cmbx-10">285</span><!--tex4ht:ref: pdfcairo --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-394002"></a>.
<!--l. 15933--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">eps </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">pdf </span>select the type of grahics output. Use <span 
class="cmbx-10">eps </span>with latex/dvips and <span 
class="cmbx-10">pdf </span>for pdflatex.
<!--l. 15936--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">blacktext </span>forces all text to be written in black even in color mode;
<!--l. 15938--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">cairolatex </span>driver offers a special way of controlling text positioning: (a) If any text string begins with &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>&#8217;, you
also need to include a &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>&#8217; at the end of the text, and the whole text will be centered both horizontally and
vertically by LaTeX. (b) If the text string begins with &#8217;[&#8217;, you need to continue it with: a position
specification (up to two out of t,b,l,r,c), &#8217;]<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>&#8217;, the text itself, and finally, &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>&#8217;. The text itself may be anything
LaTeX can typeset as an LR-box. <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>rule<span 
class="cmsy-10">{}{}</span>&#8217;s may help for best positioning. See also the documentation
for the <span 
class="cmbx-10">pslatex (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-460000IV"><span 
class="cmbx-10">294</span><!--tex4ht:ref: pslatex --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-394003"></a> terminal driver. To create multiline labels, use <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>shortstack, for example
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ylabel</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;[r]{\shortstack{first</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;line</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\\</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;second</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;line}}&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 15950--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 15953--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">back </span>option of <span 
class="cmbx-10">set label </span>commands is handled slightly different than in other terminals. Labels using &#8217;back&#8217;
are printed behind all other elements of the plot while labels using &#8217;front&#8217; are printed above everything
else.
<!--l. 15958--><p class="noindent" >The driver produces two different files, one for the eps or pdf part of the figure and one for the LaTeX part. The
name of the LaTeX file is taken from the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set output </span>command. The name of the eps/pdf file is derived by
replacing the file extension (normally &#8217;.tex&#8217;) with &#8217;.eps&#8217; or &#8217;.pdf&#8217; instead. There is no LaTeX output
if no output file is given! Remember to close the <span 
class="cmbx-10">output file </span>before next plot unless in <span 
class="cmbx-10">multiplot</span>
mode.
<!--l. 15965--><p class="noindent" >In your LaTeX documents use &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>input<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>filename<span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>&#8217; to include the figure. The &#8217;.eps&#8217; or &#8217;.pdf&#8217; file is included by the
command <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>includegraphics<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>...<span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>, so you must also include <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>usepackage<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>graphicx<span 
class="cmsy-10">} </span>in the LaTeX preamble. If you
want to use coloured text (option <span 
class="cmbx-10">colourtext</span>) you also have to include <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>usepackage<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>color<span 
class="cmsy-10">} </span>in the LaTeX
preamble.
<!--l. 15971--><p class="noindent" >The behaviour concerning font selection depends on the header mode. In all cases, the given font size is used for the
calculation of proper spacing. When not using the <span 
class="cmbx-10">standalone </span>mode the actual LaTeX font and font size at the
point of inclusion is taken, so use LaTeX commands for changing fonts. If you use e.g. 12pt as font size for your
LaTeX document, use &#8217;<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, 12<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>&#8217; as options. The font name is ignored. If using <span 
class="cmbx-10">standalone </span>the given font and font size
are used, see below for a detailed description.
<!--l. 15980--><p class="noindent" >If text is printed coloured is controlled by the TeX booleans <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>ifGPcolor and <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>ifGPblacktext. Only if <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>ifGPcolor is
true and <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>ifGPblacktext is false, text is printed coloured. You may either change them in the generated TeX file or
provide them globally in your TeX file, for example by using <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\newif\ifGPblacktext</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\GPblacktexttrue</span>
<!--l. 15989--><p class="noindent" ></pre> in the preamble of your document. The local assignment is only done if no global value is given.
<!--l. 15994--><p class="noindent" >When using the cairolatex terminal give the name of the TeX file in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set output </span>command including the file
extension (normally <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.tex<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>). The graph filename is generated by replacing the extension.
<!--l. 15998--><p class="noindent" >If using the <span 
class="cmbx-10">standalone </span>mode a complete LaTeX header is added to the LaTeX file; and <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>-inc<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is added to the
filename of the gaph file. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">standalone </span>mode generates a TeX file that produces output with the correct size
when using dvips, pdfTeX, or VTeX. The default, <span 
class="cmbx-10">input</span>, generates a file that has to be included into a LaTeX
document using the <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>input command.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 16005--><p class="noindent" >If a font other than <span 
class="cmtt-10">"" </span>or <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>default<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is given it is interpreted as LaTeX font name. It contains up to three parts,
separated by a comma: &#8217;fontname,fontseries,fontshape&#8217;. If the default fontshape or fontseries are requested, they can
be omitted. Thus, the real syntax for the fontname is &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>fontname<span 
class="cmsy-10">}{</span>,fontseries<span 
class="cmsy-10">}{</span>,fontshape<span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>&#8217;. The naming convention
for all parts is given by the LaTeX font scheme. The fontname is 3 to 4 characters long and is built as follows: One
character for the font vendor, two characters for the name of the font, and optionally one additional character for
special fonts, e.g., &#8217;j&#8217; for fonts with old-style numerals or &#8217;x&#8217; for expert fonts. The names of many fonts is described
in
<!--l. 16015--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.tug.org/fontname/fontname.pdf" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">http://www.tug.org/fontname/fontname.pdf </span></a>
<!--l. 16018--><p class="noindent" >For example, &#8217;cmr&#8217; stands for Computer Modern Roman, &#8217;ptm&#8217; for Times-Roman, and &#8217;phv&#8217; for Helvetica. The font
series denotes the thickness of the glyphs, in most cases &#8217;m&#8217; for normal (<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>medium<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>) and &#8217;bx&#8217; or &#8217;b&#8217; for bold fonts.
The font shape is &#8217;n&#8217; for upright, &#8217;it&#8217; for italics, &#8217;sl&#8217; for slanted, or &#8217;sc&#8217; for small caps, in general. Some fonts may
provide different font series or shapes.
<!--l. 16025--><p class="noindent" >Examples:
<!--l. 16027--><p class="noindent" >Use Times-Roman boldface (with the same shape as in the surrounding text): <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;cairolatex</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;ptm,bx&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 16031--><p class="noindent" ></pre> Use Helvetica, boldface, italics: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;cairolatex</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;phv,bx,it&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 16037--><p class="noindent" ></pre> Continue to use the surrounding font in slanted shape: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;cairolatex</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;,,sl&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 16043--><p class="noindent" ></pre> Use small capitals: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;cairolatex</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;,,sc&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 16049--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 16052--><p class="noindent" >By this method, only text fonts are changed. If you also want to change the math fonts you have to use the
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>gnuplot.cfg<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>file or the <span 
class="cmbx-10">header </span>option, described below.
<!--l. 16056--><p class="noindent" >In <span 
class="cmbx-10">standalone </span>mode, the font size is taken from the given font size in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set terminal </span>command. To be able to
use a specified font size, a file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>size<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>size<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>.clo<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>has to reside in the LaTeX search path. By default, 10pt,
11pt, and 12pt are supported. If the package <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>extsizes<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is installed, 8pt, 9pt, 14pt, 17pt, and 20pt are
added.
<!--l. 16062--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">header </span>option takes a string as argument. This string is written into the generated LaTeX file. If using the
<span 
class="cmbx-10">standalone </span>mode, it is written into the preamble, directly before the <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>begin<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>document<span 
class="cmsy-10">} </span>command. In the <span 
class="cmbx-10">input</span>
mode, it is placed directly after the <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>begingroup command to ensure that all settings are local to the
plot.
<!--l. 16068--><p class="noindent" >Examples:
<!--l. 16070--><p class="noindent" >Use T1 fontencoding, change the text and math font to Times-Roman as well as the sans-serif font to Helvetica:
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;cairolatex</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;standalone</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;header</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"\\usepackage[T1]{fontenc}\n\\usepackage{mathptmx}\n\\usepackage{helvet}"</span>
<!--l. 16076--><p class="noindent" ></pre> Use a boldface font in the plot, not influencing the text outside the plot: <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;cairolatex</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;input</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;header</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"\\bfseries"</span>
<!--l. 16082--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 16085--><p class="noindent" >If the file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>gnuplot.cfg<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is found by LaTeX it is input in the preamble the LaTeX document, when using
<span 
class="cmbx-10">standalone </span>mode. It can be used for further settings, e.g., changing the document font to Times-Roman, Helvetica,
and Courier, including math fonts (handled by <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>mathptmx.sty<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>): <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\usepackage{mathptmx}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\usepackage[scaled=0.92]{helvet}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\usepackage{courier}</span>
<!--l. 16094--><p class="noindent" ></pre> The file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>gnuplot.cfg<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is loaded before the header information given by the <span 
class="cmbx-10">header </span>command. Thus, you can use
<span 
class="cmbx-10">header </span>to overwrite some of settings performed using <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>gnuplot.cfg<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>
<!--l. 16100--><p class="noindent" >
