class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>xsize<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>ysize<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>set the size of the plot area in pixels. The default size in standalone mode is 600 by 400
pixels. The default font size is 10.
<!--l. 16128--><p class="noindent" >NB: Only one font is available, the ascii portion of Hershey simplex Roman provided in the file canvastext.js. You
can replace this with the file canvasmath.js, which contains also UTF-8 encoded Hershey simplex Greek and math
symbols. For consistency with other terminals, it is also possible to use <span 
class="cmbx-10">font </span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">name,size</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. Currently the font <span 
class="cmbx-10">name</span>
is ignored, but browser support for named fonts is likely to arrive eventually.
<!--l. 16135--><p class="noindent" >The default <span 
class="cmbx-10">standalone </span>mode creates an html page containing javascript code that renders the plot using
the HTML 5 canvas element. The html page links to two required javascript files &#8217;canvastext.js&#8217; and
&#8217;gnuplot_common.js&#8217;. An additional file &#8217;gnuplot_dashedlines.js&#8217; is needed to support dashed lines. By default these
point to local files, on unix-like systems usually in directory /usr/local/share/gnuplot/<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>version<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>/js. See installation
notes for other platforms. You can change this by using the <span 
class="cmbx-10">jsdir </span>option to specify either a different local directory
or a general URL. The latter is usually appropriate if the plot is exported for viewing on remote client
machines.
<!--l. 16145--><p class="noindent" >All plots produced by the canvas terminal are mouseable. The additional keyword <span 
class="cmbx-10">mousing </span>causes the
<span 
class="cmbx-10">standalone </span>mode to add a mouse-tracking box underneath the plot. It also adds a link to a javascript file
&#8217;gnuplot_mouse.js&#8217; and to a stylesheet for the mouse box &#8217;gnuplot_mouse.css&#8217; in the same local or URL directory as
&#8217;canvastext.js&#8217;.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 16151--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">name </span>option creates a file containing only javascript. Both the javascript function it contains and the id of
the canvas element that it draws onto are taken from the following string parameter. The commands
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;term</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;canvas</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;name</span><span 
