<!--l. 16231--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">solid </span>draws all curves with solid lines, overriding any dashed patterns; <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>mode<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is <span 
class="cmbx-10">landscape</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">portrait</span>, or
<span 
class="cmbx-10">default</span>; <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>plot_width<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is the assumed width of the plot in points; <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>line_width<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is the line width in points (default
1); <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>fontname<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is the name of a font (see list of fonts below) <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>fontsize<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is the size of the font in points (default
12).
<!--l. 16238--><p class="noindent" >The first six options can be in any order. Selecting <span 
class="cmbx-10">default </span>sets all options to their default values.
<!--l. 16241--><p class="noindent" >The mechanism of setting line colors in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term </span>command is deprecated. Instead you should set the
background using a separate keyword and set the line colors using <span 
class="cmbx-10">set linetype</span>. The deprecated mechanism
accepted colors of the form &#8217;xrrggbb&#8217;, where x is the literal character &#8217;x&#8217; and &#8217;rrggbb&#8217; are the red, green and blue
components in hex. The first color was used for the background, subsequent colors are assigned to successive line
types.
