<!--l. 16334--><p class="noindent" >You cannot introduce a new font in a <span 
class="cmbx-10">set label </span>command.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-399000IV"></a>Cgm fontsize</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-793"></a>
<!--l. 16341--><p class="noindent" >Fonts are scaled assuming the page is 6 inches wide. If the <span 
class="cmbx-10">size </span>command is used to change the aspect ratio of the
page or the CGM file is converted to a different width, the resulting font sizes will be scaled up or down accordingly.
To change the assumed width, use the <span 
class="cmbx-10">width </span>option.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-400000IV"></a>Cgm linewidth</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-795"></a>
<!--l. 16352--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">linewidth </span>option sets the width of lines in pt. The default width is 1 pt. Scaling is affected by the actual width
of the page, as discussed under the <span 
class="cmbx-10">fontsize </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">width </span>options.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-401000IV"></a>Cgm rotate</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-797"></a>
<!--l. 16361--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">norotate </span>option may be used to disable text rotation. For example, the CGM input filter for
Word for Windows 6.0c can accept rotated text, but the DRAW editor within Word cannot. If you
edit a graph (for example, to label a curve), all rotated text is restored to horizontal. The Y axis
label will then extend beyond the clip boundary. With <span 
class="cmbx-10">norotate</span>, the Y axis label starts in a less
attractive location, but the page can be edited without damage. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">rotate </span>option confirms the default
behavior.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-402000IV"></a>Cgm solid</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-799"></a>
<!--l. 16374--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">solid </span>option may be used to disable dashed line styles in the plots. This is useful when color is enabled and the
dashing of the lines detracts from the appearance of the plot. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">dashed </span>option confirms the default behavior,
which gives a different dash pattern to each line type.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-403000IV"></a>Cgm size</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-801"></a>
<!--l. 16385--><p class="noindent" >Default size of a CGM plot is 32599 units wide and 23457 units high for landscape, or 23457 units wide by 32599
units high for portrait.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-404000IV"></a>Cgm width</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-803"></a>
<!--l. 16393--><p class="noindent" >All distances in the CGM file are in abstract units. The application that reads the file determines the size
of the final plot. By default, the width of the final plot is assumed to be 6 inches (15.24 cm). This
distance is used to calculate the correct font size, and may be changed with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">width </span>option. The
keyword should be followed by the width in points. (Here, a point is 1/72 inch, as in PostScript. This
unit is known as a <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>big point<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>in TeX.) Gnuplot <span 
class="cmbx-10">expressions </span>can be used to convert from other
units.
<!--l. 16402--><p class="noindent" >Example: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
