<!--l. 16466--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 16469--><p class="noindent" >In non-standalone (<span 
class="cmbx-10">input</span>) graphic only parameters <span 
class="cmbx-10">size </span>to select graphic size, <span 
class="cmbx-10">fontscale </span>to scale all
the labels for a factor <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>fontscale<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>and font size, make sense, the rest is silently ignored and should
be configured in the .tex file which inputs the graphic. It&#8217;s highly recommended to set the proper
fontsize if document font differs from 12pt, so that gnuplot will know how much space to reserve for
labels.
<!--l. 16476--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">default </span>resets all the options to their default values.
<!--l. 16478--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">defaultsize </span>sets the plot size to 5in,3in. <span 
class="cmbx-10">size </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>scale<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>sets the plot size to <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>scale<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>times <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>default value<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. If two
arguments are given (separated with &#8217;,&#8217;), the first one sets the horizontal size and the second one the vertical size.
Size may be given without units (in which case it means relative to the default value), with inches (&#8217;in&#8217;) or
centimeters (&#8217;cm&#8217;).
<!--l. 16485--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">input </span>(default) creates a graphic that can be included into another ConTeXt document. <span 
class="cmbx-10">standalone </span>adds some
lines, so that the document might be compiled as-is. You might also want to add <span 
class="cmbx-10">header </span>in that
case.
<!--l. 16490--><p class="noindent" >Use <span 
class="cmbx-10">header </span>for any additional settings/definitions/macros that you might want to include in a standalone graphic.
<span 
class="cmbx-10">noheader </span>is the default.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 16493--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">notimestamp </span>prevents printing creation time in comments (if version control is used, one may prefer not to
commit new version when only date changes).
<!--l. 16496--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">color </span>to make color plots is the default, but <span 
class="cmbx-10">monochrome </span>doesn&#8217;t do anything special yet. If you have any good
ideas how the behaviour should differ to suit the monochrome printers better, your suggestions are
welcome.
<!--l. 16500--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">rounded </span>(default), <span 
class="cmbx-10">mitered </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">beveled </span>control the shape of line joins. <span 
class="cmbx-10">round </span>(default), <span 
class="cmbx-10">butt </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">squared</span>
control the shape of line caps. See PostScript or PDF Reference Manual for explanation. For wild-behaving
functions and thick lines it is better to use <span 
class="cmbx-10">rounded </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">round </span>to prevent sharp corners in line joins. (Some
general support for this should be added to Gnuplot, so that the same options could be set for each line (style)
separately).
<!--l. 16508--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">dashed </span>(default) uses different dash patterns for different line types, <span 
class="cmbx-10">solid </span>draws all plots with solid
lines.
<!--l. 16511--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">dashlength </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">dl </span>scales the length of the dashed-line segments by <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>dl<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. <span 
class="cmbx-10">linewidth </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">lw </span>scales all linewidths by
<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>lw<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. (lw 1 stands for 0.5bp, which is the default line width when drawing with Metapost.) <span 
class="cmbx-10">fontscale </span>scales text
labels for factor <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>fontscale<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>relative to default document font.
<!--l. 16516--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">mppoints </span>uses predefined point shapes, drawn in Metapost. <span 
class="cmbx-10">texpoints </span>uses easily configurable set of symbols,
defined with ConTeXt in the following way: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\defineconversion[my</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;own</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;points][+,{\ss</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x},\mathematics{\circ}]</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\setupGNUPLOTterminal[context][points=tex,pointset=my</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;own</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;points]</span>
<!--l. 16523--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 16526--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">inlineimages </span>writes binary images to a string and only works in ConTeXt MKIV. <span 
class="cmbx-10">externalimages </span>writes PNG
files to disk and also works with ConTeXt MKII. Gnuplot needs to have support for PNG images built in for this to
work.
<!--l. 16530--><p class="noindent" >With <span 
class="cmbx-10">font </span>you can set font name and size in standalone graphics. In non-standalone (<span 
class="cmbx-10">input</span>) mode only the font size
is important to reserve enough space for text labels. The command <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;term</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;context</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"myfont,ss,10"</span>
<!--l. 16537--><p class="noindent" ></pre> will result in <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\setupbodyfont[myfont,ss,10pt]</span>
<!--l. 16543--><p class="noindent" ></pre> If you additionaly set <span 
class="cmbx-10">fontscale </span>to 0.8 for example, then the resulting font will be 8pt big and <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;label</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;...</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"myfont,12"</span>
<!--l. 16550--><p class="noindent" ></pre> will come out as 9.6pt.
<!--l. 16554--><p class="noindent" >It is your own responsibility to provide proper typescripts (and header), otherwise switching the font will have no
effect. For a standard font in ConTeXt MKII (pdfTeX) you could use: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;context</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;standalone</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;header</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;\usetypescript[iwona][ec]&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"iwona,ss,11"</span>
<!--l. 16561--><p class="noindent" ></pre> Please take a look into ConTeXt documentation, wiki or mailing list (archives) for any up-to-date information
about font usage.
