<!--l. 16580--><p class="noindent" >
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-407000IV"></a>Requirements</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-809"></a>
<!--l. 16582--><p class="noindent" >You need gnuplot module for ConTeXt
<!--l. 16583--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://ctan.org/pkg/context-gnuplot" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">http://ctan.org/pkg/context-gnuplot </span></a>
<!--l. 16586--><p class="noindent" >and a recent version of ConTeXt. If you want to call gnuplot on-the-fly, you also need write18 enabled. In most TeX
distributions this can be set with shell_escape=t in texmf.cnf.
<!--l. 16590--><p class="noindent" >See
<!--l. 16591--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://wiki.contextgarden.net/Gnuplot" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">http://wiki.contextgarden.net/Gnuplot </span></a>
<!--l. 16594--><p class="noindent" >for details about this terminal and for more exhaustive help &amp; examples.
<!--l. 16596--><p class="noindent" >
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-408000IV"></a>Calling gnuplot from ConTeXt</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-811"></a>
<!--l. 16598--><p class="noindent" >The easiest way to make plots in ConTeXt documents is <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\usemodule[gnuplot]</span>
<span 
