<!--l. 16745--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 16748--><p class="noindent" >Options: You can give options in any order you wish. &#8217;color&#8217; causes gnuplot to produce <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>color<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>...<span 
class="cmsy-10">} </span>commands so that
the graphs are colored. Using this option, you must include <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>usepackage<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>color<span 
class="cmsy-10">} </span>in the preambel of your latex
document. &#8217;dashed&#8217; will allow dashed line types; without this option, only solid lines with varying thickness will be
used. &#8217;dashed&#8217; and &#8217;color&#8217; are mutually exclusive; if &#8217;color&#8217; is specified, then &#8217;dashed&#8217; will be ignored. &#8217;rotate&#8217; will
enable true rotated text (by 90 degrees). Otherwise, rotated text will be typeset with letters stacked above each
other. If you use this option you must include <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>usepackage<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>graphicx<span 
class="cmsy-10">} </span>in the preamble. &#8217;small&#8217; will use
<span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>scriptsize symbols as point markers (Probably does not work with TeX, only LaTeX2e). Default is to
use the default math size. &#8217;tiny&#8217; uses <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>scriptscriptstyle symbols. &#8217;default&#8217; resets all options to their
defaults = no color, no dashed lines, pseudo-rotated (stacked) text, large point symbols. <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>fontsize<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is a
number which specifies the font size inside the picture environment; the unit is pt (points), i.e., 10
pt equals approx. 3.5 mm. If fontsize is not specified, then all text inside the picture will be set in
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>footnotesize.
<!--l. 16770--><p class="noindent" >Notes: Remember to escape the # character (or other chars meaningful to (La-)TeX) by <span 
class="cmsy-10">\\ </span>(2 backslashes). It seems
that dashed lines become solid lines when the vertices of a plot are too close. (I do not know if that is a general
problem with the tpic specials, or if it is caused by a bug in eepic.sty or dvips/dvipdfm.) The default size of an eepic
plot is 5x3 inches. You can change this using the <span 
class="cmbx-10">size </span>terminal option. Points, among other things, are drawn using
the LaTeX commands <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>Diamond<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>Box<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, etc. These commands no longer belong to the LaTeX2e core;
they are included in the latexsym package, which is part of the base distribution and thus part of any
LaTeX implementation. Please do not forget to use this package. Instead of latexsym, you can also
include the amssymb package. All drivers for LaTeX offer a special way of controlling text positioning: If
any text string begins with &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>&#8217;, you also need to include a &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>&#8217; at the end of the text, and the whole
text will be centered both horizontally and vertically. If the text string begins with &#8217;[&#8217;, you need to
follow this with a position specification (up to two out of t,b,l,r), &#8217;]<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>&#8217;, the text itself, and finally &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>&#8217;.
The text itself may be anything LaTeX can typeset as an LR-box. &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>rule<span 
class="cmsy-10">{}{}</span>&#8217;s may help for best
positioning.
