<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"Can&#8217;t</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;find</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;PostScript</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;prologue</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;file</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;...</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"</span>
<!--l. 16988--><p class="noindent" ></pre> Please see and follow the instructions in <span 
class="cmbx-10">postscript prologue (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-458000IV"><span 
class="cmbx-10">294</span><!--tex4ht:ref: postscript prologue --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-418002"></a>.
<!--l. 16992--><p class="noindent" >The option <span 
class="cmbx-10">color </span>enables color, while <span 
class="cmbx-10">monochrome </span>prefers black and white drawing elements. Further,
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmbx-10">monochrome </span>uses gray <span 
class="cmbx-10">palette </span>but it does not change color of objects specified with an explicit <span 
class="cmbx-10">colorspec</span>. <span 
class="cmbx-10">solid</span>
draws all plots with solid lines, overriding any dashed patterns. <span 
class="cmbx-10">dashlength </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">dl </span>scales the length of the
dashed-line segments by <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>DL<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>, which is a floating-point number greater than zero. <span 
class="cmbx-10">linewidth </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">lw </span>scales all
linewidths by <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>LW<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>.
<!--l. 17000--><p class="noindent" >By default the generated PostScript code uses language features that were introduced in PostScript Level 2,
notably filters and pattern-fill of irregular objects such as filledcurves. PostScript Level 2 features are
conditionally protected so that PostScript Level 1 interpreters do not issue errors but, rather, display a
message or a PostScript Level 1 approximation. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">level1 </span>option substitutes PostScript Level 1
approximations of these features and uses no PostScript Level 2 code. This may be required by some
old printers and old versions of Adobe Illustrator. The flag <span 
class="cmbx-10">level1 </span>can be toggled later by editing a
single line in the PostScript output file to force PostScript Level 1 interpretation. In the case of files
containing level 2 code, the above features will not appear or will be replaced by a note when this flag
is set or when the interpreting program does not indicate that it understands level 2 PostScript or
higher.
<!--l. 17014--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">rounded </span>sets line caps and line joins to be rounded; <span 
class="cmbx-10">butt </span>is the default, butt caps and mitered joins.
<!--l. 17017--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">clip </span>tells PostScript to clip all output to the bounding box; <span 
class="cmbx-10">noclip </span>is the default.
<!--l. 17020--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">palfuncparam </span>controls how <span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette functions </span>are encoded as gradients in the output. Analytic color
component functions (set via <span 
class="cmbx-10">set palette functions</span>) are encoded as linear interpolated gradients in the postscript
output: The color component functions are sampled at <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>samples<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>points and all points are removed from this
gradient which can be removed without changing the resulting colors by more than <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>maxdeviation<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. For almost
every useful palette you may safely leave the defaults of <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>samples<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>=2000 and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>maxdeviation<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>=0.003
untouched.
<!--l. 17029--><p class="noindent" >The default size for postscript output is 10 inches x 7 inches. The default for eps output is 5 x 3.5 inches. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">size</span>
option changes this to whatever the user requests. By default the X and Y sizes are taken to be in inches, but
other units are possibly (currently only cm). The BoundingBox of the plot is correctly adjusted to
contain the resized image. Screen coordinates always run from 0.0 to 1.0 along the full length of the plot
edges as specified by the <span 
class="cmbx-10">size </span>option. NB: <span 
class="cmbx-10">this is a change from the previously recommended</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">method of using the set size command prior to setting the terminal type</span>. The old method left
the BoundingBox unchanged and screen coordinates did not correspond to the actual limits of the
plot.
<!--l. 17041--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">blacktext </span>forces all text to be written in black even in color mode;
<!--l. 17043--><p class="noindent" >The epslatex driver offers a special way of controlling text positioning: (a) If any text string begins with &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>&#8217;, you also
need to include a &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>&#8217; at the end of the text, and the whole text will be centered both horizontally and
vertically by LaTeX. (b) If the text string begins with &#8217;[&#8217;, you need to continue it with: a position
specification (up to two out of t,b,l,r,c), &#8217;]<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>&#8217;, the text itself, and finally, &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>&#8217;. The text itself may be anything
LaTeX can typeset as an LR-box. <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>rule<span 
class="cmsy-10">{}{}</span>&#8217;s may help for best positioning. See also the documentation
for the <span 
class="cmbx-10">pslatex (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-460000IV"><span 
class="cmbx-10">294</span><!--tex4ht:ref: pslatex --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-418003"></a> terminal driver. To create multiline labels, use <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>shortstack, for example
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ylabel</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;[r]{\shortstack{first</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;line</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\\</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;second</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;line}}&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 17055--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 17058--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">back </span>option of <span 
class="cmbx-10">set label </span>commands is handled slightly different than in other terminals. Labels using &#8217;back&#8217;
are printed behind all other elements of the plot while labels using &#8217;front&#8217; are printed above everything
else.
<!--l. 17063--><p class="noindent" >The driver produces two different files, one for the eps part of the figure and one for the LaTeX part. The name of
the LaTeX file is taken from the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set output </span>command. The name of the eps file is derived by replacing the file
extension (normally <span 
class="cmbx-10">.tex</span>) with <span 
class="cmbx-10">.eps </span>instead. There is no LaTeX output if no output file is given! Remember to close
the <span 
class="cmbx-10">output file </span>before next plot unless in <span 
class="cmbx-10">multiplot </span>mode.
<!--l. 17070--><p class="noindent" >In your LaTeX documents use &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>input<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>filename<span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>&#8217; to include the figure. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">.eps </span>file is included by the command
<span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>includegraphics<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>...<span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>, so you must also include <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>usepackage<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>graphicx<span 
class="cmsy-10">} </span>in the LaTeX preamble. If you want to
use coloured text (option <span 
class="cmbx-10">textcolour</span>) you also have to include <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>usepackage<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>color<span 
class="cmsy-10">} </span>in the LaTeX
preamble.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 17076--><p class="noindent" >Pdf files can be made from the eps file using &#8217;epstopdf&#8217;. If the graphics package is properly configured, the
LaTeX files can also be processed by pdflatex without changes, using the pdf files instead of the eps
files. The behaviour concerning font selection depends on the header mode. In all cases, the given font
size is used for the calculation of proper spacing. When not using the <span 
class="cmbx-10">standalone </span>mode the actual
LaTeX font and font size at the point of inclusion is taken, so use LaTeX commands for changing
fonts. If you use e.g. 12pt as font size for your LaTeX document, use &#8217;<span 
class="cmtt-10">"" </span>12&#8217; as options. The font
name is ignored. If using <span 
class="cmbx-10">standalone </span>the given font and font size are used, see below for a detailed
description.
<!--l. 17088--><p class="noindent" >If text is printed coloured is controlled by the TeX booleans <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>ifGPcolor and <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>ifGPblacktext. Only if <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>ifGPcolor is
true and <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>ifGPblacktext is false, text is printed coloured. You may either change them in the generated TeX file or
provide them globally in your TeX file, for example by using <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\newif\ifGPblacktext</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\GPblacktexttrue</span>
<!--l. 17097--><p class="noindent" ></pre> in the preamble of your document. The local assignment is only done if no global value is given.
<!--l. 17102--><p class="noindent" >When using the epslatex terminal give the name of the TeX file in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set output </span>command including the file
extension (normally <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.tex<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>). The eps filename is generated by replacing the extension by <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.eps<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.
<!--l. 17106--><p class="noindent" >If using the <span 
class="cmbx-10">standalone </span>mode a complete LaTeX header is added to the LaTeX file; and <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>-inc<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is added to the
filename of the eps file. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">standalone </span>mode generates a TeX file that produces output with the correct size when
using dvips, pdfTeX, or VTeX. The default, <span 
class="cmbx-10">input</span>, generates a file that has to be included into a LaTeX document
using the <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>input command.
<!--l. 17113--><p class="noindent" >If a font other than <span 
class="cmtt-10">"" </span>or <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>default<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is given it is interpreted as LaTeX font name. It contains up to three parts,
separated by a comma: &#8217;fontname,fontseries,fontshape&#8217;. If the default fontshape or fontseries are requested, they can
be omitted. Thus, the real syntax for the fontname is &#8217;[fontname][,fontseries][,fontshape]&#8217;. The naming convention for
all parts is given by the LaTeX font scheme. The fontname is 3 to 4 characters long and is built as follows: One
character for the font vendor, two characters for the name of the font, and optionally one additional character for
special fonts, e.g., &#8217;j&#8217; for fonts with old-style numerals or &#8217;x&#8217; for expert fonts. The names of many fonts is described
in
<!--l. 17123--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://www.tug.org/fontname/fontname.pdf" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">http://www.tug.org/fontname/fontname.pdf </span></a>
<!--l. 17126--><p class="noindent" >For example, &#8217;cmr&#8217; stands for Computer Modern Roman, &#8217;ptm&#8217; for Times-Roman, and &#8217;phv&#8217; for Helvetica. The font
series denotes the thickness of the glyphs, in most cases &#8217;m&#8217; for normal (<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>medium<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>) and &#8217;bx&#8217; or &#8217;b&#8217; for bold fonts.
The font shape is &#8217;n&#8217; for upright, &#8217;it&#8217; for italics, &#8217;sl&#8217; for slanted, or &#8217;sc&#8217; for small caps, in general. Some fonts may
provide different font series or shapes.
<!--l. 17133--><p class="noindent" >Examples:
<!--l. 17135--><p class="noindent" >Use Times-Roman boldface (with the same shape as in the surrounding text): <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;epslatex</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;ptm,bx&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 17139--><p class="noindent" ></pre> Use Helvetica, boldface, italics: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;epslatex</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;phv,bx,it&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 17145--><p class="noindent" ></pre> Continue to use the surrounding font in slanted shape: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;epslatex</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;,,sl&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 17151--><p class="noindent" ></pre> Use small capitals: <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;epslatex</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;,,sc&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 17157--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 17160--><p class="noindent" >By this method, only text fonts are changed. If you also want to change the math fonts you have to use the
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>gnuplot.cfg<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>file or the <span 
class="cmbx-10">header </span>option, described below.
<!--l. 17164--><p class="noindent" >In standalone mode, the font size is taken from the given font size in the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set terminal </span>command. To be able to use
a specified font size, a file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>size<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>size<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>.clo<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>has to reside in the LaTeX search path. By default, 10pt,
11pt, and 12pt are supported. If the package <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>extsizes<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is installed, 8pt, 9pt, 14pt, 17pt, and 20pt are
added.
<!--l. 17170--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">header </span>option takes a string as argument. This string is written into the generated LaTeX file. If using the
<span 
class="cmbx-10">standalone </span>mode, it is written into the preamble, directly before the <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>begin<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>document<span 
class="cmsy-10">} </span>command. In the <span 
class="cmbx-10">input</span>
mode, it is placed directly after the <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>begingroup command to ensure that all settings are local to the
plot.
<!--l. 17176--><p class="noindent" >Examples:
<!--l. 17178--><p class="noindent" >Use T1 fontencoding, change the text and math font to Times-Roman as well as the sans-serif font to Helvetica:
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;epslatex</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;standalone</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;header</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"\\usepackage[T1]{fontenc}\n\\usepackage{mathptmx}\n\\usepackage{helvet}"</span>
<!--l. 17184--><p class="noindent" ></pre> Use a boldface font in the plot, not influencing the text outside the plot: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;epslatex</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;input</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;header</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"\\bfseries"</span>
<!--l. 17190--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 17193--><p class="noindent" >If the file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>gnuplot.cfg<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is found by LaTeX it is input in the preamble the LaTeX document, when using
<span 
class="cmbx-10">standalone </span>mode. It can be used for further settings, e.g., changing the document font to Times-Roman, Helvetica,
and Courier, including math fonts (handled by <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>mathptmx.sty<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>): <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\usepackage{mathptmx}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\usepackage[scaled=0.92]{helvet}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\usepackage{courier}</span>
<!--l. 17202--><p class="noindent" ></pre> The file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>gnuplot.cfg<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is loaded before the header information given by the <span 
class="cmbx-10">header </span>command. Thus, you can use
<span 
class="cmbx-10">header </span>to overwrite some of settings performed using <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>gnuplot.cfg<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>
<!--l. 17208--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-419000IV"></a>Epson_180dpi</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-833"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-419001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-419002"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-419003"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-419004"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-419005"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-419006"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-419007"></a>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<a 
 id="dx1-419008"></a>
<!--l. 17266--><p class="noindent" >This driver supports a family of Epson printers and derivatives.
<!--l. 17268--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">epson</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">_180dpi </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">epson</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">_60dpi </span>are drivers for Epson LQ-style 24-pin printers with resolutions of 180 and 60 dots
per inch, respectively.
<!--l. 17271--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">epson</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">_lx800 </span>is a generic 9-pin driver appropriate for printers like the Epson LX-800, the Star NL-10 and NX-1000,
the PROPRINTER, and so forth.
<!--l. 17274--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">nec</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">_cp6 </span>is generic 24-pin driver that can be used for printers like the NEC CP6 and the Epson LQ-800.
<!--l. 17277--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">okidata </span>driver supports the 9-pin OKIDATA 320/321 Standard printers.
<!--l. 17279--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">starc </span>driver is for the Star Color Printer.
<!--l. 17281--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">tandy</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">_60dpi </span>driver is for the Tandy DMP-130 series of 9-pin, 60-dpi printers.
<!--l. 17284--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">dpu414 </span>driver is for the Seiko DPU-414 thermal printer.
<!--l. 17286--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">nec</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">_cp6 </span>has the options:
<!--l. 17288--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;nec_cp6</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{monochrome</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;colour</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;draft}</span>
<!--l. 17292--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 17295--><p class="noindent" >which defaults to monochrome.
<!--l. 17297--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">dpu414 </span>has the options:
<!--l. 17299--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
