<!--l. 17350--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">monochrome </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">color </span>determine whether the picture is black-and-white or <span 
class="cmbx-10">color</span>. <span 
class="cmbx-10">small </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">big </span>produce a 5x3
or 8x5 inch graph in the default <span 
class="cmbx-10">landscape </span>mode and 3x5 or 5x8 inches in <span 
class="cmbx-10">portrait </span>mode. <span 
class="cmbx-10">size </span>sets (overrides)
the size of the drawing area to <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>xsize<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>*<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>ysize<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>in units of inches or centimeters depending on the
<span 
class="cmbx-10">inches </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">metric </span>setting in effect. The latter settings is also used as default units for editing with
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>xfig<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.
<!--l. 17358--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">pointsmax </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">max</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">_points</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>sets the maximum number of points per polyline.
<!--l. 17360--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">solid </span>inhibits automatic usage of <span 
class="cmbx-10">dash</span>ed lines when solid linestyles are used up, which otherwise
occurs.
<!--l. 17363--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">font </span>sets the text font face to <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>fontname<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>and its size to <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>fontsize<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>points. <span 
class="cmbx-10">textnormal </span>resets the text flags and
selects postscript fonts, <span 
class="cmbx-10">textspecial </span>sets the text flags for LaTeX specials, <span 
class="cmbx-10">texthidden </span>sets the hidden flag and
<span 
class="cmbx-10">textrigid </span>the rigid flag.
<!--l. 17368--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">depth </span>sets the default depth layer for all lines and text. The default depth is 10 to leave room for adding material
with <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>xfig<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>on top of the plot.
<!--l. 17372--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">version </span>sets the format version of the generated fig output. Currently only versions 3.1 and 3.2 are
supported.
<!--l. 17375--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">thickness </span>sets the default line thickness, which is 1 if not specified. Overriding the thickness can be achieved by
adding a multiple of 100 to the <span 
class="cmbx-10">linetype </span>value for a <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command. In a similar way the <span 
class="cmbx-10">depth </span>of plot elements
(with respect to the default depth) can be controlled by adding a multiple of 1000 to <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>linetype<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. The depth is then
<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>layer<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>+ <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>linetype<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>/1000 and the thickness is (<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>linetype<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>%1000)/100 or, if that is zero, the default line
thickness. <span 
class="cmbx-10">linewidth </span>is a synonym for <span 
class="cmbx-10">thickness</span>.
<!--l. 17383--><p class="noindent" >Additional point-plot symbols are also available with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">fig </span>driver. The symbols can be used through <span 
class="cmbx-10">pointtype</span>
values % 100 above 50, with different fill intensities controlled by <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>pointtype<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>% 5 and outlines in black (for
<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>pointtype<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>% 10 <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C; </span>5) or in the current color. Available symbols are <pre class="prettyprint">
