<!--l. 17548--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">animate </span>option is available only if your local gd library supports the creation of animated gifs. The default
delay between display of successive images may be specified in units of 1/100 second (default 5). The actual delay
may vary depending on the program used as a viewer. Number of animation loops can be specified, default 0 means
infinity. An animation sequence is terminated by the next <span 
class="cmbx-10">set output </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term </span>command. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">optimize </span>option
has two effects on the animation.
<!--l. 17556--><p class="noindent" >1) A single color map is used for the entire animation. This requires that all colors used in any frame of the
animation are already defined in the first frame.
<!--l. 17560--><p class="noindent" >2) If possible, only the portions of a frame that differ from the previous frame are stored in the animation file. This
space saving may not be possible if the animation uses transparency.
<!--l. 17564--><p class="noindent" >Both of these optimizations are intended to produce a smaller output file, but the decrease in size is
probably only significant for long animations or very small frame sizes. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">nooptimize </span>option turns
off both of the effects just described. Each frame is stored in its entirety along with a private color
map. Note that it is possible to post-process a non-optimized animation using external utilities, and
this post-processing can yield a smaller file than gnuplot&#8217;s internal optimization mode. The default is
<span 
class="cmbx-10">nooptimize</span>.
<!--l. 17574--><p class="noindent" >The output plot size <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>x,y<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is given in pixels &#8212; it defaults to 640x480. Please see additional information under
<span 
class="cmbx-10">canvas (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-17000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">23</span><!--tex4ht:ref: canvas --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-423003"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set size (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-292000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">197</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set size --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-423004"></a>. Blank space at the edges of the finished plot may be trimmed using the
<span 
class="cmbx-10">crop </span>option, resulting in a smaller final image size. Default is <span 
class="cmbx-10">nocrop</span>.
<!--l. 17579--><p class="noindent" >The background color must be given in the form &#8217;xrrggbb&#8217;, where x is the literal character &#8217;x&#8217; and &#8217;rrggbb&#8217; are the
red, green and blue components in hexadecimal. For example, &#8217;x00ff00&#8217; is green. The specification of additional
colors other than the background is deprecated.
<!--l. 17584--><p class="noindent" >
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-424000IV"></a>Examples</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-843"></a>
<!--l. 17588--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;gif</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;medium</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;size</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;640,480</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xffffff</span>
<!--l. 17590--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 17593--><p class="noindent" >Use the medium size built-in non-scaleable, non-rotatable font. Use white (xffffff) for the non-transparent
background.
<!--l. 17597--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
