class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"animate2.dem"</span>
<!--l. 17610--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 17613--><p class="noindent" >Open the gif terminal for creation of an animated gif file. The individual frames of the animation sequence are
created by the script file animate2.dem from the standard collection of demos.
<!--l. 17617--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-425000IV"></a>Gpic</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-845"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-425001"></a>
<!--l. 17626--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">gpic </span>terminal driver generates GPIC graphs in the Free Software Foundations&#8217;s <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>groff<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>package. The default
size is 5 x 3 inches. The only option is the origin, which defaults to (0,0).
<!--l. 17630--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;gpic</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{&#x003C;x&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;y&#x003E;}</span>
<!--l. 17634--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 17637--><p class="noindent" >where <span 
class="cmbx-10">x </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">y </span>are in inches.
<!--l. 17639--><p class="noindent" >A simple graph can be formatted using
<!--l. 17642--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;groff</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-p</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-mpic</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-Tps</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;file.pic</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;file.ps.</span>
<!--l. 17644--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 17647--><p class="noindent" >The output from pic can be pipe-lined into eqn, so it is possible to put complex functions in a graph with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">label </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set </span><span 
class="cmbsy-10">{</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">x/y</span><span 
class="cmbsy-10">}</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">label </span>commands. For instance,
<!--l. 17652--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ylab</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;@space</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;int</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;from</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;to</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;alpha</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;t</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;roman</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;d</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;t@&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 17654--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 17657--><p class="noindent" >will label the y axis with a nice integral if formatted with the command:
<!--l. 17660--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;gpic</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;filename.pic</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;geqn</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-d@@</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-Tps</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;groff</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-m[macro-package]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-Tps</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;filename.ps</span>
<!--l. 17663--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 17666--><p class="noindent" >Figures made this way can be scaled to fit into a document. The pic language is easy to understand, so the graphs
can be edited by hand if need be. All co-ordinates in the pic-file produced by <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>are given as
x+gnuplotx and y+gnuploty. By default x and y are given the value 0. If this line is removed with an
editor in a number of files, one can put several graphs in one figure like this (default size is 5.0x3.0
inches):
<!--l. 17674--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;.PS</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;8.0</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x=0;y=3</span>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;copy</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"figa.pic"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x=5;y=3</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;copy</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"figb.pic"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x=0;y=0</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;copy</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"figc.pic"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x=5;y=0</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;copy</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"figd.pic"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;.PE</span>
<!--l. 17685--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 17688--><p class="noindent" >This will produce an 8-inch-wide figure with four graphs in two rows on top of each other.
<!--l. 17691--><p class="noindent" >One can also achieve the same thing by the command
<!--l. 17694--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;gpic</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;y</span>
<!--l. 17696--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 17699--><p class="noindent" >for example, using
<!--l. 17702--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;.PS</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;6.0</span>
<span 
