class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;norotate}</span>
<!--l. 18052--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 18055--><p class="noindent" >By default the plot will inherit font settings from the embedding document. You have the option of forcing either
Courier (cmtt) or Roman (cmr) fonts instead. In this case you may also specify a fontsize. Unless your
driver is capable of building fonts at any size (e.g. dvips), stick to the standard 10, 11 and 12 point
sizes.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 18061--><p class="noindent" >METAFONT users beware: METAFONT does not like odd sizes.
<!--l. 18063--><p class="noindent" >All drivers for LaTeX offer a special way of controlling text positioning: If any text string begins with &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>&#8217;, you also
need to include a &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>&#8217; at the end of the text, and the whole text will be centered both horizontally and vertically. If
the text string begins with &#8217;[&#8217;, you need to follow this with a position specification (up to two out of t,b,l,r), &#8217;]<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>&#8217;, the
text itself, and finally &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>&#8217;. The text itself may be anything LaTeX can typeset as an LR-box. &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>rule<span 
class="cmsy-10">{}{}</span>&#8217;s may help
for best positioning.
<!--l. 18071--><p class="noindent" >Points, among other things, are drawn using the LaTeX commands <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>Diamond<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>and <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>Box<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. These commands no
longer belong to the LaTeX2e core; they are included in the latexsym package, which is part of the base distribution
and thus part of any LaTeX implementation. Please do not forget to use this package. Other point types use
symbols from the amssymb package.
<!--l. 18077--><p class="noindent" >The default size for the plot is 5 inches by 3 inches. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">size </span>option changes this to whatever the user requests.
By default the X and Y sizes are taken to be in inches, but other units are possible (currently only
cm).
<!--l. 18081--><p class="noindent" >If &#8217;rotate&#8217; is specified, rotated text, especially a rotated y-axis label, is possible (the packages graphics or graphicx
are needed). The &#8217;stacked&#8217; y-axis label mechanism is then deactivated.
<!--l. 18085--><p class="noindent" >Examples: About label positioning: Use gnuplot defaults (mostly sensible, but sometimes not really best):
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;\LaTeX\</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;--</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\gamma</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$&#8217;</span>
