<!--l. 18581--><p class="noindent" >The option <span 
class="cmbx-10">color </span>causes lines to be drawn in color (on a printer or display that supports it), <span 
class="cmbx-10">monochrome </span>(or
nothing) selects black lines. The option <span 
class="cmbx-10">solid </span>draws solid lines, while <span 
class="cmbx-10">dashed </span>(or nothing) selects lines with different
patterns of dashes. If <span 
class="cmbx-10">solid </span>is selected but <span 
class="cmbx-10">color </span>is not, nearly all lines will be identical. This may occasionally be
useful, so it is allowed.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 18588--><p class="noindent" >The option <span 
class="cmbx-10">notex </span>bypasses TeX entirely, therefore no TeX code can be used in labels under this option. This is
intended for use on old plot files or files that make frequent use of common characters like <span 
class="cmbx-10">$ </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">% </span>that require
special handling in TeX.
<!--l. 18593--><p class="noindent" >The option <span 
class="cmbx-10">tex </span>sets the terminal to output its text for TeX to process.
<!--l. 18595--><p class="noindent" >The option <span 
class="cmbx-10">latex </span>sets the terminal to output its text for processing by LaTeX. This allows things like <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>frac for
fractions which LaTeX knows about but TeX does not. Note that you must set the environment variable TEX to the
name of your LaTeX executable (normally latex) if you use this option or use <span 
class="cmbx-10">mpost &#8211;tex=</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">name of</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">LaTeX executable</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span><span 
class="cmbx-10">...</span>. Otherwise metapost will try and use TeX to process the text and it won&#8217;t
work.
<!--l. 18602--><p class="noindent" >Changing font sizes in TeX has no effect on the size of mathematics, and there is no foolproof way
to make such a change, except by globally setting a magnification factor. This is the purpose of the
<span 
class="cmbx-10">magnification </span>option. It must be followed by a scaling factor. All text (NOT the graphs) will be scaled
by this factor. Use this if you have math that you want at some size other than the default 10pt.
Unfortunately, all math will be the same size, but see the discussion below on editing the MP output. <span 
class="cmbx-10">mag </span>will
also work under <span 
class="cmbx-10">notex </span>but there seems no point in using it as the font size option (below) works as
well.
<!--l. 18612--><p class="noindent" >The option <span 
class="cmbx-10">psnfss </span>uses postscript fonts in combination with LaTeX. Since this option only makes sense, if
LaTeX is being used, the <span 
class="cmbx-10">latex </span>option is selected automatically. This option includes the following
packages for LaTeX: inputenc(latin1), fontenc(T1), mathptmx, helvet(scaled=09.2), courier, latexsym and
textcomp.
<!--l. 18618--><p class="noindent" >The option <span 
class="cmbx-10">psnfss-version7 </span>uses also postscript fonts in LaTeX (option <span 
class="cmbx-10">latex </span>is also automatically selected), but
uses the following packages with LaTeX: inputenc(latin1), fontenc(T1), times, mathptmx, helvet and
courier.
<!--l. 18622--><p class="noindent" >The option <span 
class="cmbx-10">nopsnfss </span>is the default and uses the standard font (cmr10 if not otherwise specified).
<!--l. 18625--><p class="noindent" >The option <span 
class="cmbx-10">prologues </span>takes a value as an additional argument and adds the line <span 
class="cmbx-10">prologues:=</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">value</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>to the
metapost file. If a value of <span 
class="cmbx-10">2 </span>is specified metapost uses postscript fonts to generate the eps-file, so that the result can
be viewed using e.g. ghostscript. Normally the output of metapost uses TeX fonts and therefore has to be included
in a (La)TeX file before you can look at it.
<!--l. 18631--><p class="noindent" >The option <span 
class="cmbx-10">noprologues </span>is the default. No additional line specifying the prologue will be added.
<!--l. 18634--><p class="noindent" >The option <span 
class="cmbx-10">a4paper </span>adds a <span 
class="cmbx-10">[a4paper] </span>to the documentclass. Normally letter paper is used (default). Since this
option is only used in case of LaTeX, the <span 
class="cmbx-10">latex </span>option is selected automatically.
<!--l. 18638--><p class="noindent" >The option <span 
class="cmbx-10">amstex </span>automatically selects the <span 
class="cmbx-10">latex </span>option and includes the following LaTeX packages: amsfonts,
amsmath(intlimits). By default these packages are not included.
<!--l. 18642--><p class="noindent" >A name in quotes selects the font that will be used when no explicit font is given in a <span 
class="cmbx-10">set label </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">set title</span>. A
name recognized by TeX (a TFM file exists) must be used. The default is <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>cmr10<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>unless <span 
class="cmbx-10">notex </span>is selected, then it
is <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>pcrr8r<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>(Courier). Even under <span 
class="cmbx-10">notex</span>, a TFM file is needed by Metapost. The file <span 
class="cmbx-10">pcrr8r.tfm </span>is the name given
to Courier in LaTeX&#8217;s psnfss package. If you change the font from the <span 
class="cmbx-10">notex </span>default, choose a font that matches the
ASCII encoding at least in the range 32-126. <span 
class="cmbx-10">cmtt10 </span>almost works, but it has a nonblank character in position 32
(space).
<!--l. 18651--><p class="noindent" >The size can be any number between 5.0 and 99.99. If it is omitted, 10.0 is used. It is advisable to use <span 
class="cmbx-10">magstep</span>
sizes: 10 times an integer or half-integer power of 1.2, rounded to two decimals, because those are the most available
sizes of fonts in TeX systems.
<!--l. 18656--><p class="noindent" >All the options are optional. If font information is given, it must be at the end, with size (if present) last. The size is
needed to select a size for the font, even if the font name includes size information. For example, <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term mp</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">cmtt12</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>selects cmtt12 shrunk to the default size 10. This is probably not what you want or you would have used
cmtt10.
<!--l. 18662--><p class="noindent" >The following common ascii characters need special treatment in TeX: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&amp;,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;#,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;%,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;_;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;|,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003E;;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;^,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;~,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;and</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;}</span>
<!--l. 18666--><p class="noindent" ></pre> The five characters $, #, &amp;, _, and % can simply be escaped, e.g., <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">$</span>. The three characters <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>, <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>, and <span 
class="cmsy-10">| </span>can be
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
wrapped in math mode, e.g., <span 
class="cmbx-10">$</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">$</span>. The remainder require some TeX work-arounds. Any good book on TeX will give
some guidance.
<!--l. 18673--><p class="noindent" >If you type your labels inside double quotes, backslashes in TeX code need to be escaped (doubled). Using single
quotes will avoid having to do this, but then you cannot use <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">n </span>for line breaks. As of this writing, version 3.7 of
gnuplot processes titles given in a <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command differently than in other places, and backslashes in TeX commands
need to be doubled regardless of the style of quotes.
<!--l. 18680--><p class="noindent" >Metapost pictures are typically used in TeX documents. Metapost deals with fonts pretty much the same way TeX
does, which is different from most other document preparation programs. If the picture is included in a LaTeX
document using the graphics package, or in a plainTeX document via epsf.tex, and then converted
to PostScript with dvips (or other dvi-to-ps converter), the text in the plot will usually be handled
correctly. However, the text may not appear if you send the Metapost output as-is to a PostScript
interpreter.
<!--l. 18688--><p class="noindent" >
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-445000IV"></a>Metapost Instructions</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-885"></a>
<!--l. 18696--><p class="noindent" >- Set your terminal to Metapost, e.g.: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;mp</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;mono</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"cmtt12"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;12</span>
<!--l. 18700--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 18703--><p class="noindent" >- Select an output-file, e.g.: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;output</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"figure.mp"</span>
<!--l. 18707--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 18710--><p class="noindent" >- Create your pictures. Each plot (or multiplot group) will generate a separate Metapost beginfig...endfig group. Its
default size will be 5 by 3 inches. You can change the size by saying <span 
class="cmbx-10">set size 0.5,0.5 </span>or whatever fraction of the
default size you want to have.
<!--l. 18715--><p class="noindent" >- Quit gnuplot.
<!--l. 18717--><p class="noindent" >- Generate EPS files by running Metapost on the output of gnuplot: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;mpost</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;figure.mp</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;OR</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;mp</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;figure.mp</span>
<!--l. 18721--><p class="noindent" ></pre> The name of the Metapost program depends on the system, typically <span 
class="cmbx-10">mpost </span>for a Unix machine and <span 
class="cmbx-10">mp </span>on many
others. Metapost will generate one EPS file for each picture.
<!--l. 18727--><p class="noindent" >- To include your pictures in your document you can use the graphics package in LaTeX or epsf.tex in plainTeX:
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\usepackage{graphics}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;%</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;LaTeX</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\input</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;epsf.tex</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;%</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plainTeX</span>
<!--l. 18733--><p class="noindent" ></pre> If you use a driver other than dvips for converting TeX DVI output to PS, you may need to add the following line
in your LaTeX document: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\DeclareGraphicsRule{*}{eps}{*}{}</span>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 18740--><p class="noindent" ></pre> Each picture you made is in a separate file. The first picture is in, e.g., figure.0, the second in figure.1, and so on....
To place the third picture in your document, for example, all you have to do is: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\includegraphics{figure.2}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;%</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;LaTeX</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\epsfbox{figure.2}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;%</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plainTeX</span>
<!--l. 18749--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 18752--><p class="noindent" >The advantage, if any, of the mp terminal over a postscript terminal is editable output. Considerable effort went into
making this output as clean as possible. For those knowledgeable in the Metapost language, the default line types
and colors can be changed by editing the arrays <span 
class="cmbx-10">lt[] </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">col[]</span>. The choice of solid vs dashed lines,
and color vs black lines can be change by changing the values assigned to the booleans <span 
class="cmbx-10">dashedlines</span>
and <span 
class="cmbx-10">colorlines</span>. If the default <span 
class="cmbx-10">tex </span>option was in effect, global changes to the text of labels can be
achieved by editing the <span 
class="cmbx-10">vebatimtex...etex </span>block. In particular, a LaTeX preamble can be added
if desired, and then LaTeX&#8217;s built-in size changing commands can be used for maximum flexibility.
Be sure to set the appropriate MP configuration variable to force Metapost to run LaTeX instead of
plainTeX.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-446000IV"></a>Next</h4>
