<!--l. 18997--><p class="noindent" >The fonts are retrieved from the usual fonts subsystems. Under Windows, those fonts are to be found and configured
in the entry <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>Fonts<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>of the control panel. Under UNIX, they are handled by <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>fontconfig<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.
<!--l. 19001--><p class="noindent" >Pango, the library used to layout the text, is based on utf-8. Thus, the pdfcairo terminal has to convert
from your encoding to utf-8. The default input encoding is based on your &#8217;locale&#8217;. If you want to use
another encoding, make sure gnuplot knows which one you are using. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">encoding (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-218000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">150</span><!--tex4ht:ref: encoding --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-450003"></a> for more
details.
<!--l. 19007--><p class="noindent" >Pango may give unexpected results with fonts that do not respect the unicode mapping. With the Symbol font, for
example, the pdfcairo terminal will use the map provided by http://www.unicode.org/ to translate
character codes to unicode. Note that <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>the Symbol font<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is to be understood as the Adobe Symbol font,
distributed with Acrobat Reader as <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>SY______.PFB<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. Alternatively, the OpenSymbol font, distributed with
OpenOffice.org as <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>opens___.ttf<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, offers the same characters. Microsoft has distributed a Symbol font
(<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>symbol.ttf<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>), but it has a different character set with several missing or moved mathematic characters.
If you experience problems with your default setup (if the demo enhancedtext.dem is not displayed
properly for example), you probably have to install one of the Adobe or OpenOffice Symbol fonts,
and remove the Microsoft one. Other non-conform fonts, such as <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>wingdings<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>have been observed
working.
<!--l. 19021--><p class="noindent" >The rendering of the plot cannot be altered yet. To obtain the best output possible, the rendering involves two
mechanisms : antialiasing and oversampling. Antialiasing allows to display non-horizontal and non-vertical lines
smoother. Oversampling combined with antialiasing provides subpixel accuracy, so that gnuplot can
draw a line from non-integer coordinates. This avoids wobbling effects on diagonal lines (&#8217;plot x&#8217; for
example).
<!--l. 19030--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-451000IV"></a>Pm</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-897"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-451001"></a>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 19039--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">pm </span>terminal driver provides an OS/2 Presentation Manager window in which the graph is plotted. The window
is opened when the first graph is plotted. This window has its own online help as well as facilities for
printing, copying to the clipboard and some line type and color adjustments. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">multiplot </span>option is
supported.
<!--l. 19045--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pm</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{server</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{n}}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{persist}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{widelines}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{enhanced}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{"title"}</span>
<!--l. 19049--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 19052--><p class="noindent" >If <span 
class="cmbx-10">persist </span>is specified, each graph appears in its own window and all windows remain open after <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>exits. If
<span 
class="cmbx-10">server </span>is specified, all graphs appear in the same window, which remains open when <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>exits. This option
takes an optional numerical argument which specifies an instance of the server process. Thus multiple server
windows can be in use at the same time.
<!--l. 19059--><p class="noindent" >If <span 
class="cmbx-10">widelines </span>is specified, all plots will be drawn with wide lines. If <span 
class="cmbx-10">enhanced </span>is specified, sub- and superscripts and
multiple fonts are enabled (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">enhanced text (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-22000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">26</span><!--tex4ht:ref: enhanced text --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-451002"></a> for details). Font names for the core PostScript fonts may
be abbreviated to a single letter (T/H/C/S for Times/Helvetica/Courier/Symbol).
<!--l. 19065--><p class="noindent" >If <span 
class="cmbx-10">title </span>is specified, it will be used as the title of the plot window. It will also be used as the name of the server
instance, and will override the optional numerical argument.
<!--l. 19069--><p class="noindent" >Linewidths may be changed with <span 
class="cmbx-10">set linestyle</span>.
