<!--l. 19199--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 19202--><p class="noindent" >This terminal supports an enhanced text mode, which allows font and other formatting commands (subscripts,
superscripts, etc.) to be embedded in labels and other text strings. The enhanced text mode syntax is shared with
other gnuplot terminal types. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">enhanced (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-22000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">26</span><!--tex4ht:ref: enhanced --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-454002"></a> for more details.
<!--l. 19207--><p class="noindent" >The width of all lines in the plot can be modified by the factor <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>lw<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>.
<!--l. 19209--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">rounded </span>sets line caps and line joins to be rounded; <span 
class="cmbx-10">butt </span>is the default, butt caps and mitered joins.
<!--l. 19212--><p class="noindent" >The default size for the output is 640 x 480 pixels. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">size </span>option changes this to whatever the user requests. By
default the X and Y sizes are taken to be in pixels, but other units are possible (currently cm and inch). A size
given in centimeters or inches will be converted into pixels assuming a resolution of 72 dpi. Screen
coordinates always run from 0.0 to 1.0 along the full length of the plot edges as specified by the <span 
class="cmbx-10">size</span>
option.
<!--l. 19219--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>font<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is in the format <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>FontFace,FontSize<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, i.e. the face and the size comma-separated in a single string. FontFace
is a usual font face name, such as &#8217;Arial&#8217;. If you do not provide FontFace, the pngcairo terminal will use &#8217;Sans&#8217;.
FontSize is the font size, in points. If you do not provide it, the pngcairo terminal will use a size of 12 points.
