<!--l. 19408--><p class="noindent" >Linewidths and pointsizes may be changed with <span 
class="cmbx-10">set style line</span>.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 19410--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">postscript </span>driver supports about 70 distinct pointtypes, selectable through the <span 
class="cmbx-10">pointtype </span>option on <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and
<span 
class="cmbx-10">set style line</span>.
<!--l. 19413--><p class="noindent" >Several possibly useful files about <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot</span>&#8217;s PostScript are included in the /docs/psdoc subdirectory of the
<span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>distribution and at the distribution sites. These are <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>ps_symbols.gpi<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>(a <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>command file that, when
executed, creates the file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>ps_symbols.ps<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>which shows all the symbols available through the <span 
class="cmbx-10">postscript </span>terminal),
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>ps_guide.ps<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>(a PostScript file that contains a summary of the enhanced syntax and a page showing what the octal
codes produce with text and symbol fonts), <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>ps_file.doc<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>(a text file that contains a discussion of the organization
of a PostScript file written by <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot</span>), and <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>ps_fontfile_doc.tex<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>(a LaTeX file which contains a
short documentation concerning the encapsulation of LaTeX fonts with a glyph table of the math
fonts).
<!--l. 19425--><p class="noindent" >A PostScript file is editable, so once <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>has created one, you are free to modify it to your heart&#8217;s desire. See
the <span 
class="cmbx-10">editing postscript (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-456000IV"><span 
class="cmbx-10">292</span><!--tex4ht:ref: editing postscript --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-455005"></a> section for some hints.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-456000IV"></a>Editing postscript</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-907"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-456001"></a>
<!--l. 19438--><p class="noindent" >The PostScript language is a very complex language &#8212; far too complex to describe in any detail in this document.
Nevertheless there are some things in a PostScript file written by <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>that can be changed without risk of
introducing fatal errors into the file.
<!--l. 19443--><p class="noindent" >For example, the PostScript statement <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>/Color true def<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>(written into the file in response to the command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">terminal postscript color</span>), may be altered in an obvious way to generate a black-and-white version of a plot.
Similarly line colors, text colors, line weights and symbol sizes can also be altered in straight-forward ways. Text
(titles and labels) can be edited to correct misspellings or to change fonts. Anything can be repositioned, and of
course anything can be added or deleted, but modifications such as these may require deeper knowledge of the
PostScript language.
<!--l. 19452--><p class="noindent" >The organization of a PostScript file written by <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>is discussed in the text file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>ps_file.doc<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>in the docs/ps
subdirectory of the gnuplot source distribution.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-457000IV"></a>Postscript fontfile</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-909"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-457001"></a>
<!--l. 19465--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">fontfile </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">fontfile add </span>option takes one file name as argument and encapsulates this file into the postscript
output in order to make this font available for text elements (labels, tic marks, titles, etc.). The <span 
class="cmbx-10">fontfile delete</span>
option also takes one file name as argument. It deletes this file name from the list of encapsulated
files.
<!--l. 19471--><p class="noindent" >The postscript terminal understands some font file formats: Type 1 fonts in ASCII file format (extension <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.pfa<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>),
Type 1 fonts in binary file format (extension <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.pfb<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>), and TrueType fonts (extension <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.ttf<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>). Pfa files are understood
directly, pfb and ttf files are converted on the fly if appropriate conversion tools are installed (see
below). You have to specify the full filename including the extension. Each <span 
class="cmbx-10">fontfile </span>option takes exact
one font file name. This option can be used multiple times in order to include more than one font
file.
<!--l. 19481--><p class="noindent" >The font file is searched in the working directory and in all directories listed in the fontpath which is determined by
<span 
class="cmbx-10">set fontpath</span>. In addition, the fontpath can be set using the environment variable GNUPLOT_FONTPATH. If
this is not set a system dependent default search list is used. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set fontpath (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-220000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">151</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set fontpath --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-457002"></a> for more
details.
<!--l. 19487--><p class="noindent" >For using the encapsulated font file you have to specify the font name (which normally is not the same as the file
name). When embedding a font file by using the <span 
class="cmbx-10">fontfile </span>option in interactive mode, the font name is printed on the
screen. E.g. <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;file</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;p052004l.pfb&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;contains</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;the</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;URWPalladioL-Bold&#8217;.</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Location:</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;/usr/lib/X11/fonts/URW/p052004l.pfb</span>
<!--l. 19495--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 19498--><p class="noindent" >When using pfa or pfb fonts, you can also find it out by looking into the font file. There is a line similar to
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>/FontName /URWPalladioL-Bold def<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. The middle string without the slash is the fontname, here
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>URWPalladioL-Bold<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. For TrueType fonts, this is not so easy since the font name is stored in a binary format. In
addition, they often have spaces in the font names which is not supported by Type 1 fonts (in which a TrueType is
converted on the fly). The font names are changed in order to eliminate the spaces in the fontnames. The easiest
way to find out which font name is generated for use with gnuplot, start gnuplot in interactive mode and type in
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>set terminal postscript fontfile &#8217;<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>filename.ttf<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>&#8217;<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.
<!--l. 19510--><p class="noindent" >For converting font files (either ttf or pfb) to pfa format, the conversion tool has to read the font from a file and
write it to standard output. If the output cannot be written to standard output, on-the-fly conversion is not
possible.
<!--l. 19515--><p class="noindent" >For pfb files <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>pfbtops<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is a tool which can do this. If this program is installed on your system the on the
fly conversion should work. Just try to encapsulate a pfb file. If the compiled in program call does
not work correctly you can specify how this program is called by defining the environment variable
GNUPLOT_PFBTOPFA e.g. to <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>pfbtops %s<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">%s </span>will be replaced by the font file name and thus has to exist
in the string.
<!--l. 19523--><p class="noindent" >If you don&#8217;t want to do the conversion on the fly but get a pfa file of the font you can use the tool <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>pfb2pfa<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>which
is written in simple c and should compile with any c compiler. It is available from many ftp servers,
e.g.
<!--l. 19527--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="ftp://ftp.dante.de/tex-archive/fonts/utilities/ps2mf/" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">ftp://ftp.dante.de/tex-archive/fonts/utilities/ps2mf/ </span></a>
<!--l. 19530--><p class="noindent" >In fact, <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>pfbtopfa<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>and <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>pfb2ps<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>do the same job. <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>pfbtopfa<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>puts the resulting pfa code into a file, whereas
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>pfbtops<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>writes it to standard output.
<!--l. 19534--><p class="noindent" >TrueType fonts are converted into Type 1 pfa format, e.g. by using the tool <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>ttf2pt1<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>which is available
from
<!--l. 19536--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="http://ttf2pt1.sourceforge.net/" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">http://ttf2pt1.sourceforge.net/ </span></a>
<!--l. 19539--><p class="noindent" >If the builtin conversion does not work, the conversion command can be changed by the environment variable
GNUPLOT_TTFTOPFA. For usage with ttf2pt1 it may be set to <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>ttf2pt1 -a -e -W 0 %s - <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. Here again, <span 
class="cmbx-10">%s </span>stands
for the file name.
<!--l. 19545--><p class="noindent" >For special purposes you also can use a pipe (if available for your operating system). Therefore you start the file
name definition with the character <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>and append a program call. This program has to write pfa data to standard
output. Thus, a pfa file may be accessed by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set fontfile </span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C; </span><span 
class="cmbx-10">cat garamond.pfa</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.
<!--l. 19551--><p class="noindent" >For example, including Type 1 font files can be used for including the postscript output in LaTeX documents. The
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>european computer modern<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>font (which is a variant of the <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>computer modern<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>font) is available in pfb format
from any CTAN server, e.g.
<!--l. 19555--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="ftp://ftp.dante.de/tex-archive/fonts/ps-type1/cm-super/" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">ftp://ftp.dante.de/tex-archive/fonts/ps-type1/cm-super/ </span></a>
<!--l. 19558--><p class="noindent" >For example, the file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>sfrm1000.pfb<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>contains the normal upright fonts with serifs in the design size 10pt (font name
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>SFRM1000<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>). The computer modern fonts, which are still necessary for mathematics, are available
from
<!--l. 19562--><p class="noindent" >     <a 
href="ftp://ftp.dante.de/tex-archive/fonts/cm/ps-type1/bluesky" ><span 
class="cmtt-10">ftp://ftp.dante.de/tex-archive/fonts/cm/ps-type1/bluesky </span></a>
<!--l. 19565--><p class="noindent" >With these you can use any character available in TeX. However, the computer modern fonts have a strange
encoding. (This is why you should not use cmr10.pfb for text, but sfrm1000.pfb instead.) The usage of TeX fonts is
shown in one of the demos. The file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>ps_fontfile_doc.tex<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>in the /docs/psdoc subdirectory of the <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>source
distribution contains a table with glyphs of the TeX mathfonts.
<!--l. 19573--><p class="noindent" >If the font <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>CMEX10<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is embedded (file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>cmex10.pfb<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>) gnuplot defines the additional font <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>CMEX10-Baseline<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. It
is shifted vertically in order to fit better to the other glyphs (CMEX10 has its baseline at the top of the
symbols).
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-458000IV"></a>Postscript prologue</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-911"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-458001"></a>
<!--l. 19585--><p class="noindent" >Each PostScript output file includes a %%Prolog section and possibly some additional user-defined sections
containing, for example, character encodings. These sections are copied from a set of PostScript prologue files that
are either compiled into the gnuplot executable or stored elsewhere on your computer. A default directory where
these files live is set at the time gnuplot is built. However, you can override this default either by using the
gnuplot command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set psdir </span>or by defining an environment variable GNUPLOT_PS_DIR. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">set psdir</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-286000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">196</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set psdir --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-458002"></a>.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-459000IV"></a>Postscript adobeglyphnames</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-913"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-459001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-459002"></a>
<!--l. 19602--><p class="noindent" >This setting is only relevant to PostScript output with UTF-8 encoding. It controls the names used to describe
characters with Unicode entry points higher than 0x00FF. That is, all characters outside of the Latin1 set.
In general unicode characters do not have a unique name; they have only a unicode identification
code. However, Adobe have a recommended scheme for assigning names to certain ranges of characters
(extended Latin, Greek, etc). Some fonts use this scheme, others do not. By default, gnuplot will use
the Adobe glyph names. E.g. the lower case Greek letter alpha will be called /alpha. If you specific
<span 
class="cmbx-10">noadobeglyphnames </span>then instead gnuplot will use /uni03B1 to describe this character. If you get this setting
wrong, the character may not be found even if it is present in the font. It is probably always correct to use
the default for Adobe fonts, but for other fonts you may have to try both settings. See also <span 
class="cmbx-10">fontfile</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-457000IV"><span 
class="cmbx-10">292</span><!--tex4ht:ref: fontfile --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-459003"></a>.
<!--l. 19617--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-460000IV"></a>Pslatex and pstex</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-915"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-460001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-460002"></a>
<!--l. 19633--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">pslatex </span>driver generates output for further processing by LaTeX, while the <span 
class="cmbx-10">pstex </span>driver generates output for
further processing by TeX. <span 
class="cmbx-10">pslatex </span>uses <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>specials understandable by dvips and xdvi. Figures generated by <span 
class="cmbx-10">pstex</span>
can be included in any plain-based format (including LaTeX).
