<!--l. 19853--><p class="noindent" >Multiple plot windows are supported: <span 
class="cmbx-10">set terminal qt </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">n</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>directs the output to plot window number
n.
<!--l. 19856--><p class="noindent" >The default window title is based on the window number. This title can also be specified with the keyword
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>title<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.
<!--l. 19859--><p class="noindent" >Plot windows remain open even when the <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>driver is changed to a different device. A plot window can be
closed by pressing the letter &#8217;q&#8217; while that window has input focus, by choosing <span 
class="cmbx-10">close </span>from a window manager
menu, or with <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term qt </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">n</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span><span 
class="cmbx-10">close</span>.
<!--l. 19864--><p class="noindent" >The size of the plot area is given in pixels, it defaults to 640x480. In addition to that, the actual size of the window
also includes the space reserved for the toolbar and the status bar. When you resize a window, the plot is
immediately scaled to fit in the new size of the window. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">qt </span>terminal scales the whole plot, including fonts and
linewidths, and keeps its global aspect ratio constant. If you type <span 
class="cmbx-10">replot</span>, click the <span 
class="cmbx-10">replot </span>icon in the terminal
toolbar or type a new <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command, the new plot will completely fit in the window and the font size and the
linewidths will be reset to their defaults.
<!--l. 19874--><p class="noindent" >The active plot window (the one selected by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term qt </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">n</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>) is interactive. Its behaviour is shared with other
terminal types. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">mouse (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-243000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">171</span><!--tex4ht:ref: mouse --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
