class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>y<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>are the size of the SVG plot to generate, <span 
class="cmbx-10">dynamic </span>allows a svg-viewer to resize plot, whereas
the default setting, <span 
class="cmbx-10">fixed</span>, will request an absolute size.
<!--l. 19984--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">linewidth </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">w</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>increases the width of all lines used in the figure by a factor of <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>w<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>.
<!--l. 19987--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>font<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is the name of the default font to use (default Arial) and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>fontsize<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is the font size (in points, default 12).
SVG viewing programs may substitute other fonts when the file is displayed.
<!--l. 19991--><p class="noindent" >The svg terminal supports an enhanced text mode, which allows font and other formatting commands to be
embedded in labels and other text strings. The enhanced text mode syntax is shared with other gnuplot terminal
types. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">enhanced (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-22000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">26</span><!--tex4ht:ref: enhanced --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-466002"></a> for more details.
<!--l. 19996--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">mouse </span>option tells gnuplot to include a link to a javascript module that supports toggling individual plots
on/off by clicking on the corresponding key entry. By default this script is taken from a local directory, usually
/usr/local/share/gnuplot/<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>version<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>/js. You can change this by using the <span 
class="cmbx-10">jsdir </span>option to specify either a different
local directory or a general URL. The latter is usually appropriate if you are embedding the svg into a web
page.
<!--l. 20004--><p class="noindent" >SVG allows you to embed fonts directly into an SVG document, or to provide a hypertext link to the desired font.
The <span 
class="cmbx-10">fontfile </span>option specifies a local file which is copied into the <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>defs<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>section of the resulting SVG output file.
This file may either itself contain a font, or may contain the records necessary to create a hypertext
reference to the desired font. Gnuplot will look for the requested file using the directory list in the
GNUPLOT_FONTPATH environmental variable. NB: You must embed an svg font, not a TrueType or PostScript
font.
