<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-472000IV"></a>Tikz</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-939"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-472001"></a>
<!--l. 20187--><p class="noindent" >This driver creates output for use with the TikZ package of graphics macros in TeX. It is currently implemented via
an external lua script, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term tikz </span>is a short form of the command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term lua tikz</span>. See
<span 
class="cmbx-10">term lua (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-438000IV"><span 
class="cmbx-10">274</span><!--tex4ht:ref: term lua --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-472002"></a> for more information. Use the command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term tikz help </span>to print terminal
options.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-473000IV"></a>Tkcanvas</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-941"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-473001"></a>
<!--l. 20201--><p class="noindent" >This terminal driver generates Tk canvas widget commands based on Tcl/Tk (default) or Perl. To use it, rebuild
<span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>(after uncommenting or inserting the appropriate line in <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>term.h<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>), then
<!--l. 20206--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">gnuplot&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;term</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;tkcanvas</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{perltk}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{interactive}</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">gnuplot&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;output</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;plot.file&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 20209--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 20212--><p class="noindent" >After invoking <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>wish<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, execute the following sequence of Tcl/Tk commands:
<!--l. 20215--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">%</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;source</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;plot.file</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">%</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;canvas</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;.c</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">%</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;pack</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;.c</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">%</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;gnuplot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;.c</span>
<!--l. 20220--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 20223--><p class="noindent" >Or, for Perl/Tk use a program like this:
<!--l. 20226--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">use</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Tk;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">my</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$top</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;MainWindow-&#x003E;new;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">my</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$c</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$top-&#x003E;Canvas-&#x003E;pack;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">my</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$gnuplot</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;=</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;do</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"plot.pl";</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">$gnuplot-&#x003E;($c);</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">MainLoop;</span>
<!--l. 20233--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 20236--><p class="noindent" >The code generated by <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>creates a procedure called <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>gnuplot<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>that takes the name of a canvas as its
argument. When the procedure is called, it clears the canvas, finds the size of the canvas and draws the plot in it,
scaled to fit.
<!--l. 20241--><p class="noindent" >For 2-dimensional plotting (<span 
class="cmbx-10">plot</span>) two additional procedures are defined: <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>gnuplot_plotarea<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>will return a list
containing the borders of the plotting area <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>xleft, xright, ytop, ybot<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>in canvas screen coordinates, while the ranges
of the two axes <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>x1min, x1max, y1min, y1max, x2min, x2max, y2min, y2max<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>in plot coordinates can be obtained
calling <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>gnuplot_axisranges<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>. If the <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>interactive<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>option is specified, mouse clicking on a line segment will print the
coordinates of its midpoint to stdout. Advanced actions can happen instead if the user supplies a procedure named
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>user_gnuplot_coordinates<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, which takes the following arguments: <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>win id x1s y1s x2s y2s x1e y1e x2e y2e x1m y1m
x2m y2m<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, the name of the canvas and the id of the line segment followed by the coordinates of its start and end
point in the two possible axis ranges; the coordinates of the midpoint are only filled for logarithmic
axes.
<!--l. 20255--><p class="noindent" >The current version of <span 
class="cmbx-10">tkcanvas </span>supports neither <span 
class="cmbx-10">multiplot </span>nor <span 
class="cmbx-10">replot</span>.
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-474000IV"></a>Tpic</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-943"></a>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<a 
 id="dx1-474001"></a>
<!--l. 20265--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">tpic </span>terminal driver supports the LaTeX picture environment with tpic <span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>specials. It is an alternative to the
<span 
class="cmbx-10">latex </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">eepic </span>terminal drivers. Options are the point size, line width, and dot-dash interval.
<!--l. 20269--><p class="noindent" >Syntax: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;tpic</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;pointsize&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;linewidth&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;interval&#x003E;</span>
<!--l. 20273--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 20276--><p class="noindent" >where <span 
class="cmbx-10">pointsize </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">linewidth </span>are integers in milli-inches and <span 
class="cmbx-10">interval </span>is a float in inches. If a non-positive value
is specified, the default is chosen: pointsize = 40, linewidth = 6, interval = 0.1.
<!--l. 20280--><p class="noindent" >All drivers for LaTeX offer a special way of controlling text positioning: If any text string begins with &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>&#8217;, you also
need to include a &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>&#8217; at the end of the text, and the whole text will be centered both horizontally and vertically by
LaTeX. &#8212; If the text string begins with &#8217;[&#8217;, you need to continue it with: a position specification (up to two out of
t,b,l,r), &#8217;]<span 
class="cmsy-10">{</span>&#8217;, the text itself, and finally, &#8217;<span 
class="cmsy-10">}</span>&#8217;. The text itself may be anything LaTeX can typeset as an LR-box.
<span 
class="cmsy-10">\</span>rule<span 
class="cmsy-10">{}{}</span>&#8217;s may help for best positioning.
<!--l. 20288--><p class="noindent" >Examples: About label positioning: Use gnuplot defaults (mostly sensible, but sometimes not really best):
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;\LaTeX\</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;--</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\gamma</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 20294--><p class="noindent" ></pre> Force centering both horizontally and vertically: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;label</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;{\LaTeX\</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;--</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\gamma</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$}&#8217;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;at</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;0,0</span>
<!--l. 20300--><p class="noindent" ></pre> Specify own positioning (top here): <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;xlabel</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;[t]{\LaTeX\</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;--</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\gamma</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$}&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 20306--><p class="noindent" ></pre> The other label &#8211; account for long ticlabels: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ylabel</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;[r]{\LaTeX\</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;--</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;\gamma</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;$\rule{7mm}{0pt}}&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 20312--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
