class="cmbx-10">solid </span>select dashed or solid lines. Note that
<span 
class="cmbx-10">color </span>defaults to <span 
class="cmbx-10">solid</span>, whereas <span 
class="cmbx-10">monochrome </span>defaults to <span 
class="cmbx-10">dashed</span>. <span 
class="cmbx-10">enhanced </span>enables enhanced text mode
features (subscripts, superscripts and mixed fonts, see <span 
class="cmbx-10">enhanced text (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-22000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">26</span><!--tex4ht:ref: enhanced text --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-478002"></a> for more information). <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">fontspec</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>
is in the format <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>fontface<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>,<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>fontsize<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, where <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>fontface<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is the name of a valid Windows font, and
<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>fontsize<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is the size of the font in points and both components are optional. Note that in previous versions of
gnuplot the <span 
class="cmbx-10">font </span>statement could be left out and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>fontsize<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>could be given as a number without double
quotes. This is no longer supported. <span 
class="cmbx-10">linewidth </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">fontscale </span>can be used to scale the width of lines
and the size of text. <span 
class="cmbx-10">title </span>changes the title of the graph window. <span 
class="cmbx-10">size </span>defines the width and height of
the window in pixel and <span 
class="cmbx-10">position </span>the origin of the window i.e. the position of the top left corner
on the screen (again in pixel). These options override any default settings from the <span 
class="cmbx-10">wgnuplot.ini</span>
file.
<!--l. 20445--><p class="noindent" >Other options may be changed using the <span 
class="cmbx-10">graph-menu </span>or the initialization file <span 
class="cmbx-10">wgnuplot.ini</span>.
<!--l. 20448--><p class="noindent" >The Windows version normally terminates immediately as soon as the end of any files given as command line
arguments is reached (i.e. in non-interactive mode), unless you specify <span 
class="cmbx-10">- </span>as the last command line option. It will also
not show the text-window at all, in this mode, only the plot. By giving the optional argument <span 
class="cmbx-10">-persist </span>(same as for
gnuplot under x11; former Windows-only options <span 
class="cmbx-10">/noend </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">-noend </span>are still accepted as well), will not close
gnuplot. Contrary to gnuplot on other operating systems, gnuplot&#8217;s interactive command line is accessible after the
-persist option.
<!--l. 20457--><p class="noindent" >The plot window remains open when the gnuplot terminal is changed with a <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term </span>command. The plot window
can be closed with <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term windows close</span>.
<!--l. 20460--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>supports different methods to create printed output on Windows, see <span 
class="cmbx-10">windows printing (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-480000IV"><span 
class="cmbx-10">306</span><!--tex4ht:ref: windows printing --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-478003"></a>. The
windows terminal supports data exchange with other programs via clipboard and EMF files, see <span 
class="cmbx-10">graph-menu</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-479000IV"><span 
class="cmbx-10">305</span><!--tex4ht:ref: graph-menu --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-478004"></a>. You can also use the <span 
class="cmbx-10">terminal emf </span>to create EMF files.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-479000IV"></a>Graph-menu</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-953"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-479001"></a>
<!--l. 20472--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot graph </span>window has the following options on a pop-up menu accessed by pressing the right mouse
button(*) or selecting <span 
class="cmbx-10">Options </span>from the system menu:
<!--l. 20476--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Copy to Clipboard </span>copies a bitmap and an enhanced Metafile picture.
<!--l. 20478--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Save as EMF... </span>allows the user to save the current graph window as enhanced metafile
<!--l. 20480--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Print... </span>prints the graphics windows using a Windows printer driver and allows selection of the printer and scaling
of the output. The output produced by <span 
class="cmbx-10">Print </span>is not as good as that from <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot</span>&#8217;s own printer drivers. See also
<span 
class="cmbx-10">windows printing (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-480000IV"><span 
class="cmbx-10">306</span><!--tex4ht:ref: windows printing --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-479002"></a>.
<!--l. 20485--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Bring to Top </span>when checked brings the graph window to the top after every plot.
<!--l. 20488--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Color </span>when checked enables color linestyles. When unchecked it forces monochrome linestyles.
<!--l. 20491--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Double buffer </span>activates drawing into a memory buffer before copying the graph to the screen. This
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
avoids flickering e.g. during animation and rotation of 3d graphs. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">mouse (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-243000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">171</span><!--tex4ht:ref: mouse --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-479003"></a> and <span 
class="cmbx-10">scrolling</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-246000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">173</span><!--tex4ht:ref: scrolling --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-479004"></a>.
<!--l. 20495--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Oversampling </span>doubles the size of the virtual canvas. It is scaled down again for drawing to the screen.
This gives smoother graphics but requires more memory and computing time. It requires <span 
class="cmbx-10">double</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">buffer</span>.
<!--l. 20499--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Antialiasing </span>selects smoothing of lines and edges. Note that this slows down drawing.
<!--l. 20502--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Background... </span>sets the window background color.
<!--l. 20504--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Choose Font... </span>selects the font used in the graphics window.
<!--l. 20506--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Line Styles... </span>allows customization of the line colors and styles.
<!--l. 20508--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Update wgnuplot.ini </span>saves the current window locations, window sizes, text window font, text window font size,
graph window font, graph window font size, background color and linestyles to the initialization file
<span 
class="cmbx-10">wgnuplot.ini</span>.
<!--l. 20513--><p class="noindent" >(*) Note that this menu is only available by pressing the right mouse button with <span 
class="cmbx-10">unset mouse</span>.
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-480000IV"></a>Printing</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-955"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-480001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-480002"></a>
<!--l. 20525--><p class="noindent" >In order of preference, graphs may be printed in the following ways:
<!--l. 20527--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">1. </span>Use the <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>command <span 
class="cmbx-10">set terminal </span>to select a printer and <span 
class="cmbx-10">set output </span>to redirect output to a
file.
<!--l. 20530--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">2. </span>Select the <span 
class="cmbx-10">Print... </span>command from the <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot graph </span>window. An extra command <span 
class="cmbx-10">screendump </span>does this from
the text window.
<!--l. 20533--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">3. </span>If <span 
class="cmbx-10">set output </span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">PRN</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>is used, output will go to a temporary file. When you exit from <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>or when you
change the output with another <span 
class="cmbx-10">set output </span>command, a dialog box will appear for you to select a printer port. If
you choose OK, the output will be printed on the selected port, passing unmodified through the print manager. It is
possible to accidentally (or deliberately) send printer output meant for one printer to an incompatible
printer.
<!--l. 20541--><p class="noindent" >
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-481000IV"></a>Text-menu</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-957"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-481001"></a>
<!--l. 20549--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot text </span>window has the following options on a pop-up menu accessed by pressing the right mouse button
or selecting <span 
class="cmbx-10">Options </span>from the system menu:
<!--l. 20553--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Copy to Clipboard </span>copies marked text to the clipboard.
<!--l. 20555--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Paste </span>copies text from the clipboard as if typed by the user.
<!--l. 20557--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Choose Font... </span>selects the font used in the text window.
<!--l. 20559--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">System Colors </span>when selected makes the text window honor the System Colors set using the Control Panel. When
unselected, text is black or blue on a white background.
<!--l. 20563--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Wrap long lines </span>when selected lines longer than the current window width are wrapped.
<!--l. 20566--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Update wgnuplot.ini </span>saves the current settings to the initialisation file <span 
class="cmbx-10">wgnuplot.ini</span>, which is located in the
user&#8217;s application data directory.
<!--l. 20569--><p class="noindent" >
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
