<!--l. 20715--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 20718--><p class="noindent" >Multiple plot windows are supported: <span 
class="cmbx-10">set terminal wxt </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">n</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>directs the output to plot window number
n.
<!--l. 20721--><p class="noindent" >The default window title is based on the window number. This title can also be specified with the keyword
<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>title<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.
<!--l. 20724--><p class="noindent" >Plot windows remain open even when the <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>driver is changed to a different device. A plot window can be
closed by pressing the letter &#8217;q&#8217; while that window has input focus, by choosing <span 
class="cmbx-10">close </span>from a window manager
menu, or with <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term wxt </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">n</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span><span 
class="cmbx-10">close</span>.
<!--l. 20729--><p class="noindent" >The size of the plot area is given in pixels, it defaults to 640x384. In addition to that, the actual size of the window
also includes the space reserved for the toolbar and the status bar. When you resize a window, the plot is
immediately scaled to fit in the new size of the window. Unlike other interactive terminals, the <span 
class="cmbx-10">wxt </span>terminal scales
the whole plot, including fonts and linewidths, and keeps its global aspect ratio constant, leaving an empty space
painted in gray. If you type <span 
class="cmbx-10">replot</span>, click the <span 
class="cmbx-10">replot </span>icon in the terminal toolbar or type a new <span 
class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command, the
new plot will completely fit in the window and the font size and the linewidths will be reset to their
defaults.
<!--l. 20740--><p class="noindent" >The active plot window (the one selected by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term wxt </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">n</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>) is interactive. Its behaviour is shared with other
terminal types. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">mouse (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-243000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">171</span><!--tex4ht:ref: mouse --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-484002"></a> for details. It also has some extra icons, which are supposed to be
self-explanatory.
<!--l. 20745--><p class="noindent" >This terminal supports an enhanced text mode, which allows font and other formatting commands (subscripts,
superscripts, etc.) to be embedded in labels and other text strings. The enhanced text mode syntax is shared with
other gnuplot terminal types. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">enhanced (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-22000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">26</span><!--tex4ht:ref: enhanced --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-484003"></a> for more details.
<!--l. 20750--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>font<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>is in the format <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>FontFace,FontSize<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, i.e. the face and the size comma-separated in a single string. FontFace
is a usual font face name, such as &#8217;Arial&#8217;. If you do not provide FontFace, the wxt terminal will use &#8217;Sans&#8217;.
FontSize is the font size, in points. If you do not provide it, the wxt terminal will use a size of 10 points.
