class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;terminal</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x11</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{reset}</span>
<!--l. 20835--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 20838--><p class="noindent" >Multiple plot windows are supported: <span 
class="cmbx-10">set terminal x11 </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">n</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>directs the output to plot window number n. If n is
not 0, the terminal number will be appended to the window title (unless a title has been supplied manually) and the
icon will be labeled <span 
class="cmbx-10">Gnuplot </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">n</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>. The active window may be distinguished by a change in cursor (from default to
crosshair).
<!--l. 20844--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">x11 </span>terminal can connect to X windows previously created by an outside application via the option <span 
class="cmbx-10">window</span>
followed by a string containing the X ID for the window in hexadecimal format. Gnuplot uses that external X
window as a container since X does not allow for multiple clients selecting the ButtonPress event. In this way,
gnuplot&#8217;s mouse features work within the contained plot window.
<!--l. 20852--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;term</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x11</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;window</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"220001e"</span>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 20854--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 20857--><p class="noindent" >The x11 terminal supports enhanced text mode (see <span 
class="cmbx-10">enhanced (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-22000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">26</span><!--tex4ht:ref: enhanced --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-485003"></a>), subject to the available fonts. In order for
font size commands embedded in text to have any effect, the default x11 font must be scalable. Thus the first
example below will work as expected, but the second will not.
<!--l. 20863--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;term</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x11</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;enhanced</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"arial,15"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;{/=20</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Big}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Medium</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{/=5</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Small}&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 20866--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 20870--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;term</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x11</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;enhanced</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"terminal-14"</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;title</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;{/=20</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Big}</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Medium</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;{/=5</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Small}&#8217;</span>
<!--l. 20873--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 20876--><p class="noindent" >Plot windows remain open even when the <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>driver is changed to a different device. A plot window can be
closed by pressing the letter q while that window has input focus, or by choosing <span 
class="cmbx-10">close </span>from a window manager
menu. All plot windows can be closed by specifying <span 
class="cmbx-10">reset</span>, which actually terminates the subprocess
which maintains the windows (unless <span 
class="cmbx-10">-persist </span>was specified). The <span 
class="cmbx-10">close </span>command can be used to close
individual plot windows by number. However, after a <span 
class="cmbx-10">reset</span>, those plot windows left due to persist
cannot be closed with the command <span 
class="cmbx-10">close</span>. A <span 
class="cmbx-10">close </span>without a number closes the current active plot
window.
<!--l. 20886--><p class="noindent" >The gnuplot outboard driver, gnuplot_x11, is searched in a default place chosen when the program is compiled. You
can override that by defining the environment variable GNUPLOT_DRIVER_DIR to point to a different
location.
<!--l. 20891--><p class="noindent" >Plot windows will automatically be closed at the end of the session unless the <span 
class="cmbx-10">-persist </span>option was
given.
<!--l. 20894--><p class="noindent" >The options <span 
class="cmbx-10">persist </span>and <span 
class="cmbx-10">raise </span>are unset by default, which means that the defaults (persist == no and raise ==
yes) or the command line options -persist / -raise or the Xresources are taken. If [no]persist or [no]raise are specified,
they will override command line options and Xresources. Setting one of these options takes place immediately, so the
behaviour of an already running driver can be modified. If the window does not get raised, see discussion in <span 
class="cmbx-10">raise</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-184000III"><span 
class="cmbx-10">124</span><!--tex4ht:ref: raise --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-485004"></a>.
<!--l. 20902--><p class="noindent" >The option <span 
class="cmbx-10">title </span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">title name</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>will supply the title name of the window for the current plot window or
plot window <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>n<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>if a number is given. Where (or if) this title is shown depends on your X window
manager.
<!--l. 20906--><p class="noindent" >The size option can be used to set the size of the plot window. The size option will only apply to newly created
windows.
<!--l. 20909--><p class="noindent" >The position option can be used to set the position of the plot window. The position option will only apply to newly
created windows.
<!--l. 20912--><p class="noindent" >The size or aspect ratio of a plot may be changed by resizing the <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>window.
<!--l. 20915--><p class="noindent" >Linewidths and pointsizes may be changed from within <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>with <span 
class="cmbx-10">set linestyle</span>.
<!--l. 20918--><p class="noindent" >For terminal type <span 
class="cmbx-10">x11</span>, <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>accepts (when initialized) the standard X Toolkit options and resources such as
geometry, font, and name from the command line arguments or a configuration file. See the X(1) man page (or its
equivalent) for a description of such options.
<a 
 id="dx1-485005"></a>
<!--l. 20924--><p class="noindent" >A number of other <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>options are available for the <span 
class="cmbx-10">x11 </span>terminal. These may be specified either as
command-line options when <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>is invoked or as resources in the configuration file <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.Xdefaults<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.
They are set upon initialization and cannot be altered during a <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>session. (except <span 
class="cmbx-10">persist </span>and
<span 
class="cmbx-10">raise</span>)
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-486000IV"></a>X11_fonts</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-967"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-486001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-486002"></a>
<!--l. 20938--><p class="noindent" >Upon initial startup, the default font is taken from the X11 resources as set in the system or user .Xdefaults file or
on the command line.
<!--l. 20941--><p class="noindent" >Example: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;gnuplot*font:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;lucidasans-bold-12</span>
<!--l. 20945--><p class="noindent" ></pre> A new default font may be specified to the x11 driver from inside gnuplot using <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;term</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;x11</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;"&#x003C;fontspec&#x003E;"&#8216;</span>
<!--l. 20952--><p class="noindent" ></pre> The driver first queries the X-server for a font of the exact name given. If this query fails, then it tries to interpret
<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>fontspec<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>as <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>font<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>,<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>size<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>,<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>slant<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>,<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>weight<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>and to construct a full X11 font name of the form
<pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-*-&#x003C;font&#x003E;-&#x003C;weight&#x003E;-&#x003C;s&#x003E;-*-*-&#x003C;size&#x003E;-*-*-*-*-*-&#x003C;encoding&#x003E;</span>
<!--l. 20961--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
<!--l. 20965--><p class="noindent" ><pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x003C;font&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;is</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;the</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;base</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;name</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;of</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;the</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;font</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(e.g.</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Times</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;or</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Symbol)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x003C;size&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;is</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;the</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;point</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;size</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(defaults</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;to</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;12</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;if</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;not</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;specified)</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x003C;s&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;is</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;i&#8216;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;if</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;slant&#x003E;=="italic"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;o&#8216;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;if</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;slant&#x003E;=="oblique"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;r&#8216;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;otherwise</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x003C;weight&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;is</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;medium&#8216;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;or</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;bold&#8216;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;if</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;explicitly</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;requested,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;otherwise</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;*&#8216;</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x003C;encoding&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;is</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;based</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;on</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;the</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;current</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;character</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(see</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8216;set</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;encoding&#8216;).</span>
<!--l. 20971--><p class="noindent" ></pre> So <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term x11 font </span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">arial,15,italic</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>will be translated to -*-arial-*-i-*-*-15-*-*-*-*-*-iso8859-1 (assuming
default encoding). The <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>size<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>, <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>slant<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>, and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>weight<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>specifications are all optional. If you do not specify <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>slant<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>
or <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>weight<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>then you will get whatever font variant the font server offers first. You may set a default enconding via
the corresponding X11 resource. E.g. <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;gnuplot*encoding:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;iso8859-15</span>
<!--l. 20982--><p class="noindent" ></pre> The driver also recognizes some common PostScript font names and replaces them with possible X11 or TrueType
equivalents. This same sequence is used to process font requests from <span 
class="cmbx-10">set label</span>.
<!--l. 20988--><p class="noindent" >If your gnuplot was built with configuration option &#8211;enable-x11-mbfonts, you can specify multi-byte fonts by using
the prefix <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>mbfont:<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>on the font name. An additional font may be given, separated by a semicolon. Since multi-byte
font encodings are interpreted according to the locale setting, you must make sure that the environmental
variable LC_CTYPE is set to some appropriate locale value such as ja_JP.eucJP, ko_KR.EUC, or
zh_CN.EUC.
<!--l. 20995--><p class="noindent" >Example: <pre class="prettyprint">
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
