<!--l. 21051--><p class="noindent" >The options are shown above in their command-line syntax. When entered as resources in <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>.Xdefaults<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, they require
a different syntax.
<!--l. 21054--><p class="noindent" >Example: <pre class="prettyprint">
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;gnuplot*gray:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;on</span>
<span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;gnuplot*ctrlq:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;on</span>
<!--l. 21059--><p class="noindent" ></pre>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 21062--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>also provides a command line option (<span 
class="cmbx-10">-pointsize </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">v</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>) and a resource, <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot*pointsize: </span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">v</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span>, to
control the size of points plotted with the <span 
class="cmbx-10">points </span>plotting style. The value <span 
class="cmbx-10">v </span>is a real number (greater than 0 and
less than or equal to ten) used as a scaling factor for point sizes. For example, <span 
class="cmbx-10">-pointsize 2 </span>uses points twice the
default size, and <span 
class="cmbx-10">-pointsize 0.5 </span>uses points half the normal size.
<!--l. 21069--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">-noevents </span>switch disables all mouse and key event processing (except for <span 
class="cmbx-10">q </span>and <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">space</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>for closing
the window). This is useful for programs which use the x11 driver independent of the gnuplot main
program.
<!--l. 21073--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">-ctrlq </span>switch changes the hot-key that closes a plot window from <span 
class="cmbx-10">q </span>to <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">ctrl</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">q</span>. This is useful is you are using
the keystroke-capture feature <span 
class="cmbx-10">pause mouse keystroke</span>, since it allows the character <span 
class="cmbx-10">q </span>to be captured just as all
other alphanumeric characters. The <span 
class="cmbx-10">-ctrlq </span>switch similarly replaces the <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>space<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>hot-key with <span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span>ctrl<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;&#x003C;</span>space<span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E; </span>for
the same reason.
<!--l. 21079--><p class="noindent" >
<h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-488000IV"></a>Monochrome_options</h5>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-971"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-488001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-488002"></a>
<!--l. 21088--><p class="noindent" >For monochrome displays, <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>does not honor foreground or background colors. The default is black-on-white.
<span 
class="cmbx-10">-rv </span>or <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot*reverseVideo: on </span>requests white-on-black.
<!--l. 21092--><p class="noindent" >
