<!--l. 21319--><p class="noindent" >
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-494000IV"></a>Xlib</h4>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-983"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-494001"></a>
<!--l. 21328--><p class="noindent" >The <span 
class="cmbx-10">xlib </span>terminal driver supports the X11 Windows System. It generates gnuplot_x11 commands, but
sends them to the output file specified by <span 
class="cmbx-10">set output &#8217;</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003C;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">filename</span><span 
class="cmmi-10">&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#8217;</span>. <span 
class="cmbx-10">set term x11 </span>is equivalent
to <span 
class="cmbx-10">set output </span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmsy-10">|</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">_x11 -noevents</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">; set term xlib</span>. <span 
class="cmbx-10">xlib </span>takes the same set of options as
<span 
class="cmbx-10">x11</span>.
<h1 class="partHead"><span class="titlemark">Part&#x00A0;V<br /></span><a 
 id="x1-495000V"></a>Bugs</h1>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<a 
 id="dx1-495001"></a>
<!--l. 21336--><p class="noindent" >Please e-mail bug reports to the gnuplot-bugs mailing list or upload the report to the gnuplot web site on
SourceForge. Please give complete information on the version of gnuplot you are using and, if possible, a test script
that demonstrates the bug. See <span 
class="cmbx-10">seeking-assistance (p.</span><span 
class="cmbx-10">&#x00A0;</span><a 
href="#x1-5000I"><span 
class="cmbx-10">17</span><!--tex4ht:ref: seeking-assistance --></a><span 
class="cmbx-10">)</span><a 
 id="dx1-495002"></a>.
<!--l. 21342--><p class="noindent" >
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-496000V"></a>Known limitations</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-986"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-496001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-496002"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-496003"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-496004"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-496005"></a>
<!--l. 21349--><p class="noindent" >Floating point exceptions (floating point number too large/small, divide by zero, etc.) may occasionally be
generated by user defined functions. Some of the demos in particular may cause numbers to exceed the floating
point range. Whether the system ignores such exceptions (in which case <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>labels the corresponding point as
undefined) or aborts <span 
class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>depends on the compiler/runtime environment.
<!--l. 21356--><p class="noindent" >The gamma, bessel, and erf functions do not work for complex arguments.
<!--l. 21358--><p class="noindent" >Coordinates specified as <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>time<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>wrap at 24 hours.
<!--l. 21360--><p class="noindent" >The &#8217;nohidden3d&#8217; option that is supposed to exempt individual plots from the global property &#8217;set hidden3d&#8217; does
not work for parametric curves.
<!--l. 21363--><p class="noindent" >X11 terminal: It is difficult to select UTF-8 fonts. The program does not track the true aspect ratio of the x11
terminal window. In order for commands such as <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>set size ratio<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>to work, the x11 window must itself have
equal height and width. Only one color palette at a time is active for any given x11 plot window.
This means that multiplots whose constituent plots use different palettes will not display correctly in
x11.
<!--l. 21370--><p class="noindent" >Qt terminal: If the local qt environment does not support <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>opengl<span 
class="cmtt-10">" </span>as a rendering mode then display of polygons
and surfaces can be very slow.
<!--l. 21373--><p class="noindent" >
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-497000V"></a>External libraries</h3>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-988"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-497001"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-497002"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-497003"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-497004"></a>
<a 
 id="dx1-497005"></a>
<!--l. 21381--><p class="noindent" >External library GD (used by PNG/JPEG/GIF drivers): Versions of libgd through 2.0.33 contain various bugs in
mapping the characters of Adobe&#8217;s Symbol font. Also it is possible to trigger a library segfault if an anti-aliased line
crosses an upper corner of the canvas.
<!--l. 21386--><p class="noindent" >External library PDFlib (used by PDF driver): Gnuplot can be linked against libpdf versions 4, 5, or 6. However,
these versions differ in their handling of piped I/O. Therefore gnuplot scripts using piped output to PDF may work
only for some versions of PDFlib.
<!--l. 21391--><p class="noindent" >External library svgalib (used by linux and vgagl driver): Requires gnuplot to be suid root (bad!) and has many
bugs that are specific to the video card or graphics driver used in X11.
<!--l. 21395--><p class="noindent" >Internationalization (locale settings): Gnuplot uses the C runtime library routine setlocale() to control locale-specific
formatting of input and output number, times, and date strings. The locales available, and the level of support for
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
locale features such as <span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>thousands&#8217; grouping separator<span 
class="cmtt-10">"</span>, depend on the internationalization support provided by
your individual machine.
